<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON HUNDLEY FOR OPENING DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For the first time since 1992, a Los Angeles
Dodgers catcher not named Mike Piazza will be in the starting
lineup opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson is praying the new name is Todd Hundley. With the
season opener two days away, Johnson said he will be watching
Hundley as he watches no other player during the final two
exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think about anything else,'' Johnson said before the
Dodgers played the Anaheim Angels in the annual Freeway Series.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, acquired in a trade with the Mets on Dec. 1, has a
surgically repaired right elbow. The question all spring has been
his ability to throw.
</P>
<P>
   Those doubts may have been alleviated Friday during batting
practice, when Hundley playfully took grounders at shortstop and
threw around the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a big grin on his face all day,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he will wait until the end of the weekend to
determine if the Dodgers will carry three catchers. Hundley, rookie
Paul LoDuca and journeyman Rick Wilkins all made the trip west from
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been any pessimism about Hundley's bat. He set a
major-league single-season record with 41 homers in 1996 with the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But he only had 18 at-bats in Florida. Hundley batted in the
No.2 spot Friday night and went 3 for 4 with an infield single and
bloop single.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled outfield: The catching position isn't Johnson's only
weekend decision. The race between Jacob Brumfield and Trenidad
Hubbard for the fifth outfielder spot is going down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Brumfield, a 33-year-old non-roster invitee, batted .283 with
two homers and six RBI in 18 spring games. Hubbard, 32, was the
Dodgers' opening-day center fielder last year, and was the only
player in that lineup who wasn't traded or lost for the season to
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard's luck ran out on March 8 in Vero Beach, when he
collided with Hiram Bocachica. Hubbard played in only 12 games and
batted .130 (3 for 23).
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Brumfield,'' Johnson said. ``He's had a good spring. He
wasn't even in the picture at the beginning. Hubbard was really set
back with the collision. We'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you listening?: Johnson's penchant is motivating talented
teams with eclectic personalities. That's why he said he admires
the New York Yankees, who tonight make their first appearance in
Dodger Stadium since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following as a subtle warning for his own players:
</P>
<P>
   `The thing I like about the Yankees is there are a lot of stars
on that club but none of them are selfish,'' he said. ``None of
them complained (last year) about playing time or anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez will start for the Dodgers tonight. David Cone will
start for the Yankees. The first pitch is scheduled for 7:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie award: Left-handed relief pitcher Onan Masaoka was named
the top rookie during spring training. Masaoka, 21, allowed only
one earned run and struck out 11 in seven appearances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
