<HEADLINE>
NATO ATTACKS YUGOSLAV CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2nd graf to add info on fired cruise missiles; 11th graf to
move up info on selection of targets; 13th graf to add Pentagon
info on use of ground troops; 7th graf from end (``Cruise
missile....'') to add info on destruction of Yugoslav fuel
supplies; last graf for further info on selection of targets.) (See also: KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-WEATHER, KOSOVO-NATO,
KOSOVO-TROOPS, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-MCCAIN.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After nine days of hesitation, NATO attacked the
center of Yugoslavia's capital, destroying the headquarters of the
security forces carrying out President Slobodan Milosevic's
offensive against the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A barrage of seven cruise missiles _ fired from American
warships in the Adriatic _ struck just before 1 a.m. Saturday in
Belgrade, the officials said. A British submarine, the Splendid,
fired an eighth cruise missile at another target outside Belgrade,
they said, declining to specify where.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon refused Friday night to disclose the targets hit,
but flames raged from two buildings near the Sava River in
Belgrade's core, the federal Ministry for Internal Affairs and the
Ministry of the Interior. The buildings house the headquarters of
the paramilitary police forces that have carried out Milosevic's
yearlong crackdown against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 10 days of attacks that NATO had struck
the center of Belgrade, a once-thriving capital that has slowly
withered under years of economic sanctions and diplomatic isolation
caused by Milosevic's policies.
</P>
<P>
   Although previous attacks battered military targets on
Belgrade's edges, the missiles Friday night struck with a
thunderous clap that shook the entire capital. Within minutes of
the first explosion, an enormous arc of flames soared hundreds of
feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of casualties from the strikes was not immediately
clear, but the attack occurred in the middle of the night, at a
time when the buildings would presumably have few people in them.
</P>
<P>
   The two buildings are close to other government buildings,
including a hospital. But it appeared that the cruise missiles _
each with a 1,000-pound warhead _ struck their targets with
pinpoint precision, leaving other buildings nearby still standing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Yugoslavia's deputy prime minister, Vuk Draskovic,
said there were ``many, many victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Militarily and psychologically, the strikes were the first firm
evidence that NATO was carrying out the warning by its commander,
Gen. Wesley Clark, that there would be ``no sanctuary'' for
Yugoslavia's political and military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week NATO gave Clark the authority to expand the
raids beyond strictly military targets in or near Kosovo. On
Thursday American F-15s destroyed a bridge over the Danube River in
the city of Novi Sad, and Pentagon and NATO officials have vowed
that more bridges and other targets in cities would be pounded as
long as Milosevic continued his repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The targets of this phase of NATO's campaign _ first the bridge,
then the two ministry buildings _ are being deliberately chosen and
timed to maximize their psychological impact and to leave the
Yugoslav authorities uncertain of when and where the next strike
will be, a senior administration official said. The official said
other buildings, like the Ministry of Defense, were on the target
list.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's strikes came after nine days of bombing had made
little progress in slowing Milosevic's onslaught against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo. Refugees continued to pour from Kosovo into
Albania and Macedonia, telling of killings and forced expulsions
from villages, towns and cities throughout the province.
</P>
<P>
   The mushrooming refugee crisis along Kosovo's border _ where
hundreds of thousands of refugees have gathered, short of food and
shelter _ has put new pressure on the United States and NATO to
intensify its campaign, even if that meant considering the use of
ground troops. While NATO officials have discussed the possibility
of NATO troops' escorting ethnic Albanians back to Kosovo and
protecting a self-governing enclave there, those plans are
preliminary, and senior officials here in Washington said the
administration continued to adamantly oppose any proposal to use
ground troops in combat in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, facing sharp questions at a White House news
briefing, appealed for patience and expressed confidence that an
air campaign alone would be able to achieve NATO's military and
political objectives in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be determined,'' Clinton said. ``We must be
persistent. We must be patient if we expect to see this mission
through. And I am absolutely determined to do that. We have to make
sure that Milosevic pays a heavy price for this policy of
repression. We have to seriously diminish his capacity to maintain
that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air campaign has been severely hampered by the Balkan
weather, with rain, low clouds and fog forcing many warplanes to
abandon their targets. Through the first nine nights, alliance
aircraft flew some 2,700 missions over or near Yugoslavia, 405 of
them combat strikes. The Pentagon estimated that 20 percent of the
missions had been scrubbed because of foul weather, but other
officials have said the number was much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, a number of NATO warplanes _ including F-16s and
F-15s _ took advantage of a brief break in the rainy weather to
launch the first daylight air raids against Yugoslav forces. The
jets attacked ground forces operating near the center of Kosovo,
NATO and Pentagon officials said, declining to identify what was
struck.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, however, clouds and rain once again blanketed the
region, forcing frustrated NATO commanders to limit their attacks
to weapons unaffected by weather, including the Tomahawk cruise
missiles that struck Belgrade Friday night. Forecasts predict that
the weather will clear over the weekend, and when it does,
officials at NATO and the Pentagon said, the raids will increase in
scope and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's headquarters in Brussels, officials said the brunt of
the raids occurring now are falling on ground forces directly
involved in the campaign against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. A
military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby of Britain, described
a series of strikes against military targets on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   One strike hit what he described as a support base for
Yugoslavia's 243rd Mechanized Brigade, which is now operating in
the Pagarusa Valley, where thousands of Albanians have reportedly
been surrounded by Yugoslav forces and repeatedly shelled. The
Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said American B-1 bombers,
joining the attacks for the first time, had also bombed a staging
area for armored forces in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those attacks, the Yugoslav forces have continued to
press their offensive in the Pagarusa Valley and near Malisevo, a
city west of Kosovo's capital, Pristina, that is the last
stronghold of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence reports collected here in Washington suggest that
Milosevic's forces have largely routed the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, but Wilby said Friday that the rebels remained a
viable force.
</P>
<P>
   He and other officials also reported that the Yugoslav forces
were being slowed, if not stopped, by the cumulative effects of
NATO's raids, particularly the destruction of fuel and ammunition
depots. Wilby said one Yugoslav unit, the 549th motorized brigade,
had been ``immobilized'' near Djakovica while waiting for more
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``therefore, NATO air-to-ground operations against
fielded forces in Kosovo are already degrading and disrupting'' the
Yugoslav military's ability to use tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missile strikes against fuel storage sites in Prokuplje
on Wednesday and at Leskovac and Pristina on Thursday destroyed an
estimated 35 percent of Yugoslavia's entire supply of fuel, a
senior Pentagon official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Bacon said the attacks were taking a toll on
Yugoslav morale, too, though he offered little evidence to back
that up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly are having some impact on command and control,'' he
said. ``We're seeing some morale problems in the army. The forces
are clearly more wary of being hit. They've had to disperse more
and are having a harder time operating in large, coherent units.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also acknowledged the limits of the success. ``We have
not seen tanks stopped in their tracks, if that's what you mean,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite signs of some progress, officials have pressed for new
weapons that would allow NATO to intensify the attacks on the
ground forces. Clark has asked Secretary of Defense William Cohen
to approve the use of Apache helicopter gunships _ used to attack
tanks _ and long-range rocket batteries to support them.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Cohen had not yet made a decision on the request. The
helicopters would require large numbers of Army troops to move into
the region _ 300 soldiers for a battalion of 18 helicopters _ and
that has raised fears that it would amount to an introduction of
American ground forces into the Balkans. The Clinton administration
has repeatedly ruled that out.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivity of bombing Belgrade was so great that Clinton
himself approved the target list earlier this week and authorized
the attack itself within the last 24 hours, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and other NATO planners chose the targets each day, but
because of the possibility of substantial civilian loss of the
life, aides sought Clinton's specific approval for the attack on
the two ministries Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
