<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IRISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IRA'S OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British and Irish prime ministers have given the Irish
Republican Army an opportunity to chart a new course for its
nationalist cause. The IRA should give up some of its weapons to
make the case politically for a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has rejected previous demands that it give up, or
``decommission,'' its weapons as tantamount to surrender. But not
even the most rabidly anti-IRA Unionist in Northern Ireland expects
every last rifle to go on the scrapheap immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum on the agreement last May and Assembly elections
in June have exposed fissures in Unionism. David Trimble, the
pro-agreement Unionist who would become chief minister in the new
government, needs a gesture on decommissioning to maintain control
of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern, the British and Irish prime
ministers, were unable to broker a compromise this week. However,
they did devise an arrangement under which some weapons would be
put ``beyond voluntary use'' during a day of reconciliation
featuring ceremonies of remembrance for all victims of violence. An
international commission would verify IRA compliance. There would
be no surrender here; only a symbolic renunciation of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA and its political adjunct, Sinn Fein, have until April
13 to accept this offer, which will no doubt be met by objections
that the IRA needs arms to defend Catholics from Protestant mobs.
</P>
<P>
   Communal violence of this magnitude has not been a problem in
Northern Ireland for years. IRA guns were powerless to protect the
lawyer Rosemary Nelson and other Catholic nationalists from
carefully planned assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   With the slow separation of Scotland, Great Britain is on the
verge of extraordinary constitutional change. The Irish Republic,
no longer the sectarian backwater of Unionist caricature, is the
most dynamic economy in Europe. Northern Ireland itself has
renounced the bigoted policies that kept Catholics down for
hundreds of years. The IRA should not be bound by the strictures of
the past when the future holds great opportunities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
