<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNOWING NO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The duke and duchess of Northumberland make welcome headlines in
a permissive world. Fearing that their teenage son would go the way
of many a dissolute earl who inherited too much money too young,
they got a court order to postpone his coming of age.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of acquiring his $1.6 million fortune and additional
annual allowance of $400,000 at age 18 as stipulated in a trust set
up by a deceased uncle, the 14-year-old boy will now have to wait
until he is 25 to be independently wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   People long out of their 20s might suggest age 40 or beyond as
the threshold of maturity, but the duke and duchess still get
credit for a courageous ``no'' _ a word too many American parents
have forgotten how to use, mainly because it's a lot harder to say
than ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh to have the Northumberlands in the grocery store pushing the
cart with the brat in the seat. The tantrum for candy might never
take place, or it would stop in midscreech, because ``No, not until
you've had dinner'' would mean exactly that. Instead, what it
usually means is eventual capitulation.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true as the child grows older and makes bigger
demands for the most expensive fad toy, the designer wardrobe, the
car, the credit card, the private phone line, the unchaperoned trip
with a boyfriend or girlfriend. Instead of enforcing household law,
parents duck the role of the heavy in favor of being a pal. Or they
shrug and say, ``Kids grow up a lot faster than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they don't _ societal pressure just makes young people think
they've grown up. They need, and often secretly want, to hear a
firm older voice say, ``Wait a few years on that.''
</P>
<P>
   So much of life is geared to instant gratification. ``Just do
it,'' the shoe advertisement tells us. Like most commercials, it
promotes the invincibility of youth.
</P>
<P>
   But youth is quite fragile, much like a greenhouse plant getting
its first taste of the elements. A watchful gardener gives it room
to grow without letting it go wild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
