<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MELISSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MACRO PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week the computer virus Melissa tore through cyberspace _ a
reminder that the trick with viruses is learning to live with them.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, virus authors would always be caught, as 30-year-old
David Smith, the alleged author of Melissa, was. But this kind of
tracking can be difficult and could pose privacy threats. Even
electronic identification numbers _ such as those recently found to
be generated by some Microsoft products _ leave questionable clues.
That's because the numbers can be fudged, explains Richard Smith,
the software company president who discovered the Microsoft
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This makes awareness essential.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa is a macro virus. Macros carry a series of commands that
can be grouped together into one command, so one keystroke, for
example, could save a document and send it to another user. Macro
viruses contain malicious commands that destroy data or interfere
with how software runs.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace training could help. Employers should do better at
training employees on computer basics as well as antivirus software
and techniques. But education has limits. Training can be seen as a
time-consuming luxury. Sometimes it's a grass-roots effort that
spreads slowly.
</P>
<P>
   This puts Microsoft on the line. The company has improved
software security. It works with companies that produce antivirus
software. And recent versions of its software alert users when they
are about to open a document that has macros, some of which might
be viruses. Users can then choose to disable the macros.
</P>
<P>
   Some have asked Microsoft to mute the strength of macros, making
them less effective as viruses. Instead, Microsoft is beefing up
security, saying its customers like the power of macros. So the new
Office 2000 software tries to make it impossible to open a macro
virus accidentally. It's a sound step, but the company must keep
striking a balance between power and security.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 20,000 viruses found by such antivirus software
firms as Symantec, informed vigilance is the best protection
against infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
