<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES MAY BE PULLED IN DIALLO PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-POLICE-HARASSMENT) 
(DW) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Manhattan district attorney, Robert M.
Morgenthau, said Friday that he would probably ask for the
dismissal of charges against the 1,200 people who were arrested for
civil disobedience last month during the daily mass protests over
the police killing of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said that was the usual practice for minor offenses
when ``there is no significant inconvenience to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like they went out and blocked the Brooklyn
Bridge,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In systematic and well-publicized demonstrations at Police
headquarters that ended only this week with the arraignment of four
New York City police officers, hundreds of people a day were
charged with disorderly conduct for refusing to leave One Police
Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said that because the protests were not violent, the
detention of the protesters for five to seven hours on the days of
their arrests was enough punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a model demonstration, both on the part of the
protesters and the police,'' he said. ``I just think it's the right
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said in a statement Friday that
he disagreed with Morgenthau's plan. ``It is my opinion that these
summonses should have been prosecuted through the system with a
judge making the final determination,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said that the most each protester would face if
convicted would be a $250 fine. The protesters would not have
received jail time or criminal records because they had been
charged with a violation, the equivalent of a traffic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting all of the cases would not only strain the burdened
criminal courts, which were able to handle fewer than 800 trials
last year, but would also provide the protest movement another
stage for gaining publicity for its cause.
</P>
<P>
   Among those arrested were national and local politicians,
actors, civil rights leaders and religious figures.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said he and other lawyers who were defending the
protesters had urged Morgenthau to ask for dismissals in a meeting
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The first batch of people arrested, including the organizer of
the mass protests, the Rev. Al Sharpton, is scheduled to appear in
court on April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Requests from prosecutors to dismiss charges are usually made at
the first hearing on the charges before a criminal court judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now expect the cases to be dismissed in the interest of
justice,'' Siegel said. ``This would be, in our opinion, the
correct thing to do, because otherwise the criminal justice system
would be facing a huge logistical nightmare that would backlog the
courts for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest movement that was ignited by the Feb. 4 killing of
Diallo, an unarmed Guinean immigrant, now confronts a new
challenge: how to maintain its momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups, including Women for Justice, planned
demonstrations and prayer vigils in front of station houses in
nearly 30 police precincts around the city. But the crowds were
thin.
</P>
<P>
   One exception was a demonstration outside the 26th Precinct
station house, at 520 W. 126th St., when a church service held to
oppose the death penalty drew several hundred people who went on to
protest the Diallo killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to focus our demands and our demands have to be
crystallized,'' said Johanna Fernandez, a Columbia University
graduate student who helped organize the service at St. Mary's
Episcopal Church, across the street from the police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the movement needs leadership,'' she added. ``Al
Sharpton was instrumental in creating it, but now we need leaders
coming from all the communities and groups. We need to push it
further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
