<HEADER>
A4507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      04-03 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES POSTPONEMENT BID IN LOUIMA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The judge in the case of four police officers charged
with brutalizing Abner Louima on Friday denied a postponement
request made by defense lawyers who said news coverage of the case
and of the police shooting of Amadou Diallo had given rise to
anti-police sentiment in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will be able to get a fair and impartial jury,''
Judge Eugene Nickerson of federal District Court in Brooklyn said
in denying the request. Citing the large number of prospective
jurors who filled out questionnaires on Monday to begin the
selection of 12 jurors and six alternates, the judge said, ``There
must be 18 people among 785 who will be fair and impartial.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers had sought a postponement of at least four
months.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers are accused of beating Louima, a Haitian
immigrant, in a police car after arresting him in a street brawl in
Brooklyn in 1997. Two of the four are also accused of torturing him
in a police station. A police sergeant, also on trial, is accused
of trying to cover up part of the alleged assault. All five deny
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson also rejected a defense motion to dismiss the entire
panel of prospective jurors and call in a new one, a motion made
after some panel members gave interviews to reporters outside the
courthouse Monday. The defense argued that the interviews had
tainted the panel and compromised the judge's earlier ruling that
the jurors would be anonymous, their identities not disclosed to
the public or the lawyers and other parties in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But in an effort to prevent further interviews, Nickerson
ordered that no one ``shall interview, talk to, photograph or
sketch any juror or prospective juror in the courthouse or
elsewhere during the duration of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, a lawyer specializing in First Amendment matters,
said that efforts to insure a fair trial for the defendants were
understandable, but the breadth of the order might be
unconstitutional because of the ban on photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to take steps to prevent any communication
between jurors or prospective jurors and the press,'' he said, ``or
to shield jurors and prospective jurors from the press in the
courthouse, but a ban on taking pictures of jurors or prospective
jurors outside the courthouse seems to me to be troublingly
overbroad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
