A4510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FOOD-TAXES-740&AMP;ADD     04-03 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOOD-TAXES-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CURIOUS PROCESS OF DETERMINING WHICH FOODS GET TAXED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sure, it was a small thing, but to shopkeepers,
it was a milestone nonetheless. Last year, New York abolished
marshmallow discrimination, the long-standing rule that while
marshmallows were subject to the sales tax, mini-marshmallows were
not.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where business has long complained that regulations
take on the rigor, complexity and fervor of religion, the
marshmallow dichotomy had become a sort of reverse talisman, a
notorious symbol of all that was wrong with New York's ample
bureaucracy. And now, after the ruling that marshmallows are candy
no matter how small, all marshmallows bear a 4 percent state sales
tax, plus a local tax of about the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took away my best line,'' said Michael Rosen, vice
president of the Food Industry Alliance of New York state, who
liked to cite the marshmallow rule in his critiques of state
government.
</P>
<P>
   He needn't worry _ the sales tax rules still supply plenty of
material. Consider, for example, the amazing, transforming Twix.
Sold by the box from a store shelf, the state deems it a cookie,
and thus tax free. But sold in a single package at the check-out
counter, it morphs into a candy, and becomes taxable.
</P>
<P>
   If that distinction is lost on you, try these: Mini-M&AMP;Ms are tax
free, though the regular-sized ones are taxed. Aussie Mega shampoo?
Taxable. Head &AMP; Shoulders? Nontaxable. Powdered drink mixes are
taxed. Except Tang. Don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to keep track of it,'' said Brian
Riesenburger, manager of the Fairway store on Broadway at 74th
Street in Manhattan. ``It's so easy to make mistakes, and we're
constantly calling up the state to make sure we're doing it right
so we don't get in trouble. On salad there's no tax, but on fruit
salad there's tax. Where's the sense?''
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, the sales tax, especially as it applies to
food, has been historically subject to a particularly fine degree
of hair-splitting at the state Department of Taxation and Finance,
which has the job of interpreting tax laws. Retailers say that
other states have nonsensical tax rules, too, but that New York
stands out in its knack for making the simple complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insane,'' Michael Urbach, the state commissioner of
taxation and finance, said of the current system of rules. ``From
the time I began to see this stuff, I wondered, `What were they
thinking?'''
</P>
<P>
   He will probably never get an answer. Many of the rules were
imposed in the first years after New York adopted a sales tax in
1965, and the civil servants who devised them are either retired or
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner and the man who appointed him, Gov. George
Pataki, have long said that they wanted to simplify the tax rules,
which were largely imposed by departmental decree rather than by
legislation, and can be changed the same way. It is no surprise
that Urbach began last year by doing away with the marshmallow
dichotomy.
</P>
<P>
   He says he plans to eliminate other such distinctions, but that
he has to move carefully, both to make sure the changes are within
his legal power and to take into account the sums of money
involved. Usually, he estimated, making a rule more uniform would
mean no more than tens of thousands of dollars a year gained or
lost by the state. But in some cases, he said, it could mean
millions, not a trivial amount, even in a state with a $71 billion
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Each rule rests on a bit of logic that sounds, to the
uninitiated and expert alike, a little tortured.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, state law says that candy, unlike most food, is
taxable, and great effort has gone into judging what is candy and
what is not. Thus, the marshmallow rule. Marshmallows, the
department decided, were candy, but mini-marshmallows were a
cooking ingredient, and so were nontaxable. The same went for
mini-M&AMP;Ms.
</P>
<P>
   The law dictates that medical products are nontaxable, but what,
exactly, is a medical product? Dandruff shampoo, the department has
ruled, but not regular shampoo; sterile cotton balls, but not
regular cotton balls; adult bladder-control underpants, but not
baby diapers.
</P>
<P>
   The state long ago decreed that foods meant to be taken home
were tax free, but that anything meant to be eaten on the spot was
taxable, a discrimination whose justification has been lost in the
mists of time. So a pint of ice cream is not taxed, but an ice
cream cone is. A frozen knish is tax free, but one right out of the
oven is taxed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for the reasoning that turns Twix from cookie to candy, state
officials just shrug their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the ``cheese-board rule.'' Cheese, crackers, fruit
and jams are all nontaxable. But wrap them in one of those popular
gift packs, add a taxable cutting board or basket, and the whole
thing becomes taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Strangest of all is the rule that states that among powdered
drink mixes, only Tang is free from sales tax. No one seems to know
why. ``I've heard it's because they took it to the Moon, but I'm
not sure what that has to do with anything,'' Urbach said.
</P>
<P>
   If the state, in reviewing a store's records, finds that it
failed to levy the tax, the shop is still liable for it. State
officials and shopkeepers say they cannot recall anyone being
penalized for collecting too much tax, so many store owners say
that when in doubt, they tax, rather than run afoul of the state,
an approach that can irk customers who catch on.
</P>
<P>
   On something as small as a candy bar, a store usually adjusts
the price so that, with tax, it becomes a round number, and the
shopper rarely notices the levy. But with higher-priced items, the
tax becomes more noticeable to the customer, and store owners say
they sometimes end up being peppered with questions about the bills
that they are ill-equipped to answer.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are a particular burden on the majority of stores in
New York that do less than $100,000 a year in business, said Mark
Alesse, state director of the National Federation of Independent
Business. Unlike larger stores that are equipped with computer
scanners that automatically apply the tax where appropriate, small
shops have to train cashiers to memorize the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're mom-and-pop operations,'' Alesse said. ``They don't
have staff to devote to tracking this stuff, and their employees
tend to be teen-agers working part time.''
</P>
<P>
   One such store is DiNapoli Deli, at Third and Marine Avenues in
the Bay Ridge section of Brooklyn. ``It's a dumb system, and it's
hard for us,'' said Louis DiNapoli, owner of the store. ``Listen to
this: I sell cold cuts _ salami, prosciutto _ there's no tax, but I
put them on a platter or a piece of bread, there's tax. And if I
sell a whole salami ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
