<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CLOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT SYNCHING FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, April 5, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We lost only an hour, but it feels like two. The first Monday
after the clocks spring forward is the real test of time; Sunday is
too relaxed to count.
</P>
<P>
   Clocks, external and internal, tick much more loudly at the
office. Coffee breaks, walks, trips to the check-cashing window,
meetings, and deadlines all have their designated slots in the
eight-hour shift, which has just shifted gears. The entire day
feels off center, beginning and ending too early and announcing a
high noon that's not quite high enough for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   People won't be in synch with the rhythm for a couple of days,
maybe not for a week, as they adjust to trading morning sleep for
evening light. It's a fair trade with excellent long-term benefits,
but the short term is a killer, especially for anyone who is into
power breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving work under a too-bright afternoon sky can make a person
feel guilty about ducking responsibility after months of exiting in
shadow or, more recently, in the glare of a setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   A restlessness sets in, too, for one feels one should be making
good use of the extra daylight hours Congress has given the
American people. But by the time one gets home and changed, there
isn't quite enough sun left for a long ballgame. The climate isn't
warm enough for planting, and the grass isn't ready for cutting.
</P>
<P>
   So a person stands on the porch, hands in pockets, watching the
dusk come on and listening to the peepers singing in the wetlands _
a fine, if passive, way to appreciate the gift of light.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from ``standard'' to ``daylight saving'' mirrors
a lot of passages in life _ looked forward to, celebrated, but
still not easy. Changing jobs, getting married, going to graduate
school, having children, and retiring all take people into
different time zones that promise growth for the price of the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities beckon now, despite the grimace at the alarm
clock and the extra coffee needed to see it clearly. Tomorrow will
be easier, and soon the game will go into extra innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
