<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-EMAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIN E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, April 5, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop the e-mail madness! In addition to destructive viruses,
e-mail has been the conduit for a troubling collection of chain
letters, petitions, and virus hoaxes. At the heart of the problem
are individuals who continue to circulate these documents.
</P>
<P>
   One example is a hoax and chain letter in one, the so-called
Disney Giveaway. A letter that appears to be from Bill Gates and
Walt Disney Jr. claims that Disney and Microsoft are experimenting
with an e-mail tracer program, and the companies need ``your
help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forward this,'' the e-mail says, ``to everyone you know, and
if it reaches 13,000 people, 1,300 of the people on the list will
receive $5,000, and the rest will receive a free trip for two to
Disney World for one week during the summer of 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   But Disney World says there's no experiment and no free
vacation. And there's no Walt Disney Jr. Walt Disney Sr. had only
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Stumping for a good cause, another e-mailed petition claimed to
be gathering support to defend National Public Radio and the Public
Broadcasting Service from funding cuts. This was a legitimate
effort in 1995 by students at the University of Northern Colorado.
But the students were reprimanded for misuse of university
resources. Still, the petition continued to be passed around _ and
dutifully signed _ for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Other chain letters warn about computer viruses. Some are true,
others false. Either way, the US Energy Department offers this
sound advice: Don't forward the warning to ``everyone you know,''
as messages may request. Even if a warning is real, it's best given
to security professionals such as the computer emergency response
team at Carnegie Mellon University.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department's computer incident advisory group and
others have Web sites tracking many of these messages. But the main
defense has to be people who refuse to forward nuisance e-mail
messages, scold friends for sending them, and loudly say: This is
too good to be true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
