<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST OF GUARDS SAID TO PROMPT GOTTI REQUEST TO RETURN TO JAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ John A. Gotti requested to return to jail
because the cost and intrusiveness of guards and other conditions
of his bail will no longer make sense once he begins spending much
of his days on trial here, his sister and a lawyer said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, who is to go on trial Tuesday on charges of racketeering
and extortion, stunned a federal courtroom Thursday when he asked
Judge Barrington D. Parker Jr. to return him to jail in nearby
Valhalla and end the arrangement in which he lives at home and pays
$5,000 a week for guards to patrol his property. His telephone
calls are also monitored. The judge granted the request, effective
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti spent nine months in jail until his lawyers were able to
negotiate his release in October on a $10 million bond secured by
the properties of two dozen relatives, friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, who federal prosecutors say has been the acting boss of
the Gambino crime family since his father, John J. Gotti, was given
a life sentence for murder in 1992, did not give the reasons for
his request.
</P>
<P>
   But his sister, Victoria Gotti, said that he felt it was
senseless to pay for guards to patrol his home in Oyster Bay 24
hours a day when he will soon spend much of his time at U.S.
District Court here, closer to the jail.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gotti, a novelist whose husband, Carmine Agnello, owns an
auto salvage business, has been paying much of the cost for the
guards, a point she said has wounded Gotti's pride.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer in the case, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said that although Gotti appreciated being home with his wife and
children and being able to meet with his lawyers in their Manhattan
offices, he has been dissatisfied with the conditions for his bail.
</P>
<P>
   He is barred from meeting with certain friends and relatives,
including Agnello, a suspected associate of the Gambino crime
family. And the monitoring of his phones makes his wife
uncomfortable about speaking with her friends, said the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more controlled by the government out than when he's
in,'' said the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, 35, is charged with leading a mob enterprise that, among
other crimes, extorted more than $1 million from the former owner
and employees of Scores, a Manhattan strip club. If convicted, he
faces up to 20 years in jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
