<HEADLINE>
WEATHER PLAYS COLD PRANK ON ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 and LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An April storm delivered surprises Friday to almost every part
of Arizona, burying newly sprouted spring flowers in Flagstaff
under 20 inches of snow and isolating a village northeast of
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   A photographer who flew in from England to take scenic photos of
sunny Arizona ran into a wind storm. He will have to come back
another week.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists arriving at Sky Harbor International Airport for an
Easter getaway in balmy Phoenix grumbled about the raw weather.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days into spring, the wintry storm swept the state,
dumping several feet of snow in some northern locations that had
barely seen a flake until now. The wind and rain dropped Valley
temperatures to 30 degrees below normal. The high in Phoe nix on
Friday reached only 59 degrees _ the first time the mercury had
failed to reach 60 on April 3.
</P>
<P>
   The effects were far-ranging.
</P>
<P>
   Some northern Arizona highways had to be shut down. Drivers
wrestled with chains weeks after they removed snow tires.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Flagstaff closed.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Valley, people searched for packed-away sweaters and
hats. Avondale and Carefree residents marveled at the snow that
temporarily graced their lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Flurries were reported at several locations in the Valley on
Friday. The Tradition Golf Tournament in north Scottsdale and the
Rattlers' Rally for the Arizona Rattlers arena football team were
canceled Friday because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   And snowbirds, in town for Easter weekend, found it colder in
the Valley of the Sun than in the places they'd tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The spring storm dumped more snow than some places had received
all winter.
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff's 20 inches was 69 percent of the winter's total of 29
inches.
</P>
<P>
   Weather watchers say a slow-moving low-pressure system, coupled
with a cold jet stream from the Gulf of Alaska, created the
surprising spring weather. And coming in the midst of La Nina,
which has brought warmer, drier conditions, many found it a shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual,'' said Sean McLaughlin, a meteorologist for
Channel 12 (KPNX). ``There's the whole psychological effect of
people saying, `Gosh, it's a late storm.' ''
</P>
<P>
   High temperatures in Phoenix at the beginning of April usually
hover around 80 degrees. Today's temperatures will be in the low
60s and remain the same for Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The first low-pressure system hit Thursday, dumping snow
throughout northern Arizona. McLaughlin said the jet stream, which
carried the system, normally would have carried the cold to the
Rockies. Instead, it parked over southern Utah, sending snow and
cold to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's damp came from another system that moved through. A
third system should show up Sunday, bringing more rain and snow,
McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nasty,'' said Tyree Wild, a meteorologist for the
National Weather Service in Flagstaff. ``Definitely not good for an
Easter egg hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   The snowstorm followed a windstorm earlier this week in which
gusts reaching 100 mph sent trucks tumbling and closed a stretch of
Interstate 40 for 11 hours.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, chains were required, even on vehicles with
four-wheel drive, in many parts of northern Arizona. The Beeline
Highway (Arizona 87) closed just north of Sunflower because of
snow.
</P>
<P>
   Photographer Chris Coe was looking for biking, hiking weather,
blue skies, sunshine and lots of wildflowers when he came from
England to do a promotional shoot for the Arizona Department of
Tourism. By the end of this week, he was wearing a sweat shirt
instead of sunscreen, but he did get desert shots with snow on
them.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to come back in October for the shots he didn't get,
said Leia James, marketing and communications director for the
Department of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The department also took calls from tourists asking when this
weather cycle was going to break.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go to a higher authority to get the answer to that
question,'' she told them. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Although this weather may have upset tourists, it also
challenged Valley residents who have guests in town, feeling the
guilt of having people come visit from cooler climates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's warmer in Iowa this week than here,'' said schoolteacher
Teri Lewis, who lives Iowa City. She was on spring break and
staying at a motel near South Mountain, where she and a friend had
hoped to hike and run every day.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the weather would be warm, she brought only one pair
of sweats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm freezing,'' she said Friday, on her way to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the prettiest snowy places in the state were impossible
to reach Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pleasant and picturesque, utterly tranquil up here _
like a scene out of a magazine,'' Don Underhill said of the
picture-postcard view from his Alpine Lodge, 8,000 feet up Mount
Lemmon near Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The only problems he and other residents of Summerhaven have is,
they're stranded and without power.
</P>
<P>
   Summerhaven has been snowed in for two days. The flakes began at
8 a.m. Thursday and haven't stopped. About 4 feet of snow has piled
up, Underhill said Friday by phone, and Summerhaven residents are
keeping warm by the lodge fireplace. They hope the road will be
opened today.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, officials at HomeBase Youth Services, which helps 35
or 40 kids under 21 who live on the street, say this cold weather
worsens an already difficult situation. The organization
distributes sleeping bags, which are no good to anyone when they
get wet.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Leach, executive director of HomeBase Youth Services,
worries that someone using the wet bags will get pneumonia or
bronchial infections, beginning another cycle of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone objected to the cold and rainy weather. Some people
enjoyed the cold and snowy weather, playing hooky from work or just
settling in by their fireplaces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maureen West can be reached at (602) 444-8167 or at
maureen.west(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Laura Trujillo can be reached at (602) 444-8891 or at
laura.trujillo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
