<HEADLINE>
CLIMBING BROOKLYN BRIDGE AS STUNT, MAN FALLS TO DEATH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 27-year-old man apparently hoping to gain a spot in
the Guinness Book of World Records fell to his death Friday morning
while scaling a steel suspension cable on the Brooklyn Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The climber, Robert C. Landeta, told a witness that he planned
to set a world record by climbing five bridges in four hours, said
a police spokesman, John Giammarino.
</P>
<P>
   However, Landeta did not get further than the Brooklyn Bridge,
his first of the morning, Giammarino said.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:17 a.m., after Landeta got halfway up one of the steel
cables, his hand apparently slipped and he plunged approximately
250 feet to his death.
</P>
<P>
   He landed on the Brooklyn side of the bridge, in an alley next
to the River Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old friend who was there to record the endeavor caught
the entire incident on videotape, said the police, who did not
release the boy's name.
</P>
<P>
   Landeta's ambition apparently exceeded his experience. He had no
published accomplishments as a daredevil, and it was unclear Friday
night whether his family knew of his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The Guinness Book of World Records contains no entry for bridge
climbing.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 edition lists only one feat related to bridges: Donald
H. Betty of Lancaster, Pa., has walked across 98 different
suspension bridges around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Since its construction in 1883, the Brooklyn Bridge has
attracted the daring and the desperate. In 1984, two men who
climbed one of the gothic stone towers for a thrill were arrested
and charged with misdemeanors after tying up bridge traffic for two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic again came to a halt on a morning in May 1993, when a
naked man shouting ``it's a beautiful day'' was struck and killed
by a car, just hours before a suicidal woman climbed the cables and
threatened to jump.
</P>
<P>
   Only employees of the city's Department of Transportation are
permitted to climb the bridge, an agency spokesman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Landeta lived at 31 Fleet Walk in Brooklyn. His immediate family
could not be reached for comment Friday. An uncle, Jose Landeta,
said that he knew little about the incident or his nephew's
climbing exploits.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, Landeta set out wearing a pair of black climbing
shoes, pants and jacket in a camouflage pattern and a small pair of
goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Before he began to climb, he told a photographer who happened to
be at the bridge that he was attempting to establish a world
record.
</P>
<P>
   He began at the bridge's road deck, 133 feet above the East
River. With a small crowd watching, he climbed more than 100 feet
before he slipped, and slid down the cable to his death.
</P>
<P>
   The police did not know whether he had been climbing one of two
wide cables, or one of the skinnier suspension cables.
</P>
<P>
   He landed to the side of the River Cafe, a few yards from a
warehouse for the Department of Citywide Administrative Services.
</P>
<P>
   Workers nearby said they had not seen him fall and only noticed
the commotion when the police arrived at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Ryan, a construction worker repairing the bridge's road
deck, said that he learned of Landeta's fall when he saw ``two kids
come running across'' the car lanes.
</P>
<P>
   A dizzying distance below them, Landeta lay on his back, dead
from the impact. His pants were in shreds, and his wallet, driver's
license, pager and keys were strewn in a nearby puddle.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the River Cafe, a back room manager for the restaurant,
Peter Demers, taped garbage bags and cardboard over a section of
chain-link fence so that the body would not be visible to lunchtime
patrons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
