<SLUG> BC-BOX-CORRUPTION-INVESTIGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREMAN SUBPOENAED TO TESTIFY IN CORRUPTION INVESTIGATION OF IBF
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former heavyweight champion George Foreman has been subpoenaed
to testify before a federal grand jury in New Jersey that is
investigating allegations of corruption by the IBF, said a lawyer
Foreman retained a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Lawrence Wechsler, based in Washington, said he had
not spoken to Foreman at length about the inquiry and did not know
what kind of information federal prosecutors were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Wechsler, who represented Betty Currie, President Clinton's
secretary, in the Monica Lewinsky inquiry, said he confirmed on
Monday with Jose Sierra, an assistant U.S. attorney in Newark, that
Foreman had been subpoenaed, but he did not know when Foreman would
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Wechsler told The Bergen Record that federal prosecutors view
Foreman as a victim of an extortion scheme run by the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Druwniak, a spokesman with the U.S. attorney's office in
Newark, refused to comment on the investigation or whether Foreman
had been subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lee, the IBF president, has denied any wrongdoing. Gerald
Krovatin, Lee's lawyer, told The Associated Press that the
investigation was groundless.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 15 years, people have been making allegations against Bob
Lee that have proven false and hollow and gone absolutely
nowhere,'' Krovatin said. ``I have no reason to believe that this
investigation will be any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman had a run-in with Lee in 1995 after his controversial
split decision over Axel Schulz. Foreman retained his IBF title
with the victory, but he refused to defend it in a rematch against
Schulz and Lee stripped him of the title.
</P>
<P>
   Lee elevated Francois Botha to the No. 1 contender spot ahead of
Evander Holyfield, Riddick Bowe, Michael Moorer and Ray Mercer.
Botha beat Schulz in a match for the vacant title, but Botha was
stripped of the title for testing positive for steroids after the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Moorer sued the IBF to get ranked as the No. 1 contender and
later won a split decision over Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's lawyer, said Holyfield had not been
subpoenaed to testify before the grand jury in Newark. ``We don't
know anything about any of this, and we'd be the last to know
anyway,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Lee said that the organization had
some problems with its ranking system and had recently overhauled
it so that the No. 1 and No. 2 contenders had to fight each other
before fighting for a title.
</P>
<P>
   However, the coming May bout between Felix Trinidad, the IBF
welterweight champion, against Vincent Petway, the No. 1 contender,
has raised some eyebrows in the boxing industry. Trinidad has been
ordered by the IBF to fight Petway or lose his title.
</P>
<P>
   Petway has fought twice in the last three years _ once in 1997
and once in 1999. Those two fights were against the same boxer _
Gerald Reed, who is 37 years old and has a 15-24-3 record. Reed
took Petway the distance in both fights. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
