<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SITTING OUT CHASE FOR ROGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers do not appear to be among
the prominent suitors for left-hander Kenny Rogers, whom the
Oakland Athletics could trade before Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin Friday acknowledged recent
conversations with A's general manager Billy Beane, but he declined
to discuss specifics or whether their dialogue continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to him, and they could move him before the season
starts,'' Melvin said. ``We haven't had any lengthy discussions,
though. We never got into specific names, but if you're going to
get someone's No. 1 starter before the season starts, you're
probably going to overpay for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not appear willing to entertain such a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I hear, everything is dead,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said. ``D-E-A-D. Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians and New York Mets appear to be the leading
candidates to acquire the 34-year-old Rogers, who went 16-8 with a
3.17 earned-run average for the A's during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had discussions, and I would anticipate having more
discussions,'' Beane told reporters earlier this week. ``From the
A's standpoint, if we do something, we want to make sure we find a
balance _ something that doesn't just address the future, but
allows us to address the present, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets reportedly offered right-handers Masato Yoshii, Jason
Isringhausen and Octavio Dotel for Rogers, while the Indians'
proposal included right-hander Dwight Gooden and first baseman
Richie Sexson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The asking price for Rogers is pretty steep for one year,''
Indians general manager John Hart said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who can become a free agent after this season, continues
to be slowed this spring by inflammation in his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some concerns with Kenny's elbow, too,'' Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers will miss his scheduled Opening Day start against the New
York Yankees, who instead will be opposed by right-hander Gil
Heredia. The A's plan for Rogers to pitch during a simulated game
Sunday and build his endurance to 80-85 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, though, has yet to pitch more than three innings or
throw more than 45 pitches during an appearance this spring.
Nevertheless, the A's expect Rogers to start Thursday against the
Seattle Mariners at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who pitched for the Rangers from 1989-95, reiterated his
desire to return to Texas earlier this spring. Rogers went 70-51
with a 3.88 ERA during his 376 appearances with the Rangers, and
that included his perfect game against the Anaheim Angels on July
28, 1994, at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin knows of Rogers' desire and that the Rangers will be
linked to every trade rumor involving the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will go on all year,'' Melvin said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
