<HEADLINE>
TIGHT HAMSTRING UPSETS MCLEMORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ |Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore did not
attempt to hide his frustration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, whose healthy knees served as the source of his
renewed enthusiasm this spring, removed himself from last night's
game after experiencing tightness in his left hamstring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McLemore departed the game immediately after his
over-the-shoulder catch of Derek Bell's popup in foul territory
down the right-field line for the third out of the first inning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through the entire spring without anything except a
broken fingernail, and then this happens,'' said McLemore, who has
under.MDBU/gone[ .MDNM/went.MDBU/].MDNM/ four knee surgeries since
May .MDBU/of .MDNM/1997. ``I don't want to sound like it's all
gloom and doom, but it's just frustrating.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two days remain before Opening Day, but the injury clouds
McLemore's availability. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll know more .MDBU/\R.MDNM/today.MDBU/\S.MDNM/,'' McLemore
said. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Rangers get third baseman &QL; 
[body]The Rangers yesterday gained depth at third base after being
awarded Toronto third baseman Tom Evans on a waiver claim for
$20,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evans, whom the Rangers do not expect to join the ballclub for
today's exhibition game with the New York Mets at The Ballpark in
Arlington, likely will begin this season at Triple-A Oklahoma. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lack a third baseman with significant major-league
experience in their minor-league system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not that deep at third base,'' general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``We don't have an experienced guy, and he's got
some.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evans, 24, hit .233.MDBU/[ .MDNM/(10-for-43).MDBU/].MDNM/ with
one run batted in during 26 games this spring with the Blue Jays.
Evans played only 12 games with the Blue Jays during .MDBU/the
.MDNM/1997.MDBU/ season.MDNM/ and another seven .MDBU/last year.[
.MDNM/during '98..MDBU/].MDNM/ The right-handed batter spent most
of 1998 with Triple-A Syracuse of the International League and hit
.300 with 15 home runs and 55 RBI .MDBU/in[
.MDNM/during.MDBU/].MDNM/ 109 games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evans once appeared to be the Blue Jays' third baseman.MDBU/
.MDNM/of.MDBU/ .MDNM/the.MDBU/ .MDNM/future, but shoulder injuries
stalled his progress. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had good reports on him,'' Melvin said. ``He's a young
third baseman who put up pretty good numbers at Triple-A last
year.'' &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Angels nab Levine &QL; 
[body]The move likely will not alter the balance of power in the
American League West, but the Anaheim Angels yesterday claimed
former Rangers right-hander Al Levine on unconditional release
waivers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Levine, whom the Rangers released Wednesday, must decide within
five days whether to accept the assignment or elect free agency.
Levine, 30, went 2-1 with one save and a 5.23 earned-run average
during seven appearances covering 10 1/3 innings this spring for
the Rangers. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Mateo set for scan &QL; 
[body]The Rangers scheduled outfielder Ruben Mateo to undergo a
bone scan for his right wrist this morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mateo experienced discomfort in the wrist during batting
practice yesterday and served only as a seventh-inning pinch-runner
for Rafael Palmeiro. Mateo suffered a bone bruise to the wrist
earlier this spring and underwent tests, which then proved
negative. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll check it out again to make sure there's nothing there,''
manager Johnny Oates said. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Briefly &QL; 
[body][s]The Rangers yesterday reached an agreement with
KDXT//106.7 FM, which will broadcast the 162-game schedule in
Spanish this season. KESS//1270 AM also will broadcast one game per
week in Spanish on either Saturday or Sunday. That schedule remains
to be determined. Luis Mayoral and Josue Perez will call the
action. &QL;
</P>
