<HEADLINE>
COLLINS CHOOSES `EVERYDAY' SHEETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels are excited for the 1999
season to begin, what with the expectations of a banner year ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most excited player is recently acquired utility
infielder Andy Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins confirmed that Sheets would be his
everyday shortstop until Gary DiSarcina returns in three to four
months from surgery on his left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be out there on a daily basis,'' Collins said
prior to Friday night's Freeway game against the Los Angeles
Dodgers. ``He can run and catch the ball and he has a great arm. If
he hits, that's a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels acquired Sheets from the San Diego Padres earlier
this week in a trade for catcher Phil Nevin. Sheets, a key bench
player for San Diego's World Series team a year ago, batted .242
with 31 runs, seven home runs and 29 RBI in 88 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about it,'' said Sheets, who spent part of
1997 with the Seattle Mariners, including a stint at third base for
the injured Russ Davis. ``I'm finally getting a chance to play
short and I just want to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets, 27, said he doesn't need to live up to DiSarcina's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to come in and fill his shoes,'' Sheets said.
``He's a big part of this team, so I'm just here to hold down short
until he gets back. ... But still, I don't think anyone's as
excited as me for the season to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Line drive: Left-hander Chuck Finley is still recovering from a
line drive he took on the left bicep in the team's final spring
game in Tempe, Ariz., on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Finley will not pitch today in the team's
exhibition game against the Aguascalientes Railroadmen, but could
see action against Cal State Fullerton on Sunday or possibly Monday
in a simulated game.
</P>
<P>
   Finley suffered a large bruise on his arm, but threw on the side
Friday with no ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he felt fine, but we'll just have to wait and see
because you don't know if it will swell up and not feel fine
tomorrow,'' Collins said. ``If we have to skip him on start it
won't kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds has MRI: Center fielder Jim Edmonds sat out Friday's
game, still trying to shake a groin injury and some back pain he
has been experiencing lately.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds underwent an MRI on his back and a number of other tests
Friday at UC Irvine Medical Center to help determine his course of
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' said Edmonds, who spent six
hours at UCI. ``I'm just trying to prepare myself for (opening
day). The back is more of a precautionary thing. It's not something
that's bothered me before.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquisition: The Angels claimed right-handed pitcher Al Levine
of the Texas Rangers off waivers Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Levine, 30, split the 1998 season between Arlington and Triple-A
Oklahoma City. With the Rangers, Levine was 0-1 with a 4.50 ERA in
30 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
