</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-DUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' HOPES DEALT A BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a grim showing for two star centers of the
Rangers Friday night in a critical game against Anaheim at Madison
Square Garden. Petr Nedved tried to play with injured ribs, skated
for about a minute in the first period, and sat the rest of the
night. Wayne Gretzky grimaced after an early hard hit from Kevin
Haller, then took four minutes in penalties for trying to spear
Haller.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mighty Ducks, it was a brilliant performance for two
star wings. Teemu Selanne, leading the National Hockey League in
goals, scored two more to raise his total to 45, improving his
candidacy for the first Maurice Richard Trophy. Paul Kariya, the
other dazzling forward on Anaheim's top line, scored one goal and
added an assist. His performance showed speed reminiscent of Yvon
Cournoyer, passes like Gretzky's in his prime and shots like those
of Guy Lafleur.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to a 4-1 Anaheim victory, which left the Rangers
7 points out of a playoff berth with seven games remaining, five on
the road. They have played one more game than the Boston Bruins,
who hold the eighth and final berth in the Eastern Conference. The
Rangers played listlessly, managing only 13 shots, just three in
the first period. They are 2-4-2 in their last eight games. They
were not good, but the two main Ducks were better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great,'' Ranger Coach John Muckler said, referring to
Kariya and Selanne. ``I haven't seen two guys skate that hard in a
long time. They could play 60 minutes. They make your team retreat.
They are worth the admission. We backed off. They caused
turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedved, battered by Philadelphia checks and sticks last
Saturday, injured his ribs on Monday during a 3-1 victory over the
Islanders. He missed practice and left the pre-game warm-up early
Friday night. Nedved tried to play with a pain-killing injection,
but could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most frustrating thing,'' Nedved said. ``One thing I
know is I'm in a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he had collided with Bryan Smolinski of the Islanders
and then doubled over in pain after a face-off a few minutes later.
When Nedved entered the building Friday afternoon, the stitched and
bruised skin around his right eye bore witness to another rough
game, the one before that, in Philadelphia, when he was cut by the
high stick of Eric Lindros, the Flyers' captain.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who passed Gordie Howe in career goals on Monday with
1,072, took a hard hit Friday night into the boards from Haller, a
defenseman who is known for baiting the best opponents. When
Rangers teammates formed a scrum around Haller in retaliation,
Gretzky circled the group and jabbed the blade end of his stick
toward Haller, without making contact with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of silly on my part,'' Gretzky said. ``I lost my cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers play their next four games on the road: Sunday at
the Devils, on Monday at Philadelphia, on Thursday at Chicago and
on Friday at Dallas. It is now very likely that they will miss the
post-season tournament for two consecutive years for the first time
in more than two decades. The Ducks, an improving and interesting
contender in the Western Conference, are 17-7-2 in their last 26
games. They will play their third game this week in the New York
area when they visit the Islanders Saturday night. At the same
time, Kariya's brother, Steve, will play for Maine against New
Hampshire in the championship game of the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had a 2-0 lead on goalie Mike Richter before the
Rangers had taken a shot against the Ducks' Guy Hebert. Scoring
first was Selanne, who took advantage of a Brian Leetch turnover to
race in and fire the puck past Richter at 2 minutes 28 seconds.
Travis Green made it 2-0 at 6:43 by finishing a three-on-one rush.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stevens, who played an aggressive game, got one back for
the Rangers at 10:07 with a long slap shot, the first shot of the
game for the Rangers, which caromed off the glove of Hebert. The
Ducks made it 3-1 on the power play at 10:09 of the second period
when Selanne, next to Richter's crease, punched the puck over the
line after Kariya darted to a rebound, whirled and fed him a
perfect pass. Kariya made it 4-1 at 16:41 by one-timing a slap shot
from the top of the left-wing circle while drifting backward and
taking a pass as the teams skated four to a side.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, from Finland, could be seen smiling on the bench when
the scoreboard screen showed fans from his homeland waving the
national flag, wearing horned hats and cheering from the high
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was laughing,'' Selanne said. ``I think they were pretty
drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks visit here but once a year, so it was a sobering
experience for Ranger fans and players like Leetch. But even rivals
rave about them. ``It's exciting,'' he said, when asked what it is
like to play against Selanne and Kariya. ``They are always moving.
Very creative and very talented. There is always something going on
every shift.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
