<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSAGE TO MELVIN: DEAL FOR PITCHING NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ I flipped the calendar ahead three months to
July and flashed it in front of Doug Melvin's face last night at
The Ballpark in Arlington. Sorry, Rangers fans, he didn't bite.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if we all show up at today's exhibition game wearing
shorts and tank tops _ admittedly not a good look for me _ we can
somehow convince the Rangers general manager it's actually the end
of July instead of the first week in April.
</P>
<P>
   Trade-deadline time, Doug. Time to make a deal for some
pitching. Time to save the Rangers, again.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't played a game that means squat yet, but they
already look like they need saving.
</P>
<P>
   Move the fences in, says Juan Gonzalez? With this pitching
staff? You've got to be kidding.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that left Florida with a team earned-run average
that could challenge the New York Stock Exchange. The four starters
Johnny Oates ``likes'' had a combined 5.54 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, cornered in the press box during last night's exhibition
game, wore the hunted and resigned look of a man who has exhausted
all avenues in a search for starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a pitcher had a decent spring,'' Melvin said, ``he's not
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means there must be a lot of Rangers pitchers on the
``available'' list.
</P>
<P>
   The initial thought today was to demand that Melvin pull the
trigger on a deal for Kenny Rogers. There's talk he'll be traded
this weekend, inflamed elbow and all. Cleveland wants him. So do
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   So do the Rangers, but apparently not at the price it would take
to make the deal sooner, rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do it now,'' Melvin said, ``you're going to overpay for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's not even talking about the $5 million a year the
payroll would have to absorb.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Oates would settle for just about anything. The
Knicks' player who hit Shaquille O'Neal in the back with a
basketball the other night _ is he available?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably my best team in eight-plus years of
managing,'' Oates said. ``We've got offensive balance, power,
speed. If there's a concern, it's the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not gimpy John Wetteland, mind you. Oates doesn't even want to
consider what it would mean if he couldn't pitch. It's what comes
before the ninth that worries him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good six-inning team,'' Oates said through his
rose-colored shades. ``The seventh and eighth innings will be so
important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone has to bridge the game from the sixth to the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those will be the key innings for us,'' Oates said. ``We're
probably not going to have a lot of complete games. A lot of our
games are going to be decided in the seventh and eighth innings.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not good.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, three relievers will be entrusted with the bulk
of the work in those two innings: left-hander Eric Gunderson and
right-handers Tim Crabtree and Danny Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree was terrific in September, but owns a 9.75 ERA this
spring and has not made his manager happy. Gunderson has a 1.64 ERA
for the spring but has a reputation for losing his effectiveness in
the second half of the season. The Rangers are waiting for
Patterson to recover the form he showed two seasons ago, before
elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consistency and resiliency is what we need to see,'' Oates
said. ``There's no Xavier Hernandez out there to help those guys
this year. They may have to pitch back-to-back days, and to do
that, they're going to have to keep their pitch counts down. We
can't afford good-game, bad-game either. They have to be more
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so forget getting a starter. How about merely a serviceable
reliever?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's anybody out there better than a guy
like Jeff Zimmerman \R15 innings, one walk this spring\S,'' Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then why, pray tell, is he in Oklahoma City?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching,'' Gonzalez said the other day before the Rangers
left Florida. ``We need pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Patterson, falling behind hitters, inherited a
3-3 tie with the Astros in the seventh inning last night and gave
up a run before striking out Richard Hidalgo and Mitch Meluskey
with the bases loaded to escape further trouble. It wasn't the
low-pitch-count inning Oates had hoped to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long season,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   And a long wait until July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
