</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-MARTINEZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ A HITTING MARVEL WITH NO SIGNS OF SLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ ``Edgar gave me great advice,'' Mariners
shortstop Alex Rodriguez was saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You know what, take full advantage of your youth
because age takes a toll on you. You don't want to ever be 35 years
old and saying, man, I could have stolen bases, I could have been
diving for balls.' He said, `Do it all when you're young, because
when you're older it's a lot more difficult.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That made a lot of sense to me. By having a great work ethic
when you're young, your body will be much better when you're older,
and it's hard to start something when you're 30 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard, but not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   As Edgar Martinez enters his 13th season in Seattle, he doesn't
like being reminded that he's 36 years old. He will let teammate
David Segui muss his hair and tease him about going gray _ even if
he's not _ but the M's dignified designated hitter won't concede
anything to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself old,'' Martinez said. ``I'm 36; that's
still young to play this game. It doesn't matter if you're 20, 25,
30 or 35, you can be in great shape. Age will affect you, but if
you're in great shape you can still play like you're young.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Martinez's youth was lost roaming the ranks of the
Mariners' minor leagues. He didn't become a big-league regular
until he was 27 years old, and a new study shows he could be the
best ``late bloomer'' of the last quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's ``Baseball Scoreboard,'' STATS Inc. studied every
player since 1950 who didn't receive regular playing time until
after turning 27. Maury Wills, Hal McRae and Minnie Minoso top the
career hits list among qualifying players, but Martinez already
ranks ninth. With two more quality seasons, he would jump to fourth
_ and first among players whose careers began in the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   It's something of a dubious honor, calling attention to years
spent toiling in oblivion. Those seasons don't necessarily give
Martinez greater appreciation for all he's accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some long years down there,'' he said, simply.
</P>
<P>
   But it does point out, and perhaps accentuate, what Martinez is
doing at an age when most are winding down. Last year was his
fourth consecutive season with an average above .320 and more than
25 homers, 100 runs batted in and 100 walks.
</P>
<P>
   When former Mariners catcher John Marzano joined the Rangers
this year, his new teammates bombarded him with questions about
Seattle's hitters. The first guy they asked about wasn't Rodriguez
or Ken Griffey Jr. It was Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the great hitters over there wanted to know about him,''
Marzano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great reputation around baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a professional hitter,'' said the Chicago White Sox's
Frank Thomas, the only active player with a better career on-base
percentage than Martinez's .424. ``He's been great for a long time,
very consistent, steady. He's got a level swing, knows his
strengths and weaknesses. He stays with his strengths and makes
adjustments, and that's hard to do at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's staying power has much to do with conditioning.
Mariners trainer Rick Griffin said Martinez is in better overall
shape this year than in the past two or three years, mostly because
he changed his workout routine. Instead of lifting heavy weights,
Martinez now lifts lighter weights with more repetitions, lending
greater flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said because Martinez doesn't play in the field, his
legs are saved from the pounding others experience. That's
important, because players last only as long as their legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legs go,'' said manager Lou Piniella. ``I played until I
was 40, and my thought process was better than it had ever been. I
just couldn't get to the ball anymore with consistency. It's your
legs that get you out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez thinks it's more mental than anything else. He would
like to play one or two more years, but without a contract past
this season, he's taking his future a year at a time. What is
important now, he says, is that he is still having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to look back and regret that you didn't enjoy
it,'' Martinez said. ``That's important; you don't want to say, `I
should have had more fun.' Sometimes I stressed out about the game
too much. When I made bad plays in the field, it really bothered me
for a while and it carried over into the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to be able to relax, forget about that game
and move on. I still (stress) sometimes, but I think it's less than
before _ a lot less than before. I guess if it gets to a point
where I don't enjoy the game as much, it's probably time to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel it. You just know. If you're coming to the ballpark
every day and you don't feel excited about the game, it might be
time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez's time comes, he hopes the jersey he hangs up is a
Mariner one. He would seem to have earned the right to play as long
as he wishes in Seattle, but he knows that might not be realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in baseball today, that's pretty difficult,'' Martinez
said. ``Anybody would be so thrilled to have that choice and so
appreciative of that choice, but that's really for very special
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Very special players? Martinez would seem to qualify.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
