<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL SITS, STEWS DOWN STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Shaquille O'Neal loved everything about Glen Rice's
game-winning 17-foot jumper on Friday. Everything except his
vantage point on the play.
</P>
<P>
   He watched the dramatic swish from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   And sitting out the crucial final seconds of a one-point game
didn't sit well with him.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis lifted O'Neal for Robert Horry to put a
smaller, swifter, defensive unit on the floor. On offense, Rambis
worried the Suns would try to send O'Neal to the foul line, where
he's shooting 54.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the strategy, it didn't make sense to O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know (anything),'' O'Neal said. The defensive strategy
``makes sense.... But nothing else really makes sense. But I guess
I don't know what the (heck) I'm doing, so I just go with the
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's second-leading scorer made this much clear: He wants
to be on the floor with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I do. I guess it shows what type of confidence people
have in me. But we won the game, so it don't matter,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis subbed out O'Neal in favor of Horry with 48.9 seconds
left and the Los Angeles Lakers up by three points. He sent O'Neal
back in with 37.8 seconds left, then pulled him again for the final
offensive play with 11.3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of, defensively, putting a unit out there
that we could switch everything. That's how I looked at it,''
Rambis said. ``I put a smaller unit out there ... and that ended up
being very good for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the offensive side ... we were worried about ... Shaq
getting the ball and (the Suns) fouling.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting O'Neal in the fourth quarter ended in a loss a week
earlier, against Sacramento. But this time, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great move, I guess,'' O'Neal said. ``It's cool, we
won the game. It's all about winning. Nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ousted: Rick Fox, who's had a hot shooting hand off the bench
lately, shot off his mouth instead Friday, and paid the price,
getting ejected in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was limited by two early fouls and had scored just three
points. With 18.5 seconds left in the third, he was called for an
illegal, out-of-bounds screen and his vociferous protest drew two
quick technical fouls, and an automatic ejection, from referee Ted
Bernhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute later, official Joey Crawford tossed the
Suns' Chris Morris for grousing, and coach Danny Ainge had to
restrain him from going after Crawford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
