u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     04-03 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, April 3.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ After nine days of hesitation,
NATO attacked the center of Yugoslavia's capital early Saturday
morning, destroying the headquarters of the security forces
carrying out President Slobodan Milosevic's offensive against the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Morini, Albania) _ With ethnic Albanian
refugees from Kosovo continuing to stream across the tiny mountain
border crossing here at the rate of more than 2,000 an hour,
officials said Friday that the week-old exodus is creating an
ominous humanitarian crisis. ``The situation is out of control. It
is catastrophic,'' the Albanian information minister, Musa Ulqini,
said Friday as the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
declared, ``a major humanitarian emergency in northern Albania.''
By John Kifner. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace, Macedonia) _ The flood of Kosovar
Albanians into Macedonia, an estimated 90,000 refugees since March
24, has completely overwhelmed the Macedonian authorities. Soldiers
were brought in to stem the flow along the railroad tracks, and
riot police armed with automatic weapons and wearing flak jackets
and helmets formed a barrier to block refugees from the main road.
By Carlotta Gall. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Senior Clinton administration
officials say the United States will have to consider accepting
some of the tens of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees who have
fled Kosovo in recent days, if only to encourage reluctant European
nations to do the same. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton said Friday that
despite the continued campaign of repression by Slobodan Milosevic
and the mass exodus of refugees from Kosovo, the military and
political objectives of the western allies were still attainable.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Berlin) _ The situation of NATO forces based in
Macedonia appears to illustrate the contradictions in the West's
military plans. The forces are in Macedonia to reinforce a Kosovo
peace plan seemingly overtaken by events. The mission of the
Western troops in Macedonia has already changed once, from an
``extraction force'' for the 1,500 officials of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe who were in Kosovo until the
bombing began, to a force to carry out any possible peace accord.
By Roger Cohen. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WEATHER (Washington) _ There has been fog and rain over
Yugoslavia for most of NATO's 10-day air campaign, but politicians
and their assessment of public sensitivities have grounded just as
many bombing runs as has the weather. By Eric Schmitt. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Credibility in military news
briefings is everything, and the lack of it in the early days of
the Vietnam war was one reason why the American public soured
against involvement. But instead of providing details on allied
bombing missions, spokesmen for the alliance here have been issuing
heated daily denunciations of the Yugoslav anti-Albanian campaign
in Kosovo, a campaign that the allied military command itself
acknowledges the bombing has so far been unable to stop. By Craig
R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-HUNGER (Beijing) _ The food scarcity engulfing North
Korea will intensify in the next two months because the government
rations on which a majority of the population depends are running
out, a senior U.N. aid official said Friday. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ALGERIA-JOURNALISTS (Algiers, Algeria) _ Omar Bellouchet's name
is not on the ballot for the presidential election on April 15, an
election that many of Algeria's voters see as a gateway to
democracy. But many Algerians consider him and others like him at
least as important to hopes of freedom as any of the presidential
candidates. Bellouchet, 46, is editor in chief of El Watan (The
Nation), the most spirited of a dozen independent newspapers that
have sprung up. He has been a champion of liberties that Algerians
have been denied by a repressive oligarchy of generals and
bureaucrats. By John F. Burns. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MELISSA-VIRUS (Trenton, N.J.) _ Federal and state authorities
arrested a central New Jersey man Thursday night and and charged
him with originating the e-mail virus known as Melissa. By David
Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-DEATH-PENALTY (Undated) _ The nation's Roman Catholic
bishops issued a statement against the death penalty, their first
in 19 years. It draws on Pope John Paul II's recent
anti-death-penalty statement in St. Louis. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   MACDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Two parts of the
wide-ranging investigation of President Clinton converged here
Friday, when a woman testified in behalf of a former business
partner of the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton. By Steve
Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   NH-SCHOOL-TAX (Undated) _ New Hampshire no longer seems such a
granite monolith of anti-tax sentiment. It is one of only two
states without an income or sales tax. But there are signs that the
``Live Free or Die'' sentiment that is emblazoned on New
Hampshire's license plates, and that has long influenced the
state's first-in-the-nation presidential primary, may be mellowing.
By Carey Goldberg. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (New York) _ U.S. policy toward the terrorism of
Slobodan Milosevic has been constrained in the past by our public's
wariness of military involvement abroad. But that
political-psychological calculus may have changed under the impact
of the Serbian atrocities in Kosovo. Most Americans do not want to
temporize with Milosevic. We want to finish the job. By Anthony
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The nation's jobless rate dropped in
March to its lowest level in 29 years, the Labor Department
reported Friday, falling from 4.4 percent in February to 4.2
percent in the latest of many signs that the labor market in the
United States remains remarkably robust. But in a break from the
feverish hiring of the last three years, American companies added
far fewer new workers to their payrolls last month than had been
typical lately. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-INDEPENDENTS (Undated) _ Independent oil companies account
for 40 percent of the oil produced in the United States. While they
have seen many downturns, the last year has hit them particularly
hard. Their problems make it unlikely that domestic production,
which hit a 50-year low last month, will recover soon. By Agis
Salpukas. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN-WALLENBERG (Stockholm, Sweden) _ Since the mid-19th
century, Swedish industry has been largely synonymous with the
Wallenberg family. The dynasty's tentacles reach everywhere, from
heavy trucks and mobile phones at home to board rooms in the United
States. But like Sweden itself, the Wallenberg business empire is
under siege these days. By Alan Cowell. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ A smaller-than-expected increase in nonfarm
payroll jobs last month set off the bond market's best rally in
four weeks on Friday. The bond market is normally closed on Good
Friday, but trading occurred until noon. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ These are truly boom times for the
nation's airlines: Their earnings are stronger than ever, and they
flew a record 611 million passengers last year without a single
fatality. They did so while maintaining their on-time performance
and without a significant increase in officially registered
complaints. So successful, and yet, by many accounts, they have
never been so unloved. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPEND (Shanghai, China) _ Worried about slowing export
growth, falling foreign investment and declining domestic demand,
Beijing spent nearly $200 billion on public construction projects
last year and plans to do the same this year. By Seth Faison. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CRONON-ENVIRON (Madison, Wis.) _ A profile of William Cronon,
whose ideas have made him a pivotal and provocative figure in the
growing field of environmental history. By Janny Scott. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-RELIGION (Undated) _ How religions other than
Christianity view the apocalypse and the end of time. By Dinitia
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHAUDHURI-INDIA (Undated) _ A talk with the Indian writer Amit
Chaudhuri, whose ``Freedom Song,'' a collection of three short
novels, was published last month. By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column: As Jim
Harrick and other coaches who are trading teams prove, the NCAA
tournament is as much an audition for coaches as it for players. By
William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BROWNS (Berea, Ohio) _ Feature on mini-camp practice for the
NFL expansion Cleveland Browns. For a city that mourned and raged
when Art Modell moved the original Browns in 1996 for a sweet
stadium deal in Baltimore, these evolving Browns will do quite
fine. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
