<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It sure didn't look much different than any
other year.
</P>
<P>
   If Friday night, indeed, marked the end of the Freeway Series,
the significance seemed to be lost on the fans as the Los Angeles
Dodgers knocked off the Anaheim Angels 8-1 in front of 28,405 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance was sparse, the crowd mostly subdued _ many left
early, as usual _ and the atmosphere was relatively tame for an
Angel-Dodgers game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because the annual series has lost some of its
luster since the teams now play one another during the regular
season in interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, there didn't seem to be many who were broken
up over the issue, although nothing has been finalized for possible
future exhibition meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The first inning of Friday's game at least appeared to have
plenty of fireworks. Eric Young singled off Angels right-hander Ken
Hill to open the game, moving to third on another single by Todd
Hundley, who finished 3 for 4 with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps trying to make a statement regarding his new catcher's
health, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson kept Hundley in the game into
the eighth inning. Hundley's longest catching stint during spring
training prior to Friday was five innings.
</P>
<P>
   After Hill struck out Gary Sheffield, Raul Mondesi singled off
the glove of third baseman Troy Glaus to score Young for the first
run.
</P>
<P>
   Hill then struck out former Angel Devon White for the second
out, but Eric Karros followed with his fourth homer of the spring,
a three-run blast to left for a 4-0 Dodgers lead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shaky start, Hill struck out the side when he
retired Todd Hollandsworth for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Hill actually settled down to pitch effectively over the final
three of his four innings of work, a trend the Angels hope he'll
continue into the season. Hill allowed only a hit, a walk and no
runs in that span.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Angels responded in the bottom of the first
inning _ albeit without the same firepower the Dodgers displayed _
and got a key contribution from an expected source.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, in his first Edison Field at-bat as an Angel, smacked
a 2-1 pitch from Ismael Valdes for a towering home run to center,
setting off a celebration scene the Angels hope is repeated with
frequency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who signed a six-year, $80-million deal with the Angels
in the offseason, had not hit a spring homer until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were a pretty good team the last two years,''
Angels manager Terry Collins said before the game, ``but you take
one of the best players in the game and put him in the middle of
our lineup and you get a whole lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer to Vaughn turned out to be one of the few blemishes
for Valdes, who has had a strong spring for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander pitched five innings Friday, allowing only two
hits and striking out four. Valdes, who was 3-0 with a 1.37 spring
ERA coming into the game, finished off his effort by retiring 13
consecutive Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored another run in the fifth and two more in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's flair single to left with the infield in brought home
Adrian Beltre, who had doubled, with the fifth run.
</P>
<P>
   A Hollandsworth tapper in front of the plate scored Tripp Cromer
in the eighth and a single by Grudzielanek brought in Trenidad
Hubbard to make it 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers left-hander Onan Masaoka struck out the side in the
eighth, working his way out of a bases-loaded jam to quell one of
the Angels' few threats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
