<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FREEWAY-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT ANGELS IN FREEWAY GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It sure didn't look much different than any
other year.
</P>
<P>
   If Friday night, indeed, marked the end of the Freeway Series as
we know it, the significance seemed to be lost as the Los Angeles
Dodgers knocked off the Anaheim Angels 8-1 in front of 28,405 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance was sparse, the crowd mostly subdued _ many left
early, as usual _ and the atmosphere was relatively tame for an
Angels-Dodgers game.
</P>
<P>
   Even Angels manager Terry Collins, who was irritated earlier
this spring when talking about the demise of the series, seemed
resigned to what might happen in the future _ although he'd prefer
things to be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a traditionalist like everyone else and I think tradition
in baseball is starting to fade,'' Collins said. ``Sure, we'd love
to play the Dodgers two more times, but I don't begrudge them
wanting to play the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for some reason this turns out to be the last game .. Maybe
the game at one time meant more, since we play during the season
now. Those games in June are the ones that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The first inning of Friday's game appeared to have plenty of
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros smacked a three-run homer off Angels right-hander
Ken Hill and Todd Hundley singled to help start the four-run rally
on his way to a 3-for-4 night with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps trying to make a statement regarding his new catcher's
health, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson kept Hundley in the game into
the eighth inning, his longest stint by three innings during what
has been a slow-starting spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a really good test, but we'll see how he is
tomorrow,'' Johnson said of Hundley. ``He passed it today with
flying colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who also had an RBI and scored two runs, was equally
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legs feel fresh and that was the main thing,'' Hundley
said. ``The elbow's been fine. It was just getting the legs in
shape. It's a `good tired' I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Angels responded in the bottom of the first
inning _ albeit without the same firepower the Dodgers displayed _
getting a key contribution from an expected source.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, in his first Edison Field at-bat as an Angel, smacked
a 2-1 pitch from Ismael Valdes for a towering 430-foot home run to
center, his first of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, it was high enough,'' Collins said, noting the recent
changes in field dimensions at Edison Field didn't matter on this
drive. ``When he's swinging like that, he can hit them out of any
part of any park.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's turned out to be one of the few blemishes for Valdes,
who has had a strong spring for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander pitched five innings Friday, allowing only two
hits and striking out four. Valdes, now 4-0 this spring allowing
only four earned runs in 242/3 innings, finished off his effort by
retiring 13 consecutive Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored another run in the fifth and two more in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's flair single to left with the infield in brought home
Adrian Beltre, who had doubled, with the fifth run.
</P>
<P>
   A Todd Hollandsworth tapper in front of the plate scored Tripp
Cromer in the eighth and a single by Mark Grudzielanek brought in
Trenidad Hubbard to make it 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger left-hander Onan Masaoka, the team's top rookie this
spring, struck out the side in the eighth, working his way out of a
bases-loaded jam to quell one of the Angels' few threats.
</P>
</TEXT>
