<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-BURBANK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED TO SELL SITE WHERE COMPANY WAS BORN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. -- Closing a book rich in this nation's military
history, Lockheed Martin Corp. said Friday that it has signed a
contract to sell a 103-acre manufacturing site in Burbank _ a major
hub in the home front World War II effort _ to a Los Angeles
developer.
</P>
<P>
   Terms with the Zelman Cos. were not announced but escrow should
close by year's end, said Gail Rymer, a spokeswoman at Bethesda,
Md.-based Lockheed's West Coast corporate office in Westlake
Village, Calif. The deal was concluded this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping it confidential and will let Zelman release it
when they are ready,'' Rymer said of the purchase price. Zelman's
offices were closed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank city officials have been working on development plans
for the property _ which borders the Golden State Freeway _ for
about eight years. Plans call for a $100 million office, retail and
hotel complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about it,'' Community Development Director Bob
Tague said of the sale. ``Zelman has a good reputation as a can-do
developer and hopefully we can get this project moving now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for a hotel on seven acres, car dealerships on 27
acres, a campus-style office park on 17 acres with the balance
devoted to big-box retailers, Tague said. Permits should be issued
this fall with the retail component open by November 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The site was the birthplace of Lockheed when the company was
formed in the 1920s. Employment there peaked at 100,000 workers
during World War II, when the facility known as Plant B-1 built the
famous twin-tailed P-38 fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed has spent several million dollars during the past eight
years on an environmental cleanup and that work continues.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed still owns a 32-acre site nearby that was most recently
the headquarters of Calstart, the advanced transportation
consortium. The company has about 5,200 people working at its Skunk
Works research facility in Palmdale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A previous deal to sell the property to Vestar Development Co.
of Phoenix collapsed when a December 1998 escrow deadline could not
be met. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
