<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS TORPEDO SUB-SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Sonics point guard Gary Payton, known for his
brash mouth and intimidating scowl, was actually somber and nearly
sedated.
</P>
<P>
   Just how far have the Sonics fallen?
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's 107-95 loss to the Portland Trail Blazers
at the Rose Garden, the Sonics' record hit a low that has not been
seen since the 1990-91 season _ the last time the team owned a
sub-.500 record after 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' third straight road loss dropped them to 15-16. They
who are 4-12 away from KeyArena after finishing a
five-game-in-six-nights road trip with a 1-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   The dire circumstances were enough to flush out Payton, who has
mostly avoided the media the past month.
</P>
<P>
   He is stunned, baffled and weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think I'm going to be 15-16,'' Payton said. ``It's
hard for me to take right now.''
</P>
<P>
   What is even more difficult is the Sonics' plight. On the
horizon is Sunday's game against the Houston Rockets, another
Western Conference power.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, is how the Sonics finish out the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, who are barely holding on to the No. 7 seed in the
Western Conference, have 19 games left to scrap for a playoff spot
_ something that has been alien to this organization for eight
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one could have predicted this at the beginning of the
year,'' Hawkins said. ``With our talent and experience, we think
we're one of the more talented teams in the Western Conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. The Sonics used to own the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Trail Blazers are staking claim.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, boasting the best record in the NBA at 25-6, by just
two points after three quarters. However, the Sonics could not
overcome a 13-point deficit with 2:25 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could the Sonics make up for 11 fourth-quarter turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what is was, 11?,'' said Sonics coach Paul Westphal,
who was visibly astonished. ``You're not going to win too many
games with that. ... I like the fight we've shown. But that has to
get us some wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Payton admits that it is tough to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about 11 of the team's 18 turnovers coming in the
final frame, Payton said: ``You see what kind of year we're having.
... I don't see a damn thing going right, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton's 27 points and 13 assists led the Sonics, who overcame a
nine-point second-quarter deficit and an 11-point deficit in the
third to stay with the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The team trailed just 50-44 at halftime. They were fortunate to
be that close, considering the Sonics shot just 39 percent and were
out-rebounded 29-19 in the first two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   What helped the Sonics was their aggressive start.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the trend of starting games sluggishly, the Sonics
matched Portland's intensity early. They ran with the young,
athletic Trail Blazers. The Sonics also banged the Trail Blazers,
who are big and deep at just about every position.
</P>
<P>
   Six points by rookie Vladimir Stepania helped the Sonics quickly
take an eight-point lead. He scored six of the team's first 12
points via open baseline jumpers. The Sonics took a 12-4 lead in
the first four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, though, quickly heated up and shot 58 percent in the
first quarter behind Isaiah Rider's 13 points. The Sonics trailed
26-23 after the period, and played from behind most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blazers were fresher than we were,'' Westphal said. ``But
give them credit. Their bench played a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider led the Trail Blazers with 23 points. Portland had seven
players score in double figures, and its reserves outscored the
Sonics' reserves 32-15.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are still struggling without a firm presence in the
paint. Vin Baker has missed the past eight games with a partially
torn ligament in his right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   The team is 3-5 so far without him. Perhaps the outcome of this
past week would have been different with Baker around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Payton said. ``That's 20 points over there.
That's an all-star. ... You see the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether his team's record was a true indication of
its season, Westphal said: ``That's what our record is. If we don't
want to be considered a .500 team, we've got to get some
victories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
