<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blues Over Blue Moons
</P>
<P>
   That howling heard last week was probably just the neighborhood
dogs sounding off at the full moon, the second in March _ and thus,
by common understanding, a blue one. Then again, it could have been
a reaction to the disclosure by the venerable astronomy magazine
Sky &AMP; Telescope that the common understanding of blue moons was
based on a misunderstanding, perpetrated by the magazine 53 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Sky &AMP; Telescope writer with an apparently hazy memory was at
fault, the magazine said. Writing in 1946, he recalled a reference
to blue moons from an edition of the Maine Farmers' Almanac from
the 1930s. But his recollection was incomplete. ``He heard the
phrase `13 full moons in a year' and made, I'd guess you'd call it,
an error,'' said Donald Olson, a Texas astronomer who researched
the mistake. ``He inferred incorrectly that there must be a month
with two, and that the second of the month was called the blue
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what the almanac's editors were thinking, Olson
determined. To them, a blue moon was an extra moon in a season,
which normally has three. If the writer had checked the almanac, he
would have quickly realized the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Moon lovers can rest easy, however. They may have lost one blue
moon in March (and another in January, which had made this year a
two-blue-moon special), but they gained one in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HENRY FOUNTAIN
</P>
<P>
   A Crowd-Pleasing Campaign
</P>
<P>
   New York City transit officials had a short-lived and, in the
end, ill-advised idea to make the trains run on time: Ordering
subway conductors not to use the word ``please'' in announcements
over the public-address system. As in, ``Please stand clear of the
closing doors.''
</P>
<P>
   But the officials dropped the idea in the face of protests from
riders. After all, even in New York there has been a trend toward
customer-friendly civility: Toll collectors have been ordered to
say, ``Thank you,'' and taxis blast cheery fasten-your-seat belt
reminders by celebrities like Sally Jessy Raphael and Paul Sorvino.
</P>
<P>
   As for the subways, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority
was trying to solve a system-wide problem arising from a boom in
ridership. No, not the problem of incomprehensible announcements.
(That remains a problem, though: The agency's own surveys indicate
that only 3 in 5 announcements come through loud and clear.) This
time, the issue was time: The MTA calculated that dropping the word
``please'' would save several seconds at each stop, or several
minutes on each run. Pressed to provide more service, the agency
saw shorter announcements as a way to clear the way for the next
train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every second counts,'' said Al O'Leary, a spokesman for the
transit agency. ``In some stations at some times of the day, it
would take longer to make the announcements than to get the
passengers on and off.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule-conscious agency does not want conductors turning
mundane announcements into Shakespeare (``To close, or not to
close, that is the question''). So conductors are being told to
stick to the script, please.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're taking away, stylistically, is the freedom
conductors had to become flowery and descriptive,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BARRON
</P>
<P>
   Dow Finishes Above 10,000 Before Getting a Hangover
</P>
<P>
   The trek of the Dow Jones industrial average has looked like an
assault on Everest lately _ a steady march toward the summit for
its select group of 30 stocks, leaving most of the others behind at
base camp.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of near misses, the Dow finally finished above the
magical _ but essentially meaningless _ 10,000 level on Monday. The
achievement brought cheers on Wall Street and the biggest headline
in The Wall Street Journal since the outbreak of the gulf war. But
the celebration was short-lived: The index fell back on Tuesday and
finished the week at 9832, only slightly above its level a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most stocks remain far below record levels. Nearly 9
out of 10 stocks traded on the New York Stock Exchange are more
than 10 percent below their record highs. And on the same day the
Dow peaked, twice as many Big Board stocks fell to new lows as hit
new highs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDWARD WYATT
</P>
<P>
   Pleas in Diallo Case
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of protests calling for their arrest and indictment,
the four New York City police officers whose 41 shots killed an
unarmed African immigrant Feb. 4 were suspended from duty and
arraigned on charges of second-degree murder and reckless
endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   All four officers _ Edward McMellon, Sean Carroll, Kenneth Boss
and Richard Murphy _ pleaded not guilty to the charges stemming
from the death of Amadou Diallo. Bronx District Attorney Robert
Johnson, demanded that the officers be put in custody, but the
judge set bail at $100,000 each, which the officers posted. Now the
real waiting begins: it could be a year or longer before a trial
starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ By AMY WALDMAN
</P>
<P>
   $81 Million Smoking Verdict
</P>
<P>
   In another legal setback for the tobacco industry, an Oregon
state jury awarded $81 million to the family of a man who smoked
Marlboro cigarettes for 40 years before his death.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a California state jury ordered the Philip Morris
Companies, the maker of Marlboro, to pay $51.5 million in another
case brought by a smoker. Both awards involved largely punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The release of damaging tobacco company documents in recent
years is cited by experts as one factor behind the verdicts. And
analysts predict more legal setbacks for producers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Prison for Baptist Leader
</P>
<P>
   The former president of the National Baptist Convention, the
nation's largest black religious organization, was sentenced to
five and a half years in prison for swindles that brought him more
than $4 million during his tenure. The Rev. Henry Lyons, 57, who
was also ordered to repay almost $2.5 million, was convicted in
February of selling bogus convention membership lists to companies
seeking to do business with the group's members.
</P>
<P>
   He was also convicted of stealing nearly $250,000 donated by a
Jewish organization to rebuild Southern black churches destroyed by
arson. Apologizing for that crime, Lyons told the judge, ``It
stinks in God's nostrils, and I know it stinks in the law's
nostrils, and it stinks in mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts on Bottled Water
</P>
<P>
   Americans spend about $4 billion a year on bottled water. Is it
worth it? Not from the standpoint of purity or healthfulness, says
the Natural Resources Defense Council, an environmental advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   The group tested about a thousand bottles of water, sampling
more than a hundred brands. While most of the water was fine, in
many bottles the tests detected traces of microbial or chemical
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no assurance that bottled water is any safer than tap
water,'' the council said in its report.
</P>
<P>
   The group is seeking tougher regulations and better labeling.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
