<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FISHER-ISLAND-ART     04-03 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FISHER-ISLAND-ART-$ADV04-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STRUGGLE IN PARADISE PITS RICH AGAINST RICH 
</HEADLINE>
 
(repeating to correct take numbering)   (For release Sunday, April 4)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FISHER ISLAND, Fla. _ When he sold Hebrew National, the family
cold-cuts business, for more than $100 million six years ago,
Isadore Pines did not imagine that he would spend his retirement
stirring up his neighbors on this idyllic redoubt a short ferry
ride south of Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Pines _ whose friends call him Skippy _ seems a most unlikely
rebel. He owns a $4.5 million apartment that overlooks the ocean,
and he has rickety legs that undermine his tennis game. But like
dozens of others here, he believes that plans by the developers who
recently bought much of Fisher Island to build 315 lavish
condominiums amid the royal palms and banyan trees can only
diminish the current residents' quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   And so Pines has become a captain in a war between the haves and
the haves that has raged for two years across this 216-acre island,
which Oprah Winfrey, Mel Brooks, retired corporate moguls and
various South American jet-setters call home _ at least during the
high season.
</P>
<P>
   An incident last month illustrates just how tense, and sometimes
comic, the conflict has become.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pines, he was nearly mowed down at dusk on March 11
by a golf cart driven by one of the island's developers. Pines
acknowledges that he was distributing fliers despite a warning from
security guards, but he contends that the developer, Daniel McLean,
veered away to avoid hitting him only at the last possible moment.
</P>
<P>
   Although McLean said that the near sideswipe was unintentional
and that he simply did not see Pines ``in the dark,'' Pines called
the police, his lawyer and his publicist.
</P>
<P>
   And a passer-by, seeing Pines talking with a Miami police
officer, used a cell phone to alert fellow rebels at a nearby
cocktail party. Twenty men jumped into their own golf carts and
converged on the scene. No riot ensued, but the incident moved
quickly from the gossip pages of the local newspapers into the lore
of the island.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute on Fisher Island, which has spawned at least a dozen
lawsuits, is not unlike those that touch off the kind of Florida
condominium wars caricatured in ``Seinfeld'' episodes _ or
Manhattan development battles like the current effort by
well-heeled East Side residents to stop Donald Trump from building
a residential tower near the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to think of a turf war involving as many captains
of industry, millionaire entrepreneurs and celebrities as the one
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fisher Island is a beautiful, glamorous development that's
captured a lot of people's attention,'' said Lewis Goodkin, a
longtime Miami real estate consultant. ``There's nothing more
difficult than a developer going into a community populated largely
by wealthy people, all of whom have influence that could work
against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher Island, which advertisements depict as ``unrivaled in
luxury, seclusion and grace,'' sits in the aquamarine waters of
Biscayne Bay, accessible only by private ferries that make the
seven-minute run from Miami Beach every quarter-hour. Security
guards check each visitor, insuring privacy. A narrow tree- and
shrub-lined road circles the island. In the center is a nine-hole
golf course; strung along the perimeter are red-roofed
condominiums, an exquisite clubhouse, a marina, six restaurants and
17 tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   McLean, a major Chicago developer, and his partner John Melk, a
Chicago financier, bought their chunk of the island for about $50
million last July after a lengthy, fractious and unsuccessful
attempt by the residents to buy it themselves. The two men acquired
33 unsold apartments, boat slips, unsold memberships in the Fisher
Island Club and 40 acres of land, with the right to add 637 new
units of housing to the island's existing 563.
</P>
<P>
   Melk, a bearish, gray-haired man, bought his own
5,800-square-foot apartment on the island in 1990, for $2.3
million. He said he was surprised by the opposition to last year's
development deal, especially since he planned to reduce the total
number of club memberships and build only 315 new units, just half
the number for which he had permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd be the white knight,'' said Melk, who together
with his friend H. Wayne Huizenga made a fortune from investments
in Waste Management Inc. and the Blockbuster video chain. ``We're
downsizing, so there should be cheers and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pines and others, including Murray Norkin, a retired
residential builder from New York, say that the new units, though
fewer than had been planned, would be larger, and that the total
amount of residential space on the island would jump by 70 percent.
That, they say, would overwhelm the island's services, causing long
lines at the restaurants and unconscionable delays at the ferry and
the golf club.
</P>
<P>
   The battle, fought largely among fewer than half the island's
residents _ those who spend more than several weeks a year here _
has grown mean-spirited. ``They're not held back by honesty or
ethics,'' Melk said of his opponents, who return the compliment in
their characterizations of him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekday, there was ample parking available and
little competition for tables at the island's six restaurants,
although everyone agrees the island is more crowded on the weekends
and virtually empty during the summer. Aside from tennis pro Pete
Sampras, who was warming up on Court 6 for the Lipton Championships
on Key Biscayne, the tennis courts were empty. There was a traffic
jam at the ferry, though, when activists on both sides of the
dispute headed to Miami for a public hearing on the development
project.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels concede that they bought their property on the island
knowing that plans called for the total number of apartments here
to reach as many as 1,200, although they now find that
unacceptable. Pines favors banning more growth altogether, but many
other residents say they would accept an additional 100 or even 200
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melk is not selling _ and we did not buy _ traffic fumes and
overcrowding,'' said Gerri LeBow, who has opposed the developers'
efforts along with her husband, maverick financier Bennett LeBow,
best known for his Brooke Group's break with other tobacco
companies when it turned over documents in the states' historic
anti-smoking lawsuits. The LeBows live year-round on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought privacy, beauty, and most of all, safety, which will
disappear with 315 more condominiums,'' Mrs. LeBow said. ``The
island has one road only to serve residents, visitors and staff of
all kinds, not to mention hotel guests and their guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Each side contends that it represents the majority view, and
each says that property values will plummet if the other prevails.
</P>
<P>
   `` Melk stands to make more than $100 million,'' Pines said.
``He expects us to watch the value of our apartments go down, our
expenses go up and our beautiful island be paved over with
concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   Monette Klein-O'Grady, a longtime resident who had been involved
in residents' negotiations to buy the island, now supports Melk.
She said that Pines, whom she labels an ``extremist,'' and the
others opposing the developers are part of a cabal that has
intimidated residents in a ``radical'' attempt to take control of
the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not come to terms with not owning the island,'' said
Ms. Klein-O'Grady, a real estate consultant, as she and the
developers' publicist sat on her apartment veranda, just 15 yards
from the ocean. ``They're making life miserable for the majority of
people on the island. Today we have a respected developer who has a
passion for the island. I believe we as a group should move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The competing factions have showered residents with enough
leaflets, position papers and open letters to constitute the
island's first snowfall. Sadly, some one-time friends no longer
talk to one another. And some people are unable to find golf or
tennis partners.
</P>
<P>
   In what many residents viewed as a referendum on the development
issue, David Bianchi, a Miami lawyer backed by the rebels, recently
won election as a director of the Fisher Island Club, which
oversees the golf club, restaurants and recreational facilities. He
received about 60 percent of the vote, defeating Ira Kaufman, the
former chairman of the Exchange National Bank in Chicago, who
supports the developers. The rebels also gathered more than 200
signatures on a petition demanding a moratorium on development and
submitted it to the Miami-Dade County Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hearing on the petition in Miami, on March 18, that
caused the traffic jam on the way to the ferry. In the hearing
room, the bitterness of the division was apparent. Knots of
residents turned their backs on one another.
</P>
<P>
   One side contended that a physician living on the island had
strong-armed a patient into signing a petition; the other countered
that a resident had switched sides because the developer promised
him a piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heartbreaking,'' said a visibly dismayed Sharon Gless,
who played Cagney in the television crime drama ``Cagney and
Lacey'' and is neutral in the development dispute. ``Friendships
have been severed, it seems like for life. All the affection people
had seems to be gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   The rhetorical salvos continued during the six-hour hearing.
``This is a block war, a unit-by-unit war by some people who don't
want to wait 15 minutes for a ferryboat,'' testified Clifford
Shulman, a lawyer for the developers. ``They've had this little
island paradise to themselves, and they want to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13-member commission rejected the moratorium. Pines said he
had not expected to win, though he took solace in the commission's
decision to conduct a traffic study and to examine whether island
development had violated covenants with Miami. The rebels vowed to
keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that the residents, with 450 employees to
maintain the amenities they share, lead a pampered existence. But
many residents feel that they have paid for the pampering. The
average cost of their apartments was about $1.8 million, and it
costs an additional $80,000 to join the island club. The owner of a
large apartment can also expect to pay about $130,000 a year in
club dues, taxes and condominium and community fees.
</P>
<P>
   Bianchi, like Melk and residents on the other side of the
barricade, becomes almost poetic in describing life on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the crown jewel of real estate, surrounded by turquoise
water, a stone's throw from South Beach, 15 minutes from an
international airport,'' he said. ``You can get up early, walk past
the royal palms when no one's around and see the macaws flying in
the trees. You're in paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1905 when the federal government sliced off the
southern tip of Miami Beach to make a shipping channel from Miami
to the Atlantic Ocean, Fisher Island has long been both a bauble
for the rich and a financial black hole for anyone who struggled to
develop its sandy, sun-drenched surface.
</P>
<P>
   The island got its name from Carl Fisher, the flamboyant
entrepreneur who converted an alligator-infested mangrove swamp
into Miami Beach. He bought the island in 1919 from Dana Dorsey, a
prominent black businessman in Miami who had given up on an effort
to build a resort for blacks who were barred from Miami's beaches.
Fisher spent nearly $5 million developing plans for a seaport and
squabbling with the City of Miami before he swapped the island in
1927 for a 250-foot yacht owned by William K. Vanderbilt II, the
railroad heir.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt built an estate on the island with marble fireplaces,
oak and mahogany paneling, servants' quarters, swimming pools and a
nine-hole golf course.
</P>
<P>
   After he died in 1944, Fisher Island passed through the hands of
several other millionaires before a development group that included
Charles (Bebe) Rebozo and his friend Richard M. Nixon bought it in
1963. The group wanted to build 5,000 apartments and a 1,200-room
hotel but got bogged down in a zoning battle with the city, which
wanted the island for a public park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Mutual Benefit Life Insurance Co., based in Newark,
N.J., bought the island and formed a partnership with William
Rebozo, Charles' nephew, to develop a more modest 1,200
condominiums for the upper middle class. Expenses mounted while
nothing was built, and Mutual Benefit ousted Rebozo in 1985 and
redesigned the plans for a wealthier market. By 1993, two years
after Mutual Benefit had fallen into receivership, the insurance
company had poured $317 million into building apartments, a health
spa, tennis courts, restaurants and a new golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rave reviews for the development, 225 of 563
condominiums remained unsold. It would take another six years to
sell them.
</P>
<P>
   The current battle for Fisher Island began in 1997, when Mutual
Benefit announced that it would sell the development as a prelude
to the sale of the insurance company itself, which was completed
early this year. Various groups on the island formed a negotiating
team to buy the island for the residents, but just as a $10 million
deal was taking shape in December 1997, the unity of the residents
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Klein-O'Grady, who had appointed some members of the
negotiating team, sent a letter to the chairman of the insurance
company, Alan Bowers, stating that his representatives were meeting
with ``a narrow group of residents'' and urging him to meet instead
with a ``responsible developer.'' Many of the activists on both
sides blame her for the failure of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Klein-O'Grady said she disagreed with the terms, fearing
that they would drive up the average resident's costs by $30,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits flew between the residents and the insurance company
and among residents themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Benefit, which was suffering $6 million to $10 million a
year in operating losses, then turned to Boca Developers, a
residential developer in Florida. But Boca, too, failed to conclude
a deal, and it filed yet another lawsuit, this one contending that
14 island residents had scared off lenders.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Pines, who had not yet been involved in the
disputes, joined with others in another unsuccessful effort to buy
the island for the residents. The group included Richard Voell, the
former president of the Rockefeller Group, a private real estate,
entertainment and telecommunications company, and David Paresky,
who had sold his company, Thomas Cook Travel, to American Express
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Melk said, he and McLean received a call from a
real estate broker asking them to consider bidding for Fisher
Island. In a matter of weeks, the developers signed a deal with the
desperate insurance company. However, Melk, like the residents'
team and Boca Developers, had been bound by a confidentiality
agreement that prevented him from talking about the deal during
negotiations, a condition that bred distrust among residents.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was any common ground with the developer, Ms.
LeBow gave an answer born of the boardroom. ``All of life is a
negotiation,'' she said, suggesting that there was room to talk
about the number of new apartments that the rebels could accept.
``It's time to sit around the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean, however, does not sound like someone ready to make
peace. ``They can harass us to death,'' he said, ``but there's no
way they can prevent us from building.''
</P>
<P>
   The developer may not have taken the full measure of Pines. He
spent decades, he said, worrying about someone finding a piece of
glass in one of his Hebrew National kosher hot dogs; after all, his
company described itself as answering ``to a higher authority.''
But after selling the company to Conagra in 1993, he looked forward
to a stress-free life.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has become a man with a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so not my life style,'' Pines said, sounding a bit
sheepish as he explained the tactics of his protest, including his
new habit of parking his Lexus, with a rear-window sign emblazoned
``Stop the Destruction of Fisher Island,'' in front of the island's
sales office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loner,'' he said. ``But I've spoken to more people in
the last year than in my lifetime. I'm at a stage in life where I
don't want to be taken advantage of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
