<HEADLINE>
THERE'S HUGE PAYROLL DISPARITY AMONG TEAMS, BUT SOME PLAYERS LIKE
IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball people have probably spent more time this winter
talking about the growing disparity in team payrolls than they have
about this year's top rookies or even Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Officials, owners, general managers and other club executives
all lament the disparity and predict doom and gloom for those teams
_ more than half the clubs in the majors _ whose payrolls will be
under $50 million this year. The first ball has not been thrown out
for Sunday night's season-opening game in Monterrey, Mexico, and
already 16 of the 30 teams, if not more, they say, have no chance
to contend for the playoffs six months from now.
</P>
<P>
   Payroll disparity is No. 1 on management's list of problems.
Commissioner Bud Selig, in fact, has named a blue-ribbon panel to
try to find a solution to the problem that has the Yankees opening
the season with an $85 million payroll and the Montreal Expos
paying about one-fifth of that.
</P>
<P>
   Players are not represented on the panel; officials have not
asked them what they think. On a recent HBO ``Real Sports'' segment
dealing with the disparity, Texas Rangers owner Tom Hicks had this
to say of the union's opposition to a salary cap: ``If 85 or 90
percent of their constituents are unhappy because they don't have a
chance to win on the day the season opens, the union's going to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere near that percentage of players, however, is unhappy
with their contending status. Some are, to be sure. But a growing
number has reason to like the disparity because it has created jobs
for them. That view became evident this spring during interviews
with dozens of players and managers on teams that are the have-nots
or the haves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have a team in that predicament, they're
going to have a lot of young guys who are glad to have a chance of
playing,'' said Kevin Brown, whose $105 million contract with the
Los Angeles Dodgers magnified the disparity. ``They're getting a
chance to get their foot in the door and start their big league
careers. It's hard to damn that situation. It's produced a lot of
good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, players even on low-paid teams refuse to begin a
season feeling beaten. ``If you're a major leaguer, you shouldn't
be coming into a clubhouse at the beginning of the season saying
you don't have a chance,'' Dustin Hermanson of Montreal said. ``If
you do, you shouldn't be in the major leagues. I believe in
Cinderella stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players do see the problem that management officials and
fans see. ``The disparity is definitely ridiculous,'' Ed Sprague,
Pittsburgh's veteran third baseman, said. ``The number of teams
with a legitimate shot every year is shrinking. Something needs to
be done. I think players are starting to realize that. I don't
think the playing field should be totally equal. But I think the
disparity needs to shrink a little bit. I don't think you can have
a team with a $90 million payroll and one with a $10 million
payroll. That's not a healthy industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The players who expressed Sprague's view, though, generally also
said they felt the owners were the ones who should devise a
solution. And while they were at it, they said the owners shouldn't
bother proposing any kind of a payroll cap. The last such
suggestion led to a labor dispute that nearly killed the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the winterlong anguish over disparity, though, no one had
considered the benefits some of the players and managers discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Maddux, a veteran relief pitcher with the Expos, who have
the major leagues' lowest payroll, has seen first-hand the point
Brown made. His teammates, Maddux said, don't feel deprived of a
chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a factor for anyone here,'' he said one
day in Jupiter, Fla. ``You have young guys trying to establish
themselves. They get their time in. In the past Montreal has been a
feeder for other clubs. A lot of guys see that here and use it as
an apprenticeship.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly and Tony Muser, managers of two economically
challenged teams, use the system as motivation for their young
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players what an avenue that has opened up for
you,'' said Kelly, who has 10 rookies among his 25 Minnesota
players. ``It's a wonderful avenue to drive down. They're not
stupid. They see a chance here to play in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Walker, the Twins' second baseman, is good enough that he
would have won a job in the majors under any system, but he
acknowledged the break young players get with teams like the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as players consider it a blessing just to be in the big
leagues and have an opportunity to play,'' the third-year player
said. ``You'd like to make the playoffs and win some championship
games, but we don't count ourselves out based on economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Muser, the Kansas City manager, said he has told his players,
young and older, to take advantage of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got guys in here who have a chance to be major league
players who wouldn't have a chance somewhere else,'' he said. ``We
have guys like Rey Sanchez and Joe Randa who have a chance to be
everyday players that were said to be platoon-type players, and
maybe they are. But here they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff King has experienced downsizing in Pittsburgh and Kansas
City, making him an expert on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some young guys on this team who are going to turn
out to be very good players,'' King, the Royals' first baseman,
said. But he added a caveat that has been demonstrated vividly in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going to be a matter of time before they won't be
able to keep those guys,'' he said. ``That's why nothing is going
to change. When I was just coming up, teams were holding on to
these guys until they were free agents. Now after three or four
years guys are making so much money that they probably won't be
able to hold onto them. That's something somebody's going to have
to think about and maybe try to fix.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although opening-day payrolls won't be set until teams name
their 25-man rosters and players who open on the disabled list, it
is a given that half a dozen teams will have payrolls beyond or
just under $70 million. They and another six or eight with payrolls
exceeding $50 million are considered the only teams with a chance
for the playoffs. The other, lower-paid teams are fodder for the
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the disparity in the payrolls is obviously
creating a bad situation for a lot of teams,'' Mike Mordecai of
Montreal said. ``Looking at it from the fans' standpoint, why would
they want to waste their money and go see a team that isn't going
to finish in the top four in the division?''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, players said that owners have to create a
more level playing field by sharing more of their revenue and
requiring that clubs that receive money under the revenue-sharing
plan use it for their payrolls. The Expos received $13 million
under baseball's partially implemented welfare plan last year but
had only an $8.3 million payroll. They acknowledge that they made
money.
</P>
<P>
   Players also said that if particular owners can't afford to
compete, they should sell their teams, and if particular cities
can't support teams, the teams should move. Tim Belcher, a veteran
starter now with Anaheim after having spent the past three seasons
in Kansas City, suggested that baseball created a problem by
overexpanding.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Players Association should do anything to deal with
the problem, Mordecai said, ``Listen to what the owners have to
offer at the next bargaining session.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Montgomery of Kansas City, who has been active in union
affairs, said the union should ``take the pulse of the players to
see how guys feel over all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the responsibility of our association,'' the veteran
closer added, ``to decide what's best, not just for the players but
for baseball. Players are only going to prosper if baseball
prospers and that's what worries me about baseball. I don't know
how much longer it's going to go on like this before there's a
problem that's beyond repair.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone of the Yankees, the union's most articulate spokesman
among its members, acknowledged some frustration among players on
have-not teams. But he cautioned both sides to await further
results of the plans in place and the opening of the half-dozen
stadiums under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get all the data in and re-evaluate,'' Cone said.
``Everybody says we need a more level playing field. Everybody
seems to agree, but how do you get that? How much does the luxury
tax help? How much revenue-sharing is really needed? How much will
all these new stadiums help solve some of these problems? They
aren't the end-all answer to the problems, but you have to start
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he talk to players on other teams about the situation?
``Sure I do,'' Cone said. ``A lot of them want to get traded to
contenders.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
