<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SEASON-ONETIMERS-     04-03 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SEASON-ONETIMERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY BALL! A NEW SEASON FOR HEROES AND ONE-GAME WONDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID MARGOLICK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 50 years after the ball was hit, Joe Cleary can still
see the bad hop. Coming in for the Washington Senators in his first
major league game, with two runners on base and one out, Cleary got
the first Boston batter to hit what looked like a perfect
double-play ball. Instead, it skipped into the outfield. Then the
roof fell in.
</P>
<P>
   Eight more batters came to the plate that day in August 1945,
and Cleary got only one of them out: the pitcher. The Red Sox
scored 12 runs, leaving him with an earned run average of 189.00 _
still the highest calculable ERA in the history of baseball. When
he returned to the dugout, he and his manager nearly came to blows.
And ``the short, unhappy life of Joe Cleary in the big leagues,''
as Cleary himself now calls it, was over.
</P>
<P>
   The major league season starts Sunday and, as is always the
case, dozens of rookies will see stardom looming before them. But
for all their promise, at least a few of them will become answers
to a trivia question, appearing but once. Then something _ injuries
or fate or their own abilities _ will keep them from ever coming
back.
</P>
<P>
   Countless ballplayers have come up to the major leagues for the
proverbial cup of coffee, but only a few hundred have tasted the
demitasse of a single game _ often at the end of blowouts or in the
waning days of a losing season. Most were standouts at every
previous level of play. In the more democratic ranks of the minor
leagues or spring training camps, all rubbed shoulders with
baseball's immortals: names like Satchel Paige, Duke Snider, Bobby
Thomson and Ted Williams fill their reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   Some bask in those memories. For others, their short careers
still gnaw at or embarrass them. Most have replayed their cameo
appearances a thousand times, and can recall the minutest details.
And they still hear from fans. When Earl Huckleberry died a few
weeks ago at the age of 88, 65 years after starting a game for
Connie Mack, he left behind a pile of autograph requests at the
Bowlegs, Okla., post office.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Shepard, a returning veteran who had lost the bottom of his
leg when shot down over Germany, came in to relieve Joe Cleary that
day in 1945. Though he pitched well _ giving up one run on three
hits over the rest of the game _ he, too, never played in the major
leagues again. Shepard suspects it was partly a matter of sympathy.
``Nobody wanted to see me go in and get clobbered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Van Dusen, an 18-year-old fresh from Bryant High School in
New York City, got his turn 10 years later, with two outs in the
bottom of the ninth against the Milwaukee Braves. His team, the
Philadelphia Phillies, was getting trounced and had run out of
pinch-hitters, even sending up a pitcher, Robin Roberts, before Van
Dusen. He finally got his chance _ and was hit by a pitch. He never
batted again. ``Well, they didn't get me out,'' said Van Dusen, an
insurance broker in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   In the ranks of these one-game wonders can be found baseball's
rarest commodity: perfection. There are numerous hitters who batted
1.000 and pitchers who never allowed a base runner. More common are
pitchers with astronomical _ or even incalculable _ ERA's and
batters with a long string of goose eggs. And numerous oddities
fall somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Like Archibald (Moonlight) Graham, the New York Giants
outfielder immortalized in ``Field of Dreams,'' Frank Verdi of the
Yankees played an inning in the field but never got to bat; Casey
Stengel sent him up to pinch hit, only to change his mind when the
Red Sox changed pitchers. John Corriden of the 1946 Brooklyn
Dodgers pinch ran and scored, but also never got to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Harley Hisner of the Red Sox struck out Mickey
Mantle twice and gave up Joe DiMaggio's last regular-season hit. He
also batted 1 for 2, ending up with a career average higher than
either of them. ``That ought to be worth $2 million now,'' said
Hisner, a retired machinist in Monroeville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1981 season, John Lickert came in to catch for
the Red Sox in the seventh inning. But the closest he got to the
batter's box (apart from crouching behind home plate) was the
on-deck circle. So upset was Lickert's father that he confronted
the Red Sox manager, Ralph Houk, in the locker room. ``I'm probably
the only guy who has 17 zeroes in the record book,'' said Lickert,
who lives in Rhode Island and delivers cars for Subaru.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the fraternity of these footnoters, there are
legends. Playing for a team cobbled together when the real Detroit
Tigers went on strike in 1912, a seminarian named Aloysius Travers
pitched a complete game, and gave up 26 hits.
</P>
<P>
   After yielding four hits to the first five batters in his debut
in 1918, a Brooklyn rookie named Harry Heitman stalked off the
mound, enlisted in the Navy and never played again. Another famous
Dodger, Walter Alston, struck out in his only at-bat for the St.
Louis Cardinals (and made an error in the field). Then there was
Eddie Gaedel, the midget who walked in his only plate appearance,
for the St. Louis Browns, in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four players Mike Palagyi of the Washington Senators
faced in one game in 1939, three were future members of the Hall of
Fame: Ted Williams and Joe Cronin, both of whom he walked, and
Jimmy Foxx, whom he hit with a pitch. ``I threw but 2 strikes out
of 15 pitches _ a very short big league career,'' Palagyi told
Richard Tellis, author of ``Once Around the Bases'' (Triumph Books,
1998), which chronicles the stories of 40 players who lasted a
single game.
</P>
<P>
   There is John Paciorek, the only player ever to get three hits
in three at-bats. And while Robin is the Yount being inducted into
the Hall of Fame this year, his older brother, Larry, has his own
superlative: perhaps the shortest major league career ever. Yount
made the box score but never threw a pitch, opting while warming up
on the mound to save his sore arm for another day, a day that never
came. ``I never thought in my wildest dreams that it would be the
end of my career,'' Yount now says.
</P>
<P>
   In a game based more on money, in which every prospect is an
investment, expansion has made manpower more precious and
serendipity and whimsy have largely vanished, the frequency of
one-game wonders has dwindled. So too, then, has the likelihood
that certain elusive milestones will ever be achieved. While two
players (pitchers, at that) have tripled in their only plate
appearances, no one has ever homered. And perhaps no one ever will.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Davidson pitched an inning for the Yankees in 1989, enough
time to give up a two-run homer to George Brett. ``Sometimes I
think about it, it almost feels like a dream,'' he said of his
brief big league career. Davidson, who became a chimney sweeper and
now works in computers in Cincinnati, has never been back to the
Bronx; he said he can't afford the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the lost child, the prodigal son, except I don't
feel there's a way to return,'' Davidson said. ``Every spring
there's a feeling that you're not where you're supposed to be. I
don't know if that will ever leave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Roe Skidmore had been riding the bench for the Chicago
Cubs for weeks when, in September 1970, Leo Durocher sent him up to
pinch hit. He hit the second pitch from Jerry Reuss over the head
of Joe Torre, then the Cardinals' third baseman, for a single.
</P>
<P>
   The ball was then retrieved _ the ball which still sits on his
mantelpiece, the one on which his wife wrote ``1st Big League
hit,'' not knowing she could have written ``last'' or ``only'' too.
Why? He thinks Durocher had it right about nice guys finishing
last. ``I didn't whine,'' said Skidmore, now a businessman in
Decatur, Ill. Every spring training, he said, a certain hollow
feeling grabs his gut. ``I'll go two or three weeks where I don't
even want to pick up the paper,'' he said. ``I just kind of ignore
the fact that it's starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore is one of at least 60 players to go 1 for 1. Only two
went 2 for 2, and only 18-year-old John Paciorek, brother of two
other major leaguers, went 3 for 3, singling three times and
walking twice for the ninth-place Houston Colt .45's against the
last-place Mets in the final game of the 1963 season. ``Every time
I came up the ball looked like a watermelon,'' said Paciorek, now a
physical education teacher and coach at a private school in
California. But a bad back did him in.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme was Joe Campbell of the 1967 Cubs, one of
only a few players to strike out all three times he batted. (True,
George Goetz fanned all four times he got up in 1889, but he was a
pitcher.) ``I was just too anxious, not that anyone's stuff was all
that great,'' said Campbell, who runs a Chevrolet dealership in
Lexington, Ky. ``I hit four or five balls out of the park foul. I
was getting good wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Bruckbauer, the first native Minnesotan to play for the
Minnesota Twins, seemed to spend more of his career at the Mayo
Clinic, nursing a bad arm, than on any team. He faced four batters
in 1961; three got hits on bloopers and scratch singles, he insists
_ and one walked. ``We'll get 'em next time,'' the Twins' manager,
Cookie Lavagetto, told him before giving him the hook. But there
was no next time, leaving Bruckbauer with an ignominious career ERA
of infinity.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dusen, who had hit a grand slam in a high school
championship game at Ebbets Field only a few weeks before his major
league debut, can still recall what Humberto Robinson threw him.
There was a strike down the middle (``That was the one I should
have swung at''), then a check swing, then a ball. Then came the
breaking pitch that nicked him on the knee. He didn't feel it. It
was his first game, he said, and he was already numb.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter Van Dusen was in the minors, where he partied
hard __ ``a million-dollar body with a nickel head'' is how he
described himself _ and quickly went ``from being a prospect to a
suspect.'' Soon he was through, and 20 years went by before he
could live with baseball again. ``Sometimes I go to sleep thinking
about hitting a hanging curve, even to this day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 80-year-old Cleary, the last major leaguer born in
Ireland, who watched Babe Ruth at Yankee Stadium and regularly
sneaked into the Polo Grounds (``it was a sieve''), he has not been
to a game since 1954, though he lives in the Bronx. Then again, his
memories are more painful.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary had played years of semipro ball _ ``You've got a great
arm there, Kid, but you throw too many curveballs,'' Grover
Cleveland Alexander once told him _ and fought overseas before his
inning of infamy. Nothing fazed him. ``I always said, I get that
ball in my hand, I'm the boss, what can they do to hurt me?'' he
recalled. ``I never had butterflies. I could hardly wait to get on
the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   But then came the bad hop, some wildness, some bad breaks; the
payoff pitch to Dolph Camilli, Cleary insists, could just as easily
have been called a strike. Not deigning to come to the mound, the
Washington manager, Ossie Bluege, disgustedly waved for Cleary to
come in to the dugout. ``It was like he'd just found me in bed with
his wife,'' Cleary recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cleary waited for the manager to do the right thing: to
come and get him. ``Son, I think you better leave now,'' the umpire
eventually told him. But only when Bert Shepard reached the mound _
``Anyone can have a bad day, but imagine being replaced by a guy
with one leg!'' Cleary lamented _ did he walk toward the dugout.
``I took 30-mile hikes in the Army that weren't as long,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bluege greeted him with an obscenity which suggested that he was
never much of a pitcher to begin with. Cleary replied in kind, and
only his teammates prevented a fist fight. The next day he was
shipped to the minors, and he never came back.
</P>
<P>
   Dominican immigrants have brought a passion for baseball back to
Cleary's neighborhood. On the street, at the bar, in the liquor
store where he now picks up his mail _ it gets stolen when left in
his apartment building _ he is a minor celebrity, who still gets
ribbed about his baseball career and his bloated earned run
average. But he can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only answer I give them is, `Hey, I was there,' '' he
said. ``Only 14,000 guys have made it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
