<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SEASON-PIAZZA-2TA     04-03 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SEASON-PIAZZA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LOOK TO PIAZZA, AN ENIGMATIC SUPERSTAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (jt)  
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Piazza prepares to enter his first full season as the
centerpiece of a rebuilt Mets offense and claim his place on the
most demanding of sports stages, he remains an enigmatic superstar.
</P>
<P>
   His detractors accuse him of self-interest, saying he is
concerned only with his bank account and his statistics. They say
he is not a great catcher and never will be. His supporters point
to the hard work and determination that allowed him to rise from
the oblivion of a 62nd-round draft choice into potentially the
best-hitting catcher ever.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza himself gives off conflicting signals, allowing multiple
impressions to flourish under the spotlight. His expression
alternates between a brooding scowl and an easy smile. Some days he
is aloof; others, friendly and approachable. Although his drive and
intensity are unquestioned, off the field he comes across as
California laid-back.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, even likely, that Piazza is all of the above.
But as the Mets prepare to open the season Monday night in Florida,
the question is whether the man who mixes urban fire and suburban
cool, the one who recently bought a house in affluent but anonymous
Bergen County, N.J., while still renting an Upper East Side
bachelor pad in Manhattan, will lead the franchise into the
post-season for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only reason you play this game,'' Piazza said
recently. ``But if I do my job and do it well, I have nothing to
worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the contradictions, one thing is certain about the
30-year-old catcher: he has chosen a career path based on degree of
difficulty, like an Olympic dive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being constantly booed by impatient Mets fans waiting
for him to break out and despite appearing uncomfortable in his new
surroundings, Piazza chose to re-up for more hard labor in New
York. Without even testing the free-agent market, he signed a
seven-year, $91 million contract that briefly made him the
highest-paid player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   And he stated unequivocally that the goal of succeeding in New
York City was a major factor in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that I've never really turned away from a challenge
in my career,'' Piazza said. ``You can't ever be afraid to do
something. The Mets went a long way to acquire me. I just wanted to
give it a shot and fulfill their expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza said he read a number of books in the off season dealing
with the differences between winning teams and losing teams. He
said he accepted the responsibility of having to provide
leadership, something his onetime Dodger teammate, Brett Butler,
once said Piazza was unable to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in leadership,'' Piazza said. ``And I definitely
believe I'm a leader. But I believe I lead by example. I've never
been anybody who reacts to somebody who is waving the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this cool facade, no matter what fire burns beneath it,
that distinguishes Piazza from the two main leaders of the Mets'
1986 world championship team: the gung-ho Gary Carter and the
steady, tutorial Keith Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Didier, a senior executive of the Arizona Diamondbacks and a
longtime Piazza family friend, said Piazza and Carter are ``just
the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary was the gung-ho kind,'' Didier said. ``This guy is quiet.
He leads by doing. He's not going to jump up and down. But he'll be
behind the plate every day and he will play hurt and nobody will
know about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think he's cocky or arrogant because of the
way that he walks. No, no, no. He's confident because of the way he
worked his tail off, because he was not a gifted player. He made
himself into a player. A lot of people don't know what Mike's been
through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' manager, Bobby Valentine, said, ``Mike takes his job
as personal as anybody I've ever been in uniform with.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's rise to the top of his profession has been recast into
baseball myth, an oft-told story of a tireless youth who never
succeeded until he switched to catcher and the Los Angeles Dodgers
drafted him as a favor to the family. Even today, Piazza's father,
Vince, cannot say who pushed harder, he or Mike, the second of his
five sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, it was him,'' Mike Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of both,'' said Vince Piazza, an
immigrant's son who dropped out of high school at 16 and parlayed a
small garage from which he sold used cars into a lucrative auto
dealership. ``But what I did with Michael then, if I did that now,
they'd probably get me for child abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   From an early age, Mike Piazza spent countless hours hitting
from both sides of the plate. Indoors, he would hit balls into a
mattress propped up against the basement wall in their home in
Phoenixville, Pa. Outdoors, he hit into the makeshift batting cage
that Vince Piazza built from scratch and added lights to. As a boy,
Mike would shovel the snow out of it in the middle of winter when
he wanted to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it would rain, we'd go under the boardwalk and I'd throw
to him,'' Vince Piazza said, referring to some of the summers his
family spent on the Jersey Shore. ``In the apartment we rented, I'd
move the furniture out and he would hit Whiffle balls.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Vince Piazza grew up in Norristown, Pa., with Tommy Lasorda, the
former Dodger manager, and Mike would serve as a batboy for the
Dodgers when Lasorda brought his team to Veterans Stadium in
Philadelphia. Mike played first base through high school, then
found little success, or playing time, at the University of Miami
and then Miami-Dade. When Piazza was passed over in the major
league draft after one nondescript season at the junior college,
his father suggested the switch to catcher as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the story is well documented. Lasorda intervened in 1988
to get Mike selected by the Dodgers with a courtesy pick.
</P>
<P>
   The former Dodgers pitcher Burt Hooton was one of Piazza's
rookie league coaches at Salem, Ore., in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story that if you sat down and wrote it as fiction, it
would be an unbelievable story,'' Hooton, who is now the pitching
coach at the University of Texas, said the other day. ``Because I
tell you, he was awful in Salem. And I won't be the only one to say
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a guy who fit the proverbial saying, `He can't
walk and chew gum at the same time,' it applied to him,'' Hooton
said. ``He didn't have a position he could play. And he pretty much
struck out most of the time. But every once in a while, if he did
hit it, it would go 450 or 500 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling while playing for the Dodgers' Class A Vero Beach
team in 1990, Piazza nearly quit for good. ``I had a bad
attitude,'' Piazza said. ``If I wasn't playing, I felt like I was
wasting my time.'' But after Lasorda, Didier and general manager
Fred Claire intervened, Piazza returned.
</P>
<P>
   Mike could have easily quit and joined the family business,
Vince Piazza said, ``and he just didn't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, behind Piazza's back, some of his minor league teammates
resented the player they derisively called ``Tommy's boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza persevered. He spent a winter at the Dodgers' academy in
the Dominican Republic rooming in a dormitory as the only
English-speaking player just so he could catch more games. ``He
paid for his own fare,'' said Joe Ferguson, the former Dodger
catcher who was Piazza's manager there. ``He was kind of criticized
for that, because he never asked for permission. If anything, he
should have been applauded.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza spent another winter in Mexico, and another at the
Arizona Fall League. Gradually, he transformed himself into a
serviceable catcher and one of the finest right-handed hitters in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has been an All-Star each of his six seasons in the
league, and his .333 career batting average is second among active
players (behind Tony Gwynn at .339) with a minimum of 1,000 at
bats. If Piazza can just catch his usual 150 or so games a season
and approach his usual offensive numbers _ he's averaged 33 homers
and 106 runs batted in his six full seasons _ he will, in the Mets'
view, be worth every cent of the highest salary they have ever
paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nobody in the ball park,'' said the Mets' co-owner,
Nelson Doubleday, explaining why he instructed general manager
Steve Phillips to pursue a trade for Piazza. ``And as soon as Mr.
Piazza showed up, things picked up. You've got to put a nickel in
to get a nickel out. We did need to sign him, absolutely. And we
built the team around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said: ``Mike doesn't have to be anything more than what
he's always been. He doesn't have to be a vocal leader. He just has
to go out and play like he's played _ and do it for the next seven
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
