<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SEASON-ANDERSON-C     04-03 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SEASON-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: McGWIRE, SOSA, AND THE UNCERTAIN STRIKE ZONE  
(jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hitting home runs is not like singing an encore at a concert. To
answer the applause, Bruce Springsteen or Whitney Houston can
always turn to the band and do one more, but this season it won't
be that easy for Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa to do what they did
last year, much less improve on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened last year might never happen again,''
McGwire was saying early last week. ``For people to expect it to
happen is unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   But judging by ticket sales in St. Louis and Chicago, some
people expect McGwire and Sosa to hit 70 and 66 homers again, or at
least hope they will.
</P>
<P>
   Never before had anybody buying season tickets in Busch Memorial
Stadium requested seats in the upper deck in left field. But when
the Cardinals open the season there Monday night against the
Milwaukee Brewers, about 200 season-ticket holders (at $16 a game,
that's $1,296 a ticket) will be up there pleading for Big Mac to
unload his first homer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall season ticket total is approaching our record of
21,000 in 1990,'' said Jose Arnold, the Cardinals' ticket director.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Cubs return to Wrigley Field April 12 for their
home opener against the Cincinnati Reds, about 150 of what are
quaintly known as Bleacher Bums will be season-ticket holders (at
$15 a game, that's $1,215 a ticket) out there waiting for one of
Sosa's shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do sell a limited number of bleacher season tickets,'' said
Frank Maloney, the Cubs' ticket director, ``but that's double the
number we sold a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   And those ticket sales are realistic. But for McGwire and Sosa
to match their numbers of last season is, as the Cardinals slugger
warned, indeed unrealistic. Even so, through Friday's games in
spring training, Sosa led all hitters with 11 home runs and McGwire
was tied for second with 9. And if they resume their friendly duel,
each could hit at least 50 again.
</P>
<P>
   When Sosa hit his 66th homer in the final week of last season,
remember, the Cubs' right fielder was one ahead of McGwire, but the
Cardinals' first baseman responded, as he had all season, with five
homers in his last three games. Each inspired the other.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody knows if Sosa's 66 was an aberration; he hit only 36
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 sluggers who hit at least 50 homers in a season, only
two _ McGwire and Ruth _ ever increased their production in a
following season. And McGwire is the only one to increase his
production the next two years. He jumped from 52 in 1996 to 58 in
1997 to his record 70 last year; he is also the only slugger to hit
at least 50 in three straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth went from 54 in 1920 (his first year with the Yankees) to
59 the next year. But he skidded three times after 50-homer
seasons, dropping from 59 in 1921 to 35, and from his then-record
60 in 1927 to 54, then to 46.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. has hit 56 in each of the last two seasons, the
only slugger with at least 50 who did not go up or down. Sosa and
Greg Vaughn, now with the Reds after hitting 50 for the Padres last
season, must cope for the first time with the season after joining
the ``50 Club.''
</P>
<P>
   All the other members of the 50 Club skidded the next season,
notably Roger Maris, who went from 61 in 1961 to 33, and Hack
Wilson, who went from what was then a National League record of 56
in 1930 to only 13.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron, the career leader with 755 homers, never hit 50 in
a season. His high was 47 in 1971 with the Atlanta Braves; he hit
34 the next year. After his other 40-plus years, he dropped from 44
in 1957 to 30 and from 45 in 1962 to 44 and then 24 in Milwaukee,
and from 44 in 1966 to 39, from 44 in 1969 to 38 and from 40 in
1973 (at age 39) to 20 in Atlanta. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A foggy factor for McGwire, Sosa and all hitters this season is
the uncertainty of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   When a Feb. 15 memo from Commissioner Bud Selig's office ordered
the umpires to call a higher strike (2 inches above the belt) as
well as tighten the strike zone on the outside of home plate, the
umpires filed a grievance; they argued that the rules had been
changed without their input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel all the umpires are following the directive in
spring training,'' said Sandy Alderson, Major League Baseball's new
executive vice president for baseball operations. ``But we intend
to be diligent in monitoring how the strike zone is called.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson, the former Oakland general manager, remembered hearing
``players being more concerned about the next day's plate umpire
than the next day's starting pitcher; something's wrong there.''
And during last year's post-season, many pitches apparently wide of
the plate were called strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get the ball back over the plate,'' Alderson said,
``we'll see more strikes, more swings.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more home runs, too. Mark McGwire walked 162 times last
season, Sammy Sosa 73. But if hitters have to wonder what each
umpire's strike zone is, it will create more confusion than
confidence. Not only for sluggers, but for all those new
season-ticket holders out where the home runs land in St. Louis and
Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
