<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU  
 (SUBS to clarify Kosovo coverage. KOSOVO-NATO is now by Michael
Gordon. The Jane Perlez article is now slugged KOSOVO-U.S.)  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, April 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels, Belgium) _ Responding to the staggering
refugee crisis caused by Serb attacks against ethnic Albanian
civilians in Kosovo, NATO said Saturday it was planning to send a
force of six to eight thousand troops to Albania to provide
security and emergency relief for the masses of people Serb forces
are driving from their homeland. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO is waging war by
committee. The 19-member alliance operates by consensus, and its
members run the gamut from the hawkish Britain to the somewhat
skittish Italy, a country just 40 miles across the Adriatic from
Albania. By Michael R. Gordon
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ The NATO allies have no plans to try
to stop the brutalities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo except
through an extended air campaign, which could continue for a ``few
months,'' according to senior Clinton administration officials. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The two Interior
Ministry buildings hit by NATO cruise missiles overnight smoldered
on Saturday in Belgrade's morning haze, collapsed in on themselves
at wacky angles. They provided angry citizens evidence both of
NATO's astounding accuracy _ Yugoslav authorities said there were
no casualties of any kind _ and of the alliance's vow to strike
military and security headquarters, even in the heart of Serbia's
capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ President Clinton may
seem tired and worn these days, but President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia is looking on top of his little world. Milosevic is
riding above the fray, while his army and his police are capturing
(or abducting) American soldiers, shooting down a stealth airplane
and expelling ethnic Albanians from Kosovo in numbers beyond any
Washington policy maker's most embarrassing nightmares. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ If NATO's air raid strategy
was meant to prevent Serbian forces from committing atrocities
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, as President Clinton and other
officials have said, it is an utter failure. The stark evidence of
that failure is in the haunted eyes of more than a quarter-million
refugees who have already been driven out of Kosovo in Slobodan
Milosevic's systematic, brutally efficient Serbian campaign to
depopulate the province of its majority Albanian population. A news
analysis. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HISTORY (Undated) _ The conflict between Serbs and
Albanians, currently embodied by the desperate Albanian families
fleeing Serbian pursuers in Kosovo, has a very long history that is
deeply felt, if selectively recalled, by those condemned to live
it. At the same time it has never been much understood or
appreciated beyond the southern Balkans. By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LEGAL (Washington) _ From the briefing room at the State
Department to the corridors of Whitehall in London and NATO
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, a word usually avoided by
policymakers is being uttered ever more frequently to describe
events in Kosovo: genocide. By invoking the word, policymakers in
the United States and Europe are helping provide a legal
justification for their military campaign against Serbia. By Neil
A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA (Washington) _ With the NATO bombing campaign in
Yugoslavia so far unable to deter the atrocities in Kosovo, and the
United States unwilling to commit ground troops, the idea of arming
the Kosovo guerrillas has garnered support from a number of
politicians and former policymakers. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Skopje, Macedonia) _ A top commander of the
Kosovo Liberation Army made an impassioned plea Saturday for NATO
countries to supply weapons and ammunition to his guerrilla force,
which he said was hampered in its losing battle to defend Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians from Serbian forces. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Since the Cold War ended, no other
event has so divided the West and Russia as the NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia. The chasm is so deep that even words have taken on
opposite meaning. While Americans and Europeans talk about the
`'genocide'' of Kosovo Albanians by Serbs, many Russians talk about
the ``genocide'' of Serbs by American bombs. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-McCAIN (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain spent more than
five years as a prisoner of war in Vietnam and learned, he says,
the dangers of limited measures. He is now a forceful advocate of
all-out intervention in the Balkans. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton urged Americans
to donate money to provide food, water, medicine, blankets,
clothing and shelter for hundreds of thousands of refugees driven
from Kosovo. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CRIME (Havana) _ Today Cuba, which for decades was immune
to the high crime rates of more open societies, is itself grappling
with a rising tide of common crime that has swelled in the last
year. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ China's charismatic prime minister and
