familial homeland and to invest in it, but stopped short of giving
them the right to vote, as many of them have sought. By Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GREEN-PARTY (Piedmont, Calif.) _ When fellow Green Party
members persuaded Audie Bock to run for the state Assembly last
December, they told her she had a choice. She could run a symbolic
campaign by putting her name on the ballot _ or she could campaign
seriously. Ms. Bock chose to run a real race, and she won _ making
her the first member of the Green Party to serve in a state
legislature anywhere in the nation, and the first third-party
candidate to serve in the California Assembly since 1914. By Bill
Staggs.
</P>
<P>
   RAPE-SPEAKOUT (Los Angeles) _ Several women who have lived
through rape are speaking out about it in Los Angeles, both in a
public service announcement broadcast on television and at a
conference on April 17 intended to help other victims. In speaking
out, the women are further lifting what has traditionally been a
protective curtain of anonymity to unveil the faces _ mother,
fiancee, the elderly _ of what they call a ``secret sorority.'' By
Christian Berthelsen.
</P>
<P>
   LUXURY-LINER (Philadelphia) _ An enormous luxury liner lies
empty and dark at the municipal pier here. The task facing its
owner and an avid band of preservationists is not focused on ocean
voyages but simply on gaining a secre future for a behemoth that
stands seven stories high, weighs 59,000 tons and stretches nearly
1,000 feet _ or ``110 feet longer than Titanic and she's still
floating,'' as one slogans says. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ABSTINENCE-EDUC (Undated) _ For all the uproar when Congress set
aside $50 million a year for states to create abstinence-education
programs teaching the benefits of delaying sex until marriage,
every state in the nation ultimately applied for the money when it
became available in fiscal 1998. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATES-FINANCE (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ Both Bill Bradley and
John McCain, presidential candidates who are known for championing
campaign finance reform, say that the existing laws leave them no
choice but to devote much time to traveling the country hunting for
millions of dollars or hitting up prospects during interminable
telephone calls. Neither is willing to follow the lead of Sen.
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., who almost lost his re-election last year
because of several restrictions he imposed on his own fund raising.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORY-INDUSTRY (Undated) _ The graying of America has created
an emerging industry: a wave of herbal and dietary supplements,
books, courses and even clinics aimed at healthy people who are
having trouble remembering and concentrating. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   WYO-MURDER-AFTERMATH (Laramie, Wyo.) _ In the six months since
the fatal beating of Matthew Shepard, a gay 21-year-old college
student, the spot has become a pilgrimage site, as people bearing
poems and floral bouquets have worn deep ruts in a dirt track to
the lonely section of fence. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Yuppie Foxhole. By Maureen Dowd.
