<SLUG> BC-BBO-SEASON-GLOVES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVEN OVER, DOUSED AND MICROWAVED, LEATHER ENDURES AS THE PLAYERS'
CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By NOAH LIBERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six million baseball gloves are sold in the United States each
year; maybe 2,000 end up on the hands of major leaguers. For most
of these players, there is no piece of equipment more important
than their glove, which makes sense: bats break and balls disappear
into the stands, but a player's glove is always waiting for him on
the bench. Last season, home run balls got all the attention; it
seems appropriate now to give equal time to gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Leather
</P>
<P>
   At the slaughterhouse, the 50- to 60-pound cowhides are sliced
in two lengthwise, cured in salt brine (so they do not spoil) and
stripped of flesh. They are shipped to tanneries, such as Horween
Leather in Chicago, which has prepared leather for decades to
Rawlings _ maker of about half of the gloves used in the major
leagues _ and now supplies Mizuno and Louisville Slugger. There,
hair, fats and oils are removed, the hides go through chemical and
water washes, a sulfuric acid pickling and a chromium-sulfate
tanning.
</P>
<P>
   Only then can Horween sort out the spotless 5 percent of hides
worthy of becoming a major leaguer's glove. ``If the animals had an
evil thought, it shows up,'' said Arnold Horween Jr., the
third-generation company president.
</P>
<P>
   Now considered leather, the hide is ``split'' to a thickness of
2 to 2.4 millimeters (less than 1 inch), treated with a fish oil,
buffed with sandpaper and stained to the glove maker's
specifications. From slaughter to leather, the process takes
roughly six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   No material beats leather in a baseball glove. Meshes are too
fragile and prone to stretching, and shiny synthetic leathers look
cheap. The game-day glove of Dodgers shortstop Mark Grudzielanek,
the Wilson G4, does feature a pebble-grain synthetic back that is
billed as twice as strong and half as heavy as leather. The glove
designer Shigeaki Aso discovered the material on Wilson's
basketballs.
</P>
<P>
   Construction
</P>
<P>
   It takes another 10 days to construct a glove, though the
Rawlings designer Bob Clevenhagen says the process can be squeezed
into an hour if a prominent player is in a pinch. ``I just sent
Tony Gwynn a new one, UPS red label,'' Clevenhagen said, referring
to the San Diego outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   The palm is cut from the dense hide that ran along the cow's
backbone. The back of the glove comes from the flank; the lining
comes from the softer, stretched belly, and the web gets scraps
from anywhere. In all, it takes 16 to 20 pieces of leather (all
stamped out cookie-cutter style) and 8 to 12 feet of lacing.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces are sewn together inside-out and then inverted; fingers
are slid over an aluminum ``hot hand'' that smooths and shapes the
leather to accept the synthetic wool padding. Lace holes are
punched, eyelets added, straps and logos (ever larger) sewn on and,
finally, the glove is laced by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Web
</P>
<P>
   Imitation (and a 17-year limit on glove patents) means there are
only a few basic web styles, shared by all the makers.
</P>
<P>
   Solid webs, such as Wilson's Dual Hinge, are preferred by
pitchers, who want to hide their throwing hand as they adjust their
grip.
</P>
<P>
   Many middle infielders choose open webs, such as the single-post
crisscross on the Rawlings of Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez or
the half-solid H-web on the Mizuno of Atlanta third baseman Chipper
Jones, to give themselves ``quicker hands.'' They are an ounce or
so lighter than solid webs, which equals a pound to an infielder's
psyche.
</P>
<P>
   First basemen, outfielders and some third basemen prefer
multiple-crisscross webs. These players can afford a longer web,
and this pattern is a compromise between sturdiness and light
weight. The longtime Chicago Cubs third baseman Ron Santo may have
pioneered this style for Wilson, when he told the company he
sometimes could not feel line drives hit the solid web of his A2000
model.
</P>
<P>
   Some players at every position swear by the Basket Web, a woven
solid pattern that was under patent to Rawlings until 1983. ``I
just felt I could really get in there and find the ball,'' says
Ryne Sandberg, the former Cubs' second baseman, who abandoned the
single-post web when he switched from third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six fingers are better than five,'' Ozzie Smith says of the
Rawlings Trap-Eze model he used as a teen-ager and as an All-Star
shortstop for the Padres and Cardinals after the company
reintroduced it in 1978. With a long, laced-in finger for a web,
the Trap-Eze probably suited Smith's preference for a harder
surface he could use to ricochet the ball into his throwing hand,
as many shortstops do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a good-feeling glove with a nice look and nice
lines, like a nice car,'' Smith said. This gets to the heart of the
matter: often, players simply like something about the way a glove
looks. Then other players imitate them and manufacturers imitate
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Heel and Thumb
</P>
<P>
   Glove designers will suggest that the heel may have changed the
most over the last 30 years, getting progressively thinner. Joe
Morgan, the Hall of Fame second baseman, recognized that heel
padding was somewhat superfluous and removed layer after layer of
it until a glove suited him. Recently manufacturers have responded
to requests for thinner thumbs, as well, by using thinner plastic
thumb stays _ 1.5 millimeters compared with 2 before.
</P>
<P>
   Back
</P>
<P>
   Here's where a glove's architecture is revealed. Outfielders
(and roughly two-thirds of the retail market) prefer a closed-back
glove. These tend to have longer ``finger stalls,'' the leather
that divides the fingers, which allows outfielders to wear the
glove out on their fingertips like a ``claw.'' The traditional
open-back glove is preferred by infielders; it is lighter and has
shorter finger stalls, which allow the fingers farther into the
glove for more glove-to-palm contact.
</P>
<P>
   Most players slip their index finger outside the glove for
comfort. Joe Morgan went a step further, pressing it toward the
glove to flatten the pocket on grounders and pulling it back to
protect his palm on line drives. The Atlanta Braves ace Greg Maddux
learned he was tipping pitches by the way his index finger
protruded from his Wilson glove, so the company developed the Pro
Sleeve, a leather sheath sewn to the glove's back.
</P>
<P>
   The back also reveals an essential but often overlooked
component: the welts. These are the thin slices of leather sewn
into the seams between and on the backs of the fingers. Their grain
runs 90 degrees to the other leather, to provide needed stiffness
and shape-retention.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Color
</P>
<P>
   Remember red gloves? They went out with Mitch Williams. In the
pro ranks, outfielders tend to prefer black gloves and infielders
brown ones, but it is the exceptions that are the most interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire wears a black glove at first base for the
Cardinals, but a few years ago, in a pinch, Rawlings replaced a
worn palm section and one bar of the web with tan. Now all of
McGwire's gloves are made that way. Two-tone gloves are popular in
the middle-infield positions, too; some trace this to the
well-traveled former second baseman Manny Trillo, who used to
darken the back of his glove with shoe polish when he came up with
the Oakland Athletics in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers outfielder Raul Mondesi may have the most colorful
current mitt, a scarlet and navy Rawlings number, and Tony Gwynn's
black Rawlings now sports two tan lightning bolts on the back of
each finger. Unlike McGwire's glove, Gwynn's will soon be available
at retail.
</P>
<P>
   Size and Shape
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Commissioner Fay Vincent ordered umpires to enforce the
rule that gloves could not be longer than 12 inches, measured from
the heel to the tip of the index finger. Manufacturers make no
secret of the fact that the longest glove made today is 13 inches,
and it is used by almost every outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Second basemen's gloves are the smallest, at 11 or 11\ inches,
the culmination of a shrinking process Nellie Fox began, Bill
Mazeroski continued and Joe Morgan completed. Nevertheless, White
Sox Manager Jerry Manuel, himself a second baseman, told his young
second baseman Ray Durham that his glove was too small last season;
Durham switched and his fielding improved.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstops' gloves run 11\ to 11{ inches, and third basemen's
may reach 12 inches. Third basemen tend to break in their gloves a
little longer and narrower, preferring the length for confidence
when diving for line shots. Middle infielders want the fingers
short and spread wide, to create a broad, shallow pocket. ``I tell
young shortstops to make the glove look like their open hand,''
Ozzie Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the younger catchers prefer smaller mitts, broken in
``from the top down,'' like a shortstop's. This distresses
traditionalists, who see it as a byproduct of one-handed catching.
</P>
<P>
   Break-In and Maintenance
</P>
<P>
   Throw it in the Jacuzzi, the microwave or the dryer. Put it
under the mattress or drive over it with the car. Put it in a
bucket of water. Douse it with coffee. All of these have been
tried, with success, by major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   But breaking in a glove has become relatively easy. For
starters, fine glove leather is not the rock-hard material it was
30 years ago, and some players now swear by the even softer
oil-tanned leather. And most major leaguers like their gloves stiff
to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Hernandez, an All-Star with the Cardinals and Mets, broke
in his first baseman's mitt by first playing some catch and then
tightening the laces around the fingertips. Then he saturated the
pocket with water, tied two balls inside it and hung it in his
locker for a week. When he untied it, the fingertips curled inward
and were ``as hard as reinforced concrete,'' he said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Ryne Sandberg kneaded his glove over a pot of boiling water
until he noticed it getting softer. Tigers first baseman Tony Clark
will ``pull up a chair in front of the pitching machine and play
some fast catch.'' Pirates catcher Jason Kendall has the equipment
manager pound the pocket and hinge with various round-tipped wooden
mallets made especially for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In a fine example of symbiosis, Gillette has been supplying its
Foamy shave cream to major league clubhouses for years, and many
players now use it to condition their gloves. Bob Clevenhagen, the
Rawlings glove designer, says shaving cream is fine, as long as it
contains lanolin (the oil from sheepskin) but not much soap.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment and Superstition
</P>
<P>
   Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina has used the same glove since
1988 and carries it on planes with him. Scott Erickson stanched a
losing streak in college by dying all his equipment black; now a
starter for the Orioles, he has Mizuno deliver him tan gloves,
which he dyes black. Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius switched
gloves in the middle of last season and went on an error streak
that may have cost him the Gold Glove; he is still agonizing over
finding a good new glove.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, only hours after giving away his ``gamer'' to a
member of the country-rock band Alabama, the Cubs' Doug Dascenzo
booted a ball in center field and lost his chance at the
consecutive games without an error streak for outfielders. ``Doug's
such a nice guy, but he wasn't thinking too much,'' Sandberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez, a rationalist by baseball standards, went through
too many gloves to get attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every glove is beautiful once it's broken in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing
</P>
<P>
   If there is an enduring tradition in baseball, it is the glove
makers' practice of signing minor leaguers to five-year contracts
for two gloves a season. It is a boon for poor farmhands and a
no-brainer for the companies, as most players, including All-Stars,
stick with the same glove company.
</P>
<P>
   When a player becomes a star, he may sign a two- or three-year
contract for gloves and cash, worth up to $100,000. Or the contract
may call for payment in kind: Mizuno gives Dodgers outfielder Devon
White five dozen high-end bats each year and DiSarcina a set of
golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   When a player gets famous, glove reps come calling. Pitchers are
prime targets, as the logos on the backs of their gloves get prime
TV exposure. Wilson lured Kerry Wood away from Zett this year, but
Zett feels it is on a good-luck string: closer Mariano Rivera's
Zett was in dozens of prominent photos of the Yankees World Series
celebration last year.
</P>
<P>
   Glove makers will go to great lengths to keep their marquee
endorsers happy, including overnight adjustments to gloves and
minute design changes. Still, some players are fickle. Roger
Clemens won three Cy Young awards in a Wilson, one in a Zett and
one in a Cooper. Roberto Alomar, the Cleveland Indians' second
baseman, was considering his fourth glove company this spring.
``He's all over the place,'' said one exasperated glove rep. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
