<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4644 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-03 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BEYOND THE DIALLO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The killing of Amadou Diallo was cold-blooded, but it
probably wasn't murder. It appears that one or more of the officers
genuinely believed Diallo had a gun and that all four officers,
imagining danger when in fact there was none, panicked and began
firing.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the shooting was reckless and wrong. The
41 shots from the frightened cops turned a terrible mistake into a
hideous one. But even a hideous mistake by police officers who
think their lives are in danger falls short of the threshold for
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   There may or may not be evidence to sustain some lesser charge.
That will be determined at a trial. But there is a danger in
raising expectations about the outcome of the Diallo case too high.
If the officers are convicted of lesser crimes, or ultimately walk,
which is possible, the fury could be so great that it would detract
from the growing movement to correct the policies that made a
catastrophe like the Diallo shooting all but inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The major benefit to emerge from the protests against the Diallo
shooting was not the indictment of the cops on murder charges, but
the fact that a spotlight was turned on the serious and systematic
police abuses that accompanied the Giuliani administration's
crackdown on crime.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani insisted from the moment he took office
that police officers adopt a much more aggressive approach to
fighting crime and combatting the so-called quality-of-life
offenses. What he didn't do was insist that this citywide crackdown
be carried out by officers who were properly trained and closely
supervised. And he never gave enough attention to the idea that
law-abiding New Yorkers, including those who are black or Latino,
should always be treated with respect by the police.
</P>
<P>
   As crime rates plummeted, New Yorkers tended to overlook the
complaints about brutality and other forms of police misconduct.
But now, because of the publicity generated by the Abner Louima
case and the protests that followed the killing of Diallo, there is
a growing acknowledgment that while the plunging crime rate has
been a blessing, there is something terribly wrong about the ways
in which some police officers are conducting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And within law enforcement circles there is a steadily
increasing recognition that much of the problem can be traced to
the centerpiece of the administration's crime crackdown: the
heralded Comstat meetings at which police commanders are hounded to
get arrests and gun seizures up and crime statistics down.
</P>
<P>
   Comstat stands for computer statistics. The meetings frequently
featured the public humiliation of precinct commanders whose
statistics were subpar. The idea was to get results, period. Those
who could not get their stats in order would be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Intentionally or not, the message conveyed by Comstat was that
the desired end of reduced crime statistics could justify virtually
any means.
</P>
<P>
   Said one cop: ``There was a whole `go-get-'em' mentality that
was shaky from the very beginning. The top police commanders were
under tremendous pressure. There never was a complete management
package, which would have insured that the cops were properly
trained and the community protected. We weren't told to be
even-handed and fair. All we had was the crime-reduction piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Innocent New Yorkers were stopped and frisked by the tens of
thousands. Thousands more were dragged off to jail for the most
minor offenses _ traffic violations, drinking in public, riding a
bicycle on the sidewalk. And there were alarming increases in the
amounts paid by the city to settle police brutality lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and his police commissioners knew or should have known
that their anti-crime strategies were dangerously flawed and likely
to lead to tragedy. They knew or should have known that many of the
officers sent out to engage the criminals and interact with the
law-abiding public needed more training and better supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The people who have protested these policies should not allow
their efforts to be derailed by whatever happens to the officers
who killed Amadou Diallo. The primary focus should be on the
efforts to change policies that, if left in place, will surely lead
to similar tragedies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
