<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4658 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SATIRICAL-WEBSITES-RE     04-03 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATIRICAL-WEBSITES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE LOVE LETTERS: YOUSTINK.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, the whole world knows there's no hotter property than
companies that make Internet Web sites. Now here's something even
hotter: Web sites that make fun of companies.
</P>
<P>
   The sites allow disgruntled consumers to, well, express
themselves. For example, a site targeting Chase Manhattan Bank
features a cartoon of a half-naked little man in red shorts loping
across the top of the screen and dropping his drawers before
urinating on Chase's name. Mission accomplished, the little man
turns and smiles broadly at the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the companies aren't thrilled with this new
chapter in America's love affair with griping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most companies, we value customer feedback,'' said Ken
Herz, a Chase spokesman. ``But it's a pretty offensive Web site and
most of the information there is inaccurate. It's kind of pathetic,
frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has always been home to plenty of unvarnished brio,
and this new form of guerrilla consumerism is no exception. Much of
it is marked by a heavy dose of invective. Designers of the sites
might have chosen names like Chase-Gouged-Me.com or
AT&AMP;T-Isn't-Very-Nice.com, but most haven't. Instead, they use names
far too vulgar for breakfast time in the homes of readers of
high-toned newspapers like this one. (Terms sort of like
``stinks,'' only nastier.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the companies don't seem to see the humor in all this,
so they're fighting back with their most familiar weapon: money.
</P>
<P>
   Chase has been buying up the rights to names like
``ChaseStinks.com'' and ``IHateChase.com.'' Likewise, brokerage
giant Charles Schwab is protecting its flank by buying the rights
to dozens of unseemly domain names before angry consumers get their
hands on them. The same holds for General Electric, Hyatt and other
corporate heavyweights that pay between $70 and $120 to register
each domain name.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating such preemptive strikes by Corporate America, Dan
Parisi, a Secaucus, N.J., lawyer and an operator of a pornographic
Internet site, has been stockpiling the rights to all sorts of
pejorative domain names, including those invoking well-known
companies like AT&AMP;T, Sears and Kmart, according to a recent issue
of American Banker. Parisi did not respond to repeated requests for
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are already plenty of places to complain about
companies. Some of the tamer ones have names like ``Untied
Airlines'' (for unhappy United Airlines fliers), ``Allsnake''
(featuring rants against Allstate Insurance) and ``I Hate
McDonalds'' (for those with indigestion courtesy of the golden
arches).
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who favor broad-brush venting can visit
complainline.com or grumbling.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies shrug off the advent of guerrilla consumerism.
Wal-Mart, the target of a Web site where a customer calling herself
Elaine describes the company as ``underhanded and dishonest,'' said
it has no interest in securing rights to offensive site names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware that these sites are out there, but our feeling
is that our customers and associates are knowledgeable enough about
our company, services and reputation to see right through them,''
said Jessica Moser, a Wal-Mart spokeswoman. The attitude of some
Wal-Mart customers bolsters that viewpoint. ``All you guys who
write in and complain about stupid things need to go get a life,''
a customer calling herself Kim wrote on the Wal-Mart site. ``What's
wrong with you? It's just a store.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla Web sites, of course, are not confined to the business
world. Last week, supporters of New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani erected Hillaryno.com, a site aimed at deflating a
possible run for the U.S. Senate by Hillary Rodham Clinton.
Giuliani is said to harbor his own designs for the Senate, and the
site chides Mrs. Clinton for her slender government resume.
</P>
<P>
   But politicians are used to bruising, bare-knuckles criticism.
Many companies never experience full-blown invective until they
reach a certain size, and even then they remain skittish about
threats to their image. Consequently, some corporations have
launched robust counteroffensives to guerrilla consumerism.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the health club operator Bally Total Fitness filed a
trademark infringement suit against a site featuring an indecorous
variation on Bally's name. The suit was quickly dismissed and
experts on trademark law think few courts would back similar ones.
Trademark protection typically extends only to a company's
corporate name _ if an offensive adjective or verb is appended to
the name on a Web site, trademark protections evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this vast concern among corporations about whether a
domain name is a trademark or not,'' said Richard Forman, president
of register.com, a leading provider of Internet domain
registrations. ``But the courts have resoundingly ruled that a
domain name is not a trademark name.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is quite acceptable to Scott Harrison, a 23-year-old
promotions director for a Manhattan nightclub, who started the
anti-Chase site after the bank mishandled some of his accounts.
``Anything goes on the Internet, and my site is about free
speech,'' said Harrison. ``It's a way for me to literally tell the
entire world about why not to do business with this bank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-99 1220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6887 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SATIRICAL-WEBSITES-RE     04-03 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATIRICAL-WEBSITES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE LOVE LETTERS: YOUSTINK.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, the whole world knows there's no hotter property than
companies that make Internet Web sites. Now here's something even
hotter: Web sites that make fun of companies.
</P>
<P>
   The sites allow disgruntled consumers to, well, express
themselves. For example, a site targeting Chase Manhattan Bank
features a cartoon of a half-naked little man in red shorts loping
across the top of the screen and dropping his drawers before
urinating on Chase's name. Mission accomplished, the little man
turns and smiles broadly at the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the companies aren't thrilled with this new
chapter in America's love affair with griping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most companies, we value customer feedback,'' said Ken
Herz, a Chase spokesman. ``But it's a pretty offensive Web site and
most of the information there is inaccurate. It's kind of pathetic,
frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has always been home to plenty of unvarnished brio,
and this new form of guerrilla consumerism is no exception. Much of
it is marked by a heavy dose of invective. Designers of the sites
might have chosen names like Chase-Gouged-Me.com or
AT&AMP;T-Isn't-Very-Nice.com, but most haven't. Instead, they use names
far too vulgar for breakfast time in the homes of readers of
high-toned newspapers like this one. (Terms sort of like
``stinks,'' only nastier.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the companies don't seem to see the humor in all this,
so they're fighting back with their most familiar weapon: money.
</P>
<P>
   Chase has been buying up the rights to names like
``ChaseStinks.com'' and ``IHateChase.com.'' Likewise, brokerage
giant Charles Schwab is protecting its flank by buying the rights
to dozens of unseemly domain names before angry consumers get their
hands on them. The same holds for General Electric, Hyatt and other
corporate heavyweights that pay between $70 and $120 to register
each domain name.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating such preemptive strikes by Corporate America, Dan
Parisi, a Secaucus, N.J., lawyer and an operator of a pornographic
Internet site, has been stockpiling the rights to all sorts of
pejorative domain names, including those invoking well-known
