<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEMORY-INDUSTRY-2TAKE     04-03 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORY-INDUSTRY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY'S NEXT GROWTH SECTOR: MEMORY LAPSES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., N.J.)   By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The graying of America has created an emerging industry: a wave
of herbal and dietary supplements, books, courses and even clinics
aimed at healthy people who are having trouble remembering and
concentrating.
</P>
<P>
   On television commercials there is Annie Potts, who starred in
``Designing Women,'' extolling the wonders of that old standard,
One-a-Day vitamins, now reformulated by Bayer AG with the herbal
compound ginkgo biloba to sharpen memory. Hector Elizondo, star of
the hospital drama ``Chicago Hope,'' is pitching Warner-Lambert
Co.'s Quanterra Mental Sharpness Product, which also contains
ginkgo biloba.
</P>
<P>
   No elixir for forgetfulness exists. Yet even though ginkgo
biloba's ability to stimulate memory is unproved, sales of products
containing it reached $240 million in 1997, according to the
Nutrition Business Journal. The substance is only one of many
supplements said to re-energize aging minds. Such products can bear
hefty price tags, ranging from $30 to more than $100 for a month's
supply.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, giant drug companies are working on new medications
to treat Alzheimer's disease, a debilitating and thus far incurable
form of dementia; they may find a wider market among healthy people
concerned about memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line publishers have jumped into the market. Recent books
include ``Why Can't I Remember?: Reversing Normal Memory Loss''
(Avery Publishing Group), ``Menopause and the Mind'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster) and ``Brain Fitness: Anti-Aging Strategies for Achieving
Super Mind Power'' (Doubleday).
</P>
<P>
   On another front, start-up companies purvey memory training and
clinical services. One small concern, Neurocorp Ltd., operates four
Memory Centers of America and hopes to open 240 nationwide over the
next four years, marketing its services to executives, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that is prime for picking,'' said Dr. Andrew
Monjan, chief of the neurobiology of aging branch of the National
Institute on Aging. ``It is a market that is interested in its
health. It caters to the underlying American desire for a fix.''
</P>
<P>
   An aging population is driving the memory business; by 2030, the
number of Americans over 65 is expected to nearly double. But
marketers also foresee potential customers in those in their 40s _
an age when experts say memory skills begin to decline for many
people.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, marketers are going after healthy people who
experience minor shifts in memory and concentration, changes such
as difficulty in remembering the names of new acquaintances or
where the car is parked. These symptoms of middle-age forgetfulness
are quite common and in the vast majority of cases are not linked
to serious illnesses like Alzheimer's disease, which affects a
relatively small proportion of the elderly. But growing national
awareness of Alzheimer's has made many healthy people fear that
forgetting a friend's name may signal bigger problems ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the mental processes that are involved in memory and
concentration are complex and not fully understood. Some people
find it easiest to retain what they read, for example. Others rely
on visual cues to remember. How well a person can concentrate, or
screen out other distractions, also plays a role in one's ability
to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James L. McGaugh, director of the Center for the
Neurobiology of Learning and Memory at the University of California
at Irvine, says that although the aging process does not really
damage memory, it does affect what has come to be known as
short-term memory, the ability to recall recently learned
information. It is very common for a middle-age person to forget
the name of a new acquaintance at a social event only to recall it
later while driving home, McGaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Such lapses can affect people in their 20s, though those in
their 40s more commonly experience them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a disease,'' McGaugh said. ``It is the natural
consequence of aging.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the cause or causes of such changes are not clear, some
scientists have hypothesized that factors like declining
cardiovascular health, failing vision and depression may play
roles. For women, studies suggest that the use of
estrogen-replacement therapies after menopause may improve memory.
</P>
<P>
   To work around forgetfulness, experts suggest techniques like
keeping lists or placing one's keys in the same place every day.
Keeping the mind active through work and reading can also help,
psychologists and other researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   No proven commercial memory loss remedies are available, and
some supplements may have harmful side effects if taken in excess.
Still, marketers are aiming a growing number of products _ the vast
majority of which have not received rigorous scientific scrutiny _
at those concerned about losing their mental edge.
</P>
<P>
   Michaela Griggs, manager for Bayer's One-a-Day vitamin brand,
says that the company's Memory and Concentration formula, which
includes ginkgo biloba, has proved particularly popular with people
between the ages of 35 and 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to feel as sharp as they possibly can,'' Ms. Griggs
said. ``I think they want to maintain as much as they've got and
improve it as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of ginkgo biloba products jumped last year after a 1997
report in the Journal of the American Medical Association suggested
that the substance might stabilize the loss of memory and reasoning
skills in people suffering from Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers have attacked the report as methodologically
flawed because it counted people as improved even though they might
have dropped out of the study before it was done. The study, which
was financed by a German producer of ginkgo biloba, did not address
the herbal compound's effects on healthy people concerned about
their mental skills.
</P>
<P>
   Even a Bayer consultant, Judith S. Stern, a professor of
nutrition at the University of California at Davis, said there was
no definitive evidence that ginkgo biloba would improve memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine
plans to start a $15 million study soon of ginkgo biloba involving
those with mild dementia. The study could take five years or more.
</P>
<P>
   Other supplements, whose efficacy has not been proved, are also
being marketed as remedies for memory loss and weak concentration.
Deep Thought and Brain Gum, for example, contain substances similar
to phosphatidylserine, a compound found in the brain that helps
regulate neural functions.
</P>
<P>
   Other products contain forms of the human growth hormone, a
compound secreted by the pituitary gland, which plays a role in
cell growth. Still others contain forms of DHEA, another hormone,
which is involved in the production of estrogen, testosterone and
other substances. The manufacturers of these products contend that
they can aid mental performance by supplementing levels of the
hormones, which begin to decline as a person ages.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Federal Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act of
1994, a company can say that an herbal product will improve a
consumer's sense of well-being or a function of the body like
memory if the manufacturer has evidence of that effect. But even
officials of the Food and Drug Administration acknowledge that the
law does not define what constitutes evidence, thus throwing the
door open to marketing campaigns containing unproven claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this is one of the areas that need clarification,''
said Dr. Elizabeth A. Yetley, director of the FDA's Special
Nutritionals Office.
</P>
<P>
   While the Federal Trade Commission, which regulates product
advertising, has taken action against producers of herbal
supplements that claim their products cure diseases like cancer and
AIDS, the commission has taken no action against herbal products or
supplements that claim to reverse memory loss, Victoria Streitfeld,
an FTC spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   In the traditional drug industry, 20 pharmaceutical companies
including G.D. Searle, SmithKline Beecham PLC, Merck &AMP; Co. and Eli
Lilly &AMP; Co. are developing drugs that they hope will be new
medications for Alzheimer's disease, according to the
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers Association, a trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   McGaugh of the University of California at Irvine and other
experts say they believe that if such drugs prove effective and do
not have side effects, as existing Alzheimer's drugs do, they would
have great appeal for healthy, aging people seeking memory and
concentration enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the big action is, the big focus and the big
payoff,'' McGaugh said. ``I believe that some of these companies
are definitely aiming at memory impairment that is not Alzheimer's
related.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Short, who runs a business called Grow Dendrites Forever
from her home in Lakeside, Mont., said she had recently provided
memory improvement courses for Centura Health, a network of
hospitals and doctors in Colorado, as part of its wellness program
for older patients. Neurocorp Ltd. of Tarrytown, N.Y., is trying to
get into the business of selling individually tailored memory and
mental sharpness programs through its Memory Centers of America
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to one of the company's two Manhattan centers was
memorable mainly for an absence of clients. The company's public
financial filings also suggest that it has yet to hit stride; in
1998, for example, only 292 clients, or fewer than one a day,
visited its four memory centers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that start has not dimmed the enthusiasm of the company or
its president, Vernon L. Wells. With a recent infusion of $2
million of venture capital, the company has started a nationwide
advertising campaign aimed at filling the hundreds of memory
centers it hopes to open. One intended audience is the corporate
executives who fear that their job performance may be slipping
because of declining memory skills or loss of the ability to
concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   A six-to-12-week program costs about $800 and emphasizes
computer training aimed at developing memory-related skills that a
person may not have fully used before, said Wells, who until 1997
was an executive at Quest Diagnostics Inc., a clinical testing
company in Teterboro, N.J. Clients first receive a medical
examination to screen for serious underlying physical problems, and
then they embark on a series of two- to four-hour computer sessions
that may be buttressed by doses of herbal supplements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trigger for many people is that this didn't used to be a
problem for me but it is now,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Robin West, a professor of psychology at the University of
Florida in Gainesville, says it is possible to improve a specific
memory skill for a time but broad improvements are not likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Objective tests won't show any improvement except on the
specific thing learned in a course, and that typically doesn't last
long,'' said Ms. West, who studies both the real and the perceived
effects of memory loss on the aging.
</P>
<P>
   Like other experts, she said she believes that for healthy
people the best techniques to help offset declining memory are
organizational tricks such as keeping lists, jotting appointments
down on calendars and making notes. A small study based on research
sponsored by the MacArthur Foundation found that both older and
younger people could more easily remember a list of words by
incorporating them into stories, according to a Harvard University
Medical School newsletter. In addition, to better retain what one
reads it may be necessary as one ages to eliminate distractions
like television or radio, Ms. West said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, she added, there is no magic memory bullet,
though she offers Neurocorp and all the other companies hoping to
develop one the best of luck. ``Hopefully,'' Ms. West said, ``they
will prove me wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
