<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NY     04-03 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES' WAR BY CONSENSUS LIMITS MILITARY STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-CLINTON.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Soon after the bombing of Yugoslavia began
the week before last, Italy's NATO representative, Amadeo de
Franchi, pointed out in an alliance meeting that the airstrikes
were causing some difficulties for his government.
</P>
<P>
   There was the threat of a refugee crisis on Italy's borders. And
there were worries that tourists might cancel reservations in
Venice, just a short drive from one of the main NATO bases.
Perhaps, he said, the alliance would consider a bombing pause over
Easter?
</P>
<P>
   A senior alliance official noted that such a break would have to
be extended through the Orthodox Easter 10 days later and asked,
``Can you square your conscience with a bombing pause that gives''
President Slobodan Milosevic ``10 extra days to kill people?''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was dropped, but the incident illustrates an important
aspect of the campaign: NATO is waging war by committee. The
19-member alliance operates by consensus, and its members run the
gamut from the hawkish Britain to the somewhat skittish Italy, a
country just 40 miles across the Adriatic from Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The need for consensus has left an unmistakable imprint on the
alliance's military strategy, causing it to take a gradual approach
to the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats insist that NATO's bombing strategy has enabled the
alliance to achieve a remarkable degree of unity, which is
critically important since it is planning for weeks more of
bombing. Decisions that used to take the cumbersome alliance three
days are now, they boast, being made in a mere 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say, however, that NATO's carefully calibrated campaign
may backfire by prolonging the war and providing Milosevic with
more time to exploit fissures among the allies.
</P>
<P>
   It has also, they say, diminished the effectiveness of the
airstrikes, by reducing the element of surprise and limiting the
list of targets. That is an especially serious constraint since
NATO has all but rejected the use of ground troops and is relying
exclusively on air power to roll back the Serbian advance.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Saturday's early morning cruise missile attack on the
headquarters of the Serbian and Yugoslav Interior Ministries in
downtown Belgrade, NATO's attacks are a far cry from the 1991
Persian Gulf war, in which communications, command post and
political headquarters in central Baghdad were hit on the first
night of the campaign, and then repeatedly pounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military action is not consistent with the rhetoric,''
said Buster Glosson, the retired Air Force general who ran the air
campaign against Iraq during the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their plans require the approval of the political arm of NATO,
the military arm of NATO and then officials in Washington. With all
those bottlenecks, the chance of success is small.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, politics has been a big part of NATO's planning from
the outset. Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme allied commander whose
crisp and confident briefings are well known to television viewers,
developed the military plan. But it is the political arm of the
alliance, the North Atlantic Council, that has the final say over
which targets are struck and in what general sequence.
</P>
<P>
   CHAIN OF COMMAND
</P>
<P>
   Focus on Diplomacy as Much as Force
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's most powerful members appear determined to resist
Milosevic's brutal campaign against the Kosovo Albanians. The
British are the most outspoken, but President Jacques Chirac of
France has also condemned the Milosevic regime as a threat to
security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, has supported allied
firmness and recently rebuffed the effort by the Russian prime
minister, Yevgeny Primakov, to negotiate a halt in the allied
bombing without Yugoslavia having to provide any major concessions
in return.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the three-stage plan that NATO ultimately approved put as
much emphasis on sending diplomatic signals as on crushing its
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   The first stage was based on the calculation that a few bombing
strikes might be enough to persuade Milosevic to stop the attacks
in Kosovo and to agree to autonomy for the province. It
concentrated on air defense sites and stayed away from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's plan had never envisaged beginning the air campaign
with a massive application of air bombardment,'' Air Marshal Sir
John Day, the deputy chief of the British Defense Staff, said last
week. ``This was not the start of a war where we were determined to
win as quickly and as harshly as possible to overwhelm his entire
military forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Under NATO's original concept, this phase was to be followed by
a bombing pause to see if the Yugoslav president was persuaded. If
not, the planes were to attack command centers and forces involved
in attacking the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As limited as this approach was, officials said the original
plan was even more restrictive. But as the U.S. special envoy,
Richard Holbrooke, set off on one last attempt in late March to get
Milosevic to budge, the NATO representatives met in the carpeted
conference room of the sprawling allied headquarters near the
Brussels airport to consider a U.S. proposal to add a bit more
punch to the early stages of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke wanted to take news of this decision with him before
he went on to Belgrade. Allied diplomats agreed, with the provision
that they be consulted on the military decision if the moment came.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Holbrooke has everything he needs from NATO,'' NATO's
secretary-general, Javier Solana, said just before the Holbrooke
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic remained unswayed. As NATO began its first attacks,
alliance officials boasted that there would be no ``sanctuary'' for
the Yugoslav leaders. In fact, NATO leaders thought a bombing raid
or two might be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped that he would quickly get the message and not
continue his plans,'' Day said. ``We hoped for a rapid political
solution and that it would not be necessary to move from one phase
of our operation to the next, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   As Serbian forces ruthlessly began to push ethnic Albanians out
of Kosovo, however, the first phase of airstrikes appeared to be
pitifully inadequate, and the alliance shifted after a quick
consultation to the next phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``For NATO, going from phase one to phase two without a pause
was pretty big stuff,'' one alliance military expert said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the alliance's few victories were greeted uneasily by some
members, particularly those whose populations still harbor
unpleasant memories of European wars. When a Dutch pilot shot down
a Yugoslav MIG fighter jet, the authorities declined to release his
name and his commander forbade him to paint the black silhouette of
the ``kill'' on the fuselage of his aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGIC SHIFTS
</P>
<P>
   The Winding Route to Escalation
</P>
<P>
   As Serbian forces relentlessly pressed their attack, diplomats
found themselves confronting a decision they hoped they would never
have to face: whether to authorize the bombing of government
ministries in Belgrade, military factories throughout Yugoslavia
and other infrastructure listed in the third phase of their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Enlarging the target list required another meeting of the NATO
representatives, 19 of them now, since Poland, the Czech Republic
and Hungary had joined the alliance in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic seemed to be doing his best to head off an escalation
in the bombing campaign by using the Russians to launch a new
diplomatic initiative and receiving church officials in Belgrade, a
not-so-subtle appeal for an Easter pause, as well as sympathy from
Italy and Greece. And anxiety was growing in the Czech Republic
about the airstrikes, although its representative to NATO remained
supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is reading very carefully the cohesion of the alliance and
trying to identify cracks and exploit them,'' a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Klaus Naumann, the German officer who heads NATO's Military
Committee, sought to set the stage for an expansion in the target
list by telling diplomats in a closed-door meeting that military
plans usually stand up only until the battle begins, and then they
have to be adapted.
</P>
<P>
   With some allies nervous about the attacks on Yugoslavia's
infrastructure, a compromise was hammered out last week, which gave
Clark, the allied commander, more targeting flexibility, but not
the full range of targets in the third phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably a lot of different kind of things that
General Clark wants that he is not getting, whether it is
particular types of aircraft, as well as some specific targets he
is not yet authorized to strike,'' a senior NATO diplomat said.
``Overall, he is quite satisfied and impressed with the unity of
the alliance and its ability to make rapid decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark used his new flexibility early Saturday morning when NATO
sent cruise missiles flying at two Interior Ministry buildings in
the heart of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The strike showed that the alliance was prepared to attack
forces leading the campaign against the Kosovo Albanians and to
pierce the heart of the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   One senior alliance official, however, was skeptical of the
military utility of the cruise missile attack. By the time it
occurred _ 10 days into the air campaign _ there had been several
press reports that Clark had been pressing the alliance to put the
Interior Ministry buildings on his target list. Without the element
of surprise, it was very unlikely that the Serbs would be using the
buildings when they were attacked, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A DIFFERENT WAR
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Lessons Unused in Belgrade
</P>
<P>
   Some Air Force officers who commanded forces during the Persian
Gulf war say more broadly that NATO has moved too slowly to take
war to the enemy capital, and also allowed its fears of losing
pilots to make it overly cautious in attacking Serbian forces in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On the opening night of the Gulf war, allied warplanes headed
straight for downtown Baghdad. Glosson insisted that the allies
should have done more of the same in Belgrade, starting with key
nodes for controlling the nation's air defenses and communications
links in the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would also have taken out the television station, part of
the electricity and certainly some of the locations of his
political stalwarts,'' he added in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NATO officials said the attacks on Belgrade remain a
sensitive matter for members worried about civilian casualties, as
well as the perception that the alliance was waging a war against
the Yugoslav people, and not just the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belgrade is not going to be Baghdad,'' a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Some potential targets, officials said, are unlikely to be hit
at all. Milosevic's government palace, for instance, was scratched
from the target list because it was a cultural landmark.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, the NATO spokesman, Jamie Shea, suggested that
NATO might not try to destroy Yugoslavia's ability to broadcast
television programs. That was one of the first orders of business
in the Gulf war. Asked why Belgrade's television was still on the
air, Shea said, jokingly, that that was a decision for Belgrade
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials hope that their caution will serve a large goal:
enabling the alliance to hang together long enough to wage an air
campaign that could take weeks, perhaps months.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox, however, is that the self-imposed constraints may
end up prolonging the bombing, adding to the risk that the alliance
may eventually begin to splinter under the strain.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO diplomat said, ``This is an alliance effort and we
have to maintain a consensus for such a high-risk operation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
