</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS' DEFIANCE SMOLDERS AT TARGETS IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-KLA,
KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN, KOSOVO-CLINTON.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The two Interior Ministry buildings hit
by NATO cruise missiles overnight smoldered on Saturday in
Belgrade's morning haze, collapsed in on themselves at wacky
angles. They provided angry citizens with evidence of NATO's
astounding accuracy _ Yugoslav authorities said there were no
casualties of any kind _ and of the alliance's vow to strike
military and security headquarters, even in the heart of Serbia's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   But the first reactions were more defiant than defeatist.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bombs will just increase the sense that the world is
against us and we must stick together,'' said Dragan, 28, a chemist
attending the daily rock concert of solidarity in the city's
Republic Square who gave only his first name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting empty buildings will not affect this regime,'' he
said, brushing aside with a dismissive jerk of his head the idea
that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia was in any danger.
``Forget that story. They can hit one building after another, but
then what do they do? That's the whole question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has the best bunker in town,'' Dragan said. ``He'll
be the last Serb left alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The two buildings, both utterly destroyed by cruise-missile
strikes early Saturday morning, were the Yugoslav and Serbian
Ministries of the Interior, the headquarters for the police and the
special militarized police, who are most active in the fight
against the Kosovo Liberation Army and its ethnic Albanian civilian
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But officials who worked at low-level jobs in the buildings,
which had been well known as potential NATO targets, said Saturday
that both had been largely empty for more than a week. ``There
weren't even chairs,'' one woman said.
</P>
<P>
   But she could not say whether important equipment had remained
in the building or whether any underground communications centers
existed there.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said that pieces of the buildings flew 400 yards into
the air, and firefighters worked until nearly 6 a.m. to put out the
fires.
</P>
<P>
   The police cordoned off the area, and the Yugoslav army press
center was unable to obtain permission to let journalists inside,
or even to interview doctors and patients at the large university
hospital center only a few hundred yards from the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian state television, which went on the air very early
Saturday morning with dramatic footage of the fires, immediately
rebroadcast worldwide by international networks, concentrated
Saturday on the anger of doctors, patients and staff members of the
maternity, gynecological and psychiatric wards.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian interior minister, Vlajko Stojiljkovic, compared the
bombing to the Nazi Easter bombing of Belgrade in 1941 and called
NATO ``neo-Nazis.'' The missile strikes were, he said, ``the acts
of a monster criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are united and determined to save our country, to save our
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, state-run news outlets reported that
Milosevic had met top Serbian leaders and issued a statement
afterward emphasizing ``that bombs cannot damage the heroic spirit
of Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation is united in its determination to defend the
country from the aggressor,'' the statement said. ``Although the
aggressors bomb bridges, hospitals and civilian targets, the
institutions of the country function normally.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Praising the architecture of the two ministry buildings _
archetypal concrete-and-glass structures of the post-1945 communist
model _ Stojiljkovic said defiantly, ``Our children and
grandchildren will build even better buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief nurse of the maternity ward, Gordana Tasic, told state
television that about 70 newborn babies and their mothers were
safely evacuated to a basement shelter of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that it happened,'' she said. ``It's their
holiday today,'' she added, referring to the Western Easter, which
precedes the Serbs' Orthodox commemoration by a week. ``If they
believe in God, they should stop this. How are the babies guilty?
Let them at least leave the babies and the children alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital center had also taken precautions, a medical staff
member said privately.
</P>
<P>
   The central pharmacy had moved its stocks and computers to the
basement, and the maternity and psychiatric wards had sent all
ambulatory patients home.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one died, but everyone is very upset and angry,'' the staff
member said, describing how one woman who had just had emergency
abdominal surgery had to walk down stairs to the basement shelter.
</P>
<P>
   At the daily rock rally, musicians of all political stripes sang
a new anthem about Serbian unity that has swept the city. It was
written by a well-known nationalist performer, Bora Djordjevic,
known as Corba, or stew, from his band, Fish Stew. The song uses a
famous chorus of the ``Four S's'': ``Samo Sloga Srbina Spasava'' _
``Only unity saves the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Two verses translate: ``Now that they are bombing us, Serbs no
longer fight among themselves. For it is our slogan, that only
unity saves the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them come down to the ground,'' the song continues. ``Then
I will stop singing, look them in the eyes and fire without
hesitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is now completely unchallenged among Serbs, said Ivan,
25, who described himself as a ``former student'' who dislikes his
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stupid bombing makes Milosevic stronger every day,'' he
said. ``I believe that he must be America's player, because they
seem to make him stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-99 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABSTINENCE-EDUC-NYT &LR;      04-03 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABSTINENCE-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAMS ABOUT SEX ABSTINENCE HAVE IMPACT NATIONWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., N.J., Calif., N.H., Utah, La., S.C., S.D., N.Y.,
Conn.)   (bl)  
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the uproar when Congress set aside $50 million a year
for states to create abstinence-education programs teaching the
benefits of delaying sex until marriage, every state in the nation
ultimately applied for the money when it became available in fiscal
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But two states withdrew from the first year of the program,
according to a new report to be released Monday by the Sexuality
Information and Education Council of the United States, a nonprofit
group, and there are enormous variations in what the other states
are doing with the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Some have created classroom abstinence programs that, as the law
mandates, teach the harmful effects of sex outside marriage, while
others have spent the money on media campaigns encouraging parents
to talk to their children about sex, but never specifically linking
sex and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, the sky isn't falling, but the federal
abstinence-only program is beginning to change the landscape of
sexuality education,'' said Debra Haffner, the president of the
council, which advocates comprehensive sex education, including
contraceptive information. ``There were nearly 700 abstinence-only
grants nationwide, and five states have passed laws requiring that
sexuality education programs teach that delaying sex until marriage
is the expected standard for school-age children.''
</P>
<P>
   Most states, including New York and Connecticut, have split the
money between education programs, media campaigns and grants to
community organizations. But some states put all the money into one
approach.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, for example, the money has gone to the
schools, with 117 school districts and 21 charter schools receiving
grants to teach that the expected standard of human sexual activity
is ``mutually faithful monogamous heterosexual relationships in the
context of marriage.'' North Carolina also adopted a law requiring
school sex-education programs to teach that standard.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, where Gov. Christie Whitman decided not to use
the abstinence money in schools because the federal requirements
conflicted with state law mandating comprehensive sexuality
education, all the money went to community organizations for a
range of mentoring, recreational and other programs that are not
specifically confined to sex education.
</P>
<P>
   In the District of Columbia, Maine, Wyoming and elsewhere, the
survey found, the abstinence money was used to help develop media
campaigns. The District of Columbia emphasized self-esteem, Wyoming
adopted a themes of ``Sex Can Wait,'' aimed at 10- to 14-year-olds,
and Maine used 30-second television spots with the tag line, ``Not
Me, Not Now.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, after heated debated among legislators about
whether programs stressing abstinence until marriage actually
prevented young people from engaging in sexual behavior, the
lawmakers refused to appropriate the required matching state funds,
so no federally financed abstinence programs could be started.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, too, ultimately withdrew its application for the
money.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how states can, and should, use the money, which
they are required to match with $3 for every $4 received, remains a
polarizing issue. Many advocates of comprehensive sex education
still argue that a strict reading of the law interferes with
offering contraceptive information to sexually active young people.
Those who favor abstinence-only education complain that many states
are circumventing the law by using the money on things like
television commercials urging teens to delay sex until they are
ready, without ever mentioning marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things some states are doing seem to me to violate
the letter and the spirit of the law, `' said Peter Brandt,
director of the National Coalition for Abstinence Education in
Colorado Springs, a nonprofit group created to monitor how the
money is used.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're watering down the strong intent of the law,'' he said.
``Media campaigns can be very useful, but not these fuzzy
television messages we've seen in Kentucky or Massachusetts, about
not having sex until you're ready, where it's not tied to marriage
at all. It's not enough to tell a 15-year-old she should wait until
she's old enough and she's in a committed relationship. Every
15-year-old girl in America would say she's mature enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandt also said that many states were ignoring the requirement
in the federal law that the program to be financed have as its
``exclusive purpose'' the teaching of the benefits of abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   ``While mentoring or recreation can be part of a program,'' he
said, ``I don't think sponsoring a hockey league, as they're doing
in Utah, meets that requirement. The exclusive-purpose requirement
has pretty much been torn up by a lot of states.''
</P>
<P>
   Nan Streeter, the manager of Utah's reproductive health program,
said Brandt misunderstood the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Murray Boys and Girls Club, the grantee that has the
hockey league, uses multiple mechanisms to promote abstinence among
the youth they serve,'' she said. ``They work on good
decision-making, self-esteem, resiliency and refusal skills. But we
also recognize that when kids are playing hockey, or basketball,
it's hard for them to get involved in risky behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the states that used at least part of the federal money on
media campaigns, the report found, only four used `'abstinence
only, until marriage'' as their key message, while the majority
used a general abstinence message, or emphasized the importance of
adults, like parents or teachers, talking with young people about
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haffner of the Sexuality Information and Education Council
agreed that states varied in how strictly they construed the law,
with some working to find creative ways to use the Federal money
without excluding either gays or young people who were already
sexually active and in need of contraceptive information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states did exercise considerable latitude,'' she said. ``I
think they tried to use the money in a way that made sense to them.
For some, that meant public health campaigns generally promoting
abstinence to young people or encouraging parents to talk to their
children about these issues. For others, it meant following the
letter of the law exactly, teaching the harmful effects of anything
but abstinence until marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Three states, Louisiana, South Carolina and South Dakota,
declined to take part in the council's survey.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the survey found, 25 states used some of the federal
money for school programs, 23 used it for in-class instruction, and
most offered some after-school program as well. Junior high schools
were the most likely to have abstinence programs using the federal
money.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, the council's study found, the federal
abstinence money is handled by health departments, but in several,
the governor's office controls the program directly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
