<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOVOSO-POWELL-REVIEW-     04-03 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOVOSO-POWELL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWELL DOCTRINE IS LOOKING PRETTY GOOD AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Remember the Powell Doctrine?
</P>
<P>
   That was the strict and cautious set of standards espoused by
Gen. Colin Powell when he was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
for determining where, when and how U.S. military force should be
used.
</P>
<P>
   It held that the United States should intervene militarily only
when the nation's vital interests were at stake, only with decisive
force and only when there was a clear goal and a defined strategy
for getting out.
</P>
<P>
   But after the 1991 Persian Gulf war, those tenets were discarded
as Vietnam-era relics that raised barriers to military intervention
too high to suit the realities of today's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the point of having this superb military that you've
always been talking about if we can't use it?'' Madeleine Albright,
now secretary of state, demanded of Powell when she was the
country's United Nations ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   So the Clinton administration embraced Albright's ``Doability
Doctrine'' _ that the United States should use its military power
in more flexible ways to achieve practical, if limited, goals.
Successes in providing relief to Rwanda, mounting air strikes in
Bosnia and restoring some semblance of democracy in Haiti helped
bolster the new thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. Nearly two weeks of NATO bombing has failed to stop
the Yugoslav army's brutal removal of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo,
and starkly revealed the limitations of an air-only campaign in
trying to break President Slobodan Milosevic's will to wage war.
The capture of three U.S. soldiers along the Macedonia border only
made matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Powell's principles are looking a lot more attractive.
``This only affirms the Powell Doctrine,'' said Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who joined the growing chorus of those clamoring to send
ground troops into Kosovo. ``This is more reminiscent of the
gradual escalation and bombing pauses that characterized the
Vietnam War.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Powell broke his usually self-imposed silence on continuing
military operations last week, offering remarks that carried a
distinctly I-told-you-so ring. ``The challenge of just using air
power is that you leave it in the hands of your adversary to decide
when he's been punished enough,'' Powell told reporters before a
speech in Blacksburg, Va. ``So the initiative will remain with
President Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Powell principles served to neatly reconcile two strains of
U.S. foreign policy that have influenced U.S. administrations for
decades. One is never again to appease a tyrant who threatens vital
interests, as British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain did with
Hitler in Munich. With this goal painfully in mind, Clinton has
always regretted that the United States failed to address the
Bosnia problem sooner than it did.
</P>
<P>
   The second foreign policy strain weighing heavily on Clinton,
and at the heart of Powell's doctrine, is the conviction that U.S.
military forces should never again become bogged down in a quagmire
like Vietnam. A clear exit strategy now is supposed to be a
prerequisite for mounting a military operation.
</P>
<P>
   Powell believed that the military should be used only when the
country's vital interests were at stake and, when it was, used to
win and win quickly. Yet Albright has not been alone in championing
her vision of using military force as a more flexible instrument of
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1993, Powell's hand-picked successor, Gen. John
Shalikashvili, almost immediately began to distance himself from
his mentor's doctrine. Shalikashvili broadened it to include
important interests that affected the nation's well-being, if not
its very survival, along with humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powell was good for a period of time,'' said Gen. George
Joulwan, a retired commander of U.S. forces in Latin America and
Europe, who supervised the Rwanda relief operation. ``But we must
be able to adapt to the new challenges we face.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joulwan cautioned that there are still Powell principles
worth remembering, like maintaining a clear political and military
objective. ``Sometimes the State Department likes to have fuzziness
in all this, but when you commit forces, you have to have
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Scowcroft, President George Bush's national security
adviser, agreed. ``You have to tailor the use of force to the
objectives you're trying to achieve,'' he said. ``But you've got to
know what you're trying to do. You've got to look at all the
alternatives, and not just say, `We'll do this and hope it works.'
What if it doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
   And here is where, critics say, the Clinton administration
blundered in Kosovo. While the objectives may have been clear _ to
stop Serb brutality, expel Yugoslav forces from Kosovo and force
Milosevic to the peace table _ the execution was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, NATO drew up plans that could have satisfied the
demands of the Powell Doctrine, calling for as many as 200,000
allied troops to occupy Yugoslavia _ about 75,000 for Kosovo alone
_ if Belgrade refused to negotiate. Administration officials
gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Congress would oppose NATO ground troops, administration
officials said. And few in Washington predicted that the 19-member
alliance would remain united behind a land campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem was that no one on Capitol Hill had signed on
to that,'' said an administration official deeply involved in the
planning for Kosovo. ``This administration was operating on the
assumption ground troops would raise this to a new level, and we
hadn't prepared public for that or gotten the allies on board.''
</P>
<P>
   So President Clinton and NATO turned to the air campaign, even
though U.S. intelligence analysts and the Joint Chiefs of Staff
warned them that an aerial bombardment wouldn't work, and might
even hasten the Serb offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told lawmakers in private meetings that air power had
driven Milosevic to the Bosnia peace talks in Dayton, Ohio, in
1995. But in fact, the air campaign was successful because a joint
offensive by Bosnian Muslim and Croatian forces changed the
equation on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying we won't send in ground troops may be good for American
domestic political consumption, but it tells Milosevic there's a
limit to our commitment,'' said Maj. Gen. William Nash, a retired
commander of U.S. troops in Bosnia. ``He calculates there's no
reason for him to give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the air campaign has been politically shackled. Explicit in
the Powell Doctrine's notion of overwhelming force were the goals
of winning quickly while keeping casualties low and maintaining
public support.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the Balkans, the goals haven't meshed well. When fog and
rain set in, NATO commanders called off bombing runs because they
didn't want pilots to have to fly under the clouds and face a
greater risk of ground-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   And even as U.S. political leaders fear for their pilots in the
sky, they also fear civilian casualties on the ground. So NATO
hesitated last week before attacking government ministries in
Belgrade, targets dear to Milosevic's hold on power. Such
hesitation offers him another reason to hold firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-99 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
