<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4693 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW-     04-03 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-TECH THREAT WITH A LOW-TECH TRACK RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The warnings from Washington were clear. Spy satellites and high
technology eavesdropping equipment will be monitoring your forces
in Kosovo, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was told last
week. Any evidence of atrocities carried out by Serbian soldiers
will be forwarded to the War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is extremely alarmed by reports of an
escalating pattern of Serbian attacks on Kosovar Albanian
civilians,'' said James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman.
``We are using our national technical means to observe events in
Kosovo and are prepared to share that information.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech saber rattling was meant to conjure up certain
images in the Serbian leader's mind: stark aerial photographs of
swaths of freshly turned earth near Srebrenica, Bosnia, in 1995. In
a dramatic presentation to the United Nations Security Council,
Madeleine Albright, who was then the chief U.S. delegate to the
United Nations, unveiled detailed overhead photographs of what
appeared to be mass graves near Srebrenica, which had recently
fallen to Bosnian Serb forces despite its status as an area that
the United Nations had declared a safe haven for Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 Muslim men are believed to have been killed by the
Bosnian Serbs after Srebrenica fell, and war crimes investigators
later exhumed the graves and found the bodies of dozens. If such
savagery occurs in Kosovo, Milosevic was implicitly warned, it too
will be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic may not be so frightened by such threats. Three
and a half years later, Srebrenica stands as an example not of the
power of U.S. technology but of its limits; even more clearly, it
also stands as an example of how any technology can be rendered
superfluous in the absence of political will.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. satellites and spy planes indeed captured images of a dozen
suspected mass graves around Srebrenica in the summer and fall of
1995. But war crimes investigators who entered Bosnia the following
spring to exhume the graves after the signing of the Dayton, Ohio,
peace accords were troubled by their findings. Several of the
graves appeared to have been exhumed already _ by the Bosnian
Serbs. Hundreds of bodies were missing.
</P>
<P>
   A t the time, U.S. officials, who had promised that the graves
would be monitored by spy planes and satellites, said they had no
images of Bosnian Serbs removing bodies. Several explanations were
possible. Perhaps U.S. spy planes and satellites had not been
monitoring the graves as promised. Perhaps the satellites had
failed to capture the Bosnian Serb exhumations because they either
passed overhead at the wrong time or could not see through clouds.
Or perhaps the Americans had the images but, for whatever reason,
would not give them to tribunal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   So the hunt for bodies continues around Srebrenica two years
later. Only about 1,500 of the presumed 7,000 have been recovered.
Breakthroughs last spring came from low-technology sources. A
Bosnian Serb reported seeing suspicious activity in one area where
graves were later found, and a NATO work crew widening a road dug
up what turned out to be a mass grave.
</P>
<P>
   But looming far larger than the shortcomings in finding
Srebrenica's victims has been a lack of will to arrest the
perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Bosnian Serb troops who carried out the
executions, Gen. Ratko Mladic, and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic have both been indicted for command responsibility at
Srebrenica, but neither has been arrested and Mladic has reportedly
lived safely in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   While peacekeeping forces in Bosnia have arrested some low-level
officials, U.S. and European fears of heavy casualties have halted
attempts to arrest top leaders. And the international war crimes
tribunal itself has at times been slow to press the Americans for
intelligence, mount investigations of war crimes in Kosovo or
investigate Milosevic himself.
</P>
<P>
   Given that record, Milosevic seems unlikely to tremble at the
threat posed to him by U.S. surveillance equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The spy technology also appears, in one sense, to be a
double-edged sword.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a coalition of groups demanding stronger U.S.
action in Kosovo called on the Clinton administration to release
all aerial reconnaissance photos documenting human rights
violations in Kosovo. Now that the administration has used spy
photos to expose one atrocity, it is expected to capture evidence
of another and release it.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Basseuner, associate director of the Balkan Action Council,
accused the administration of trying to use vows of high-technology
monitoring as a substitute for bold action. ``I get the feeling
that they're saying that,'' he said, referring to the monitoring,
``as a filler to get around the fact that they're not fighting this
war with the drive that they should.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
