<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-810(     04-03 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-810(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC IS PLAYING TO TWO AUDIENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-KLA,
KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN, KOSOVO-CLINTON.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Clinton may seem tired and worn
these days, but President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia is
looking on top of his little world.
</P>
<P>
   With no contentious U.S. electorate or media to distract him,
Milosevic is riding above the fray, while his army and his police
are capturing (or abducting) American soldiers, shooting down a
stealth airplane and expelling ethnic Albanians from Kosovo in
numbers beyond any Washington policy-maker's most embarrassing
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the confusing structure of the federal Information
Ministry, the Serbian Information Ministry, the military press
center and Serbian state television, there is a clear understanding
that Milosevic is playing now to two audiences: domestic and
international, especially American.
</P>
<P>
   While his voice is rarely heard, even on state television, film
of his beaming, seemingly genial chat sessions are being broadcast
repetitively around the world, in part because the news channels
can get so little footage of their own past the Serbian censors.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO is pounding his country _ including, now, his capital
_ from the air, Milosevic, portly and smiling, is meeting Vatican
envoys, Russian delegations and a moderate ethnic Albanian leader
and talking of peace. His military seems to be withstanding NATO's
might, and his people, who don't especially like him, are rallying
around him anyway, as the commander in chief of an embattled
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no fifth column in Serbia now,'' said Vuk Draskovic,
the former anti-Milosevic democracy campaigner who was co-opted
into the government before the war began. ``We're all one party
now. We're all under one banner, the Yugoslav banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Zorana Ilic, a 32-year-old pharmacist interviewed on Saturday in
the crowded downtown streets, said the destruction of the Interior
Ministry buildings overnight would have little effect on the regime
or on ordinary Serbs, who are simply being driven closer together _
here and in the diaspora abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just now, there are 13 million people who are at the same time
against him and for him,'' she said. ``He will be even stronger now
than before it started. I don't know why American analysts even get
a salary.''
</P>
<P>
   People are afraid, of course, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to die, even from a fine, democratic American
bomb,'' she said. ``But people conquer their fear by standing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dejan Anastasijevic, an analyst for Vreme magazine, said the
Belgrade strikes were symbolic, meant to show Milosevic that the
alliance could hit any target.
</P>
<P>
   ``But NATO took a great risk of civilian casualties, with a
hospital so nearby, just to demonstrate that it can destroy two
totally empty office buildings,'' he said. ``This has not damaged
Milosevic's standing or his capacity to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Milosevic met with other senior officials and
issued a statement afterward praising ``the heroic spirit of
Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Another typically controlled triumph was his televised meeting
on Thursday with Ibrahim Rugova, the moderate, pacifist ethnic
Albanian leader. The meeting shocked Washington, coming on the same
day that the three U.S. soldiers were captured along the Macedonian
border. Rugova had signed the Western-drafted peace settlement
rejected by the Serbs and had been overshadowed by the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   He had reportedly sought the protection of the Serbian police in
Pristina's chaos. But suddenly he was sitting happily with
Milosevic in equal armchairs opposing NATO bombing and vowing to
pursue a political solution. For whatever reason, and perhaps under
duress, Rugova appeared to be breaking ranks as the rebels and
their supporters were being swept from Kosovo, an extraordinary
public relations coup for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The voice of neither man could be heard on television, and
requests to interview Rugova afterward went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there any way to evaluate Milosevic's tactics, which
Western diplomats fear will include an internal agreement with
Rugova on political autonomy for Kosovo and an invitation for
refugees to return, but with no peacekeeping or verification role
for NATO or any international organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the first NATO bombs in Belgrade, state
television concentrated on comparisons to the Nazi bombing of
Belgrade, also at Easter, in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than spending too much time praising the Interior
Ministry and the activities of its troops and police _ no one's
favorite authorities _ television emphasized the evacuation of
wards in the nearby hospital, with its frightened mothers, angry
staff members, and newborn babies lying in rows in a basement
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Television has also reveled in the embarrassment of Clinton at
the capture of three U.S. soldiers, who the Yugoslavs insist had
crossed the border into Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A military court has begun an investigation into their case,
collecting evidence to see if they should be brought to trial. But
there has been no response to Clinton's demands that they be
released, and no indication of where they are being held. The
supposition here is that Milosevic will not hurry either to try or
to release them, but there was little information about them in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, too, Milosevic benefits enormously from
Yugoslavia's own wartime censorship, which has also allowed the
government to accelerate its war against independent media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The independent radio station B-92, which had its transmitter
disabled just before the bombs fell but which was broadcasting on
satellite and the Internet, was silenced early Friday through a
legal maneuver that put the station under government control.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, a number of other independent newspapers and
radio stations were closed throughout Kosovo, and Radio 021 in Novi
Sad, the northern Serbian city some 250 miles from Kosovo where
NATO attacks destroyed one of two bridges across the Danube.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministry officials have excoriated NATO for destroying
the bridge, which they called a purely civilian target. Rade
Drobac, a senior Foreign Ministry official, asked in an interview,
``How does destroying a bridge and the city's water supply help the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo?''
</P>
<P>
   He said the bridge was a famous landmark, for in 1941, thousands
of Serbs and Jews were murdered on it and thrown into the river. He
said there was also damage to a 16th-century Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Drobac said that the Milosevic-Rugova meeting ``demonstrates
that at least one part of the Albanian leaders understands that
what NATO is doing is a misuse of them for NATO's goals.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Kosovo Liberation Army was almost completely
destroyed, ``so there are no more terrorists for the United States
to support with its bombing.'' Why not stop the bombs, Drobac
asked, ``to allow others, normal citizens, to return home in
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that Serbia would keep all of Kosovo. ``I assure
you,'' he said, ``that no Serb can accept the partition of his
state.''
</P>
<P>
   A young Serb named Zoran, no fan of Milosevic, said he
nonetheless admired his president's tactical acuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all his faults, Milosevic is a hero now,'' he said. ``The
Serbs are proud of fighting for Kosovo, which is ours. We are
fighting the greatest power in the world, and even losing proudly
is a victory. Just standing up to such power is a victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
