<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASTER-PLAY04-COX     04-03 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-PLAY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Easter morning service put into pictures'
 &HT;    By Kim Grizzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARM LIFE, N.C. _ This land never was much good for corn.
</P>
<P>
   It just wouldn't grow there. Stephen Manning didn't know if
anything would until that cool spring night his daughter started
carrying quilts out the door of his family's Martin County
farmhouse. They were for the crowds that had gathered on the front
lawn to watch a passion play put on by a country church.
</P>
<P>
   The ground was cold, and there was nowhere else to sit.
</P>
<P>
   By the next spring, Manning and his fellow members at Piney
Grove Baptist Church had pushed up some dirt and put up bleachers.
The corn field had become a mission field, where the church would
tell the story of Jesus to anyone who could figure out how to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to say the land was no good for raising corn, so we'd
see if we could raise some Christians on it,'' Manning's widow,
Nancy, recalled. ``They're still using our little corn field.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, the little corn field has seating for more
than 2,000, along with computerized lighting and sound systems.
Parking attendants direct traffic generated by hundreds of cars and
a dozen or more tour buses that arrive on any given night for ``The
Message of Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see those people coming across the field, it's
overwhelming to think these people have driven hundreds of miles
and come out here in the middle of nowhere,'' said Jimmy Griffin,
who has played Jesus all 20 years of the production. ``People
coming in the Trailways buses, the church buses, the vans _ people
I've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   They come from Raleigh, Rocky Mount, Winston-Salem and parts of
Virginia to see a play with no advertising budget and an
all-amateur cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have old farmers who you would not think would do this _
get up there and act,'' said Manning, who plays Mary, the mother of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who does the high priest, he used to be a parts
salesman. He's retired now; he's a dog catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just ordinary people, being used in an extraordinary
way. We don't have any special talent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning
</P>
<P>
   There were no tour buses that first year. It was mostly folks
from neighboring churches who turned out to watch the cast _
wearing costumes sewn from old bedspreads and curtains _ walk
through scenes while a narrator read from a script.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a thrown-together set,'' Griffin said. ``The rock
was made out of papier-mache. If it got wet, it would start
sagging, so we had to take it in every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, there were casting conflicts. Director and
playright E.T. Taylor had to cast himself as the ringleader of
sorts in the angry mob that demanded that Jesus be put to death.
None of the other church members would agree to take on the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult to get people to yell, `You're a liar!'
or `Crucify him!' anything derogatory to Christ,'' Taylor recalled.
``You're taking Christian people and asking them to do something
that is totally against what they would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult job. But slowly people were able to.
We have had people who have been in it all 20 years that to this
day will not say, `Crucify him!'''
</P>
<P>
   While others have volunteered for parts, church members are cast
in every role, a difficult task considering that about 250 people
attend the church and more than 150 are involved in the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of one family that's not involved,'' said Todd
Moore, who is in his first year as pastor at Piney Grove. Those who
are not in the cast help out with scenery, costumes and parking
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pretty much takes our membership,'' said Robert Perry, who
portrays one of the disciples. ``When a kid can walk, he's in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Church members do not age out from the drama as they grow older,
although the number of steps leading to the Upper Room has forced
some ``disciples'' into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Danny Griffin has had to climb the three flights
of steps that lead to the control tower. This season will be his
last as technical director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years is a long time,'' he said. ``There's no way you
can do something for 20 years and not miss it, but it's time to
bring in some new blood, some new ideas, some new energy for a new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   In two decades, Danny Griffin has perhaps seen the most change
of anyone involved with the drama. He has seen the production
through the transformation from reel-to-reel tape to computerized
sound. He once had an amplifier blow out in the middle of the
drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to send the preacher out on the field and shout it out
as best he could,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing sometimes when we look at it. When I realize
where it's come from, it's been an amazing transformation how the
whole thing comes together. Certainly we realize that the Lord's
hand is in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blessed connections
</P>
<P>
   What else, members insist, could explain the way the church has
managed to support the drama without ever charging for admission?
There are no parking fees, no popcorn or programs to buy. There are
no pledge envelopes or donation boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we need has come almost like miracles to us,''
Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can tell you stories about the man who came to us and
wanted to build us a road. The road that we came in on was just a
sandy path, and he was a road builder. He brought in rock and built
us a rock road all the way up to the set. We didn't ask him at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens all the time. The state puts up road signs for us
on Highway 17. We've just had a lot of `blessed connections,' we
call them.''
</P>
<P>
   The prophesy
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they call them, members of the Farm Life community
don't call these things coincidences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in coincidence,'' said local naturalist and
author Gail Roberson, whose great-great grandfather preached at
Piney Grove even before there was a church. Roberson, who has
written extensively about the play, believes a passage in the Rev.
Bytha Leggett's faded journal foretells the success of the drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are a special breed of people,'' the journal entry
reads. ``I sense that in the future will open a door to them, and
that through this door will walk many. It is my belief that someday
this church will put forth new seed that will ... witness to hordes
of people that will come forth to them. These people are likely to
push up a new ground and sow forth new crops. They will succeed
where others will not. How much a part of this I wish I could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson shared the passage with the church in 1985, the sixth
season of the drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read the quote many times, but it had been many years,''
she recalled. ``But when I was out there that night, something took
a hold of me. It was as if suddenly my mind was remembering that
line.''
</P>
<P>
   When she returned home that night, Roberson took out the journal
and looked for the passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had earmarked that page,'' she said. ``It just shows me that
it was supposed to be. It blows your mind the more you realize
about it. It makes the hair stand up on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest story
</P>
<P>
   Taylor knows this story about the drama, but he pays little
attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether that was a prediction come true or not, I don't
know,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The greater story, he said, is the one told by the drama, which
is based on the four Gospels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest story that's ever been told,'' Taylor said.
``This is not entertainment. It never was intended to be
entertainment. That's not the purpose in it. This is the Easter
morning service put into pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of the drama, the audience was made up of
people who recognized those pictures, fellow Christians who already
knew the Easter story. Over the years, the church has aimed its
drama ministry at different groups. Now one night's performance is
done in Spanish, and another is for the hearing impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started it, our crowds were churched people,''
said cast member Perry. ``We were `preaching to the choir.' Now
we're preaching to people who are probably unchurched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, I quit seeing people coming. I started seeing souls
coming. That sort of makes it different.''
</P>
<P>
   Touching lives
</P>
<P>
   The church receives cards and letters from people who say the
drama has touched their lives _ even changed them.
</P>
<P>
   Messages posted on the drama's Web site testify what the drama
has meant to the people who have seen it.
</P>
<P>
   One is from Tracey Gray of Chocowinity, who first saw the drama
when she was in high school. She remembers coming down the path to
the outdoor theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that went through my mind,'' Gray recalled, `I
looked at my mama and said, `This ain't going to be worth watching.
It can't be. It's out in the woods.'''
</P>
<P>
   She's been nearly every year since. Her mother died a few years
ago; now Tracey takes her own child to see the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to see this drama has almost become a part of our Easter
tradition,'' she said. ``To me, Easter's not here until you see
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like these people are doing this from their hearts. You
can tell when something is genuine. I honestly feel like God is
behind this because they could not have kept this going for 20
years it he wasn't in it.''
</P>
<P>
   20 years
</P>
<P>
   The church never planned on more than four performances. The
first year, they gave six. Today, there are a dozen performances a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably not in our wildest dreams did we think it would last
this long,'' Perry said. ``It became very apparent over the years
that it was something the Lord handed to us. We certainly couldn't
do this on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the ministry that crew our of a corn field is
dumbfounding to cast members, who say they can't understand it, let
alone take credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply do not understand why it touches people,'' Manning
said. ``Why plain people can do something and it touches people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how all that happened. We just sit back in
awe and watch them come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
