<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-DEATH04-COX     04-03 2251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-DEATH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A death in the family
 &HT;    By Janet Jacobs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOGAN, Texas _ As a family, they shared their grief.
</P>
<P>
   Side by side in the dark-paneled sanctuary of the Full Gospel
Church, the people of Logan stood with their hands outstretched,
rocking and calling for God's comfort after two members of their
community had been slain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mourners were husband and wife, Gary and Peggy
Matthews. Each of them had lost a brother _ one who was killed, the
other accused of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   But no divisions were apparent because most of the people in
this community are related.
</P>
<P>
   Leading both funerals in October was the Rev. Corwin Barnett,
uncle of the accused, and a childhood friend of one of the victims.
Suppressing his own emotions, Barnett called for healing in the
tightknit community.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said they couldn't believe the love shown in each
service,'' Barnett said, remembering that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sweet spirit that was there.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrest
</P>
<P>
   Logan's 300 or so residents live in clusters of modest homes and
trailers separated by miles of one-lane roads winding through
stands of tall pine in southern Panola County.
</P>
<P>
   Too small to have its own police force, Logan depends on Panola
County Sheriff Jack Ellett, a tall rangy man with a tanned and
deeply-lined face. Six months after the alleged crime, the normally
reticent Ellett shrugs and explains what most of the people in
Logan already know: the details of how Paul Cobble and Farrell
Rutherford were shot and why Roger Matthews was charged with
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ellett said the police radio he keeps in his house suddenly came
alive on the night of Oct. 24 with a confusion of voices summoning
deputies, ambulances and a justice of the peace to pronounce
someone dead.
</P>
<P>
   The first call was from D.W. Matthews, father of Roger Matthews,
47.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the scene, Ellett flips through files containing
witnesses' statements and deputies' reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Matthews was initially at his father's residence, where
they were having a wienie roast in back of the house,'' Ellett
explained. ``He'd left there earlier, and he'd gone to his friend
Farrell Rutherford's home.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputies later found Rutherford, 66, shot through the chest,
sitting in the shed next to his trailer home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Roger returned to his father's house, he had a rifle with
him, and he demanded his father's car,'' Ellett said.
</P>
<P>
   D.W. Matthews told the officers his son threatened him with the
rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ```He put the gun to my chest and demanded my keys,''' Ellett
quoted, reading from reports. ``He said, `I'm going to kill Mart
and Andy Gibbs.'''
</P>
<P>
   More than 15 years earlier, Roger's youngest brother, Ronnie,
had been killed in a fight with the Gibbs brothers. It was ruled
self-defense, Ellett said.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of going to the Gibbs' home, the sheriff said
Matthews headed for the home of Paul Cobble, 35. Cobble was
Matthews' best friend and the brother of his sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The second call for help came from Tammy Cobble, Paul's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told the officers that Roger had killed her husband,''
Ellett said. ``We knew who we were looking for even before we knew
we had another victim at the Rutherford residence.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputies Greg Ilmedia and Kenneth Edgmon began looking for Roger
and found him less than two miles away, sitting in the car at his
father's house, Ellett said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 light blue Buick sat facing the road with the
headlights on and the engine running. Through the glare of the
headlights, Roger Matthews' 6-foot, 250-pound frame could be seen
sitting behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies cautiously approached, guns drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got out and left the rifle in the front seat,'' Ellett
said. ``Roger put his hands in the air and said `I was waiting for
y'all.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Roger Matthews told officers he didn't remember what took
place that night, Ellett said. Family members said he cried when he
was told why he was in jail.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a Panola County grand jury charged Roger Matthews
with two counts of capital murder and one count of aggravated
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Matthews was determined sane and fit to stand
trial, said Panola County District Attorney Danny Buck Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   A trial could be scheduled as soon as June, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Family ties
</P>
<P>
   The slayings are especially disturbing to the people of Logan
because Matthews is accused of killing two men who were both
friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some way down the line, 90 percent of the people in this part
of the country are kin to each other,'' said Ricky Nunley, whose
house sits less than 200 yards from the trailer where Farrell
Rutherford was shot. He is also a distant cousin of Rutherford's.
</P>
<P>
   The men in Logan consider Roger Matthews ``a good old boy.'' He
is described as ``an excellent chess player,'' ``a man's man'' and
``someone who would do anything for you _ if he wasn't drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews occasionally worked on construction sites or fixing
cars, but he seldom held a job for more than a few days. He
preferred to work a little and hang around a lot, family members
said, not unkindly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was sober, you couldn't ask for a better friend,''
said Jerrold Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of them were friends of mine,'' he said, referring
to the victims and the accused. Price said he is distantly related
to Rutherford and Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   Price looked up from the tractor wheel he was greasing, his eyes
searching for the trailer home where Rutherford died. ``People are
just hurt. It hurt me. It hurt to know a friend would do another
friend like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He, like others in the community, felt Matthews was a
predictable danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't afraid of him, but he'd hurt you,'' Price said.
``When he'd get drunk, you'd know before the next sun up, someone
was going to get hurt. He was going to hit someone.''
</P>
<P>
   When Matthews hit someone, it was not an issue to be taken
lightly, Price cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could pick up this tractor,'' Price said, gesturing to the
huge steel machine baking in the sun. ``He was a man; he weren't no
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Price felt Roger Matthews was a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played guitar together,'' he said, remembering good times
with Matthews. ``He could make a guitar talk.''
</P>
<P>
   One account
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Cobble, who says she saw Roger Matthews shoot her husband,
chain-smokes as she describes that night, her voice shaking with
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just busted in the door one night and decided he was God,''
she said bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   That night while Paul sat on the couch, smoking a cigarette and
watching TV, Tammy was cleaning the kitchen and preparing to lock
up for the night. Her children from a previous marrige were staying
overnight with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy heard a knock and seconds later, Roger Matthews pushed in
the door, knocking her back into the wall, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said 'Paul, it's Roger and he's got a gun.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger said, 'I thought you were my brother.' Paul said 'What
you talking about?' and Roger shot him twice. Then he pulled the
gun up on me,'' Tammy said.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Cobble raced down the hall and out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went around the house and kept falling over the rocks and
ladders. I reached the gate and cut my finger trying to get through
the barbed wire,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   As she crouched in the tall grass outside her home, trying to
use the darkness as cover, she heard Roger calling to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying 'I can hear you. I'm going to find you,'''
Tammy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he couldn't hear me, because I was holding my breath,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy can't say how long Matthews is supposed to have searched
for her. It might have been minutes, but it seemed like hours.
Finally she heard a car pulling out of the gravel driveway,
spitting rocks up from under its wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house, Paul was face-down on the floor. Although
Tammy had the phone in her hand, she didn't think to call 911. She
called her family for help.
</P>
<P>
   Between calls, she ran back and forth from the kitchen to Paul's
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling him to hold on, it was going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard gurgling noises,'' she said. ``And his face was
turning black. There was just a little bit of blood on his chest,
but a lot on his face. I thought he was shot in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers and family members, aroused by a relay of phone
calls, arrived about the same time, according to Tammy, with cars
lined up for a half mile down the one-lane road that leads to her
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like hundreds of people were in her house that night,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials told her Paul was dead, and they removed his body. In
her grief, she drove her family away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shoved everybody out of the house. Even my mother. I went
into the kitchen, got some soapy water and started cleaning it up
so the kids wouldn't see it,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the last thing I could do for Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   Reputation around town Sheriff Ellett paused while trying to
think of a diplomatic way to describe Roger Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a history of doing things that are against the law.
How's that?'' he finally said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Logan feared Roger, but they felt his danger was
predictable, according to Nunley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was smoking pot or drinking beer, Roger ain't that bad,
he's just mouthy,'' Nunley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main time he would get real bad off and want to fight
somebody was when he was on whiskey or hard liquor. He was always
trying to fight somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to stay away from him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nunley was one of the first people on the scene when Farrell
Rutherford's body was found, still sitting in a chair in the open
shed next to the trailer he called home. His long, thin body had
folded over, and his face rested on his knees.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nunley, an empty bottle of vodka was sitting
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The duty of telling B.J. ``Jay'' Rutherford that his brother was
dead fell to Roger Matthews' father and brother.
</P>
<P>
   D.W. Matthews was crying when he came to the house that night,
Jay Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said 'I'd rather cut my arm off than tell you what I'm
going to tell you.''' Jay Rutherford recalled. ``He said 'Roger
done shot Farrell.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jay went to his brother's trailer and angrily demanded that
deputies allow him to check his brother's body for a pulse. Farrell
had been shot once, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the heart,'' Jay Rutherford said, poking himself in
the center of his breastbone.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Rutherford had seen his older brother alive was
around sundown on Oct. 24. He was driving home for dinner when he
saw Farrell and Roger Matthews sitting together under the cover of
the shed, he said. He honked as he drove past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both waved,'' he said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle
</P>
<P>
   Peggy and Gary Matthews live together amid divided family
loyalties. Their 28-year-marriage straddles the fault line created
that murderous night.
</P>
<P>
   Gary is Roger Matthews' older brother. Peggy is Paul Cobble's
older sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a place where we don't talk much about it,'' Peggy
Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband hasn't been to jail to visit Roger, nor has he gone
to any of the hearings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if he died to Gary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A spiritual woman with a soft voice and dark hair, Peggy talks
about her family's turmoil matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   What may have gone on between their brothers hasn't damaged
their marriage, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it's drawn us closer,'' she said. ``Gary has
always been my strength, and I've always leaned on him. Now, he's
letting me know he needs my strength.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the healing process, they are trying to focus on
their grandchildren and the future, she said. She and Gary have
four children, three of them grown, and three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at me and say, 'She should be bitter, she should
be angry,' but I'm not,'' Peggy Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Destroying Roger will not bring my brother back,'' she said
sadly. ``It won't restore my family the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Matthews balances her mother's feelings for those of her
in-laws. ``If I just knew why, maybe it would help,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary couldn't help it. Peggy couldn't help it,'' explained
Pastor Barnett. ``But when it's all said and done, each one of them
is a brother short.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking answers
</P>
<P>
   Why Matthews would target his friends is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell Rutherford's neighbor, Ricky Nunley, considered the
question, leaning against the side of his pickup, one hand tucked
into the bib of his overalls, the other holding a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what puzzles everybody,'' he said. ``Why Paul?''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Cobble thinks it was jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People took Paul into their homes _ into their hearts, and not
Roger,'' she said. ``He couldn't stand to not be loved again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerrold Price isn't so sure there is a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Paul?'' he said, repeating Nunley's question. ``Why
Farrell? Farrell couldn't hurt nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand it,'' he said. ``I think about it every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the family bonds uniting the people of Logan aren't strong
enough to withstand all that has happened, according to Jerrold
Price, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some people, and I'm not going to tell you who,''
Price said, ``but there's some who say if he does get out, they'll
kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
