<HEADER>
A4703 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     04-03 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 4, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kosovo-related stories &LR;  (Moving in the `i' category):
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW (Undated) _ The NATO attack on Serbia has
provoked strong opposition from many Eastern Orthodox Christians
and nations, raising the question whether there is in fact an
`Orthodox world' in the East that differs fundamentally from the
West in its values and principles, that perceives the NATO attacks
not as a moral crusade against a clear evil, but as a hypocritical
Western assault against an Eastern Orthodox nation. By Serge
Schmemann. (on the section dress page)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW (Washington) _ The Powell Doctrine was a
strict and cautious policy _ espoused by Gen. Colin Powell when he
was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff _ holding that the U.S.
should intervene militarily only when its vital interests are at
stake, only with decisive force, and only when there is a clear
goal and a defined strategy for getting out. After the 1991 Gulf
war, this idea was discarded as a post-Vietnam relic unsuited to
today's world. But the debacle in Kosovo is suddenly making
Powell's principles look more attractive. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Slobodan Milosevic must be
laughing at U.S. threats to use high technology to hold him
accountable. Three years after the U.S. vowed to uncover evidence
of mass executions at Srebrenica, it seems clear that there are
limits to U.S. technology and that technology can be rendered
superfluous if it is used to mask a lack of political will. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW _ Early summary: some
prognistications on what the Balkan region may be like two or three
years from now. By Roger Cohen. (on the section dress page)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other stories &LR;  (Moving in the `a' category):
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNITY-POLICING-REVIEW (Undated) _ New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has ostentatiously rejected proposals to implement
community policing, deriding such programs as turning police
officers into social workers. But, perhaps to Giuliani's surprise,
community policing is alive and working successfully in many
cities, from Chicago to San Diego and from Fort Wayne to Fort
Worth. By Fox Butterfield. (on the section dress page)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-PRIVACY-REVIEW (San Francisco) _ Hidden in the
Microsoft Word document that carried the Melissa virus around the
world was an innocuous serial number that may help identify the
computer with which the program was written. It is a powerful
illustration of how technology has growing power for promoting both
good and evil, and is the heart of arguments over tradeoffs between
individual privacy rights and the common good. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-MEDICARE-REVIEW (Washington) _ The trustees report'
extending the projected solvency of Social Security and Medicare by
a few years was political manna for Congress. It made the problem
seem less urgent and provided an excuse for postponing tough
decisions until after the next elections. But demographic data
buried in the trustees' report illustrated why the matter cannot be
put off indefinitely. By David E. Rosenbaum. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MCGWIRE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Mark McGwire's eyes lit up.
Expecting another `Can you hit 70 home runs again?'
question-and-answer fest, the St. Louis slugger was treated to the
first-ever reverse interview: He got to put questions to other
people, for a change. By Alan Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   DEPORT-VETERANS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Recent laws requiring the
deportation of resident aliens for minor offenses are being
challenged by supporters of several U.S. military veterans who face
expulsion under the law. Through legal challenges and a publicity
campaign on behalf of the veterans (at least one of who is disabled
due to combat wounds) the law's opponents are targeting what they
hope will prove to be its Achilles' heel: its extreme
inflexibility. By Mirta Ojita.
</P>
<P>
   SATIRICAL-WEBSITES-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at Web sites that
make fun of companies. The sites allow disgruntled consumers to
express themselves. The target companies don't seem to see the
humor in this, so they're fighting back with their most familiar
weapon: money. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The publishing industry _ no
stranger to overstatement _ has for a long time been cranking out
multitudes of `bibles' on popular subjects _ the Barbecue Bible,
the Bartender's Bible, etc.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The confusion over the definition of
a blue moon, and some other highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-LANGUAGE-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ Many middle-aged and elderly
Japanese must struggle through what seems like an endless language
school. In restaurants, in stores, in newspapers, on TV and in
conversation with young people, they find themselves bewildered by
what seems like an explosion of English and other foreign-language
terms. By Nicholas D. Kristof. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
