<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING MAY HOLD THE KEY TO VAN GUNDY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 36, Patrick Ewing makes no apologies for becoming a creature
of habit. Same workout regimen. Same fade-away jump shot. Same
restaurants after the game. Same old Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeff Van Gundy, it's a good thing that Ewing is as loyal as
he is stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't want to play for another coach,'' Ewing said last
week. ``I don't want to play for Phil Jackson. Phil Jackson can
take his behind back to Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing may be in the twilight of his brilliant career, but the
Knicks' franchise center can apparently still execute a power play.
His endorsement of Van Gundy _ at a time when the coach's job
security and his relationship with Knicks management are tenuous at
best _ may be a factor in the club's decision about whether to
retain Van Gundy after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said he met last week with Dave Checketts, the president
of Madison Square Garden, and received guarantees from Checketts
that no coaching changes would be made this season or next season.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts confirmed the meeting through a spokesman, but would
not divulge specifics. But a team official said it was not uncommon
for Ewing and Checketts to discuss the club's future. Ewing was
influential in keeping John Starks and Charles Oakley at the
trading deadline in 1996, and has lobbied for Van Gundy when he has
come under fire the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't nothing going to happen next year,'' Ewing said when
asked about the club's plans for its coach.
</P>
<P>
   Fair or not, given the changes made to the roster during the off
season, management views a return to the Eastern Conference finals
as a measuring stick for the Knicks. Anything short of that goal,
and Van Gundy is thought to be out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   But while the final 18 games of the regular season and then the
playoffs may have more to do with the team's decision-making than
anything, Ewing's not-so-subtle message to Checketts could put the
franchise in a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts and, by association, the team's ownership may have to
decide whether to part ways with Van Gundy, Ernie Grunfeld or both.
It's no secret that Van Gundy and Grunfeld, the team president,
rarely speak, and that issues of trust have become major problems
in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   If the organization decides that Van Gundy's run is over, and if
Ewing is to be taken at his word, would the Knicks have to consider
trading Ewing in the final two years of his four-year contract?
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely for two reasons: Ewing's $68 million deal would
almost insure that the Knicks could not get equal value in return,
and Checketts and Grunfeld have often said that they want Ewing to
retire a Knick.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ewing has said, half-jokingly, more than once, ``If Jeff's
gone, send me to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how important stability is to success in the National
Basketball Association, Ewing is more than resistant to change.
Only in the last three seasons has he begun to trust his new
teammates enough to give up the ball in crucial situations.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand his stubbornness and his loyalty. Before
Van Gundy, he played for Hubie Brown, Bob Hill, Rick Pitino, Stu
Jackson, John MacLeod, Pat Riley and Don Nelson _ at one point,
eight coaches in 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Jeff to be back here,'' he said. ``I don't want to play
for another coach. I do not want to play for another coach. You
heard it from me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's Not West's Fault
</P>
<P>
   As they work in Glen Rice and tolerate Dennis Rodman, the Los
Angeles Lakers are still finding their balance and trying to look
like a team worthy of winning a title. If they don't realize that
goal this season, don't put the blame solely on Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, West, the Lakers' team president, was against
adding Rodman to the mix and privately told at least two close
associates that he did not think it was worth the gamble. Now, one
of the league's most successful executives _ the player whose
likeness is part of the NBA logo _ is watching his team become pro
basketball's next traveling circus.
</P>
<P>
   West is hoping beyond hope that the Lakers grow up before they
self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very talented, but to say we're a team right now is not
fair,'' West said by telephone from Portsmouth, Va., where he was
scouting some of the country's best college players. ``I think
we're trying to get past this tumultuous year, where so many things
have gone on.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Rice, he added: ``In the last few games, he's demonstrated
why we have an interest in him. He's feeling out his role and
getting significant help.''
</P>
<P>
   But West is worried about Rodman, whose absences and
inconsistent play have undeniably been distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss, the Lakers' owner, was behind the Rodman acquisition
and the recent makeover _ which included not only a coaching
change, from Del Harris to Kurt Rambis, but also the overhaul of
four-fifths of a starting lineup that played for the Western
Conference championship last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to say what they want, but I do not own this
team,'' West said. ``I work for somebody. I try to implement what
my owner wants. And hopefully it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   A Legal 2-Pointer
</P>
<P>
   Showing that NBA battles are waged in the courtroom as much as
on the court in these post-lockout times, the league's lawyers went
2-0 last week on different coasts.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Latrell Sprewell's lawsuit against the league
_ challenging his 68-game suspension for choking his coach _ was
dismissed last Monday by a federal judge who said it was so
worthless that Sprewell must pay the NBA's court costs.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm representing the NBA charges from $200 to $400 an
hour for its lawyers. Though the league declined to comment, a
lawyer who does not represent the NBA said Sprewell could be
looking at a bill in the neighborhood of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In New York last Thursday, Sandra Ortiz-Del Valle, a former
referee who sued the league on charges of gender discrimination and
had been awarded $7.85 million by a jury last July, also lost big.
</P>
<P>
   The same judge who presided over the trial reduced the judgment
to less than $347,000 _ a loss of more than $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Ortiz-Del Valle was trying to become the
first woman to officiate an NBA game. After she applied for a
position with the league, the NBA says that it told her to gain
college experience before reapplying. Ortiz-Del Valle had refereed
in the United States Basketball League but did not have National
Collegiate Athletic Association or Continental Basketball
Association experience.
</P>
<P>
   Two officials with that level of experience, Violet Palmer and
Dee Kantner, broke the gender barrier last season and were hired as
NBA referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no gender discrimination here and there should have
been no award,'' said Jeffrey Mishkin, the league's chief legal
officer. ``And we are going to ask the second Circuit Court of
Appeals to reduce it to zero, which is where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Wants Jordan
</P>
<P>
   At least one future Hall of Famer is hoping Michael Jordan's
discussions about purchasing at least half of the Charlotte Hornets
are more than just talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he can stay involved in the NBA'' said Magic Johnson, who
owns 5 percent of the Los Angeles Lakers and serves as one of the
franchise's vice presidents. ``We didn't want to lose him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Jordan's possibly returning to his Wilmington, N.C., roots to
own a team, Johnson added: ``He played there. He's from there. He
couldn't have a better situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
