u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-895(2TAKE     04-03 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRSTRIKES, MAYBE FOR MONTHS, REMAIN NATO'S PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW, KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NATO allies have no plans to try to stop the
brutalities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo except through an
extended air campaign, which could continue for a ``few months,''
according to senior Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of ground troops, which Gen. Wesley Clark, the
NATO commander, has suggested is the only way to ``stop the
paramilitary murder'' of ethnic Albanian civilians, is not being
considered by President Clinton and his senior foreign policy
advisers, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If the expulsions by the forces of President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia continue at their current rate, Kosovo could be
emptied of all its estimated 1.8 million ethnic Albanians in 10 to
20 days, NATO said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This pace of cleaning out the ethnic majority and the Serbs'
success against the rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army raise the
possibility that Milosevic, having achieved his objectives, may
soon stop and call for negotiations, a senior administration
official said Saturday. ``This is a scenario we are confronting,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the prospect of a Kosovo devoid of the people that the
NATO assault was supposed to protect, the goal of the airstrikes
remains that of damaging the Yugoslav forces so badly that
Milosevic will capitulate _ or, as a senior official put it, ``cry
uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   This could take ``weeks and weeks, months,'' one official said.
Another predicted a time frame of up to a ``few months,'' depending
on the weather and the ability of Milosevic's forces to move and
conceal their weapons and dodge NATO's missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most think that within a few months it can be achieved and
without the introduction of ground troops,'' a senior State
Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though some NATO officials have used the term ``genocide''
to describe the violence accompanying a systematic effort by
Serbian security forces to clear hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo, Clinton administration officials argue
that sending in troops is not the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Ground troops would take so long to organize that they would
``achieve too little, too late,'' the senior State Department
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in the current military campaign were made clear by
another senior official involved in Kosovo policy, who said that
Clinton made the ``most fateful decision of his presidency'' when
he decided to go ahead with the airstrikes without consideration of
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely outcome envisioned by these officials would be
an ``international protectorate'' for Kosovo with the ethnic
Albanians able to return under the guard of NATO troops, who would
stay for a certain time.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of negotiating terms of a protectorate with
Milosevic, after all that he has done against the ethnic Albanians,
was more ``discomfiting'' than in the past, but was still part of
the policy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is thinking about the political arrangements
after he capitulates and accepts a negotiated outcome,'' said one
administration official, speaking of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The official did not say whether ethnic Albanian leaders had
been approached about such a solution for their people, many of
whom are now fleeing Kosovo in terror and whose homes are being
destroyed by the Serbs. It is not clear whether even NATO troops
and copious Western aid in rebuilding would be sufficient to induce
them to go back.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was treated by Washington as a partner in, and then
guarantor of, the Dayton peace accord that brought a fragile
armistice to Bosnia, even though many described the Yugoslav leader
as the architect of the wars in Croatia and Bosnia. Only at the end
of last year did the State Department call Milosevic part of the
problem in the Balkans, rather than part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO diplomat cautioned that looking at Milosevic as
someone who would surrender and then negotiate was a fairly
dangerous proposition. ``In the Balkans, you win or die, there are
no defeats, no surrender,'' the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly open-ended nature of the air campaign against
Milosevic was a theme of remarks by President Clinton on Friday,
when he spoke of the administration's efforts to organize aid for
the ethnic Albanians flooding over the borders of Kosovo into
Macedonia, Albania and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be determined, we must be persistent, we must be
patient if we expect to see this mission through,'' Clinton said.
``Ultimately, we want to make it possible for the victims to return
home, to live in security and enjoy self-government.''
</P>
<P>
   Expanding on the goal of self-government, even as ethnic
Albanians were being driven from the province of Kosovo, senior
administration officials said they believed an ``international
protectorate'' was looking like the best solution.
</P>
<P>
   Such a protectorate is envisaged as a legal entity somewhere
beyond the autonomy granted in the peace settlement proposed at
Rambouillet, France, but short of the independence that the ethnic
Albanians have sought, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and European allies have consistently opposed
independence for Kosovo, in part because of the precedent it would
set for other ethnic groups, in Europe and elsewhere, who also
might wish to redraw present sovereign boundaries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Behind the public facade of resolution to see the air campaign
through, there are signs in the State Department, the National
Security Council and the Pentagon of whether it would work.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, one official described ``so much anxiety across
the board.'' Basic questions are being asked, like ``Is this guy
going to yield?'' one official said, referring to Milosevic. Even
the fundamental question ``Do we have the right strategy?'' was
being aired, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another official said he had often mused about what would be the
``big one,'' meaning the foreign crisis that would embroil the
Clinton administration and threaten to spin out of control. ``This
is the big one,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with administration officials on the Kosovo
strategy, an underlying theme to emerge was the recognition that
they could do little to stop the violence inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say with pain that the bombing, while justified by
Milosevic's behavior, is not going to stop Arkan or the
paramilitaries,'' the official said, referring to Zeljko
Raznatovic, a Serbian paramilitary leader indicted for war crimes
by the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Having made the decision not to use ground troops, the
administration had no option but to plug away at the air campaign
and make the best of it, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian refugees have described in detail door-to-door
expulsions and families being forced onto trains and buses by
Serbian paramilitaries and dumped into neighboring Albania and
Macedonia without possessions or money.
</P>
<P>
   The officials acknowledged that conditions in Kosovo were likely
to deteriorate with a continued Serbian drive against the ethnic
Albanians. This worsening of conditions could increase the
frustration in Congress and the public with the seeming inability,
or reluctance, of the administration to stop the brutality, these
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication that the success of the airstrikes will be
measured by a military objective rather than the objective of
ending the human crisis inside Kosovo, a senior official said that
the campaign would persist until Milosevic went ``down the tubes''
in his ability to control his forces.
</P>
<P>
   Another theme that the administration officials emphasized was
that Milosevic would ``capitulate'' or ``yield'' or ``come to the
negotiating table.'' These officials went out of their way to avoid
the idea of ``defeating'' him.
</P>
<P>
   During the bombing campaign, the administration is not seeking a
change of regime in Belgrade, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of this stance assert that even as Milosevic carries out
extreme human rights abuses in Kosovo, the administration is still
willing to deal with him. Thus, the critics say, the administration
has been less specific than the British government in its
assertions that Milosevic has been responsible for genocide in
Kosovo. The State Department said last week that there were
``indications'' of genocide in Kosovo by Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   The senior NATO diplomat said that despite some differences
within the alliance, cohesion was strong, particularly after the
capture of the three U.S. soldiers by Milosevic's forces and the
continued atrocities against civilians. NATO members realize that
the future of the alliance is at stake and there are no signs of
buckling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all at a loss,'' the diplomat said, alluding to what he
called the bleakness in European capitals about how to end the
atrocities in Kosovo quickly and how to overcome Milosevic without
deploying ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the makings of a Greek tragedy _ of the unbelievable
overwhelming you,'' he added. ``We take one step, then we are
compelled to take another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
