<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      04-03 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ON ROAD OF HARD KNOCKS TO THE DRAFT, No. 1 HOPEFULS TRY TO HOLD(jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Couch was anointed as the top pick in the National Football
League draft months ago. The title did not come with a crown, but
it should have come with body armor. That is because Couch is now
taking more shots than he ever did as a quarterback for the
University of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Couch is learning the harsh reality of being rated the top
player: every move he makes is scrutinized and every pass he throws
in workouts is dissected.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Couch has made some rookie mistakes in his
dealings with National Football League teams and with choosing
agents. Those decisions have hurt him, and that has opened the door
for the Oregon quarterback Akili Smith to become the first choice
of the Cleveland Browns in the draft April 17.
</P>
<P>
   It may be harsh, even cruel, to hold a college player to almost
unreachable standards. These days NFL teams are so picky, at times
so oversaturated with information that if Superman declared himself
eligible for the draft some team would find a weakness. Yet the
microscopic inspection is understandable, especially in the case of
the Browns. This pick may be important to their franchise's
history, and one scout for the Browns, who did not want to be
identified, said that the closer they look at Couch the more
nervous they get.
</P>
<P>
   So it cannot be ruled out that the Browns will pass on Couch and
choose either Smith or the Texas running back Ricky Williams, who
has dropped the 20 pounds he gained once the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   What first raised questions about Couch in the minds of the
Browns is how he came to choose an agent, particularly an episode
that was almost identical to a scene in the film ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch was being heavily recruited by several agents, but
according to the agent Gary Wichard, Couch told him, ``You're my
guy,'' before boarding a plane to visit with International
Management Group, one of the most powerful agent firms in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Couch changed his mind once IMG guaranteed $3 million in
endorsement money and agreed to charge an extremely low fee to
negotiate his contract with the team that will eventually draft
him. Couch will pay IMG $50,000 for a service that would usually
cost about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a player's not living up to a handshake agreement is
common in the vicious agent game and usually is no big deal. What
made this situation unusual _ and awkward for Couch _ is that
Wichard is a close friend of Carmen Policy, the Browns' president.
</P>
<P>
   What hurt Couch even more, though, was a workout he held for all
NFL teams on March 11. The workout was run by IMG, something that
disappointed the Browns because they wanted to work him out
privately under the direction of the Browns' coaches instead of
former coaches hired by IMG. When Cleveland worked out Smith, it
was done in private and run by Chris Palmer, the Browns' head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Condon, who is Couch's agent at IMG, did not return phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Smith threw 75 passes in his workout versus 46 for Couch.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Clark, director of football operations for the Browns,
said of Couch, ``He didn't knock anybody off their feet, but it
didn't look like arm strength is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Workouts put on by agents can be risky. If teams think they are
too orchestrated, as some felt about Couch's, there can be a
backlash.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened to the University of Miami quarterback
John Walsh, who held a private workout run in a heavy-handed way in
March 1995 by the former San Francisco coach Bill Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   John Walsh, no relation to Bill, was considered a possible
first-round draft choice, but his stock dropped sharply after that
workout and he ended up being chosen in the seventh round by the
Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   No scout or coach likes to have someone else do their job for
them. ``That's what we get paid to do,'' an NFL scout who attended
the Couch workout said. ``Couch did not come off that well because
he did not make certain throws, certain deep throws that I would
have liked to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns were clearly upset over the circumstances of the
workout and Couch got the message. He has scheduled a private
workout with the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, the former offensive coordinator for the Jacksonville
Jaguars, knows how to evaluate quarterbacks. When he was an
assistant with the New England Patriots in 1993, Palmer was
instrumental in the team selecting Drew Bledsoe over Rick Mirer.
Bledsoe went to a Super Bowl and Mirer was a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Couch has many attributes. He is smart in the pocket, throws a
nice post pattern and is a good leader. Smith has a much stronger
arm and throws a tighter spiral, but there are concerns about him
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Smith basically had just one solid year at Oregon and the Browns
are uncertain if that was a fluke or an indication of his true
talent. He has also had wildly different scores on the Wunderlich
intelligence test the league gives potential players. His first
score was a 13 out of 40, followed by a score of 37, then of 26,
according to Smith's agent, Leigh Steinberg. The Browns aren't sure
of what to make of those results, but there is no question that the
test is one of the most overrated tools to determine if a player
can perform well on the NFL level.
</P>
<P>
   If Couch has a good workout for the Browns, he could vault to
the top again. But this will be a close race between Couch, Smith
and Williams, one that seems destined to go to the final days.
</P>
<P>
   Assistants Bide Their Time
</P>
<P>
   NFL assistant coaches, who have been fighting for better
benefits, are close to reaching an agreement with the league, but
negotiations are on hold for now.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that the assistants, who, among other things, want
the retirement age significantly lowered, will strike a deal with
the owners. But the league is concerned that if they give
assistants what they want then everyone from ticket-takers to
trainers will be in line, making their own requests.
</P>
<P>
   So while the NFL strategizes, the coaches wait.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings Like Corey Miller
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Coach Dennis Green, on the signing of the former
Giants linebacker Corey Miller, said: ``We believe Corey can
rejuvenate his career with us. He's a big, strong guy who will have
a chance to start.'' ... Some coaches believe the Giants and Jets
made great moves with their tight ends: the Jets letting Kyle Brady
go and signing Eric Green, and the Giants picking up Pete Mitchell.
Getting Mitchell, one American Conference coach said, was the best
free-agent signing the Giants have made in years. ... Arizona
cornerback Chris McAlister was considered a middle first round pick
in the coming draft by some scouts, but his recent workouts have
vaulted him into the top 10. He recently ran a 4.38 40-yard dash on
grass and his vertical jump was 37 inches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
