</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES AMERICANS TO JOIN IN AIDING REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW, KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Saturday urged Americans to
donate money for food, water, medicine, blankets, clothing and
shelter to help the hundreds of thousands of refugees driven from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton said President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia aimed ``to keep Kosovo's land while ridding
it of its people.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the NATO bombing began, ``Serbian forces have intensified
their attacks against innocent civilians,'' he said. ``An entire
people are being made to abandon their homeland or die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among them are elderly people, who have lived their whole
lives in peace with their neighbors, only to be told now to leave
everything behind in minutes or to be killed on the spot,'' Clinton
said. ``Among them are small children who walked for miles over
mountains, sometimes after watching their fathers and uncles and
brothers taken from them and shot before their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had authorized $50 million in emergency funds to
help the refugees fleeing Kosovo and had instructed the Pentagon to
organize efforts to provide emergency supplies of food, clothing
and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States would work with the United Nations and
nongovernmental organizations to help the Kosovars, and urged
Americans to call the Red Cross or to contact charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo's neighbors, Macedonia and Albania, are taking the
refugees in, despite the huge burden this places on these poor,
struggling nations,'' he said. ``So are Greece, Bosnia and
Bulgaria, showing there's more mercy than madness in the Balkans,
more compassion than cruelty in this troubled region of the world.
We also must open our hearts and our arms to the innocent victims
of this conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
