A4715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPE-SPEAKOUT-NYT &LR;      04-03 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-SPEAKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ARE SPEAKING OUT TO HEAL TRAUMA OF RAPE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kans.)   By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Betty Liebert was getting into her car to go home
after a night out with friends when a man hit her from behind and
took from her all her life had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw who it was,'' Ms. Liebert says, recalling the
night of Nov. 9, 1990. ``He hit me in the head. I lost
consciousness for a little bit. He raped me and dumped my purse out
over my back to use my back as a table to sort through what he
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Liebert, now 43, did not call the police, but went home,
took a shower, threw away everything her attacker had touched and
did not say a word about her rape to anyone for more than a year.
In that time, Ms. Liebert, a woman whose affinity for adventure
included bodybuilding, running, camping and mountain biking, feared
leaving her house, and she began to drink heavily and suffer
episodes of rage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost nine years later, Ms. Liebert and several others who
have lived through rape are speaking out about it in Los Angeles,
both in a public service announcement broadcast on television and
at a conference on April 17 intended to help other victims. In
speaking out, the women are further lifting what has traditionally
been a protective curtain of anonymity to unveil the faces _
mother, fiancee, the elderly _ of what they call a ``secret
sorority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When women are willing to go public, it strips away the
curtain and distance from the pain of the experience,'' said
Rosanna Hill, a coordinator of the conference and member of the
Rainbow Sisters Project, which is sponsoring it.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, at the Los Angeles Public Library, is billed as
a day to honor women who have been raped and those who have raised
public awareness about it. The public service announcement, filmed
in black and white, is a parade of women who say: ``I am a mother.
I am a senior citizen. I am a wife. Soy tu hermana. I am East
German. I am hopeful. I am, ah, about to be married. I am learning
to trust. I am angry. I am happy to be alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It was directed by Kate Miller, an executive at Capitol Records
who was holding a summer barbecue with friends in 1994 when two men
broke into her home, tied her and her friends up, put guns in their
mouths and raped them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to take back what was taken from you is to turn
it around and make it positive, and sharing with others,'' Ms.
Miller said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a study released last year and sponsored by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention and the National Institute of
Justice, the research arm of the Justice Department, 18 percent of
female respondents said they had been raped or had suffered an
attempted rape.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and experts estimate that as many as 60 percent of
women who are raped never report it. Such was the case for a woman
in the public service announcement, who asked not to be identified
by name. The woman did not tell the police that she had been raped
even though her attacker, whom she met at work and had spent hours
talking to, continued to contact her as if the attack had not
happened. She said she had thrown herself into her work to keep her
mind off the attack and did not seek help until she moved to Los
Angeles four years ago when she heard an advertisement on the radio
for a rape counseling service.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Spencer, 52, a senior executive assistant at Neutrogena, was
raped 22 years ago in her home in Kansas by an intruder who, she
says, considered aloud whether to kill her. When Ms. Spencer
eventually sought help, she was told she had post-traumatic stress
disorder, a syndrome known to affect some soldiers after combat.
She says there are days now when she is free of the memory, though
there are reminders, like hearing other rape stories and jokes
about rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' she said in an interview, ``it's when a man looks
at my body before he looks in my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But if it is painful to recount the incident, and to hear many
similar stories, Ms. Spencer said, it will ultimately be
worthwhile. She said she wanted to take part in the public effort
``to help myself and to help other women, and to take some of the
element of shame away from the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anything you shed light on is a healing process,'' she
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
