<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-820&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANS TO SEND TROOPS TO ALBANIA FOR REFUGEE RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW, KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO said Saturday that it was planning to
send a force of 6,000 to 8,000 troops to Albania to provide
security and emergency relief for the masses of Kosovo Albanians
who have been driven from neighboring Yugoslavia by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is mobilizing all its available resources for this urgent
humanitarian requirement,'' the alliance's spokesman, Jamie P.
Shea, said. He announced that allied ambassadors had asked the top
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of the United States, for a plan to
deploy an operational headquarters, helicopters, troops, and
supplies to Albania as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   More than 165,000 refugees have arrived in Albania from Kosovo
since the allies began bombing to try to stop the Serbian campaign,
according to allied officials. Shea said that 55,000 people crossed
into Albania Friday alone, and that 290,000 Kosovo Albanians had
fled into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro in the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that despite the allied missile attacks that
blew up the Yugoslav and Serbian Interior Ministries headquarters
in the heart of Belgrade shortly after midnight, bad weather has
kept large numbers of allied planes from going after the Serb
forces driving the ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. Those operations
would have to wait till the weather cleared, allied commanders
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the blows to the Yugoslav capital, President Slobodan
Milosevic showed no signs of relenting in his campaign against the
1.8 million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this rate,'' Shea said Saturday, ``if you do a mathematical
calculation, Serb forces will have emptied Kosovo of its entire
population in 10 to 20 days.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others here deny that the air campaign included Milosevic
as a target. ``That is not the business that we're into,'' said the
British air commodore, David Wilby, the allied military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials here believe that the Serbian campaign is aimed
at emptying a large triangle of territory in Kosovo, roughly a
triangle between Pristina, the provincial capital, and the cities
of Pec and Prizren, of its ethnic Albanian inhabitants and
replacing them with Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen some reports of Serbian refugees from the Krajina
entering Kosovo,'' said Edgar Buckley, a British official,
referring to a region of Croatia that was largely emptied of Serbs
in fighting in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With clouds and rain keeping most of the 450-odd allied planes
from hitting the Serbian military and police forces enough to keep
them from driving more refugees out, the allies are now being
forced to deal with the humanitarian disaster spreading into
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who met with the
Albanian president and prime minister Saturday in Tirana, canceled
a stopover in Rome to fly to Skopje, Macedonia, where the
government has halted the flow of refugees, concerned that the
massive influx of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo could upset the
ethnic balance of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their concerns are absolutely legitimate and understandable,''
Talbott said, after meeting with Kosovo refugees in a tent city of
2,000 in Tirana. ``We are seeing with our own eyes today a policy
on the part of Yugoslavia to undercut the viability of neighboring
states.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We are dealing with a rogue dictator who is
systematically and with premeditation using refugees as a means of
destabilizing neighboring states.''
</P>
<P>
   But Talbott's delegation also sped to Macedonia with the aim of
pressuring its leaders to open up the borders again and let the
refugees in, another American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain, commanding a
force of more than 10,000 British, French and German troops in
Macedonia that was originally intended for a peacekeeping mission
in Kosovo, was ordered Saturday to put all of them to work helping
Macedonia deal with the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Ministry officials in London said 200,000 Kosovo
Albanians were now trying to flee toward Macedonia on the road from
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The allies also say they have observed about 25,000 people
backed up inside Kosovo behind the border crossing point waiting
for the Serb authorities to let them pass.
</P>
<P>
   But Macedonia, a country with a delicate ethnic balance, has
absorbed 55,000 ethnic Albanian refugees in the last few weeks.
Saturday authorities said they would bar any more from coming in,
fearing that the country could be overwhelmed by the human
catastrophe that has seen 20 percent of the people of Kosovo driven
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not let you down,'' Prime Minister Tony Blair told the
refugees in a British television interview Saturday. ``We will make
sure that you are able to return to your homes, and live in your
homes in peace,'' he said. ``That is our promise to you and we will
carry it out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The allies have also expressed concern about the situation in
Montenegro, which is federated with Serbia within Yugoslavia.
Milosevic replaced eight Yugoslav military commanders in Montenegro
this week, allied officials said, and could be preparing a coup
there.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that Jackson had already asked for 1 million food
rations, 50,000 gallons of drinking water, and 187,000 blankets and
was setting up a feeding station for the refugees near the border
with Kosovo. Three American soldiers on a border patrol fell into
Serbian hands earlier in the week and were taken prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which fears an uncontrolled influx of refugees across the
Adriatic, asked its allies on Friday to create a force to ensure
the safety of the refugees in Albania. Italy has offered to lead
the force and provide most of the soldiers for it, according to an
Italian official here.
</P>
<P>
   American, British and French warplanes continued to launch
attacks from bases in Italy Saturday, officials said, in an effort
to stop the Serb persecution and stem the refugee flow before it
overwhelms the entire Balkans region.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the allies met here to discuss other emergency steps to
deal with the victims of the violence in Kosovo, British and NATO
officers said that American and British cruise missiles launched
from ships at targets in central Belgrade in the predawn hours this
morning had caused no significant damage to civilian buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise missile attacks destroyed the Serbian and Yugoslav
Interior Ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Air Marshal John Day, chief of the British defense staff in
London, described these headquarters as ``the nerve center of
operations planned to drive out ethnic Albanians in a campaign of
violence, intimidation, and thuggery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's attacks will continue and can be intensified even
further if necessary,'' he said. ``The weather is forecast to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We only need a couple of days of good weather to be able to
have a maximized effect,'' Shea said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said that an unspecified number of allied planes had
managed Friday to hit staging areas used by the Yugoslav 547th
Mechanized Brigade for attacks against civilians, but he did not
say how much damage the planes did.
</P>
<P>
   The location of the attacks was in three areas along the road
between Prizren and Djakovica in southwestern Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
