<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ACOG-FUNDS04-COX     04-03 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ACOG-FUNDS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACOG account: Millions still left to spend
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic
Games reported publicly on its finances, it said there would be
nothing left for local youth sports programs after a huge debt was
paid off to the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   That was almost two years ago, when the committee still had $65
million in the bank. Since then, tens of millions have changed
hands among ACOG, its top officers, its stadium construction team,
its lawyers and the tiny Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation.
Nearly $11 million remains in its account.
</P>
<P>
   Among those surprised to learn ACOG has not closed its books and
continues to write checks are some of its own board of directors.
``I find that to be truly astonishing,'' attorney Michael Coleman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not still on the board, am I?'' asked Sam Massell,
president of the Buckhead (Business) Coalition. ``I thought they
closed up.''
</P>
<P>
   ACOG officials said the committee will wind down this summer
when all accounts are settled, including a few legal disputes over
such matters as private property rights and a missing painting.
They intend to use any leftover funds to pay off a $22 million loan
from the USOC in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Stogner, the financial director who still works part
time in ACOG's small office at the Inforum, said about half the
debt has been repaid and he hopes to use any remaining funds in
ACOG's account to eliminate the rest.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave youth sports out in the cold. Under an early
agreement with the International Olympic Committee and the USOC, 20
percent of any ACOG surplus would have gone to a foundation to
benefit athletics for youngsters in Atlanta. At one time, ACOG was
forecasting a $150 million surplus; today it maintains there will
be none, although the USOC plans to launch a $1 million Community
Olympic Development Program in Atlanta that would provide seed
money for some Olympic-type sports programs.
</P>
<P>
   During the six-year buildup to the Atlanta Games, ACOG's books
were monitored by the state's Olympic watchdog authority, known as
MAOGA. That check and balance ceased in June 1996, and there is no
longer independent financial oversight to let the public know what
is happening with ACOG's millions.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors last met in the summer of 1997 to review
ACOG'S last independent financial audit and approve a dissolution
plan. The plan authorized the committee's officers _ President
Billy Payne, Chief Operating Officer A.D. Frazier Jr. and managing
directors Ginger Watkins and Patrick Glisson _ to ``wind up and
liquidate ACOG's business and affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no communication since then with the board,
leading some directors to the conclusion that ACOG had dissolved.
``Since the Games, I've had no contact with anybody regarding ACOG,
which I assumed was either out of business or effectively going out
of business,'' said former Gov. Carl Sanders, a board member.
``This is news to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of accountability, Glisson, the former chief
financial officer, said the public can rest easy. The USOC reviews
ACOG's books quarterly and annual returns are filed with the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principal concern is we get the amount they are carrying
as a contingent liability,'' said John Samuelson, the USOC's chief
financial officer. ``But we're not counting on the money until we
have it in our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ACOG had released quarterly financial updates before the Games,
even though the committee maintained it was a private organization
and under no legal obligation to share its finances. Its officials
had hoped to complete their business out of the spotlight. Stogner
now is hesitant to talk about how much money ACOG is sitting on for
fear new litigants will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   But with mounting public pressure on Olympic organizations
worldwide to open their books, ACOG officials might have difficulty
doling out their remaining millions with only themselves and the
USOC to answer to. Stewart Acuff, president of the Atlanta Labor
Council who served on the ACOG board audit committee, said of the
organization's activities: ``What I saw was as transparent and
clean as can be.'' Yet, he added, ``I do think it is important for
Atlanta's Olympic legacy and the legacy for the leadership of ACOG
to have a final accounting of where the money went.''
</P>
<P>
   Glisson said he expects the board to receive ``courtesy
information'' once business is concluded. ACOG's federal tax
returns for 1997 _ the most recent financial information available
_ provide a partial accounting of where the money went.
</P>
<P>
   ACOG spent more than $38 million in 1997, mostly to finish
converting the Olympic stadium to baseball and demolishing
Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium. And though operating with a skeleton
staff, the committee paid its officers and employees more than $5
million and its King &AMP; Spalding lawyers more than $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also that year, ACOG gave several million dollars to the Georgia
Amateur Athletics Foundation, the nonprofit organization created by
Payne in 1987 to bid for the Games and foster amateur sports in
Georgia. The two organizations, both headed by Payne, are closely
aligned.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, ACOG transferred ownership of its archives and Olympic
memorabilia to the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation and gave it
a check for $1.15 million, presumably for storage and archiving
expenses. ACOG gave GAAF an additional $1.3 million, which tax
records indicate was repayment of a loan from 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Once GAAF received the money from ACOG, the suddenly flush
foundation gave Payne $975,000 for his personal memorabilia
collection. Before its windfall from ACOG, the foundation had less
than $7,000 on hand. The Payne transaction, purposely conducted out
of the public eye, has raised questions about how ACOG is spending
its cash reserves. Indeed, the USOC's Samuelson said he was not
aware of the payment to GAAF even though he is monitoring ACOG's
money.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Games, Payne and ACOG board co-chairman Bob
Holder announced there would be no money available for bonuses for
ACOG officers.
</P>
<P>
   However, they didn't tell the public or the board about a $1
million ``extended resource availability program,'' which provided
a way to funnel money to 25 key employees after the Games. Glisson
said he created the program to ``ensure the people we needed were
available for the critical period of the shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Glisson said seven managing directors, including himself, were
in the program. Some people were paid as much as half a year's
salary to be on call, he said. ``In contrast to a bonus, this was a
very appropriate, rational business decision,'' Glisson said.
</P>
<P>
   Glisson, for example, was paid $410,811 in 1997, although he had
taken a full-time position as chief financial officer at The Emory
Clinic in September.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and Frazier were not included in the program. ``I
recognized that would be impolitic,'' Glisson said. ``They were
specifically exempted because that could be misperceived.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, both officers were handsomely compensated the year of the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was paid $806,608 in 1996, a 41 percent increase from
the year before, according to ACOG's tax returns. He received
nothing in 1997, having taken a job as president and chief
executive of Invesco Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Payne received a 17 percent raise to $766,833 in 1996 and
another $69,000 in 1997, although he had gone to work as a vice
chairman of NationsBank in February. Later that year, he received
the payment from GAAF for his memorabilia. All told, in the final
two years of Payne's reign as Atlanta's Olympic chief, he took in
$1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very surprising,'' said Coleman. ``There have been a
lot of expenditures of money that would have been appropriate for
the board to know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member Massell, a former Atlanta mayor, said he expects
ACOG to give the public a final accounting. ``I think it would be
improper to keep anything confidential as matters are brought to a
close,'' he said. ``But I do not fault the team for keeping records
close to the vest for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just so proud of what they achieved ...
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
