<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4727 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-ANDREWS04-COX     04-03 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-ANDREWS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life goes on _ at a fast clip _ for ex-NBAF chief
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dwight Andrews is on the upswing. Since the new year,
when his two-year contract with the National Black Arts Festival
expired, it has taken one less hyphen to accommodate the Atlanta
composer-educator-minister-scholar's professional activities.
</P>
<P>
   As artistic director of the NBAF, the sprawling biannual
festival that celebrates African-American arts and artists, Andrews
faced steep challenges, most in terms of digging the decade-old
event out of debt. He succeeded once, retiring a $377,000 deficit
left from the 1996 festival.
</P>
<P>
   But when the NBAF came up short after last summer _ as much as
$700,000 short _ Andrews saw only one logical move. He made his
exit. And he's not looking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with the choices I've made,'' says Andrews, 46,
a professor of music at Emory University and an ordained minister
affiliated with downtown's First Congregational Church. ``I'm
feeling creatively energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Those energies are pouring in several directions, business as
usual for Andrews. The past few months have seen him compose music
for ``Everybody's Ruby,'' the off-Broadway collaboration between
playwright Thulani Davis and director Kenny Leon; gig at New York's
Village Vanguard and the San Francisco Jazz Festival; host an
ongoing series of improvised music at his church; continue work on
``Woman at the Well,'' a music-theater piece that Jomandi
Productions will give a workshop production in May. And he bounced
back from a knockout bout with pneumonia. ``I did some good
reflecting,'' he says of his illness, which sidelined him for a
month last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast one recent morning, Andrews shared some of the
things he's been thinking about, from his brief NBAF tenure to his
rekindled desire to play live jazz:
</P>
<P>
   _ On his NBAF departure: ``I think the festival went very well.
I think it broke some new ground. I'm very proud of what we did.
... But they will have to reorganize so that the person who asks
for the money is also responsible for how the money is spent. The
other issue, and really the bigger issue for me, is I didn't really
envision spending the next two years, going into the new
millennium, being a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the arts as a spiritual pursuit: ``The one thing that's
good about First Congregational Church is there are a lot of things
that I can do, not just spiritually focused, but things that are
culturally and artistically focused, without the tremendous
administrative encumbrances of a big festival. I'm envisioning a
real heavy focus on the culture and arts and a very ecumenical
environment for poets and playwrights and actors. Especially for
artists who could use a place to explore their spiritual side and
maybe even think about how that speaks to the art they are
creating. It's always been a part of my ministry, but if the church
is willing to make a long-term commitment, I would envision a
lecture series and different kinds of dialogues, as well as
performances and panels and literally every week something
happening there. It would be like my own nightclub, a spiritual
nightclub.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On making music: ``I've got a new soprano sax, and I'm just
shedding (practicing), giving myself eight months of serious daily
work. Two hours a day, that's the most I can muster. I'm going to
actually try to do some kind of recording project.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the collapse of the Arts Festival of Atlanta and the NBAF's
struggles: ``I think (the fact) that the festivals are struggling
has to do with a much bigger issue. The two festivals are very,
very different. The Arts Festival was really struggling with
different visions of what it should be. The board wanted to keep it
more locally rooted or regionally rooted, and the artistic
leadership saw it as having a much more national visibility, a
bigger nut. I mean when you have Philip Glass and these cats from
Paris coming and dancing, that's a whole different thing. You have
to build an audience toward that. You don't just pay the big bucks
and say: `If you bring them, they will come.' Because the people
might come, but the corporations might not. Sponsors still are in
the process of their own, being educated about the arts, and they
probably aren't nearly as learned as they think they are. And why
they sponsor stuff is very different from why artists and artistic
groups present it. They sleep in the same bed, but there's a pillow
in between them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On corporate sponsorship of jumbo-size arts events: ``The
culture is changing in the way big art events are perceived.
Corporate sponsors are still incredibly silly in the way they go
about deciding whether to sponsor you. They'll ask, `Who are you
going to have?' `Well, how much money can you give us?' `Well,
we'll tell you how much when you tell us who you're going to have.'
`Well, we'll have Denzel Washington.' `Oh good, let's have Denzel,
because we know we can put him in Ebony magazine.' `Well what's he
going to do?' `It doesn't matter, just get Denzel.' But then you
say, `I want to hire (Nigerian writer) Chinua Achebe to have him do
(a theatrical version of his classic novel) ``Things Fall Apart.'''
And they say, `What?' So there's a gulf between the real money
sponsorships and their sincerity. It's a plantation system. But
interestingly enough, the musicians and artists I know are forging
ahead on their own. They're using technology and finding new ways
to create opportunities. I'm really excited about what's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Parting words: ``What the NBAF experience showed me was that
the great art will go on with or without me and the festival. On my
tombstone I don't want it to say, `Artistic Director of the
National Black Arts Festival.' I want it to say: `This cat made
some music,' or `Spirit and arts were the thing.' Something like
that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
