<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN PRESSES HIS CASE FOR SENDING GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW, KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(DW) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain spent more than five years as a
prisoner of war in Vietnam and learned, he says, the dangers of
limited measures. He is now a forceful advocate of all-out
intervention in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Almost ubiquitous on television news shows, McCain, R-Ariz.,
steadily makes the case from which President Clinton shies away _
that America can no longer afford to rule out the use of ground
troops in Kosovo. He maintains that the United States, having begun
the air campaign, must preserve its credibility by beating back the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Pyongyang and Baghdad and Tripoli, they are paying close
attention,'' he said in an interview on Friday. ``And if a military
establishment that was defeated by the Croatian army prevails, one
led by a Balkan thug prevails, then we will be vulnerable to many
challenges in many places.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is a candidate for president, and the confluence of the
early campaign season and the air attacks has set him apart in the
field, highlighting his expertise in military affairs and his war
record.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, supports an air campaign
but not ground troops. Elizabeth Hanford Dole said Friday that the
United States should not rule out ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, 62, a former Navy pilot, had long planned to announce
his candidacy formally next week, but he canceled the political
event, calling it inappropriate to campaign while the nation is at
war. The step has only seemed to increase his appeal: he appeared
on the morning shows of the three major television networks on
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   He is unapologetic about taking advantage of the platform.
``I've been asked for my view and I've given it because I think
that this situation we're in is of transcendent importance,'' he
said. In a dig at Clinton, he added: ``We're not talking about
school uniforms. We're talking about the most important aspect of
our role in government _ national security.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, despite the criticisms of the president, the
White House welcomes another voice arguing for resolve as it tries
to muster support for the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree on the utility of ground troops but that is an
honest policy disagreement,'' said Joe Lockhart, the White House
press secretary. ``I think Sen. McCain has been quite effective in
making the case for U.S. and NATO involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has long been critical of Clinton's foreign policy, and a
speech he delivered in the Senate on the eve of the NATO air
strikes now sounds prescient.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the administration of not following through on threats
to Milosevic, he said, ``Our threats of force have apparently lost
their power to restrain the remorseless and bloodthirsty Serbian
government.''
</P>
<P>
   But he went on to warn the Senate that it would be
``extraordinarily dangerous'' for it to undercut the president on
the eve of air strikes. ``Our adversaries around the globe will
take heart from our inability to act in concert,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans have argued that committing troops to Kosovo
would result in a Vietnam-like quagmire. But McCain said the lesson
he drew from the war in which he served was, ``You don't get into a
conflict unless you are willing to exercise all means necessary to
winning it.''
</P>
<P>
   His stand may seem politically risky _ Americans do not favor
ground troops. But political strategists say that such positions
are part of McCain's appeal and that as a long-shot candidate what
he most needs to do is stand out from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes McCain will self-deprecatingly mock his own war
record. At a recent Washington dinner featuring skits by reporters,
he walked to a lectern, overloaded with war ribbons, and joked
about his time as a prisoner of war and his quixotic attempts to
ban the unregulated contributions to political parties known as
soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was lying there in my prison cell in Hanoi having my legs
broken by interrogators, one thought and one thought alone kept me
going,'' he said to laughs from the crowd, ``that some day I would
come home and do some thing about soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that the capture of three Americans by the
Serbs this week left him anguished. ``It did bring back a few
memories of when I was first captured,'' he said, ``which I rarely
ever think about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
