<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-NYT &LR;      04-03 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR U.S. FUNDS TO ARM KOSOVAR REBELS WORRIES NATO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia so far
unable to deter the atrocities in Kosovo, and the United States
unwilling to commit ground troops, the idea of arming the Kosovo
guerrillas has garnered support from a number of politicians and
former policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army offers ``a credible, capable and
willing alternative to the deployment of Americans,'' Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., wrote to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell and Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., have proposed
spending $25 million to arm the Kosovo rebels. Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., was among the first to raise the idea of arming the Kosovo
guerrillas, and Zbigniew Brzezinski, who was national security
adviser to President Jimmy Carter, has expressed support for such a
plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration and its NATO partners are
resolutely against the idea. They view Kosovo's Albanian rebels
with considerable wariness, if not alarm, because of their
political ideologies and questionable commitment to democracy. Some
in the rebel movement are considered hard-line Marxists, others
Islamic fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   In March, month, Albanian officials alerted the Clinton
administration that Iran was sending weapons to the Kosovo rebels,
through Albania. As many as four flights with weapons from Iran may
have reached the rebels, according to documents and a person
involved in arms trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States were to arm the Kosovo Liberation Army, it
would ``provide a platform'' for Islamic fundamentalists from Iran,
Iraq, Sudan, Afghanistan and Pakistan, said one U.S. official. In
each of those nations, volunteers and weapons are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Another worry is that Russia could see a U.S. operation to arm
the rebels as further justification to provide weapons to Serbia,
according to U.S. and European diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they crazy?'' said a stunned diplomat at the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe when she first heard of the
proposal by McConnell and Lieberman to arm the Kosovo rebels.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official who has met frequently with the Kosovar
guerrilla leaders over the years described them as rigid
communists. ``They draw their cultural and political philosophy
from Enver Hoxha,'' he said. Hoxha, a hard-line communist who
considered the Soviet Union and even China under Mao as too soft,
ruled Albania for more than 40 years until his death in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell said the character and ideology of the Kosovo
Liberation Army was beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have to do a background check any more than
we did on the Contras,'' McConnell said, referring to the rebel
army that was trained and equipped by the Reagan administration to
topple the Sandinistas in Nicaragua in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt there may be some bad actors'' among the
Kosovo rebels, he said in a telephone interview from Australia.
``But the point is,'' he continued, ``who else is on the ground
willing to fight the ethnic cleansing?''
</P>
<P>
   The political roots of the Kosovo Liberation Army go back to the
early 1980s, when the Popular Movement for Kosovo called for an
armed uprising in favor of Kosovo's secession from Yugoslavia.
Another political party, the Democratic League of Kosovo, advocated
a policy of nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   After the breakup of Yugoslavia in 1991, the advocates of
nonviolence, headed by Ibrahim Rugova, enjoyed the backing of most
Albanians in Kosovo, where they formed 90 percent of the population
of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But as Slobodan Milosevic grew more repressive, the patience of
Kosovo's Albanians _ particularly of the young people _ waned. Then
came the disintegration of Albania, in the spring of 1997. In the
near-anarchy that followed, arms depots were looted, and suddenly
half a million Kalashnikov assault rifles were on the market, so
many that the price plummeted to $15 for one of the best assault
rifles ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's guerrillas also bought weapons in the popular arms
bazaars for rebel groups around the world these days, like Ukraine
and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more contentious issues is how much of the rebels'
money comes from drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take it for granted that the KLA benefits from heroin
trafficking,'' said Rens Lee, an expert on the international arms
trade.
</P>
<P>
   That has been widely reported in European newspapers, and
European officials say that Albania has become a major hub for the
movement of heroin and cocaine into Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The links between organized criminal groups engaged in the drug
trade and the Kosovo Liberation Army are harder to establish,
though.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said last week that the United States
does not have evidence that as an organization the Kosovo
Liberation Army is raising money through the drug trade. A senior
European diplomat from a country greatly concerned about the drugs
coming out of Albania agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But both men said it was undoubtedly true that some supporters
of the Kosovo Liberation Army were drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   A good deal of the money that came to the rebel army was from
the Albanian diaspora, mostly in Europe, as well as fund-raisers
from London to New York.
</P>
<P>
   While the guerrilla force mushroomed rapidly from a ragtag band
to a more disciplined, better-armed and organized rebel group over
the last year, the guerrillas had neither the time nor the money to
build a truly effective military arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a relatively insignificant military force,'' a senior
U.S. military commander in Europe said last month, a few weeks
before the NATO bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas numbered about 6,000 men, armed primarily with
assault rifles and small mortars, he said, adding that they had
virtually no heavy weapons and poor communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising, therefore, that the rebels have been badly
routed by the Serbian police and Yugoslav army in the last two
weeks. American officials now say the KLA is all but vanquished.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are expected to regroup in Albania, U.S. officials
said, and their supporters are expected to begin a campaign in the
United States and Europe for military support.
</P>
<P>
   A European diplomat said that the most troubling thing about the
Kosovo rebels was that it was not clear what they stood for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what they are,'' he said. ``There is an
Islamic component, a left-wing component, and there are those who
are just guerrillas.''
</P>
<P>
   Of late, he said, they have been united by a common enemy _
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   If they were victorious, they might start fighting among
themselves again _ a repeated pattern of revolutionaries throughout
history _ and there is little hope that they would establish a
democracy. ``They have no democratic experience,'' the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another European diplomat put it this way: ``They are not a
people we would feel comfortable getting too close to. It is not
like they are the military wing of a democratic resistance
movement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
