<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: REFUGEES RECOUNT THEFT OF POSSESSIONS AND
IDENTIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-KLA,
KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW, KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The stark evidence of the failure of NATO air
raids to prevent Serbian forces from driving hundreds of thousands
of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo is in the haunted eyes of almost
300,000 who have already been driven out, and in their unconfirmed,
but uniform tales of horror.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer enormity of the Serbian drive recalls both the spring
and the summer of 1992 in Bosnia, when an estimated 750,000
Bosnians were driven from their homes, and Balkan wars stretching
back to the 1870s. In this region of Europe, making policy by
shifting populations has a long tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The forces of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia seem to
be keeping to that tradition, stripping Kosovo's ethnic Albanians
of the farms and houses that are their only source of wealth, and
then reportedly taking identity documents, property deeds and car
license plates _ everything that would prove they had lived in the
southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   The shattered refugees who have crossed the border here for the
past nine days have told of Serbian forces rampaging through the
countryside looting, pillaging, burning and killing at will and,
finally, hounding the Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is a calculated program of ``massive ethnic cleansing,'' a
NATO spokesman, Sir David Wilby, said at a briefing in Brussels,
Belgium, on Saturday, ``manufactured in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO says this forced exodus from Kosovo is rapidly turning into
the biggest population movement in Europe since World War II. A
NATO spokesman, Jamie Shea, estimated on Saturday that Kosovo could
be cleared of its entire ethnic Albanian population in 10 to 20
days if the current pace at which refugees are arriving keeps up.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more refugees poured over the border here on Friday
night in the rain, spending the night on windswept hillsides with
no shelter other than plastic sheets over their farm carts. This
little town in northern Albania has been swamped with refugees, its
cracked streets filled and what little infrastructure there is
overwhelmed. Water supplies shut off and in the grimy hospital on
the edge of town doctors were pulling shrapnel from refugee
patients without anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   In the long, dejected lines of refugees, people tell almost
identical stories _ differing only in time and place _ of the
arrival of armed men, from the special Interior Ministry police,
the Yugoslav army, or private, ultranationalist paramilitary
militias like the ``Tigers,'' run by the warlord Zeljko
Raznjatovic, better known as Arkan.
</P>
<P>
   Straggling over the border in the last two days have been clumps
of people _ almost all women, children and a few old men _ from the
region around Malisevo who say they have been on the run for days,
hiding in the mountains and woods and under shellfire from tanks,
mortars and Katyusha rockets.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kind of widely dispersed, small-unit tactics that
could only be countered by opposing ground troops. To date,
President Clinton and other NATO leaders have said they would not
send ground troops into Kosovo to fight, although NATO planners and
senior administration officials have suggested that allied forces
may go into the province to create what they term a protectorate _
essentially a guarded enclave to which Kosovo's Albanians could
return, under NATO protection.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Serbian strategy of driving the ethnic Albanians out without
documents not only makes it difficult for them to prove that they
ever lived there, but also for them to be integrated into the more
regulated societies of other European countries, if they cannot or
will not eventually return home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they have no money. This is a part of the world
where accumulated wealth is traditionally not kept in banks or
other investments, but is put primarily into building and improving
one's home and furnishing it with material possessions. Thus, by
burning the houses, the Serbs are wiping out everything the ethnic
Albanians have accumulated over generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years of work, from the father to the son, and now
everything is gone,'' said Osman Osman, 44.
</P>
<P>
   If the hometowns and villages _ mostly now burned _ of the
arriving refugees are traced on a map, a clear pattern emerges of
the population being systematically swept from whole regions.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, the first refugees were mainly from around the
nearest city of Prizren, which lies on a main highway running
through the border, and then from around Dakovica, on a secondary
road to the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Next, people from Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, arrived,
saying that they were pulled from their homes, marched between
lines of masked gunmen, held overnight in a railroad station and
then bused en masse to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the refugees arriving now, villagers, are from more
outlying areas like Dragas, a pocket to the southeast, or around
Malisevo to the north.
</P>
<P>
   The first refugees had several hours or overnight to gather a
few belongings. For the past several days, the refugees have been
carrying only a blanket or a few clothes in a plastic bag. Many are
on foot and have not had food or water for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers at the border say that they are now seeing more sick
and wounded people, partly because they have been on the road
longer and are suffering from exposure and exhaustion, or are
coming from areas that have been under shellfire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
