<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SETTLING THE MICROSOFT CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, April 4:
</P>
<P>
   After a decidedly uneven presentation of its case in court,
Microsoft has come forward with a proposal to settle the antitrust
suit it has been challenging since last year. The word from the
Justice Department and some of the 19 state attorneys general
prosecuting the case is that Microsoft's initial offer does not
address their concerns about what they regard as anticompetitive
conduct by the company. But the department and the attorneys
general are right to pursue a possible settlement with Microsoft. A
negotiated agreement, if done right, would be preferable to years
of litigation, appeals and uncertainty for businesses and consumers
in the fast-changing computer and software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Any resolution of the antitrust suit, whether negotiated or
ordered by the courts, would have to remedy the problems defined
cogently by the Justice Department. Microsoft has been clearly
shown to exercise monopoly power in operating-systems software for
personal computers in ways that coerce competitors and clients,
depriving consumers of choices. The initial focus of the suit was
the contention that Microsoft, by tying its operating system to its
Internet Explorer browser, was muscling aside the rival browser
made by Netscape. During the trial, the prosecution expanded its
attack to include charges of strong-arm tactics against computer
makers, software rivals and others.
</P>
<P>
   In offering to settle, Microsoft has put forth a document
suggesting that it would consider changes in its restrictive
contracts with Internet companies and computer makers, including
possible limits on its ability to customize the opening screen of
Windows. But before accepting such promises, the Justice Department
would have to be satisfied that Microsoft truly had changed its
ways. The best mechanism to guarantee this might be an agreement on
new rules for pricing and other incentives to insure freedom of
choice by the company's rivals and consumers. If a set of adequate
ground rules cannot be agreed upon, the company may find itself
faced with demands for an outright breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and the Justice Department tried to reach a settlement
before the trial began last October. They are silent now about
their talks, which may be a healthy sign. Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson of U.S. District Court has called for the trial to resume
in May, but talks could continue even after that date. The company
should be commended for at least raising the possibility of a
settlement. Its behavior contrasts with that of Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash., the company's home state. Gorton has turned into a
Microsoft cheerleader, and clumsily tried to cut off antitrust
appropriations for the Justice Department. He also belittled
Jackson in a recent visit with employees at the company's
headquarters in Redmond. Microsoft immediately disassociated itself
from those comments, a recognition that serious discussion of the
issues is better than name-calling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
