<SLUG> BC-POLICE-BRUTALITY-PROTEST-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITAL DEMONSTRATION WIDENS SUPPORT FOR DIALLO RALLIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Texas, Calif., Ill. Pa.)   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Led by the relatives of victims of police brutality
from across the country, thousands of demonstrators marched past
the Justice Department Saturday as protests inspired by the death
of Amadou Diallo shifted from New York to the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting the familiar cry of ``No Justice, No Peace,'' the
demonstrators marched to the Capitol for a rally to demand a wide
range of federal responses to police brutality, including a
presidential commission, congressional hearings and legislation
mandating federal reports on police abuse cases.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, many of whom boarded buses before dawn to
reach Washington in time for Saturday's event, included some who
have kept the anger over the Diallo shooting simmering in New York
for two months through daily protests and acts of civil
disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   But the presence of relatives and supporters of victims of
alleged police brutality from as far away as Texas and California
reflected the nationwide attention drawn to the case of Diallo, the
unarmed African immigrant who died in a hail of 41 bullets fired by
four New York City police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's event, called the National Emergency March for
Justice and Against Police Brutality, was organized by the Center
for Constitutional Rights, a civil rights advocacy group based in
New York that has filed a lawsuit in federal court seeking to halt
operations of the New York Police Department's Street Crime Unit.
The officers involved in the Diallo shooting were members of that
unit.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference before the march, organizers said they
hoped to undertake a national movement, inspired by the recent
action in New York City, to demand reforms in police policy and in
the handling of abuse and misconduct cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come resolved to galvanize a new national movement to
fight for police reform and accountability,'' said Ron Daniels, the
executive director of the Center for Constitutional Rights.
``Following the example set by our brothers and sisters in New York
under the able leadership of the Rev. Al Sharpton, we intend to
mobilize and organize to fight for social, economic and racial
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, standing outside the First Congregational Church in
downtown Washington, where the march began, said, ``The senseless
police murder of Amadou Diallo was the proverbial straw that broke
the camel's back.'' But he added, the Diallo case ``is the tip of
the iceberg in terms of the scourge of police brutality misconduct
afflicting communities of color and poor communities across this
nation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although several speakers said they had been galvanized by the
protests in New York City, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said he did not
believe New York was a focal point of Saturday's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a very unfair impression,'' Giuliani said,
speaking to reporters at the New York International Auto Show.
``There are cases and situations all over the country. In fact, the
New York City Police Department has one of the best records in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in Saturday's march said the Diallo case has made
for a compelling rallying cry and has become the focus of opponents
of police abuses everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``His case has sparked a real eye-grabber throughout the nation
and around the world,'' said Endure X, a member of a group called
the African Revolutionized Soldiers, who traveled from Cincinnati
to join the march. ``To have somebody shot that many times who did
not even have a penknife on him really makes our country look
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As they marched, many of the demonstrators carried placards
bearing photographs of victims of alleged police violence. The
names of some of the more well-known of these victims, including
Abner Louima of Brooklyn, Jonny E. Gammage of Pittsburgh and Rodney
King of Los Angeles, were invoked again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said his group's lawsuit against the Street Crime Unit,
charging a pattern of illegal searches and arrests, would proceed
and even expand to include additional plaintiffs, despite recent
changes made by Police Commissioner Howard Safir, including putting
the unit's officers in uniform and adding more minority officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a change in complexion and a change of uniform is
encouraging,'' Daniels said, ``the most fundamental question is a
change of attitude and policy.'' Referring to Mayor Giuliani,
Daniels said, ``It's past time for him to begin steps toward
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration capped an emotional week that included the
indictment on second-degree murder charges of the four members of
the Street Crime Unit who shot Diallo in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building. All four of the officers pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators here were also buoyed by the suggestion Saturday
by the Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, that he
would seek to have charges dropped against the approximately 1,200
people who were arrested during acts of civil disobedience outside
Police Headquarters in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who led the protests and coordinated the acts of civil
disobedience, held a news conference in New York with the father of
Amadou Diallo before leaving to attend the Washington march.
Sharpton said he planned to tour the country with Diallo to protest
police brutality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
