</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-$ADV05-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SHOCKING TEETH INTO SUBMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, April 5)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are like me and hate to floss, then you will be glad to
hear of a new study that says chewing aluminum foil can reduce
cavities.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot remember the exact details of the study because as soon
as I saw the words ``chewing'' and ``aluminum foil'' in the same
sentence, I shut my eyes tight and clapped my hands over my mouth.
(I pretty much have the same reaction when I see the words ``Bob
Dole'' and ``Viagra'' in the same sentence.)
</P>
<P>
   All I recall is that the researcher concluded there is something
about the electrical charge generated by chewing aluminum foil that
scares Tooth Decay away, though he probably used a more scientific
term than `` Tooth Decay.''
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with most scientific studies, this one raises
more questions than it answers.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1, who in their right mind would volunteer for this
experiment? I am trying to estimate how much someone would have to
pay me to grind away on a wad of Reynolds Wrap, but my official New
York Times pocket calculator only goes to eight decimal places, so
I can't say for sure. But it would be a lot.
</P>
<P>
   (Even as I'm writing this, I'm recalling the times that I've
popped a piece of chewing gum into my mouth only to discover,
electrically, a few seconds later that a tiny piece of wrapper foil
had adhered to the gum and how I wished, at that moment, that my
fillings were made of a less conductive substance like, say, wood
putty.)
</P>
<P>
   No. 2, how much electrical charge is necessary to scare away
Tooth Decay? Are we talking the voltage necessary to power one of
those musical birthday cards or something more resembling the
electrical needs of the New York subway system?
</P>
<P>
   I am as supportive of a conscientiously applied program of oral
hygiene and regular professional care as the next Crest user (who
also happens to have good dental insurance), but I have to wonder
if cavity-free teeth are a good trade-off for a mouth that
regularly jams communication satellites and can cook a hot dog at
50 paces.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3, isn't it possible that people who chew aluminum foil have
bigger problems than tooth decay? I am no psychologist, but one has
to think that aluminum-foil chewers are crying out for help, and
not just because their fillings are picking up radio broadcasts of
Elvis singing live from the sixth planet orbiting Alpha Centauri.
</P>
<P>
   Another question I have is: Why aluminum foil? Of all the
substances you could ask test volunteers to chew on, why did the
researchers select the one that is most likely to make the subjects
feel as though they've just clamped their molars down on a
high-tension wire? Did the volunteers start off by chewing on
less-irritating substances like, say, jelly doughnuts? Then we move
up the ladder through ... what? Ground glass? Rusty nails? Aquarium
gravel?
</P>
<P>
   Yet the animal rights nuts go ballistic when laboratory rats
don't get enough exercise ...
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to come across as anti-science, but as far as I'm
concerned, you could promise me a set of chompers like those
displayed by the creature in the dental-health classic, ``Alien,''
and I would still not think of Reynolds Wrap as a desirable
between-meal snack.
</P>
<P>
   Though, I've got to admit, it would be nice hearing Elvis again.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
