<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very chilly air will advance southward through New England in
the wake of low pressure moving off the Maine coast. Unlike most
disturbances, the air circulation will come from the northeast
rather than from the northwest behind the cold front. As a result,
a band of showers will mainly follow the front due to moisture
being drawn inland from the North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding the front, very mild air will cover most of the Middle
Atlantic region and southern New England early Sunday. Clouds will
dominate, but a freshening breeze from the west will bring
intervals of sunshine near the east slopes of the Appalachians.
Readings may reach 85 degrees in parts of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor of humid air stretching from east Texas to the
southern Appalachians will promote showers and thunderstorms in the
Gulf states. Repetitive showers may lead to flooding in parts of
Louisiana. The Southeast be partly sunny and warm.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of a winter storm over North Dakota will still
produce a variety of inclement conditions along the Canadian
border. A cold rain will be mixed with ice in northern Michigan.
Snow will diminish to showers and flurries in the western Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   A swath of dry, pleasant, but a bit cooler air will cover the
central Plains and upper Mississippi Valley. More snow and rain
showers will accompany low pressure moving into southern Colorado.
Heavy snow will fall in parts of the southern Rockies. Sunshine
will return to large sections of the Pacific Coast, but clouds and
showers will move into the Northwest later on.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Patchwork Snowstorm
</P>
<P>
   When wintry weather comes to Colorado, a few miles makes a
staggering difference in the depth of new fallen snow. Friday
morning, 4 feet of snow covered the San Juan Mountains, while on
the other side of the Front Range, the blanket of white was just 6
inches deep in Colorado Springs. Colorado storms are shaped by the
cooling of moist air that ascends the steep slopes. The temperature
of moist air falls three degrees for each 1,000 feet it rises. As
the air cools more water vapor condenses into flakes, resulting in
a patchwork of snow depths that responds to the undulating terrain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
