<SLUG> BC-BBA-SEASON-AMERICAN-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 1999: AMERICAN LEAGUE CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
  Editors: Teams are previewed in order of predicted finish. 
(jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EAST DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 114-48, first place
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, in a reverse of ``Damn Yankees,'' it was George
Steinbrenner who made a deal with the devil last year. Now the
Yankees are starting to pay for it. Not that they will suddenly
become incapable of gaining their second straight full-season
division championship for the first time since 1978. But they begin
the season with their manager sidelined recovering from surgery for
prostate cancer and one of their hitters, Darryl Strawberry, still
rehabilitating from colon cancer. On the other hand, they have
added Roger Clemens to their starting rotation, and that is no
routine addition. He should make Don Zimmer's job as interim
manager easier. So will hitters like Bernie Williams, Derek Jeter,
Tino Martinez and Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON Pitching was the strength of the Yankees'
remarkable 1998 season, and it could be again this season. But some
cracks have appeared: Andy Pettitte's elbow and Hideki Irabu's
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Blue Jays
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fregosi, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 88-74, third place
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam War ended a quarter-century ago, but it caused the
Blue Jays enough problems this spring that they changed managers.
Tim Johnson had to go, the Blue Jays concluded, because his
fanciful tales of service in Vietnam had become a distraction to
the team. Enter Jim Fregosi, who took the 1993 Phillies to the
World Series but has had only one other winning record in eight
other full seasons of managing. The team acceded to Roger Clemens'
wishes to be traded and in the process gained a substitute starting
pitcher, David Wells, and a starting second baseman, Homer Bush. As
spring training neared an end, however, the Blue Jays were still
looking for a designated hitter, a role filled productively last
year by Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Wells, Bush, Joey Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Clemens, Canseco, Woody Williams.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON The Blue Jays, not having replaced Canseco's
productivity, may suffer offensively, so the pitching staff will
have to lead the fight for a wild-card spot. Kelvim Escobar could
play a key role in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Orioles
</P>
<P>
   Ray Miller, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 79-83, fourth place
</P>
<P>
   Ray Miller survived the Cuba game, but how far will he last into
the season? The fate of Miller, owner Peter Angelos' hand-picked
manager, will be determined by how well the team does after being
hastily put together in seemingly haphazard fashion. The Orioles
lost a host of players to free agency, so they scrambled to find
others to fill the holes: Albert Belle to hit home runs and drive
in runs, Will Clark to replace Rafael Palmeiro at first base,
Delino DeShields to replace Roberto Alomar at second. They also
acquired Charles Johnson to bolster their catching. Last year,
Miller directed the highest-paid team in baseball history to a
losing record. This year the payroll is even higher. Good luck,
Ray.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Belle, Johnson, DeShields, Clark, Mike Timlin,
Heathcliff Slocumb, Jeff Conine.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Palmeiro, Alomar, Eric Davis, Armando Benitez, Jimmy
Key, Alan Mills.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON Belle has to have a monstrous season, Timlin has
to show he can save games and the Orioles have to show they have an
idea of how to win.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 92-70, second place (won wild card)
</P>
<P>
   No Mo fun at Fenway. That's the forecast for the Red Sox, who in
their unique way invited Mo Vaughn to leave and did not replace him
after he accepted their invitation. They will be hard pressed to
replace his 40 home runs and 115 runs batted in, not to mention his
.337 batting average, which was only two points below the league's
best. Jose Offerman, who came at a steep price, is not the one to
make up for all that, as he told everyone all spring, and after
.323, 35 and 122 last year, there can be no more from Nomar
Garciaparra this season. Maybe Trot Nixon (.310, 23, 74 in the
minors) will have a sensational rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Offerman, Mark Portugal, Pat Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Vaughn, Dennis Eckersley.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON The pitching staff, which had the league's
second-lowest earned run average last season, will have to hold the
fort while the hitters figure out how to score runs.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Devil Rays
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rothschild, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 63-99, fifth place
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 12 years, his entire major league career,
Fred McGriff did not hit 20 home runs last season. For the first
time in 10 seasons he did not drive in 85 runs. For maybe the first
time in his career, McGriff worked out hard this winter. He never
used to do much in the off-season, said a Devil Rays official. At
the age of 35, McGriff has had a wake-up call. The Devil Rays hope
that as a result, he will light a spark in them, so that they
improve significantly at the age of 2. Wade Boggs, 40, does not
need a wakeup call. He needs 78 hits as the platooned third baseman
to reach 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Jose Canseco, Bobby Witt.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON The Devil Rays scored nearly 100 runs fewer than
the league's next lowest-scoring team, which is why they signed
Canseco. They need him and McGriff to provide the punch that was
missing in their rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENTRAL DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hargrove, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 89-73, first place
</P>
<P>
   If the division were a rock group, it would be the Ten Big
Indians and the Four Stooges. The other four teams are there to
serve as fodder for the Indians, who will win their fifth
consecutive division title. As a way of keeping his players from
sleepwalking until the post-season, Mike Hargrove has challenged
them to win 100 games, a plateau they have reached only once in
their four championship seasons. With the addition of Roberto
Alomar, the Indians have an All-Star at each of the nine field
positions. Not content with their star status, the Indians hope to
add a top-flight starting pitcher, especially Curt Schilling, if he
is available, later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Roberto Alomar, Wil Cordero.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Chad Ogea, Brian Giles.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON They have 162 games to figure out how to beat the
Yankees, then win the World Series, which has eluded them in their
recent run.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Tigers
</P>
<P>
   Larry Parrish, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 65-97, fifth place
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Larry Parrish is not looking that far ahead, but in the
2000 season the Tigers could improve their record in a second
straight season for the first time since 1991. Of course, first
they have to improve on last season's disappointing 65-97. Parrish,
who managed the team on an interim basis last September, has
perhaps the most promising team in the league. The 1998 Tigers
broke their promise; these Tigers would like to fulfill theirs.
Juan Encarnacion (.329 in 40 games last year) is one of the team's
bright young hitters and should join a pair of new veterans, Dean
Palmer and Gregg Jefferies, in bolstering run production. Before
the Tigers' 88th and last season at Tiger Stadium is over, their
heralded rookie, outfielder Gabe Kapler, could contribute, too.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Palmer, Jefferies, Brad Ausmus, Willie Blair.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Luis Gonzalez, Joe Randa.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON They have to find a way, at least, to gain back
the 14 games they did not win last year that they won the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago White Sox
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Manuel, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 80-82, second place
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas would not walk down Rush Street naked, but that is
how he will look at Comiskey Park. No Albert Belle, no Robin
Ventura, no one to hit with him in the team's depleted lineup. The
White Sox hope to get Thomas some help from Paul Konerko, a big
hitter in the minors but a disappointment so far in the majors
(.217 last season with the Dodgers and the Reds). Thomas himself
has to improve after the worst season, by far, of his nine-year
career. His .265 batting average slashed his career average 9
points to .321. South Side fans have tuned out the White Sox and
will most likely continue to ignore them until their rebuilding
plan produces a contender.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION Konerko.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Belle, Ventura, Mike Cameron, Jim Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON Even if Thomas overcomes his nakedness in the
lineup, the team needs vast improvement in pitching (the league's
worst last year) and defense (tied for worst).
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Royals
</P>
<P>
   Tony Muser, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 72-89, third place
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Royals, pending for many months, may take as
long to complete as it takes the team to get back to the playoffs.
The Royals have not been there since 1985, and they do not figure
to get there anytime soon, even under a new owner. In the interest
of having a lower payroll, the Royals could even take a step
backward by trading Jeff King, Kevin Appier and Jeff Montgomery,
their best but highest-priced players. Trades, however, are not
mandatory. Interesting to watch will be a pair of rookies, second
baseman Carlos Febles and center fielder Carlos Beltran. A third
rookie, Jeremy Giambi, brother of Oakland's Jason, could join them
as designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Rey Sanchez, Joe Randa, Chad Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Dean Palmer, Jose Offerman, Tim Belcher, Jeff Conine.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON If the veterans go, the team will be less
developed than an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Twins
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 70-92, fourth place
</P>
<P>
   The longest-running manager in the majors deserves an award for
loyalty, staying with the Twins despite a team that is getting
younger and cheaper. Gone are the days (1987 and '91) when Kelly
could steal a World Series championship. Now he will be lucky to
finish higher than last. Brad Radke's return to his 20-victory form
of two years ago would help Kelly, but with the team the Twins
have, Radke is unlikely to have that kind of season. This will be a
largely inexperienced team that could include a collection of
rookies: Doug Mientkiewicz, Cristian Guzman and Corey Koskie in the
infield and Chad Allen, Chris Latham and Torii Hunter in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Paul Molitor, Pat Meares, Bob Tewksbury, Otis Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON Some of the older players, such as Marty Cordova,
Ron Coomer and Denny Hocking, have to improve their game and lead
the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; WEST DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels
</P>
<P>
   Terry Collins, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 85-77, second place
</P>
<P>
   If the freakish broken arm that Gary DiSarcina suffered early in
spring training was an omen, the Angels will have another long
summer. If, on the other hand, the arrival of Mo Vaughn was the
positive sign the Angels sought, the summer could be warm and
wonderful. Vaughn's presence in the lineup and in the clubhouse
will make the Angels a more formidable threat. So, too, could Troy
Glaus at third and a healthy Todd Greene behind the plate or as the
DH. Glaus, playing his first professional season, slugged 36 home
runs for the Angels and two of their minor league teams last year.
The season will be successful if the Angels win and Chuck Finley
avoids batted balls. Three hit him last year.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Vaughn, Tim Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS Gregg Jefferies.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON In a division filled with good-hitting teams, the
winner could be the one with the best pitching. If the Angels'
veteran starters (Finley, Belcher, Ken Hill) stay healthy, they
could win the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 88-74, first place
</P>
<P>
   If Rick Helling and Aaron Sele can win 39 games between them
this season, the Rangers will win the division title again. They
did last year, in a mind-boggling feat that was as unexpected as
the home run heroics of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa. The Rangers
need Helling and Sele to pitch as well again because the other
starters come with no guar-antees. John Wetteland, the closer, has
no guarantee, either, that his spring ailments are behind him.
Three-fourths of the infield is new from the beginning of last
season. Rafael Palmeiro has returned after a five-year hiatus in
Baltimore, while Royce Clayton and Todd Zeile are holdovers from
midseason trades. Juan Gonzalez is not new, but he's not old
either. At 29, he will pursue his third most valuable player award
in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Palmeiro, Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Will Clark, Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON If the pitching can keep up with the lusty
hitting, the league's best last year, the Rangers will return to
October.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mariners
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 76-85, third place
</P>
<P>
   People are so busy asking if the Mariners can keep both Ken
Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, who can be free agents in two
seasons, that they tend to forget that the two superstars could
power the Mariners to the playoffs this year. The team's prospects
improved when Jay Buhner demonstrated that he was ready to return
to right field after having had Tommy John elbow transplant surgery
last September. Randy Johnson is gone, of course, but the players
acquired for him are ready to help the Mariners. Carlos Guillen
will start at second base, Freddy Garcia will be in the starting
rotation after a sizzling spring and John Halama will be in the
bullpen. The Mariners move into their new stadium July 15.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Jose Mesa, John Mabry, Butch Huskey, Butch Henry.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES Mike Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON Pitching, pitching, pitching. Will the Mariners
have enough of it? They will be ecstatic if Mesa can give them the
closing effort they have sorely lacked.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Athletics
</P>
<P>
   Art Howe, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 74-88, fourth place
</P>
<P>
   Faced with survival of the fittest in the division, the
Athletics are trying to match the offense the other teams generate.
They have Ben Grieve, Matt Stairs and Jason Giambi, but they aren't
enough. The A's added the aging duo of Tony Phillips and Tim Raines
for spark, but that's a stopgap measure. The team is developing
youngsters, spreading them liberally throughout the lineup. The
latest rookie is Eric Chavez, who joins the 23-year-old shortstop
Miguel Tejada on the left side of the infield. However much power
comes from their bats, the Athletics will need runs because the
pitching does not figure to dominate anyone.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS Phillips, Raines.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSS Rickey Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON They have to match the big bats of the other
division teams or come up with stronger pitching than they seem to
have to rise above last place.
</P>
</TEXT>
