<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-CATCHING04     04-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CATCHING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones amazes teammates, opponents
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Andruw Jones plays the kind of center field that puts
fans in awe, gives opponents headaches and baffles even his
teammates, the guys who need his defense the most.
</P>
<P>
   Like the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux, student of the game that he is, likes to ``study''
Jones playing defense, up close and personal. He'll stand 20 feet
behind Jones in center field during batting practice, shadow his
moves and see if he can't play center field with him. It's not
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When balls are hit off the bat, you pretty much say, `Well, I
can't catch that,' and you give up on it,'' Maddux said. ``And he
camps under it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones won his first Gold Glove last season as the National
League's best center fielder. It should be the first of many.
</P>
<P>
   He led all major-league outfielders by committing just two
errors in 435 chances. He led the majors with 413 putouts, the most
by a Braves outfielder since Sam Jethroe had 413 in 1952. Jones
tied for the major-league lead with 20 outfield assists.
</P>
<P>
   And he'll only turn 22 on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jones has spent a full season playing center for the
Braves, the comparisons to other active center fielders have
dwindled. Jones' name used to be thrown in with Ken Griffey Jr.,
Marquis Grissom and Kenny Lofton. Now it's with Willie Mays and Joe
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Viceisza, the scout who discovered Jones in
little-known Curacao, never saw any video of DiMaggio playing
center field when he was growing up. The first DiMaggio highlights
he saw were on TV last month after DiMaggio died.
</P>
<P>
   Viceisza, sitting at a table in the Braves press box at the
Disney complex, leaned in real close and said quietly, as if he
didn't want Jones to hear from the team clubhouse several floors
below, ``DiMaggio's better.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones has time.
</P>
<P>
   When Viceisza first scouted Jones in November 1992, Jones was
15. Jones never picked up a bat during that tryout, but Viceisza
saw enough to get on the telephone with the Braves and persuade
Paul Snyder, director of scouting, to come down and see for
himself. Within a month, Jones was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see from the first minute that he was something,''
Viceisza said. ``He was so natural in everything he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was playing catcher for his youth team in Curacao. He
mostly had played that position and shortstop, but Viceisza saw
center field in him.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Jones is playing the best center field in the
game, maybe the best in quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   Of those center fielders Maddux has seen in his career, Jones is
the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy,'' Maddux said. ``He catches everything. Balls that just
aren't caught, he catches. He catches maybe one or two a week that
you just never see caught, you won't see another guy catch. And
he'll catch them all, whether it's back, in, straight, to the side.
That's the thing. He makes it look so easy. It's to the point that
when he misses the ball it gives the effect that, `Oh, he didn't go
after that one.' But he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, even though Jones wasn't hitting and got into trouble
with manager Bobby Cox for not hustling, the Braves were willing to
give him some growing room in Atlanta instead of AAA Richmond. The
reason was mostly his defense.
</P>
<P>
   It has been his constant since he signed with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league prospect George Lombard played left field beside
Jones for a couple of months in 1995 in Class A Macon. Jones used
to catch balls in front of Lombard, playing the outfield as if he
didn't need left or right fielders. And for Lombard, it was OK. He
could admire a teammate who made playing the outfield look so easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can play the outfield half as smooth as he does, I'll be
all right,'' Lombard said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jones turns the frustration on National League hitters, who
have much more to contend with than just a Greg Maddux cutter, a
Tom Glavine change-up or a John Smoltz fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can cover some ground out there as good as anybody, if not
the best,'' Houston Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``A
lot of times you think you hit a ball that's going to fall, and he
closes the gap on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets catcher Mike Piazza knows the sentiment well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an outstanding outfielder, no question about that,''
Piazza said. ``With the type of pitching staff they have, they need
good defense, and he's the key. He knows how to play the hitters
and get a good jump on the ball. You've got to hit the ball way
over the fence to get it by him.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick, Piazza said, is not letting Jones get under your
skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really don't want to change your approach (at the
plate),'' Piazza said. ``It's more your attitude. If you hit a good
ball, and he catches it and makes it look easy, you can't get
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
