<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-HITTING04-     04-03 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-HITTING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New faces give Cox flexible batting order
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since 1996, Bobby Cox has devised a new lineup almost
every other game. Do not be fooled.
</P>
<P>
   The 256 different batting orders the Braves have used during the
last three seasons reflect the least change of any club in the
majors. Some of that stems from a high level of performance (a
major-league best .624 winning percentage) that has made
experimentation unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   But it also reflects Cox's comfort with his starting core, a
trait that endears him to most Braves, at least those who play
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox's comfort zone took a hit this season. Not only has
Andres Galarraga's absence meant a 15.2 percent loss in RBIs, but
Cox also will be starting three new regulars _ Bret Boone, Brian
Jordan and Otis Nixon _ who are critical to the club's offensive
performance.
</P>
<P>
   If the rest of the National League is curious about changes in
the Braves' starting rotation, how the club comes together at the
plate is surely topic 1-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got enough depth on this team to hold us,'' Jordan said.
``Roles change. You can use a lot of these guys in four or five
different spots in the order, no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Galarraga's cancer diagnosis rocked the franchise, the
Braves could not have prepared much better had they known months in
advance. Signing Jordan provided a new cleanup hitter. The Boone
trade brought the best power numbers (24 homers, 95 RBIs) by any
Braves second baseman in a quarter-century. Nixon is the
prototypical leadoff hitter the club lacked last season.
</P>
<P>
   A bench including Keith Lockhart, Gerald Williams and Ozzie
Guillen is now stocked with tough outs. Originally devised to
improve the team at second base and left and right fields, where
Cox was forced to platoon in 1998, the winter moves now work to
fill in for Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with Montreal, Boston, the Dodgers,'' Nixon said.
``I've been with Texas and Boston, Toronto, and this is the most
balanced team. There are more things (Cox) can do with this ball
club than any I've been on.''
</P>
<P>
   After last year's historic production (215 homers, 297 doubles,
2,483 total bases, .453 slugging percentage, all franchise
records), the Braves would have been hard-pressed to duplicate
those numbers with a healthy Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like having made those moves and then losing Cat,
we just kind of subtracted a lot of what those guys can do,''
Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   But the question is how the Braves will deploy the talent.
Besides Nixon hitting first and Chipper Jones hitting third, Cox
has a new versatility throughout his roster, which was the original
goal when general manager John Schuerholz first began discussing
options in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look up and down the lineup,'' Boone said. ``I still think
we're as good as anyone in baseball without (Galarraga). With him,
it's just phenomenal. But you can't replace him, nor should we get
ourselves saying we're going to replace him. And if you look at the
numbers up and down the lineup, we're as good as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves can use Boone, Andruw Jones or Walt Weiss to hit
behind Nixon. Chipper Jones, Jordan, Ryan Klesko and Javy Lopez,
who fill out the middle of the order, hit .291 with runners in
scoring position last season. Jordan even suggested a No. 8 hitter
on this team could drive in 100 runs.
</P>
<P>
   But if the 1998 Braves were driven by power, the 1999 Braves
will have to be more resourceful than that. Cox probably has more
offensive options than on any other Braves team he's managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a luxury for a manager but you need that,'' Nixon said.
``It's rare to find it. I think the Yankees were in that situation
the last couple years, with what they could do with the infield and
outfield. It was an overabundance, what they had up there. But you
see the same thing here. It's a must for a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
