<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHING04     04-03 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PITCHING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves mount a younger pitching rotation
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The news came to him in Japan during a November
all-star tour. Kevin Millwood, halfway around the world, found
himself a central part of the Atlanta Braves' new plan.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle was gone, and Millwood no longer was the curio
snatched from the depths of the minor-league system just 16 months
before. Not only was he Neagle's replacement, Millwood found
himself part of an amended Braves formula to get the club back into
another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I thought,'' Millwood said. ``I think at the
end of the season last year everybody knew something was going to
happen, and it kind of (hurts) to see a guy like (Neagle) go, who
pitched well for us and did a good job. But at the same time, it
helped me out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood and 20-year-old rookie Odalis Perez assume the jobs as
fourth and fifth starters for the same team that had preached all
decade that there is no such thing as too much starting pitching.
Neagle, who left Atlanta with a .667 winning percentage, also took
the remaining two years of his contract, valued at $9.5 million, to
the Reds, clearing some payroll space for newcomers Bret Boone and
Brian Jordan, who will make a combined $9.9 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   While financially logical, the move represents a huge leap of
faith for the Braves, who have a grand total of 37 major-league
starts from their fourth starter and none from their fifth. Bruce
Chen, who started four games late last year, struggled during much
of the spring as the fifth starter, and Perez won the job, at least
as camp closed. It has become apparent the team doesn't really have
a plan B if the new rotation doesn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many plans you're allowed when you're
putting together a club,'' general manager John Schuerholz said.
``You do what you think is the best thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Millwood's promotion appears to be a no-brainer.
His 17 wins last year tied teammate John Smoltz, New York's Al
Leiter and San Diego's Andy Ashby for sixth-most in the National
League. His .656 career win percentage as a starter (21-11) rivals
Neagle as a Brave and far surpasses both Tom Glavine and Greg
Maddux at the same points in their careers, when they were a
combined 18 games under .500 after their first full years in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Millwood was hit hard in 1998, giving up
175 hits in 174 1/3 innings. He averaged 3.9 pitches per at-bat,
fourth-highest among NL starters, and was the beneficiary of a
hefty 5.1 runs per start in support. After a 7-1 start over his
first 10 appearances, Millwood went 10-7 in the last four months,
despite posting a 3.73 ERA after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole thing last year was I got off to a good
start,'' Millwood said. ``In the minor leagues every year, I was
struggling early in the season and would not pitch real well. The
beginning of the season last year was probably the key to my whole
year. I got some confidence built up, and it just kind of
ballooned.''
</P>
<P>
   While Millwood has encountered success in the majors, Perez's
promotion is based almost entirely on potential and his spring
showing. The team is investing heavily in a rookie who pitched 10
2/3 innings in 10 September games last season and has gone 16-18
with a 2.95 ERA in 94 career minor-league games, 39 of them starts.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, the youngest player to debut last season and a member of
the Braves' postseason roster, led Atlanta in strikeouts this
spring. But even with Perez claiming his spot in Atlanta,
management will not waver on the timing of Neagle's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the emergence of Millwood last year winning 17 games and
with Chen and Perez right on the brink,'' Schuerholz said, ``it was
easier for us to consider making a move like that, where we took
the giant step, trading a high-caliber fourth starter to allow us
the opportunity to add another offensive player. We had never been
in a position like that before, where we had guys who were that
developed and capable, in our view, on the horizon that would allow
us to make this bold move.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of that boldness has not been measured fully yet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
