<HEADER>
A4801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-THEPEN04-C     04-03 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-THEPEN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves not panicking about the pen
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The whirlwind tour that has been the Braves' bullpen
for the past decade is expected to continue during the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Seven different relievers have led the team in saves during the
last nine seasons _ Joe Boever, Juan Berenguer, Alejandro Pena,
Mike Stanton, Greg McMichael, Mark Wohlers and Kerry Ligtenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, who led Atlanta in saves in 1995-1997, emerges from
spring training as the Braves' closer, but he remains a question
mark after a disastrous 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Wohlers situation became crucial with the loss of
Ligtenberg, who recorded 30 saves last year and became the first
rookie since Todd Worrell in 1986 to lead the National League.
Ligtenberg is out for the season with an elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Braves are not panicking.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that has found answers riding into camp on a
motorcycle (Mike Bielecki), buried on the list of nonroster
invitees to spring training (McMichael) and toiling away in the
independent Prairie League (Ligtenberg).
</P>
<P>
   There is another big reason why the Braves haven't taken any
drastic measures _ John Rocker appears ready to step into the
closer's role if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your two options are a right-hander who had 100 saves in
three years, and he throws 95-100, or a left-hander who does about
the same thing without the experience, I think you've got two good
choices to go to,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves also have Rudy Seanez and Mike Cather, both proven
setup pitchers. Cather has recovered from rib-extraction surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Remlinger has shown glimpses of the control
problems that cost him last year in Cincinnati, but he has been
dominating at times during the spring. The Braves can use him for
spot starts and veteran leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to have a real good bullpen,'' said pitching
coach Leo Mazzone, who conceded that Ligtenberg's loss will hurt.
``Our bullpen's been great this whole run. Sometimes they get in a
tough spot, and the reason for that is because they're coming
behind a very high standard of excellence that's been set by the
rotation, so every slip-up gets magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're satisfied with what we've seen,'' Braves
general manager John Schuerholz said. ``John Rocker's throwing the
ball well, and Mark really looks like he's close to being back.
Rudy Seanez did a great job for us last year. Remlinger has not
closed, but he's thrown the ball well in relief, so we're going to
be OK with our relief pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
