<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DONBAYLOR04-COX     04-03 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DONBAYLOR04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A hit with the Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don Baylor says he has been in uncomfortable
positions, but working as a hitting coach for Braves manager Bobby
Cox is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys are comfortable with their own situation, there's
absolutely no problem,'' Baylor said. ``He's managing like I tried
to do. When I brought guys in as coaches, you let them do their
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was bitter after being fired last season by the Colorado
Rockies after taking an expansion team to the playoffs during three
of his six years there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just confused more than anything,'' Baylor said. ``They
gave me a chance to manage and I did exactly that. I took a team to
heights they'd never been to before. ... But a manager can only do
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Seale is a man who knew Baylor when he had so many reasons
to feel uncomfortable, not to mention feel bitter. So he knows the
difference. From Seale's perspective, Baylor is going to thrive in
his new situation, and so are the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Seale has been a part of Baylor's life since the hard-working
Baylor first learned how to be confident in the face of rejection,
comfortable with who he is, thankful for his opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Seale became Baylor's baseball coach at Stephen F. Austin High
School in Austin, Texas, in the 1960s, two years after Baylor
volunteered to become one of several black students to integrate
the all-white school. Seale didn't coach the baseball team until
Baylor's junior year, but he watched the team play during Baylor's
sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   And there sat Baylor, the first black athlete in Stephen F.
Austin's history, on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The man who would become an American League MVP with the Angels
in 1979, who would play on three consecutive World Series teams
with the Red Sox, Twins, and A's in 1986-88, who would become the
sixth black manager in the history of major league baseball for the
Rockies in 1992, was being benched because of his color.
</P>
<P>
   When Seale took over the team the following year, not only did
he let Baylor play, he named him a captain. He did so against the
wishes of many parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught a little flak for that,'' Seale said. ``I didn't
really care. In my mind, he was the person who deserved it. ...
That was when being a captain wasn't just a name or a star on a
letter jacket; it really meant something.''
</P>
<P>
   Seale sees those same leadership qualities in Baylor now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had an outstanding career in high school and pro ball,
but the thing I admire most about him is the way he handled himself
through all of it, the way he still handles himself,'' Seale said.
``He's an excellent role model for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why Baylor will end up a manager in baseball again. It may
be why some people think Baylor was brought to Atlanta as a manager
in waiting after the Braves' repeated postseason disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   But Braves general manager John Schuerholz shoots down those
assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are false; they are absolutely false,'' Schuerholz said.
``That's silly. Don had a fine run as a manager, but we hired him
because he's a good hitting coach. We're not looking to find
somebody who's a replacement for our manager. We're looking for
somebody to be the best hitting coach we could get, and I think we
got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said he never felt threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never crossed my mind,'' Cox said. ``And if somebody has
to take over for me, I'd be proud if they came from our own staff.
I've always had good coaches. All of them are capable of managing
in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were in the midst of a miserable offensive slump in
the National League Championship Series last October, when
Schuerholz asked Baylor at a major league baseball party if he had
any interest in coaching for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor still had an offer from the Rockies to work in their
front office, so he took a month after the NLCS to figure out his
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I cleared the decks right here,'' Baylor said pointing to
his heart, ``I was fine with it. I knew it was time to sever that,
and I never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor turned down offers to coach in Seattle, Oakland and
Cleveland to join the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring into his decision was his friendship with Schuerholz,
who signed Baylor to the Baltimore Orioles farm system when Baylor
was 17.
</P>
<P>
   There was his desire to stay in the National League. There was
the Braves penchant for winning and a chance to return to the World
Series. There was the exposure that comes with that. And there was
Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is the best situation for me,'' Baylor said.
``I've respected Bobby for years. People who played for him always
said the same things about him and that's hard in our business _
how consistent he is, how he's a great guy to play for, good guy to
work for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves want Baylor to develop Ryan Klesko into a run
producer, to take Andruw Jones to the next level, to breathe life
into an offense that has gone into hibernation each of the last two
Octobers.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has a reputation as one of the best hitting coaches in
baseball. He has revived the careers of Andres Galarraga and Vinny
Castilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody respects him so much,'' said Walt Weiss, who played
with Baylor in Oakland and for him in Colorado. ``He has that
presence. He has that air about him. Even in Oakland. We had a lot
of characters on that team, some pretty big egos, but when he
spoke, people definitely stopped talking. Even as a player, he was
almost like a father-figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor seems already to have had a positive impact on Klesko.
The Braves lineup has looked potent at times, despite the loss of
Galarraga. And optimism is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew (Baylor) was a hard-worker, so I'm not surprised to see
that,'' Schuerholz said. ``I knew he was an intelligent and
knowledgable baseball hitting practitioner, and I'm not surprised
by that. I knew that he was a dedicated and spirited worker and I'm
not surprised by that. So the fact that the players are all saying
the same things is the highest praise of all, because that's who he
has to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz's biggest fear is that another team will need a
manager this season and recruit Baylor. Baylor's agreement with the
Braves allows him to leave without penalty if he's offered a
manager's job. That was a chance the Braves were willing to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, it happens; God bless him, he deserves it,''
Schuerholz said. ``He's established himself as a major league
manager and did a fine job at it. If somebody comes and wants him
to be a manager, I wouldn't be surprised, and I'd wish him well.
I'd hate to lose him.''
</P>
<P>
   While working with hitters is natural for Baylor, he still wants
to manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure of managing was an awesome experience,'' Baylor
said. ``You put on a squeeze and nobody in the ballpark knows
except three people. That's the fun of it.... But I'm having fun
doing what I'm doing. I enjoy working one-on-one with these guys
here. If that time comes again, it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   DON BAYLOR AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Born: June 28, 1949
</P>
<P>
   Resides: La Quinta, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Playing highlights: Played 1970 through 1988 for Baltimore,
Oakland, California, N.Y. Yankees, Boston and Minnesota. Holds the
major league record for being hit by a pitch (267).
</P>
<P>
   Coaching highlights: Served as hitting instructor for the 1990
and '91 Brewers and 1992 Cardinals. Named Rockies manager in 1993,
where he stayed through 1998. Compiled a 440-469 record (.484) in
six seasons and was named 1995 NL Manager of the Year for leading
the Rockies to a wild-card playoff spot. The Rockies lost the
playoff series to the Braves 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
