<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-JORDAN04-COX     04-03 2171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-JORDAN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan excels at football but opts for security, longevity of
baseball
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those who have watched Braves outfielder Brian Jordan
the closest during the years say they always have noticed his inner
drive.
</P>
<P>
   The kind that would have Jordan, the baseball player, busting
into an outfield wall with abandon. The kind that took Jordan, the
football player, from injured outcast status as a rookie with the
Buffalo Bills to a backup job at strong safety for the Atlanta
Falcons by the end of that year.
</P>
<P>
   The kind that had former St. Louis Cardinals general manager Dal
Maxvill extending a $2.4 million contract offer to an outfielder
whose pro baseball career consisted of only 116 minor-league games
in four seasons. The kind that made former Falcons coach Jerry
Glanville crazy about a strong safety from a small school who hit
and played hard.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of inner drive that had Jordan, as an
18-year-old kid from Baltimore, turning and leaving coach Bobby
Ross's office on college football's national signing day after Ross
told him if he wanted to play football for the University of
Maryland, he would have to give up playing baseball his freshman
year.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of drive that six months later had Jordan inches from
his father's face, pointing at his forehead, after Alvin Jordan
called his youngest son a wimp.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of drive that eventually led Jordan to one of
the biggest decisions of his life _ turning his back on a solid NFL
career to become the best professional baseball player he could be.
</P>
<P>
   The preparation
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it would seem easy to figure out where some of
that drive comes from in Jordan to not only survive but succeed in
two professional sports. The first place to look is in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Brian had just come home from playing in a high school all-star
football game one summer night in 1985. Alvin Jordan had been home
from the game for a while. He was standing at the kitchen sink
doing the dishes when Brian came home.
</P>
<P>
   Brian was still sore, mentally and physically, from losing the
game. He hadn't practiced all week because of muscle spasms in his
back but insisted on playing anyway. He had been taped up tight and
played stiff. He got away with it until late in the game when a
burly running back came up the middle toward Jordan, who was
playing safety. Instead of tackling him high like he normally
would, Jordan went in low hoping to avoid some pain. But the back
tumbled over Jordan and into the end zone for the game-winning
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That was the play Alvin Jordan was thinking about when he said
just one word to his son as he walked through the door: ``Wimp.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after Jordan's older sister Felicia dragged him downstairs
to cool off, did son and father avoid more than a heated exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I was thinking, 'What the hell does he want?'''
Brian Jordan said. ``It took a couple days before I went down and
finally apologized to him. He said, 'Hey, that's the attitude I
want you to take to college with you.' I knew then it was a setup
just to make me tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Jordan said, ``I wanted him to know when he got to
college, there would be someone who would holler out of the stands
and would make him mad. He'd have to learn how to control his
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and his father were both emotional about football. Alvin
Jordan was thought of as a great athlete in his own day, but he has
little more than neighborhood lore to back him up. The closest he
came to playing college sports was a rumor that he'd get to tryout
with the University of Michigan after one of their alumni saw him
play football on an army base in Korea. But when he got back to the
United States there was no tryout, possibly, Jordan thinks, because
he was married.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Jordan likes to think her husband chose love over sports.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan made a pact to himself that he wouldn't have to
make such a choice. Whatever sport his father couldn't play, Jordan
was going to make sure he played that one, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur years
</P>
<P>
   At Millford Mill Academy in Baltimore, Jordan was captain of the
football team, captain of the basketball team and captain of the
baseball team. He emerged as an all-star in football and baseball
and decided to pursue both in college.
</P>
<P>
   Not many schools were willing to let Jordan play two sports, but
Division I-AA University of Richmond would. So after his
disappointing news that Ross didn't want him to play baseball at
Maryland his first year, Jordan signed with Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   He made all-conference in football and baseball. He was a
Division I-AA All-American in football, but it was pro baseball
that came calling first. After his junior year, Jordan was drafted
by the Cardinals as a supplemental pick between the first and
second rounds. They wanted him to leave school, give up football
and start rookie ball. After some lengthy negotiations, Jordan took
nearly $50,000 less of a signing bonus, so that he could return to
school after his rookie-league season, play another year of
football and graduate.
</P>
<P>
   After his senior year in 1989, Jordan was taken in the seventh
round of the NFL draft. He would have gone much higher, but he had
broken an ankle in the Senior Bowl all-star game in Mobile, Ala.
The Bills released Jordan, thinking there was no way he'd come back
that season from the injury, but the Falcons picked him up, let him
heal and put him in the defensive backfield, where he started in
1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The big decision
</P>
<P>
   Watching Jordan play for the Falcons on Sundays used to make
Maxvill miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sit there and cringe when he'd slam into a 240-pound
fullback,'' said Maxvill, who is retired from baseball. ``I'd have
to turn the TV off.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan's contract with the Falcons expired after the 1991
season, Jordan, his wife, Pam, and his parents wanted him to
continue playing football. The Cardinals did not. They made him an
offer to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan asked the Falcons for around $1 million a year, but the
Falcons responded with half that amount. Jim Hay, the Falcons'
chief financial officer, said the Falcons couldn't justify paying
that type of money to a third-year player. The Cardinals, on the
other hand, were willing to pay Jordan $2.4 million for three
years, guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My dad) wanted me to wait instead of signing a baseball
contract,'' Jordan said. ``But kids, married, young, a chance to
help my parents, too _ I was just thinking about who I could help.
... Security is the key. Longevity is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   It was practically unheard of at that time to pay a
minor-leaguer that kind of money, but it made sense to the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides some raw, very raw natural ability with the bat,
glove, arm and legs, there was an internal desire,'' Maxvill said.
``A will to overcome anything to achieve, not just a big-league
career but beyond that. It was easy to sense he was special that
way. ... We had the foresight to draft him, pay him, keep him out
of football, and there's pride in that. Besides, you like to see
good guys do well. And he's a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan played his last professional football game in January
1992, when the Falcons played the Redskins in the playoffs. He made
his major-league debut with the Cardinals later that same year
after Andres Galarraga broke his wrist. But it wasn't until June
1993 that Jordan secured his place in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, especially when you're bouncing back from AAA to
the big leagues, missing all your buddies on the football field;
(the Falcons) were moving into a new dome,'' Jordan said. ``Man, I
didn't get a chance to play in that dome. So it was eating me up
there for a bit. But it was another challenge, because I hadn't
given baseball a true shot yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The present
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it's another Galarraga health problem, this time
cancer, that brings Jordan into the spotlight. The Braves' move to
sign him during the offseason got that much more important after
Galarraga was diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who will bat cleanup in Galarraga's spot, comes into the
season with a five-year, $40 million contract and peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   He just bought a second home in Orlando, Fla., where his parents
can enjoy retirement by escaping the Baltimore winters, his kids
can enjoy a swimming pool and nearby Disney World, and Jordan can
live a short ride from the Braves ballpark during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's last flirtation with football came with the Oakland
Raiders, but once again the Cardinals won out, signing Jordan to
his previous contract worth $12 million. Jordan admits he still
itches to play football from time to time _ he joked that he was
hoping Falcons coach Dan Reeves would call for his help for the
Super Bowl _ but said his future is baseball. And that's enough of
a challenge for Jordan, who's always found baseball harder than
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is straight ahead, smashmouth,'' Jordan said.
``Baseball is being patient and adjusting to a ball that's moving
every which way. It's a never-ending learning process for me. Not
playing in those minor-league games like everybody else, I'm still
catching up, still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jordan has learned much more than how to hit a
curveball, how to take full advantage of his opportunities and how
to be tough. He learned that he made decisions a lot like his
father after all, because in the end, he put his family first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss that (two-sport) challenge; I do,'' Jordan said. ``But
I have a new challenge of raising my kids, and that's a big reason
why I limited myself to one sport. I wanted to spend time with them
and be the daddy I know I can be for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The future
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that the horsing around gets a
little rowdy sometimes in the Jordan household when the former
Falcon plays a little ``football'' with his 5-year old son, Bryson.
And yes, every now and then Dad will get a little rough and Bryson
will cry, and then Dad will smile and nudge him and tell him he
just has to be tougher. Then Bryson will get up and fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said baseball is his son's best sport. As a 4-year-old,
Bryson was bumped from T-ball into coach-pitch.
</P>
<P>
   So if Bryson decides he wants to follow in his father's
footsteps and play both football and baseball when he grows up,
will he have his father's blessing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he'd just want to be a doctor,'' Jordan said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   THE BRIAN JORDAN FILE
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 32.
</P>
<P>
   Height/weight: 6-1; 215.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife Pam, daughter Briana, son Bryson. Wife Pam is
University of Richmond's second all-time leading scorer in women's
basketball. Pam and Brian were inducted into the University of
Richmond Hall of Fame in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Captain of the football, basketball and baseball
teams at Millford Mill Academy in Baltimore. Made all-district in
basketball, all-state in baseball and honorable mention
All-American in football during senior year. Was drafted by the
Cleveland Indians in the 20th round his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   College: Played football and baseball for the University of
Richmond Spiders, after being recruited by Maryland, North Carolina
and Nebraska to play football. Made All-Colonial Athletic
Association and honorable mention All-American as a center fielder.
He's second all-time in career stolen base at Richmond with 56 and
hit .321 with 32 home runs and 103 RBIs in three seasons. In
football, after being redshirted his freshman year, Jordan became
an All-Yankee Conference and honorable mention All-American
defensive back. He's fourth all-time at Richmond in interceptions
with 11 and second all-time in punt return yardage (692 yards for
an 11.53 average). Received a degree in sociology.
</P>
<P>
   NFL: Was drafted in the seventh round of the 1989 draft by the
Buffalo Bills. Was cut during training camp because of a badly
broken ankle and signed by the Falcons on Sept. 5. He returned to
health for the last four games of the 1989 season. He did not
start, but recorded five tackles in those four games. In 1990, he
started 15 of 16 games at strong safety, made 193 tackles and three
interceptions. In 1991, he started 15 of 16 games, made 145
tackles, four sacks and two interceptions. He was named an
alternate on the 1992 Pro Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball: Was drafted by the St. Louis Cardinals as
a supplemental pick between the first and second rounds in 1988.
... Signed a baseball-only contract with the Cardinals worth $2.4
million in 1992, made his major league debut that year. ... Been on
the disabled list six times with wrist, hamstring and back
injuries. ... Had a career year in 1998 with the Cardinals, batting
.316 with 25 home runs and 91 RBIs in 150 games. ... Signed with
the Braves for $40 million for five years on Nov. 23, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
