<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LATINOS-BRAVES04-     04-03 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LATINOS-BRAVES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spanish flavors Braves' beisbol success
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There has been no grand design, particularly given how
some of the components arrived at random. While the Atlanta Braves
have been linked for the ages with starting pitching, while Chipper
Jones banks the endorsement checks, while Bobby Cox rubs his skull
nightly over the global uplink, something else has happened as
important to this franchise's fate as Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves quietly have become one of the game's most Latin
America-oriented teams, and not only in the major league clubhouse
where Javy Lopez and Andruw Jones play out nightly roles. Beneath
them in the minor league system, 43 percent of the players on the
Braves register (93 players out of 217) have been signed out of 10
Caribbean, Central American and South American countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's that amazing, up against the development of
baseball in the Latin countries and the ever-increasing number of
Latin players on other rosters,'' general manager John Schuerholz
said. ``I think our increased numbers are pretty consistent with
what's happened in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Where some major league clubs have two or three
Latin players on their entire 40-man rosters, the Braves will open
the season with six on the opening day 25-man roster. And that's
not counting Venezuelan giant Andres Galarraga, who towers over the
Braves' Latin contingent from his home in West Palm Beach, Fla.,
where he continues cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan Ozzie Guillen took his first look around the club's
Turner Field quarters and said, ``We're the Caracas Braves now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for all of them, because I know where they came
from,'' said Lopez, who took batting practice as a kid in Ponce,
Puerto Rico, using a stick and a pile of rocks. ``I don't know
exactly everything about them, but I know most of them came from a
very poor family. If they're up trying to make it here, that's a
good sign for them, because then they can change their family.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Lopez on the projected opening roster are Odalis Perez,
Guillen (Venezuela), Randall Simon (Curacao), Jones (Curacao) and
Eddie Perez (Venezuela). But the 40-man roster also includes
pitchers Bruce Chen (Panama), Luis Rivera (Mexico) and Ismael
Villegas (Puerto Rico), catchers Fernando Lunar (Venezuela) and
Pascual Matos (Dominican). Add Galarraga and there are 12 Latins on
the 40-man, third only to the Cleveland Indians with 14 and the
Marlins and Expos with 13 each. No team has more than the six
nations represented on the Braves' 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most I've seen on one team,'' said dugout coach
Pat Corrales, entering his 41st season. ``I had a lot of Latins
(while managing) in Philadelphia (1982-83) but nothing like we have
here. That shows the interest they're created down there. This is a
good mix.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's more than good. The way Eddie Perez sees it, his
life's quest is over at age 30. He once played with Venezuelan
legend Davey Concepcion in winter ball and now has played with
legends Guillen and Galarraga and Lopez, a two-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first goal since I was playing baseball is make it to the
big leagues,'' Perez said. ``I make it to the big leagues and the
same year (1995), we won the World Series. That's all I was
striving for. And now they have these three guys here, what else do
I want?''
</P>
<P>
   While Galarraga and Guillen joined the club as free agents, the
rest of the crop came through scouting and was developed by the
Braves. Where in 1975 the team had one Dominican-based scout
responsible also for Venezuela and Puerto Rico, the team now has
eight scouts (seven part-time) in Venezuela alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've expanded,'' said Paul Snyder, scouting and development
director. ``This is really an area where you need a street-smart
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A global television station doesn't hurt either. Once the club
began to extend its scouting network at the start of the decade, it
quickly became clear WTBS had been recruiting potential Braves for
more than a decade. If the Los Angeles Dodgers were for years
considered the reigning power in finding Spanish-speaking talent,
the Braves were able to influence the market quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in '91, it used to be I'd come to a field, the
Braves were already known,'' said Giovanni Viceisza, the
Curacao-based scout who found and signed Andruw Jones. He has since
become an agent. ``It was this team they would see every day on TV.
As a scout, that helps you a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were kids that weren't even asking for money, as long as
they signed with the Braves. I had one kid say he'd sign for one
dollar if it's with the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves were really the only team that actually scouted
me,'' Chen said. ``There were other scouts but they never
approached me. The Braves were the first team to actually pursue
me. At that time, the Braves had just gone from last to first and
they were a real big thing in Panama. I was happy to sign with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That eagerness to please still shows in Atlanta, where the
team's Latin contingent can dominate the clubhouse. If the Braves
are still viewed as a passionless collection of buttoned-down
personalities, no one told Guillen, whose mouth has seemingly been
open since he arrived last May after his release in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to help each other,'' Guillen said. ``I'm the
one who played the most with anyone, and I think it's amazing. Some
other teams, one Latin guy doesn't get along with another one.
Here, these guys all get along. They're really close.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves will still be measured by how far the starting
pitching can take them, there is another story being told in
Spanish. In many ways, it is just as interesting as anything that
appears in the daily standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning where I first got here (in 1992) to now,
this is a totally different team, man,'' Lopez said. ``Even though
we don't have a complete success (in October), at least we have a
success in the clubhouse. That's what I've liked to see.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
