</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LATINOS-CULTURE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves clubhouse is happily multicultural
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bruce Chen, Panamanian-born of Chinese parents and a
high school honors student on the side, walked into the Braves
major-league clubhouse for the first time last spring, a stranger
in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie, like most, got a quick education.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come in and you just feel comfortable,'' Chen said. ``You
see the other guys from Spanish-speaking countries, and I think
it's part of the success Javy Lopez and Eddie Perez have had,
opening the doors for other Latin American players.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not half the story, that the Braves have assembled one of
the largest Latin American populations in any major league
clubhouse. They have also built a support group, a nuclear family
that has become a central pillar to the entire club.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Latin guys, we always try to make everybody feel like
a family,'' said Javy Lopez, who has spent more seasons (five) in
the Braves clubhouse than any current Latin American player.
``Because I don't think any team can have any success if they don't
feel that we're a family. If we're treated different, I don't think
the team is going to play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we all try to get along with each other and try to become
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But they often are nations apart. While most American-born
Braves prefer golf, fishing and playing cards, the Latin contingent
is different. The 1998 World Cup became a festival played out over
a clubhouse television. (Ozzie Guillen wore a green-and-yellow
bracelet to honor mighty Brazil.) They rely on each other, common
among foreign major league players, but the Braves' bond seems to
go beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like one guy goes out with this guy every day,''
Lopez said. ``We all go out together, like to clubs or bars or
stuff like that. They all go _ Latins, Americans, black and white.
We're like that. That's why they've had a lot of success. There's
no racism on this team, no nothing. That's what I like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   This collection is no random event, given the club's improved
scouting system. The pipeline is primed. Mexican Luis Rivera, 20,
throws a 97 mph fastball (228 strikeouts in 179 career innings) and
although he has been used almost exclusively as a starter, he could
convert to closing. Rafael Furcal of the Dominican Republic is the
most exciting infielder to come from the system in years. Furcal
hit .328 at Class A Danville last summer, with 38 doubles and 60
steals in 66 games.
</P>
<P>
   It is remarkable how strong a clubhouse bond has been struck,
for factionalism among Latin players is nothing new to the majors.
While the Big Red Machine was a model for Pan American relations _
Cuban Tony Perez, Venezuelan Davey Concepcion and Dominicans Cesar
Geronimo and Pedro Borbon _ some mixes are not so smooth. Texas'
Ivan Rodriguez and Juan Gonzalez played on the same Puerto Rican
Little League team, but their relationship hardly fosters warmth in
the Rangers' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But even without Galarraga _ he is a father figure to Latin
players throughout the league _ the Braves are a team transformed.
In the 1991 World Series, the same franchise featured Rafael
Belliard, Francisco Cabrera and Alejandro Pena. Missing Galarraga
in 1999, the Braves remain Las America's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andres is the guy everybody respects,'' Lopez said.
``Everywhere we go, he's a big man in this game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
