</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LATINOS-NEWLAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A challenge adjusting to a new land
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Bruce Chen was 16 years old, playing in the
Braves' minor-league system in West Palm Beach, Fla., he had a lot
to learn. And not necessarily about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Living away from his family in Panama City, Panama, Chen had
never made his own bed, washed his own clothes or cooked. He hadn't
handled his own money or learned to drive. But the biggest barrier
was the language. The Spanish-speaking Chen hadn't spoken English
outside of a few classes in school.
</P>
<P>
   He already knew terms like hit-and-run and squeeze, since they
carry over in Latin American baseball. But Chen, who took classes
at a local Florida school while playing baseball in the Gulf Coast
League, had to go to his English teacher to find out what
``attaboy'' meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was something good,'' said Chen, who laughs about it
now.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen, Andruw Jones, Odalis Perez and many other young Latin
major-leaguers had to grow up fast, learn the game and adapt to a
new culture.
</P>
<P>
   They turn to each other for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be the first one to break down and say, `Oh,
I miss my family,''' Chen said. ``Plus, we were playing baseball,
something we loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball was a haven. There were always other Latin players and
Spanish-speaking coaches. Communicating off the field was much
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't talk at all my first year, unless it was
necessary,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   American players would laugh when Chen said ``peeksa'' instead
of ``pizza.'' But by his third year in the organization, Chen was
the player coaches and media turned to when they needed
translations from other Latin players.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, a Dominican Republic native who came to the United States
to play for the Braves when he was 16, said Chen helped him learn
better English by encouraging him to go to restaurants and ordering
American food.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who had taken several years of English in school, also
relied on an American teammate who spoke some Spanish. He would
have his teammate talk to him in Spanish, and he'd respond in
English. If he didn't get the words right, his teammate would
correct him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if I want to progress and play in a different league
every year, I need to learn the language,'' Perez said. ``I think
I've been moving up so quick, because they know. I'm not saying I
speak very good English, but I try to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Adapting to American food also was tough for Perez and other
Latin players. When he couldn't find Latin restaurants, he would
eat with his American teammates and order what they ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said when he first got to the United States he ate a lot
of fast food, because he wasn't used to the food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can eat it because I know what it is; I tasted it
before,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was ahead of his Latin teammates with language, because in
his native Curacao, they speak Papiamento, which is a blend of
Spanish, English and Dutch. But he wasn't as comfortable speaking
English as Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know English, but I was afraid to speak,'' Jones said. ``But
being around people and hearing them talking, it started getting
better. It's like baseball, every year you go, you learn something.
You get better.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chen, Perez and Jones, getting used to American life has
been a small price to pay for a career in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I dreamed since I was little,'' Jones said. ``I
had the chance, and I never thought twice about the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen will begin the 1999 season in Richmond. During the
offseason, he attends Georgia Tech, where he's a dean's list
student in civil engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still adjusting, but I feel real comfortable now,'' Chen
said. ``I know I can go anywhere. I don't feel like I'm missing
something.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
