<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL-STATUS04     04-03 1717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-STATUS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State of the game: Recovering but uneasy
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At some point last summer, someone _ George Will? Cuba
Gooding Jr.? Ozzie Guillen? _ declared that baseball was back.
</P>
<P>
   Well, duh.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa were escorting America through some
of the game's most dramatic moments on a nightly basis. Major
league attendance surpassed a record 70.5 million. A New York team
was at the forefront, an unwritten must for the national marketing
and advertising crowd. Kerry Wood, David Wells, Cal Ripken Jr., Ken
Griffey Jr., Randy Johnson, Tom Glavine and dozens of other stars
provided reason every single day to follow this game.
</P>
<P>
   If baseball had not finally purged itself of the 1994-95 players
strike, the canvas was pretty well hosed down. There was at last
talk of the future for a game that had been living in a very wicked
short-term past.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the strike years, sometimes you were a little bit
embarrassed about doing what you do,'' Atlanta's Greg Maddux said.
``Now that the sting from that is gone, maybe you just take a
little more pride in your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet all the pride in the majors cannot correct the host of
fundamental problems that still plague baseball, problems that not
only were not addressed in 1998 but that have been fermenting since
the dawn of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is not back. All the sport got was a vitamin B-12 shot.
</P>
<P>
   The game has never been less competitive, with half the
franchises eliminated on Opening Day by a financial structure that
strangles fair play. The advent of the game's first $100-million
man underscores the inequities of a system that allows the Fox
corporation behind the Los Angeles Dodgers to pay Kevin Brown a
record $15 million this season. One player in 1999 will earn more
than the entire payroll that 11 teams were paying out in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the biggest issues facing baseball, and Braves
president Stan Kasten will give you two:
</P>
<P>
   ``The game today is captivating with new stars on the horizon,
with new stadiums and arenas,'' Kasten said. ``We just have to keep
that up. For decades, we've been able to continue to increase
exposure and thereby increase revenue. Revenue growth has been
steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side, which I really don't like to talk about
publicly, is the economics of the business of the game, which are
disastrous. Any word less than that is putting your head in the
sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' side doesn't seem comfortable with the current
course either. The financial inequities in the industry are
fundamentally identical to 1994, when the Players Association
conducted its ruinous strike. The basic work agreement expires in
2001, and some players already hear grim music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared to death to see what happens after 2001,'' McGwire
said. ``If we have a work stoppage in 2001, I'll be so disgusted
I'd walk away from the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the public interest statistics, baseball's best barometer,
are suspect. While attendance increased last year, 5.9 million new
fans were counted by first-year franchises in Arizona and Tampa
Bay. Remove those two clubs from the equation, and baseball
attendance rose 2.7 percent, a contradiction to what was regarded
as one of the most exciting seasons of the century. Attendance had
increased 4.9 percent in 1997 without the benefit of McGwire and
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   TV ratings of the New York Yankees-San Diego Padres World Series
were the lowest in history, coming on the heels of the 1997
Florida-Cleveland Series that would have been the worst on record
until it was saved by a dramatic seventh game. New York's sweep
last October wound up costing Fox $15 million, despite the presence
of big-draw Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   This draws a picture of a distracted fan, not the same one
thought to be hustling back through the turnstile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fan has two things: hope and faith,'' commissioner Bud
Selig said. ``It's my job to create as much hope and faith in as
many places as possible. So I have my work cut out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ownership has shown its faith and hope during the 1990s with
brick and structural steel. Seven new stadiums have been
constructed this decade; three more parks have been extensively
refurbished, and eight other franchises (San Diego, Seattle, San
Francisco, Detroit, Pittsburgh, Houston, Cincinnati and Milwaukee)
either have new parks under construction or planned. It is
important that six of those new facilities are being erected in
small-market cities, the strongest indication owners can give that
there is a future.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, the richer teams have upped high-stakes games in
the back room for those serious about making the World Series. The
minimum payroll for a winning team in 1998 was the $38.3 million
spent by Toronto. Eleven teams _ more than a third of the major
leagues _ could not spend so much, and none of them finished closer
than 14 games from their division champion. All eight teams that
reached the postseason were within the top 12 in the payroll
standings, with the exception of Baltimore, which led the majors
with a $75.2 payroll and finished with a 79-83 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Study Committee, conceived to cure these ills, met
in March. When member John McHale, president of the Detroit Tigers,
was asked about isolating the trouble, he replied, ``It's no secret
what the problems are. The inequities among the clubs is the whole
top-10 list of short-term problems in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to fix this,'' Kansas City general manager Herk
Robinson said. ``I think people around baseball understand the
problem. There are a bunch of teams out there, us included, that
simply cannot compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitiveness has actually become a geographic phenomenon.
Nine of the top 10 payrolls in 1998 belonged to teams in eastern or
western divisions, and if baseball is a game of the hinterlands, it
has found a strange way of showing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For baseball to succeed, it needs to succeed in middle
America,'' said Selig, acutely aware of the problems as the
Brewers' former owner. ``Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee, Kansas
City, St. Louis, Chicago, Cincinnati, Pittsburgh _ that's the focus
of my job. It needs to succeed in those places. It needs to have
the chance it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   But then it would also need the cooperation of players. The kind
of revenue-sharing and salary control that has fostered competitive
balance in the NBA and NFL continues to be opposed by the Players
Association, which works behind the scenes every winter to inflate
the free-agent market. Where the league office wants to view member
cities all as World Series contenders, the union still sees a
collection of investors, some with portfolios less than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the prices are higher,'' said Atlanta's Tom
Glavine, the NL's players representative. ``You can't expect to buy
a franchise for a third of the price of the Yankees and expect to
make the same kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely where the new 1995 basic agreement left the
issue, and financial disparity has only grown worse since. Yet at
the same time, there is a growing sense that the union, at last, is
heading for a fall. The damage done by the last strike and a
growing economic imperative have altered negotiating positions, and
some already see a shift in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised to see some marquee names become
available for a discount in the next few years from clubs that got
out there a little too far,'' Philadelphia Phillies general manager
Ed Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are a prime example of a financial system out of
whack _ a big-market team that, for reasons not all its own, finds
itself at the bottom of the pile. Wade is cutting $3 million in
payroll this year to a projected $25.9 million total, almost what
the Braves will pay Glavine, Maddux and John Smoltz this season
($25.75 million). Weary of the money-grubber accusations, some
players are preaching financial reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have agents out there today who want to get every last cent
out of a team,'' McGwire said. ``My theory is this: the agents work
for the player; the player doesn't work for the agent. Players
should stand up and say, 'Enough is enough.' You don't have to get
every last cent.''
</P>
<P>
   This amounts to sedition at the Player Association offices, but
because it's the new home run king talking, the union realizes its
ranks are looser than in the early 1990s. Financial compromise
appears more possible, if only because the union's lone weapon _the
labor action _ is nearly as repulsive in the clubhouse as in the
front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any player wants to go through (a strike)
again,'' Atlanta's Mark Wohlers said. ``I think for the players,
for the most part, once is enough. I sacrificed what I needed to
do. Obviously my tune might change further down the line. I'll
always stand strong with the union. But I think everyone is smart
enough _ the union and the owners _ to know we just can't afford
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has come so far in such a short amount of time since
the strike, you just can't jeopardize what all of us have built
over the last three or fours years. Baseball just can't afford
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, baseball embarks on another season of inequity.
While the high-rolling Braves and Yankees already have their
tickets punched for October, the other half dresses for Opening Day
knowing the schedule is only a cruel formality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's skewed for those who are going to spend money,''
Brewers manager Phil Garner said. ``When it's all over and said and
done, we might look back and say, `Well, gee whiz, Minnesota never
had a chance. Or Milwaukee never had a chance, or Kansas City or
Pittsburgh.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We may look back and say that. But the truth of the matter is
that there is a possibility that lurks out there that we may do
better than everybody thinks. One of my major objectives during
spring training is to make sure that my players believe and
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   At least until the Brewers fall 30 games behind, Garner is fired
up, and the game starts wringing its hands anew about existence in
a new century.
</P>
<P>
   If baseball is back, so are the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
