<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HANKSIDE04-COX     04-03 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HANKSIDE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aaron pleased record ball is resting in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the largest billboards at Turner Field
advertises something that isn't for sale. You've seen the slightly
yellowed baseball towering above the public entrance to the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just any ball.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ball, historic home-run ball No. 715, which left Hank
Aaron's bat and sailed over the left-center field fence on April 8,
1974, to send Aaron past Babe Ruth in the record books. Atlanta
relief pitcher Tom House caught it and returned it to Aaron, who
believes that if it had gone into the stands, someone would have
gotten hurt. He has it on loan to the Braves museum.
</P>
<P>
   But while the slugger always kept this ball safe and close, for
22 years he was annoyed that he could not retrieve his final home
run ball, No. 755. Aaron still doesn't have it, but he is pleased
that a Milwaukee Brewers groundskeeper, who was fired after
catching the ball and leaving the clubhouse with it, no longer has
it, either.
</P>
<P>
   The ball quietly sold for $869,000 in a private deal in
September after failing to reach its reserve price in an auction.
The anonymous buyer, who lives in New Jersey, was a friend of one
of Aaron's friends. ``I know where it is now,'' Aaron said. ``I
know it's in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron had been trying to get the ball away from Richard Arndt
since July 20, 1976, when no one knew that the homer out of County
Stadium would be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't talk about it that much because I get angry about
it,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Arndt claims that the Brewers would not arrange a meeting with
Aaron, but Aaron said that he met him and offered 12 autographed
balls as a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Let me think about it.''' Aaron recalled. ``I said,
'If you walk out of this clubhouse, don't talk to me.' So he walked
out, and the Brewers found out he had taken the ball out of the
clubhouse and fired him.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said Arndt called every five years or so. Aaron's sponsor,
Magnavox, offered to buy the ball, ``But just as anybody was
getting ready to make a deal, he'd draw it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Arndt again approached the Brewers. Bud Selig and his
daughter asked Aaron what he thought, and he said, ``Don't even
talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron was further miffed that the ball was autographed: Arndt
attended a card show where Aaron _ who had no idea who he was _
signed the ball. ``That was sneaky,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the ball was offered at an auction in September. Arndt
agreed to give Aaron's ``Chasing the Dream Foundation'' 42 percent
of the proceeds. But while bidding reached $800,000 for No. 755, it
didn't reach Arndt's asking price. So Aaron convinced his lawyer
and the wealthy friend to make a backroom deal. While he still
doesn't have control of the ball, Aaron said, ``I got it out of his
hands; that's the only thing I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., would
love to have that ball, or No. 715, someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the ability to purchase,'' Hall of Fame
spokesman Jeff Idelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron has donated home run balls 500, 600, 700 , 703, 704, 706,
709, 710, 714 and 717, as well as his 3,000th hit. He has also
contributed bats, gloves and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   But Aaron said No. 715 and the bat he swung belong in Atlanta,
where people can see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the home run here; the ball and bat are supposed to be
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said many years ago he was offered $1 million for the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that I have that I've sold,'' he said. ``And I
never will.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
