<HEADER>
A4811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEMKE04-COX     04-03 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEMKE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lemke waits to play
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Lemke can't remember fielding the seemingly
harmless ground ball last May in Boston, nor the Chicago White Sox
baserunner bearing down on him as he tried to make the tag and
throw to first for a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's good,'' Lemke said. ``If I could remember, I
might have had even more trouble sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare has been bad enough.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 months after suffering a concussion in a violent
baseline collision with Chad Kreuter, Lemke says he finally feels
like his old self. But as Opening Day arrives, the former Atlanta
Braves second baseman is without a job and knows his baseball
career might have come to a premature end at age 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to retire,'' said Lemke, who spent 10 seasons
with the Braves before signing with Boston last season. ``I'm going
to make sure I'm ready to play when someone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lemke works out five days a week and waits for agent Lonnie
Cooper's telephone to ring with a solid major-league offer. ``I
feel like I'm in pretty good shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lemke's priority until the last few months wasn't getting
ready for baseball again. It was just feeling normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love baseball, but it's not the most important thing for me
right now,'' Lemke said. ``My health is. It's taken a long time to
get that back. Your mind is very complex. Concussions take their
toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Six days after his May 19th collision with Kreuter in Boston,
Lemke was back in the Red Sox lineup. But his return lasted only
one game.
</P>
<P>
   His head throbbing and unable to sleep, he was re-examined the
next day. The diagnosis was postconcussive syndrome _ a condition
more common in hockey and football.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke went home to Atlanta to recuperate, with no timetable for
his return to the Red Sox. He never made it back to Boston, which
had signed Lemke to a one-year contract late in spring training as
a fill-in at second base for the injured Jeff Frye.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke, who says he had suffered several earlier concussions,
felt disoriented, even in the familiar surroundings of his suburban
Atlanta condo. His short-term memory was affected, and he had
little energy. Lemke's father, Roger, came down from Whitesboro,
N.Y., to be with his son.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite with Braves fans during his 10-year Atlanta career,
Lemke talked with his ex-teammates by telephone but visited Turner
Field only once during his recuperation, when Boston played an
interleague series in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a tough period right now,'' Lemke said then. ``I
really can't sit here and tell you what's wrong and when I'm going
to be back. Hopefully, I can get back to normal, and I'll be a
different me. Well, the old me.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took time. A lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke says he really didn't feel as if he had gotten close to
being back to normal until January. That's when he began his
workout program, which includes lifting weights at a gym in the
morning, then hitting in a batting cage and throwing in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe what I went through, but it's not
something I like talking about anyway,'' Lemke said. ``In some
ways, I'm still feeling my way. At first, you're just glad to have
more good days than bad. It's a gradual thing. You have to take it
a little at a time and be thankful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lemke, who has beaten the odds ever since he was taken in
the 25th round of the 1983 amateur draft, definitely thinks he can
play again.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox and Lemke's old Braves teammates hope he gets
the chance. Lemke has not had an injury-free season in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lemmer has always been one of my favorite players,'' Cox
said. ``I was really worried about him for a while, especially the
more I heard about head injuries like that. I'm just glad he's
finally feeling better. If anyone can make it back, he can.
Baseball needs players like Mark Lemke.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cox says Lemke has a standing offer to rejoin the
Braves organization as a coach once his playing days are over. ``He
belongs in a Braves uniform,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Lemke would like to coach. But not until he's sure he
can't play anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be a good coach if I was still thinking I might be
able to play,'' Lemke said. ``I want to give 100 percent to
anything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lemke will be apart from the game he loves as the season
begins.
</P>
<P>
   He says he doesn't plan to be at Turner Field when the Braves
open against Philadelphia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be too hard,'' Lemke said. ``But I'll definitely be
following the Braves. I still have a lot of friends on the team.
I'm rooting for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are rooting for Lemke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to him a lot,'' said pitcher Tom Glavine, one of
Lemke's closer friends. ``I know he's feeling a ton better. Now
it's just a matter of waiting for an opportunity. I know he can
still play.''
</P>
<P>
   MARK LEMKE FILE
</P>
<P>
   Birthday: Aug. 13, 1965 in Utica, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Home: Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknames: Lemmer, Dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Years in majors: Ten with Braves (1988-97) and one with Boston
(1998). Missed most of last season with post-concussive syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   1999 status: Free agent still hoping to sign with major-league
team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
