<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SLUGGERS04-COX     04-03 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SLUGGERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The power of the homer
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barely two hours after No. 70 had scorched its way
into a party suite just above Busch Stadium's left-field wall, Mark
McGwire put it on the record. The single-season home run record he
had just created in September would be his contribution to the
ages. He had no desire to break it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I did say that,'' McGwire said this spring. ``Now that
I've thought about it, anything's possible. If I had an opportunity
to do it, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   So, 1999 now has a mantra. ``Why not?'' In an era where the home
run has gone from the game's sublime moment to a nightly muscle
dance, McGwire's republishing of the record book says as much about
him as it does the sluggers around him. Baseball has gone over the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   This season will close the most pyrotechnic decade the game has
ever seen. The major-league slugging percentage in the 1990s (.417)
is the highest on record. Nine teams reached the 200-homer level
last year. Only 10 years ago, no club had more than Toronto's 158.
Of the 26 50-homer seasons recorded in major-league history, eight
of them _ 31 percent _ have come in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the hard-hitting 1930s, the majors this
decade are averaging more than nine runs a game (9.3), with at
least one home run being hit every 9 2/3 innings. Last year, that
rate jumped to one every 33 at-bats. With a new imagination
provided by McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr., the
unthinkable of just a few summers ago has now become an idle boast.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of his 50-homer season, Greg Vaughn reported to the
Cincinnati Reds this spring saying, ``I didn't come here to say
I'll hit 50 home runs. I might be short-changing myself. I might
hit 60.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn? 60? So why not?
</P>
<P>
   There are no fresh explanations. The new parks indeed are
smaller, while the contemporary player is a comparative behemoth.
Hank Aaron in his prime was 6 feet and 180 pounds. Babe Ruth was
6-2 and 215. Check out Larry Walker (6-3, 237) or Jason Giambi
(6-3, 235) or Tony Clark (6-7, 245). McGwire is 6-5, 250.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion-softened pitching has taken a beating. The addition of
four teams in the last six years _ the fastest growth ever allowed
in the game _ means that some 50 pitchers are apprenticing in the
majors instead of learning in the minors. A vast move to lighter
bats has increased bat speeds with surprisingly little drop-off in
distance, improving power numbers for smaller players who could not
wield the 36-40-ounce big sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball still insists that there is nothing different about the
ball, although pitchers and hitters alike swear otherwise. The
freshly printed sixth edition of Total Baseball, MLB's official
encyclopedia, claims that the home run explosion ``has nothing to
do with juicing the ball and everything to do with superb
professional athletes reacting to changing circumstances.''
Two-word rebuttal: Brady Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper truth is that what happened last season might well
have happened in 1994. Before the players' strike on Aug. 11, both
Griffey (40) and Matt Williams (43) were on Roger Maris' tail, and
another four players were within 25 homers with another 45-50 games
to play. The 1998 explosion was only a continuation.
</P>
<P>
   A new panic hit the spring leagues when umpires, under
instructions to call the strike zone as it is defined, stopped
giving strike calls to pitches just off the corners. San Francisco
reliever Julian Tavarez shrieked, ``The strike zone is too narrow.
A guy who hit 30 home runs last year is going to hit 50 this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the game is worried, its reaction does not say so. Almost
embarrassed after the Angels hit just 53 home runs at reconfigured
Edison Park last season, Anaheim officials ordered its center and
left-center walls moved in by nine feet during the winter. Sosa and
McGwire remain front and center in the game's marketing plans. The
first new award established by MLB in nearly a quarter-century will
honor Aaron, the all-time home run king.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if Roger Maris' record had not been torn down so easily
in September, fans would not be clamoring for more. McGwire
finished 1998 with nine more home runs than singles. If laid end to
end, his 70 homers traveled an estimated 29,598 feet, higher than
Mount Everest. In his last three seasons, McGwire has hit 180
homers, exceeding Ruth's three best career years, 173.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say Babe Ruth hit them this way,'' New York catcher
Mike Piazza said. ``But I really can't believe that Babe Ruth could
hit them higher or longer than McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why someone could ask the St. Louis first baseman if he
could do it again. Perhaps more amazingly, McGwire gave the
question some thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think you'd have to be at the 40-plateau at the
All-Star break,'' said McGwire, who had just three short of that at
the 1998 break. ``I can only imagine the amount of pressure. I know
what it entailed to reach 60, 61, 62. Try going 10 more. It's hard
to fathom.''
</P>
<P>
   Not any harder than what the nation is imagining now that it's
Opening Day: Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
