<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SEASON-NATIONAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL 1999: NATIONAL LEAGUE CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EAST DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 106-56, first place
</P>
<P>
   If there is a team that can withstand the loss of a hitter
(Andres Galarraga) who swatted 44 home runs and knocked in 121 runs
last season, it's the Braves. If there is a team that can shrug off
the loss of a reliever (Kerry Ligtenberg) who gained 30 saves last
season, it's the Braves. Until someone proves otherwise, it's the
Braves who are the class of their division. They are also deep.
Galarraga out with cancer? Move Ryan Klesko to first base.
Ligtenberg needs Tommy John surgery? Give the closer's job back to
Mark Wohlers, whose inexplicable wildness prompted the need for a
new closer last year but who for the most part has rediscovered his
control this spring. Another sign of the team's pitching depth:
Bruce Chen, a rookie, was designated as the fifth starter, but he
had a poor spring and Odalis Perez, another rookie, jumped in and
grabbed the job.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Brian Jordan, Bret Boone, Otis Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Having won only one World Series in seven
successive postseason appearances, the Braves have to figure out
how to quiet their critics by winning another.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mets
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 88-74, second place
</P>
<P>
   For a team that thought it was prepared to challenge the Braves'
dominance in the division, the Mets sure have been busy in recent
days and weeks trying to shore up their starting pitching. Orel
Hershiser was a late addition, and general manager Steve Phillips
has not stopped pursuing another starter. The Mets should have won
the wild-card spot last season, but manager Bobby Valentine could
not figure out a way to win one of the last five games. They could
be the wild-card winner this season, but they are counting an awful
lot on a pair of aging outfielders, Rickey Henderson (40) and Bobby
Bonilla (36). Robin Ventura should help at third base, and Mike
Piazza, finally comfortable in New York, should do more than help.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Bonilla, Ventura, Henderson, Hershiser, Armando
Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Todd Hundley, Armando Reynoso, Willie Blair.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The heralded newcomers have to produce to avoid a
repeat of the 1992 debacle that was fueled by the failure of
heralded newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Phillies
</P>
<P>
   Terry Francona, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 75-87, third place
</P>
<P>
   Five losing seasons have followed their stunning 1993 World
Series loss, but the Phillies appear to be doing something right.
They have systematically integrated promising young players into
their lineup, and one of these days the Phillies may actually be a
contender again. Second baseman Marlon Anderson is this season's
rookie addition, joining shortstop Desi Relaford (last year's) and
third baseman Scott Rolen (1997's). First baseman Pat Burrell is on
deck. Catcher Mike Lieberthal and right fielder Bobby Abreu are
other examples of the influx of good-looking young players. The
Phillies only have to hope that Curt Schilling, the pitcher
everyone wants, will not be ancient by the time they are
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Ron Gant, Paul Spoljaric, Chad Ogea, Jeff
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Ricky Bottalico, Mark Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The Phillies should not expect too much too soon.
Their idea should be just to nurture their young ones carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal Expos
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Alou, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 65-97, fourth place
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Alou is the National League version of Tom Kelly, a
manager who could work elsewhere and have a chance to win but who,
out of loyalty, stays where he is. Alou could be managing the
Dodgers, but he chose to stay in Montreal and was rewarded with a
contract worth $2 million a year. His patience and his
resourcefulness will be tested again this season, but he is
comforted by the presence of Vladimir Guerrero, who is on the verge
of becoming one of the game's superstars. As a 22-year-old last
season, Guerrero batted .324, whacked 38 home runs and drove in 109
runs. Alou also likes his young pitchers, even though they threw
the pitches that Mark McGwire hit for Nos. 66 through 70.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Manny Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If Alou can work his managerial magic and foster
inspired play from his youngsters, the Expos at least should be
competitive on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Marlins
</P>
<P>
   John Boles, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 54-108, fifth place
</P>
<P>
   From World Series champion to the team with the worst record in
the majors to what? Marlins fans, if any remain, just can't wait to
find out. The team has a new owner, John Henry, who most likely
would not dismantle the Marlins if they should win the World Series
again. He does not have to worry, though, about facing that dilemma
in the foreseeable future. A bright note for the Marlins is the
return of Alex Fernandez, their No. 1 pitcher, who missed last
season with a torn rotator cuff. A gloomy note is the absence of
Mike Lowell, who was supposed to play third but is out with cancer.
A confusing note is the name of their new rookie shortstop. He is
Alex Gonzalez, and he should be Alex Gonzalez II because the Blue
Jays already have a shortstop named Alex Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Jorge Fabregas.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Edgar Renteria.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Improvement is the best the Marlins can expect,
and Fernandez and a year's experience for the young players should
make that possible.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENTRAL DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Astros
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dierker, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 102-60, first place
</P>
<P>
   When Moises Alou (38 home runs, 124 runs batted in last year)
tore a knee ligament before spring training, the Astros appeared to
suffer a serious setback in their plans to win a third straight
division title under Larry Dierker. But then the teams that seemed
most likely to challenge them for the title, the Cubs and the
Cardinals, suffered their own disastrous injuries. Even if they had
not, though, the Astros might have had enough talent to prevail.
Richard Hidalgo, who batted .303 in 74 games in his rookie season,
replaces Alou in left field, leaving center to Carl Everett, who
batted .296 in 133 games. The Astros no longer have Randy Johnson,
but they did not have him for the first four months last season and
held first place for the last three of those months.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Johnson, Sean Berry, Brad Ausmus.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The Astros just have to go out and play and leave
the thinking to Dierker, who has earned the right to stop having
people question his credentials as a broadcaster-turned-manager.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Reds
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 77-85, fourth place
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bowden, the Reds' creative general manager, has given the
68-year-old McKeon, the majors' oldest manager, an interesting
team. How good it will be remains to be seen. Bowden would like to
steal the wild-card spot, but if the Reds are not in contention for
it by late July, watch Bowden trade away some of his higher-priced
players. Greg Vaughn, who last winter became the first player
traded after hitting 50 home runs, is one centerpiece of the wild
card-or-trade plan. Another is Denny Neagle, the good left-handed
pitcher, who opens the season on the disabled list. The Reds will
also rely on younger players like Sean Casey, Pokey Reese and Aaron
Boone, who make up three-fourths of the infield, and Mike Cameron,
who will steal some bases (27 last year).
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Vaughn, Neagle, Cameron, Steve Avery.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Bret Boone, Reggie Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If everything breaks right, and that includes
pitching contributions from Avery and Jason Bere, the Reds could be
a distant second to the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   Tony La Russa, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 83-79, third place
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals could not ride Mark McGwire's mind-boggling 70
home runs to a better record last season, what is he supposed to do
for them this year? The Cardinals begin with two of their starting
pitchers, Matt Morris and Alan Benes, on the disabled list; Ray
Lankford still not ready to play center, and Edgar Renteria having
played no games at shortstop this spring while recovering from a
knee injury. It is a precarious way to start for a team that wants
to contend for first place, but perhaps a newcomer, Eric Davis, and
a rookie, J.D. Drew, will help McGwire make his production
meaningful. In the absence of Morris and Benes, Jose Jimenez, an
impressive rookie, gets a chance to bolster the starting rotation.
The Cardinals may still make a trade for a pitcher, too, perhaps
Kevin Appier.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Renteria, Davis, Ricky Bottalico, Darren Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Brian Jordan, Ron Gant, Delino DeShields, John
Mabry, Jeff Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The Cardinals need peak production from their
healthy players to avoid a bleak season.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs
</P>
<P>
   Jim Riggleman, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 90-73, second place; won the wild card
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs apparently thought so much of the team that won the
one-game playoff for the playoffs last season that they only
tinkered with it. They might have made a fatal mistake. If their
failure to bolster the team was not fatal, the loss of Kerry Wood
should be. The rookie strikeout sensation is out for the season
with a torn elbow ligament, putting a major dent in the Cubs'
chances of returning to the playoffs. They did add a starting
pitcher before Wood went down, but Jon Lieber (19-28 with the
Pirates the past two years) is no Wood. Sammy Sosa is healthy, but
he is also human. The Cubs cannot expect him to give them more than
he did last season; they have to hope he can match it.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Lieber, Benito Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Mark Clark, Scott Servais.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: As goes Sosa, so go the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Pirates
</P>
<P>
   Gene Lamont, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 69-93, sixth place
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the days when they will have a new park, the
Pirates got a little frisky during the winter and signed some
experienced free agents. Pete Schourek will be in their starting
rotation, and Ed Sprague, Pat Meares and Mike Benjamin will make up
three-fourths of their infield, although Benjamin could share
second base with Warren Morris, a good-looking rookie. Two-thirds
of their outfield came in trades, Brian Giles from the Indians for
Ricardo Rincon, and Brant Brown from the Cubs for Jon Lieber. All
of that makes for an unusually high number of players from other
teams for a team that has been rebuilding. Also unusual is their
leadoff hitter, Jason Kendall. Catchers rarely lead off.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Meares, Sprague, Schourek, Giles, Benjamin,
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Tony Womack, Rincon, Lieber.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If the newcomers jell, the Pirates could cause
trouble in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Brewers
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 74-88, fifth place
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, their erstwhile owner, is the commissioner; Robin
Yount, their 3,000-hit man, is going into the Hall of Fame, and
County Stadium is making way for a new park next season. None of
those developments will affect the way the Brewers play, but they
may be the most interesting aspects of the team's season. There is
one development to watch on the field. Jim Abbott is continuing his
comeback as a one-handed pitcher, which is heartening enough, but
he also has to bat in the National League and his ability to do
that is simply uncanny. Dave Nilsson is another unusual player. One
of five native Australians who have played in the majors, he also
is the owner of the Australian Baseball League, which he bought in
the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Sean Berry, Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Mike Matheny.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: If the Brewers get creditable pitching from
Abbott, Bill Pulsipher and the rookie Rafael Roque, they could be
interesting some of the time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEST DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Dodgers
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 83-79, third place
</P>
<P>
   They signed Kevin Brown for a record $105 million, signed Devon
White and traded for Todd Hundley. But the best move the Los
Angeles Foxes made was hiring Davey Johnson to manage their team.
Felipe Alou was their first choice, and he would have been good,
too, but Johnson's record speaks volumes. In 10 full seasons of
managing, Johnson has led his teams to first- or second-place
finishes each time. This season should make it 11. The Dodgers, of
course, have spared little or no expense to ensure that Johnson's
record is not spoiled. To get Brown, for example, they paid $40
million more than the team with the next-best offer and added a
dozen round-trip charter flights for his family, as if Brown could
not pay for those flights himself.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Brown, White, Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Bobby Bonilla, Charles Johnson, Brian Bohanon.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Not even Hundley's surgically repaired elbow and
Gary Sheffield's unpredictable temperament should keep the Dodgers
from winning.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Giants
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 89-74, second place
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason for the Giants to finish second other than
the fact that Dusty Baker is their manager. Throughout baseball,
Baker is credited with getting more out of his players than most of
his peers. He finds a way to be there, they say. The Giants made
virtually no moves to improve a team that missed the playoffs by
one game, the playoff game it lost to the Cubs. That could work
against them. On the other hand, they are counting on Russ Ortiz
and Chris Brock, pitchers who spent some time with them last
season, to fortify their starting rotation. Ellis Burks, whom the
Giants acquired during the season, has shifted from center field to
right, and Marvin Benard, a .322 hitter last season, has moved to
center.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITION: Scott Servais.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Jose Mesa, Orel Hershiser, Joe Carter.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Baker has to do whatever it is that makes him so
good, and the players have to keep responding.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Rockies
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 77-85, fourth place
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies have not played a regular-season game for him, but
Jim Leyland has already learned what Don Baylor, his predecessor,
lived with every year of the team's existence. Winning will not be
easy until the Rockies raise the level of talent on the pitching
staff. Jerry McMorris, the owner, gave Leyland $2 million a year to
get the Rockies back to the playoffs, where Baylor led them in
their third year. But the only starter they added was Brian
Bohanon, and he's no No. 1. Darryl Kile was No. 1 for Houston with
a 19-7 record two years ago, but with Colorado last season he had a
13-17 record and 5.20 earned run average. Pedro Astacio had an even
higher ERA, 6.23, the league's highest for pitchers who threw more
than 75 innings.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Bohanon.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: None.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Runs will continue to pour across the plate for
the Rockies. Leyland's job is to stop the the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks
</P>
<P>
   Buck Showalter, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 65-97, fifth place
</P>
<P>
   The fastest way to respectability, if not the playoffs, is with
pitching, the Diamondbacks' brain trust concluded. The fastest way
to good pitching, they decided, was the free-agent market. Enter
Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso. But pitchers
cannot win games by themselves, unless they pitch shutouts, and in
their initial season the Diamondbacks had one of the weakest
offenses in the league. So they set out to improve there, too. They
added outfielders Luis Gonzalez, Steve Finley and Bernard Gilkey
and also acquired Tony Womack, a base-stealing second baseman, to
play in the outfield, only to have him get hit by a pitch that
broke his wrist. Matt Williams could help by wiping out one of his
worst offensive seasons (.267, 20 home runs, 71 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Johnson, Stottlemyre, Finley, Reynoso, Gonzalez,
Womack.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: The Diamondbacks have invested so much in their
pitching, it had better take them somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Padres
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy, manager
</P>
<P>
   1998: 98-64, first place
</P>
<P>
   The symmetry is too good to pass up: the Padres can become the
first team to go from first to last to first to last. No, that's
not their idea of a good pattern to follow, but they are in danger
of tumbling from first to last for the second time in three years.
The Padres argue that they have not followed the example of the
Florida Marlins after their victory in the 1997 World Series, and
they really haven't. But their offers to their free agents fell
short of what others offered, and suddenly the cupboard was barer.
Their trade of Greg Vaughn, their 50-home run man, emptied it even
more and undermined their argument. Then Carlos Hernandez ruptured
his Achilles' tendon and became lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   KEY ADDITIONS: Woody Williams, Reggie Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: Kevin Brown, Ken Caminiti, Steve Finley, Joey
Hamilton, Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   KEY TO SEASON: Reggie Sanders cannot replace Vaughn's 50 home
runs, and the rookie pitchers Stan Spencer and Matt Clement cannot
replace Kevin Brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
