<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-PROTESTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SAYS HE SEES BOTH SIDES OF PLAN NOT TO TRY PROTESTERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Saturday that he could
``see both sides'' of the plan by prosecutors to drop charges
against the 1,200 people arrested for civil disobedience last month
over the police killing of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, noting that many of the protesters had spent several
hours in jail, said he could understand both the desire, expressed
by Police Commissioner Howard Safir, to have the arrests prosecuted
and the need to have the charges dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Police Department would have preferred that the
cases had gone forward as a vindication of the law,'' he said at a
news conference at the New York International Auto Show Saturday.
But he added: ``The district attorney made a practical judgment _
1,500 or 1,700 cases _ that the point had been made through the
retention process. He felt that was sufficient punishment. I can
see both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, had said on
Friday he would most likely ask a criminal court judge to dismiss
those charges.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made a point of highlighting how Morgenthau had
praised the police officers involved in the arrests _ often
hundreds per day _ for showing respect toward the demonstrators,
many of whom were prominent politicians or celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at how all the arrests were carried out,'' the mayor
said. ``In other times and in other places you would have seen
something very different happening. But instead what you see is an
example of, even when provoked, a very restrained, very respectful
Police Department.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations, held in front of Police Headquarters, ended
last week with the arraignment of four New York City police
officers on second-degree murder charges in Diallo's shooting
death.
</P>
<P>
   The first batch of people arrested, including Sharpton, is to
appear in court on April 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
