<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-GOALS-2000     04-03 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GOALS-2000 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. TO MISS ALL 8 EDUCATIONAL TARGETS IN `GOALS 2000'
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. With GOALS-DATA. For release Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation is going to miss every one of the eight
educational goals set for next year in the ``Goals 2000'' program,
according to the state-federal panel set up to monitor its
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Some states will reach some goals, but none will achieve all
eight, according to the bipartisan National Education Goals Panel.
</P>
<P>
   The goals grew out of high-profile education summits with all 50
governors convened by President Bush in 1989 and President Clinton
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambitious aims? Of course,'' Bush said in 1990 as he announced
the first draft of the goals as Clinton and other reform-minded
governors looked on. ``Easy to do? Far from it. But the future's at
stake. This nation will not accept anything less than excellence in
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress made the final set of eight goals official in 1994 by
including them in the ``Goals 2000: Educate America Act.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the panel has measured significant national progress
toward only two of the goals: education and health programs for
pre-schoolers, and test scores in mathematics and science.
</P>
<P>
   It said conditions were unchanged or the record was mixed in
four areas: graduation rates, student citizenship and competency in
eight core subjects, parental participation, and schools free of
violence, drugs, firearms and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said performance has actually declined during the
1990s in the two other areas: teacher education and professional
development, and lifelong learning and adult literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in North Carolina, followed by South Carolina,
California, Colorado and Texas, have shown the most signs of
improvement in the 1990s, according to the panel. Another 13 showed
``significant'' improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Georgia and Ohio were among the 32 that missed that
honor roll.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Nelson, executive director of the panel, said the panel's
members all concluded in February that they should acknowledge that
the goals wouldn't be met.
</P>
<P>
   They adopted this recommendation: ``The national education goals
should be renamed 'America's education goals' and be continued
beyond the year 2000 without a specific deadline for their
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropping the deadline would be a sound idea, agreed Chairman
John Porter, R-Ill., of the House Appropriations subcommittee on
education. Otherwise, he said, ``We could end up like the former
Soviet Union, with five-year plans, 10-year plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The goals panel includes eight governors, four state
legislators, four members of Congress and two Clinton
administration officials. Some were disappointed by the failure to
meet the goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been there, frustrated, because over the period of
time we have been on (the panel) we have not had any measurable
change in the statistics in this country about the state of our
education,'' said Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., who chairs the Senate
Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions.
</P>
<P>
   But others took it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``By setting these ambitious education goals, we challenge our
children and ourselves to be the best we can be,'' said Gov. Jim
Hunt of North Carolina. His state and Texas were cited by the panel
as the nation's most successful pioneers in tying education reforms
to measurable results, rather than to how much money or effort was
devoted to change.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Hunt said, ``Parents and educators agree
that these goals are extremely important and we have made great
progress in preparing our children for school, creating safer
schools, and preparing students to succeed in life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   However, national polls show that employers and college
professors aren't as happy as parents and educators about the early
impact of recent reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who employ people out of high school or teach first-year
or second-year classes continue to believe these young people don't
have the skills for the workplace or college when they graduate,''
said Deborah Wadsworth of Public Agenda, a nonprofit, nonpartisan
research organization in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Public Agenda's review of opinion polls found ``widespread
public support for all eight national goals, on somewhat different
levels of urgency,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The goals with the most intense support from the most people are
ensuring school safety, raising academic achievement, lowering
dropout rates and increasing parental participation.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, the Goals 2000 program has been ``a relatively
successful experiment in education in a typically American way,''
according to a study conducted for the panel by Richard F. Elmore
of Harvard University's Graduate School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every state that has ventured into reform can show
some evidence of improved student performance in at least some
subjects at some grade levels in the early stages of reform,''
Elmore said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``While the transformations have been substantial
at the level of political rhetoric and policy, they have yet to
work their way fully into the daily life of schools and local
school systems in the same dramatic way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
