</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daly only thinking one game at a time
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chuck Daly says he hasn't had time to think about
whether he will return as head coach in Orlando, Fla., next season.
Daly, 68, is in the second year of a three-year, $15 million deal
that includes an option for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Daly said, ``I was talking to (team trainer) Tim
Walsh when we were sitting on the bus the other day and he said:
`Who did we play yesterday?' And he's a young guy who doesn't have
`senior' moments. I might occasionally have some senior moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can hardly remember who you played the last two games
because of the way the schedule is set up. So, quite frankly, your
job as a coach in this league is the next game. You're so worried
about the next opponent. So I really haven't had enough time to
think about anything. And I'm not going to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Celtics' jump-off point
</P>
<P>
   According to franchise patriarch Red Auerbach, the Celtics are
two players away from contending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a power forward _ in other words, a go-to rebounder, a
guy who, when that ball goes up, you've got this animal who's going
to get it,'' Auerbach said. ``And we need another big guard,
someone 6-3 or 6-4 that can play defense and shoot a little bit. If
we get those two, we'll be very highly competitive, because our
center position (Vitaly Potapenko) is good now, and I also like
(Tony) Battie. Battie plays hard and blocks shots; he's a perfect
backup. But if you get one more big guy, you'll really be in good
shape here.'' Coach Rick Pitino says things will be better next
season. Otherwise, he said, ``I'll kill myself. So you don't have
to worry about killing me, because I'll kill me. The best bridge to
hang from, because of my dear effects, is the (Boston University)
bridge. That's what I love the most is the BU bridge because of my
starting out there at a very young age.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel the Heat
</P>
<P>
   Upset by his team's play, Pat Riley put his players through
three rigorous, training camp-style practices before the Heat
returned to action Thursday, seeking to turn around a 4-5 slump.
Riley took some of the blame because he said he tried to implement
too many defensive schemes in recent games, which seemed to confuse
his players. Riley said his players will go back to playing defense
``his way.'' ... Jamal Mashburn is back after missing 26 games, and
he has a new role. There won't be as many isolations run for him.
Eventually, Mashburn will supplant Dan Majerle at small forward,
with Majerle shifting to the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Magic guard Nick Anderson will be out indefinitely with two
strained hamstrings. ``Yeah, both of my legs are hurting,''
Anderson told a reporter. ``You want to loan me one?'' . . .
Dominique Wilkins came off the bench to score 17 points in the
Magic's 100-98 win over New Jersey Tuesday. Wilkins played only 13
minutes, but got off 13 shots, hitting six, with six rebounds. ``I
do the things I've always done,'' said Wilkins, 39. ``I think
(Magic coaches) are starting to have more faith in me. They know
I'm going to come in and play hard.'' . . . He's hurting, but Allen
Iverson is playing through a right quadriceps injury. ``I'm not
sitting,'' Iverson said. ``I refuse to sit and watch this team
lose. I can't do it. I just can't.'' . . . In a 101-91 loss to the
Toronto Raptors, Cleveland fans screamed at coach Mike Fratello,
who said, ``I'm sorry.'' . . . When the Pistons went from the weary
walk-it-up Hawks to the run-crazed Celtics, coach Alvin Gentry
described it as ``facing Charlie Hough and his 40-mph knuckleball
one day and then Nolan Ryan the next.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
