<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oakley drives Raptors
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You don't expect Charles Oakley to be what he's
become. You don't expect him to take a young player like Vince
Carter by the elbow and guide him through the minefields of the
NBA. You don't expect him to be the vocal leader of a team closing
in on last year's total of 18 wins and vying for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what has happened, making the Toronto Raptors'
acquisition of Oakley for Marcus Camby the best deal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   There were bigger names in bigger transactions _ Scottie Pippen
to Houston, Tom Gugliotta to Phoenix, Glen Rice to the Lakers,
Latrell Sprewell to New York, Stephon Marbury to New Jersey. But
none has had the impact of Oakley's bruising presence and _ get
this _ calming influence.
</P>
<P>
   Going to Toronto required Oakley to become a true leader, and
not just by example.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the respect of the younger players,'' said coach Butch
Carter, who has done a commendable job of using his talent. ``Oak
has been through the wars, and he's sharing his knowledge. He's
been great. They all listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Carter has had his ear bent by Oakley. ``I give a
lot of credit to him,'' said Carter, the front-runner for rookie of
the year. ``He's taken me under his wing and helped me on the
attitude I need to have to play in this league, the way to prepare
for games and anything else you can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held Oakley in the highest regard. When the Raptors
visited New York's Madison Square Garden in February, the Knicks
showed a one-minute video montage of Oakley highlights as a tribute
to the player whose physical nature epitomized their successful
teams of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But it was shown at halftime of the game, when the Raptors were
in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wanted to do something, they should have done it
before the game,'' Oakley said. ``I appreciate it, but do it
professionally. They always talk about being professional. I didn't
see it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Oakley _ brutally blunt. When told by Knicks general
manager Ernie Grunfeld over the telephone that he was being traded,
Oakley interrupted and said, ``If I'm traded, I'm traded. I'm no
longer your commodity.'' Then he hung up on Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   When Oakley saw Grunfeld at John Starks' golf outing in
September, the general manager extended his hand. Oakley refused to
take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to tell the truth,'' he said, ``and (Grunfeld and
Knicks president Dave Checketts) are big on making things out like
they do everything for the community. We know it's all about making
money. They got rid of Anthony Mason because he was supposed to
create some problems, but then they come back and have Dennis Scott
and Latrell Sprewell.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Oakley, it's been the Knicks' loss. ``Losing Oak without
a doubt hurts you,'' said the Lakers' Derek Harper, a former Knick.
Teams ``always try to get younger. But getting younger doesn't
necessarily mean you're getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors are better with Oakley. Carter is a star in the
making. Veterans Doug Christie, Dee Brown and Kevin Willis have
been steady. Youngsters Tracy McGrady and John Wallace are
talented. And then there's the unlikely leader, Oakley, on the
unlikely playoff contender. Who would have thought this possible?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
