<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sprewell wants to start
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service ATLANTA _ In two games last week, the
<TEXT>
New York Knicks had three on-court incidents that led to technical
fouls or ejections. None involved the notorious Latrell Sprewell.
<P>
   Which speaks to the behavior the former Golden State player has
displayed in his first season back since being suspended last
season for choking Warriors coach P.J. Carlisemo. The most Sprewell
has done in the way of a distraction is continually acknowledge
that he does not like his role off the Knicks' bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'd like to be starting,'' he said. ``I'm not going
to say I'm happy coming off the bench.'' Asked if he would have
chosen the Knicks to sign with as a free agent if he knew he would
not be a regular, he said, ``I don't know. It's one of those things
where I'd see what's available.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy was less than pleased with Sprewell's
near-obsession with starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my druthers,'' Van Gundy said, ``would I have him
say, `The Knicks brought me here, showed a lot of faith in me _
I'll do whatever they wanted me to do to help us win?' Yeah. That's
what I'd rather have him not just say but believe. But this is the
NBA. I'm not sure that's going to happen or if it's realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   In attitude, Sprewell has been exemplary. Last week, he stayed
out of trouble while watching against the Lakers as forward Kurt
Thomas was ejected for taking down Dennis Rodman and Chris Dudley
got a technical for hitting Shaquille O'Neal with the ball.
Tuesday, he saw teammate Patrick Ewing and Indiana's Jalen Rose
square off in New York.
</P>
<P>
   THE CANDY MAN
</P>
<P>
   Want the inside scoop on the emergence of Orlando's Darrell
Armstrong, the reigning NBA player of the week? He has a pregame
cup of coffee with seven packets of sugar and chocolate candy bars
before games and at halftime to build his perpetual energy.
</P>
<P>
   Since Armstrong's sweet tooth was reported in Orlando, he has
been bombarded with Easter candy. ``From where he has come three or
four years ago, it's amazing,'' Miami coach Pat Riley said. ''He
gives Orlando such energy and heart. He's irrepressible, absolutely
irrepressible. It's like he's on a chocolate, sugar high all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   NO LOVE FOR NCAA
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Sam Mitchell spent Monday night doing something _
anything _ other than watching the NCAA championship game. In fact,
he missed the whole tournament because he said he can't stand the
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give coaches millions of dollars (in salary),'' he said.
``You give schools millions of dollars (in revenue). And then a kid
who's got nothing gets $20 to buy a pizza or call home, and it's a
violation. When I hear the `purity and sanctity of college
basketball,' that's bull.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
