<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mavs guard Nash pariah in Dallas
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fans in Dallas always have been laid-back. They are
much like Atlantans, except they have no chance of seeing their
team in the playoffs anytime soon. How then to explain Dallas fans'
strong dislike for new point guard Steve Nash?
</P>
<P>
   Since signing a six-year, $33 million contract extension before
the season and playing far below expectations ever since, the
poor-shooting Nash has been a prime target for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In a display reminiscent of the vicious disapproval aimed at
Kiki Vandeweghe in the 1980s, fans booed Nash loudly and
unrelentingly for most of the Mavericks' recent loss to Houston.
From the moment he missed a 3-pointer with 3:18 left in the opening
half _ the capper to Nash's 0-for-8 start _ he heard boos from a
sizable chunk of the 15,511 in the Reunion Arena crowd almost every
time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley came to Nash's defense. ``I'm very disappointed
in the Dallas fans,'' he said. ``What did he do? He's going to be
here a long time. He's a big part of their franchise. He's a good
kid. Why don't they send him down to Houston? We'll take him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whistle-blower
</P>
<P>
   Referee Marc Davis, who whistled a technical foul against Hawks
coach Lenny Wilkens for being out of the coaching box a month ago,
has been busy handing out technicals all year. He might have peaked
in Vancouver when he ejected Denver's Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, paired with Steve Javie, gave McDyess two quick
technicals with 4:46 to play, Vancouver up 86-76. With 2:05 left,
he ticketed Nuggets forward Danny Fortson and tossed him. Then,
Javie, the lead ref, gave Denver coach Mike D'Antoni the hook,
probably to keep him from going after Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Javie had tried to jump in front of Davis to keep him from
tossing Fortson, but Davis stepped around him and gave the ejection
sign.
</P>
<P>
   On joining McDyess and Fortson in the locker room before the end
of the game, D'Antoni said, ``We needed to have a team meeting, and
most of my players were in (there).''
</P>
<P>
   Hawk reject rebounds
</P>
<P>
   Remember Scot Pollard, the backup center the Hawks acquired from
Detroit and then discarded early this season with no chance to
prove himself? Well, Pollard was in the middle of the Kings' gritty
104-101 overtime victory over the Jazz last week.
</P>
<P>
   After playing a total of five minutes in two games, Pollard
stepped in for ailing Chris Webber and produced 11 points, 11
rebounds and four blocks against Karl Malone. It was Pollard who
made the play of the game in overtime with 4.2 seconds left and
Sacramento nursing a 103-101 lead. He drew an offensive foul on
Utah's Bryon Russell that nullified a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Make up your mind
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Richmond told the Washington Post that he wants to stay
with the Wizards, then told a San Francisco Bay Area paper he would
be willing to return to the Warriors, where he began his career.
Richmond, a free agent at the end of the season, said, ``All my
options are open. (Golden State) is the place where I started. My
wife is from here. I'm here in the summertime. And the relationship
I have with (general manager) Garry St. Jean is definitely a plus.
... Over the years, we've kept in touch. He's a friend of the
family. Let's put it this way _ we know each others' pluses and
minuses.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, St. Jean blamed Richmond for ruining his team
in Sacramento when he returned from the '96 Olympics and complained
bitterly that he was underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   When Jim Cleamons' record in Dallas sagged to 28-70 after he
remade the team, Don Nelson fired him. Nelson's record over his
first 98 games also was 28-70. Nelson will be replaced as coach by
his son, Donn, at season's end. ... A Utah-based quarterhorse owner
and trainer, Wes Giles, named a 2-year-old Ostertag. When Utah
center Greg Ostertag heard, he responded, ``What is he _ big and
slow?'' . . . In the last two weeks, Blazers guard Isaiah Rider has
missed two games for suspensions and not started two games as
discipline for being late to a shootaround and missing practice.
Still, he's ahead of last season, when he was suspended for seven
games and didn't start eight others for disciplinary reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
