<SLUG> BC-BKO-HOSKINS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young star Hoskins set to beat already high standards
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Before Brandi Hoskins became a local celebrity,
basketball had always been an escape for her. Something fun,
something to do, something to take her mind off her mother's
illness and pain. An eighth-grader at MacFarlane Middle School, she
had the audacity to think of the sport as a game.
</P>
<P>
   But now her basketball success has become a burden. Nobody
leaves her alone. College coaches already are writing her letters,
planting seeds, even though she hasn't picked a high school yet.
</P>
<P>
   Just where is she going to high school anyway? Will it be
Chaminade-Julienne, the Catholic school in downtown Dayton,
Pickerington in suburban Columbus or Dunbar in Dayton's City
League? Or maybe somewhere else?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it seems to be everybody's business, to the extent she
quit going to high school games because people kept asking about
her plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to get on my nerves,'' said Hoskins, 13.
</P>
<P>
   Just when there seems no end to the suffocation, here comes
Randy Faison, a community activist and an official with the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference, pleading for Hoskins to
choose a predominantly black public school over C-J or
Pickerington.
</P>
<P>
   And if some walls could talk ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been offered coaching jobs and a lot of things I can't
tell you,'' Alan Hoskins, Brandi's father, said. ``But Brandi told
me she can't be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoskins' talent will sell itself, and that talent is
considerable. Which, of course, explains all the fuss being made
over this eighth-grader who, for the record, says she's leaning
toward C-J, following in the footsteps of Dayton schoolgirl legend
and University of Connecticut star Tamika Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Girls and women's basketball has undergone unprecedented success
in recent years. Although one pro league folded, the Women's
National Basketball Association, backed by the NBA, seems
financially secure. Last month's women's NCAA championship game
drew a record number of viewers. And in Dayton, more than a dozen
area girls received either full or partial basketball scholarships
to Division I colleges during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the attention given to Williams hasn't hurt
basketball's popularity here, either. While at C-J, she was
selected as national player of the year by five different groups,
including Nike and Parade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But if you listen to Williams and many local coaches, the
5-foot-9 Hoskins has the potential to be the most complete girls
player ever to come out of this region.
</P>
<P>
   Hoskins' basketball education began at age 7 when her father
told her to warm up for their Nerf game and she took him literally,
standing next to a heater.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was sweating,'' her father said. ``I said, 'What are you
doing?' She said, 'I'm getting warmed up.' She was getting all
dehydrated. I told her that's not what I meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandi eventually caught on, and her interest in basketball
increased. When her uncle Jeff took her to the Westwood Center, she
more than held her own against boys, one of whom was John
Goldsberry, son of C-J girls basketball coach Frank Goldsberry.
</P>
<P>
   John told his dad he should see this girl play.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to be a fifth-grader at the time I first saw her,''
Goldsberry said. ``Offensively, she was very difficult to stop just
because of all the moves she has.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've seen her game elevate as she's gotten older.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoskins played for Goldsberry's 11-year-old Amateur Athletic
Union team when she was 9, helping it win the national
championship. She played on another AAU team two years later, again
winning the national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This past season she averaged 37 points for her MacFarlane
eighth-grade team, according to coach Will McKinney. ``She has
overwhelming skills for her age,'' McKinney said. ``Brandi can
shoot and has good range, even from the arc.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Flynn, the director of the Blue Star Elite camp, lives in
Philadelphia and has heard the hype about Hoskins for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard about her game and ability from people on the
outside who watch sports as well as from one of my former players,
Tamika Williams,'' Flynn said. ``She told me she's going to be a
superstar and she's got great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn invites the nation's top freshmen and sophomores to his
July camp. He sometimes adds a few eighth graders, and this year
Hoskins will be one of four.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what high school Hoskins attends, someone will be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting ready to lose some friends in the next couple of
weeks,'' Alan Hoskins said. ``People say C-J just wants her for
basketball, but if any of them are interested in her, it's for
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   And the interest is deep. Pickerington _ which finished this
season as No. 1 in the nation _ Trotwood-Madison, Dunbar, Dayton
Christian and C-J have all invited Brandi to visit their school.
</P>
<P>
   Hoskins and her family have toured the Trotwood-Madison campus
and met the principal, have met students at Dunbar, attended an
open house at C-J and are scheduled to visit Dayton Christian.
</P>
<P>
   It appears C-J will win the sweepstakes. C-J athletic director
Jim Place said Hoskins is already registered for the fall and that
a tuition down payment has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hoskins says he favors C-J. He is bracing for the
ramifications, predicting some of his black friends will have a
problem with Brandi attending the private school.
</P>
<P>
   Faison of the SCLC said Hoskins' ``best opportunity for positive
socialization'' is to attend Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should continue to stay in the Dayton Public Schools,''
Faison said. ``It has excellent academic programs, and she will
receive the support she needs. Brandi Hoskins, like a number of
other children, has had a wonderful experience athletically and
educationally in the Dayton Public Schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Faison has met with the Hoskins, but Brandi's mother, Toni, said
she believes C-J is where her daughter can get the best education.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the pile of letters from colleges grows deeper.
</P>
<P>
   They bear the signatures of coaches from Dayton, Ohio State,
Duke, Purdue and Iowa, among others. Alan Hoskins has a special
fondness for the handwritten pieces, like the one Dayton coach Jaci
Clark sent after attending one of Brandi's junior high games.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the letter was meant to show support for the young
player. ``I would never want to interfere with the process of
growing up,'' she said. ``I just wanted to encourage her with the
gift she has and tell her to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hoskins is his daughter's personal chauffeur, driving her
across the country to play in tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   He's driven her to Florida, to Oklahoma and to Richmond, Va.,
last Thursday to play in the Blue Chip Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk, we argue,'' he said. ``I like it when she sleeps. I
like music from my era, she likes music from her era.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brandi isn't listening to music or sleeping during these
excursions, she's dreaming about her mother, wishing she could come
along.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Hoskins has rarely seen her daughter play and never travels
across the country to her games because she is disabled and all but
a shut-in. The 32-year-old mother of two has cirrhosis, a
life-threatening disease of the liver.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital visits are routine for Toni, who will probably need a
transplanted liver.
</P>
<P>
   Toni's illness doesn't appear to have affected Brandi on the
court, but Brandi said it's something she often thinks about. So
before she goes on a basketball trip, she makes sure to hug her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me a lot when she's in pain,'' Brandi said. ``My
mom is like my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Toni prays she will be able to watch Brandi fulfill her
potenial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grace of God gets me by,'' she said. ``Brandi cries about
it more than me.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons between Williams and Hoskins are inevitable.
Both are tall _ Hoskins is already 5 feet 9, Williams 6-2 _ and
have good all-around games.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more of an outside player and I'm more inside,'' said
Williams, recently named freshman of the year by The Sporting News.
``But she has the same demeanor. We'll battle to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldsberry shies away from comparing the two, preferring instead
to wait and see how Hoskins adjusts to the high-school game.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first day of practice, I'll go from there,'' he
said. ``I haven't seen her play enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, if Hoskins needs advice on how to deal with the
typical problems of a budding superstar teen-age athlete, she can
call Williams, who has become a mentor and close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's almost like a little sister,'' Williams said. ``I just
tell her things, from boys to grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell her, `Every record I have, I want you to break. I want
you to set a standard.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She already has.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
