<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-CHANGE04-     04-03 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-CHANGE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Masters taking tougher course
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ They still will need to prepare for the sadistic,
slippery greens with practice putts on a kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   They still will exit off Interstate 20 to Washington Road and
turn into Magnolia Lane.
</P>
<P>
   They still will get peach cobbler on the lunch menu.
</P>
<P>
   They still will see Gene Sarazen, Byron Nelson and Sam Snead
starting things off on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, the participants of the 63rd Masters might not
recognize the Augusta National Golf Club during the 1999 Masters.
In terms of ``winds of change,'' this is a gust.
</P>
<P>
   Alterations to the hallowed grounds carved by Alister MacKenzie
and Bobby Jones are nothing new _ a pond used to front the No. 6
green and a ditch crossed the 17th tee. But not since 1980, when
the greens were switched from Bermuda to bentgrass, have there been
so many changes that could change the face, or at least the
scoring, of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   There's a rather progressive Masters chairman on the grounds.
Hootie Johnson replaced Jack Stephens, who retired.
</P>
<P>
   There have been significant changes to four holes _ 2, 11, 15
and 17 _ that have added demands on length and accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   There's more than a token ``second cut'' outside Augusta
National's generous fairways. The ``flier rough,'' as the players
are calling it, has been allowed to grow to 1 3/8 inches, from
5/8ths of an inch, and will prevent players from putting backspin
on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   From a playing standpoint, the rough could be the biggest
change. For nearly two decades, the reward for negotiating Augusta
National's treacherous bentgrass greens _ by air or on the ground _
has been the near-guarantee of a perfect lie just about anywhere on
the property.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the second cut could play a big, big role in the golf
tournament, actually,'' said David Duval, runner-up to Mark O'Meara
in 1998. ``It should make it very, very interesting on those hard,
fast greens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to get on those greens from the rough would be a
nightmare,'' Tom Lehman predicted when the plan was in its
experiment phase.
</P>
<P>
   Many people think the changes were prompted by Tiger Woods'
record score of 270 in 1997. Woods' length off the tee almost
brought Augusta National to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval is not sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't grasped where that concern has come from,''
he said. ``I think if anybody had read stuff about it and heard the
outcry, that you'd have thought that Tiger had broken the
tournament record by five or six shots and just blew all these
things out of the water. . . . In all fairness, he made a three- or
four-foot putt on the last hole to beat the tournament record by
one. So it must go back to something else.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the changes were made to help protect the tournament
for the future. High-tech clubs and balls have made the par-5s at
Augusta nearly obsolete. Something had to be done to the only major
that returns to the same venue every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the history of the club, we've made approximately 75
changes,'' Johnson said. ``We've moved some tees up and some tees
back. We've put in bunkers, and we've taken out bunkers. . . . But,
yes, part of our reasoning or rationale for these changes is that
these young men are hitting the ball a lot longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players accept the changes. ``The course gets better and
better every year, and you have to have (changes) like that;
otherwise the scoring would be lower and lower,'' said Spain's Jose
Maria Olazabal, the 1994 champion.
</P>
<P>
   The hole changes for 1999:
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2, par 5, 575 yards: The tee was moved back 25 yards and
surrounded by a stone wall. The right fairway bunker was shifted to
the right and brought more into play.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 11, par 4, 455 yards: Chiefly for flood control, the green
was raised approximately two feet, the pond about one foot. Rae's
Creek also was widened by about 50 percent. Two bunkers behind and
to the right of the green have been replaced by a single bunker.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 15, par 5, 500 yards: Fairway mounds on the right side
that could ``slingshot'' drives were reduced about 80 percent and
20 pine trees were added. Mounds on the right side of the green
were removed and six pine trees planted.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 17, par 4, 425 yards: The tee was moved back 25 yards and
a cluster of pine trees planted on the right, putting the
Eisenhower Pine on the left side, about 195 yards down the fairway,
in a larger role.
</P>
<P>
   The 17th, from pre-tournament reaction, clearly is the hole most
affected. Not everyone is prepared to hug architect Tom Fazio, who
designed the alterations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The huge difference is 17,'' said Atlanta's Billy Andrade, who
played the course in February. ``It makes you hook it off the tee,
and it's tight. The Eisenhower tree comes more into play; those
trees on the right come into play. It's going to make that hole a
lot more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price said he thinks that the extra yardage was not
necessary at the 17th, that adding the trees on the right would
have been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That green is not designed for a 5-iron,'' said Price, who
shot 63 in the 1986 Masters. ``And downwind now, instead of us
mortals hitting wedge or 9-iron, we're going to be hitting 7-iron.
No way are you going to be able to stop it on that green.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes at 15 aren't likely to cause an uproar. With people
hitting short irons into a par-5, something had to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand those humps are gone, which is kind of good,''
Tom Lehman said. ``You could be 4 yards short of the next guy (and
not get the slingshot effect), and some guy will drive it 80 yards
past you. I think it will probably make the course more fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The new No. 2 seems to have the most potential to please the
majority of the players. Although the hole is lengthened, the new
angle allows more players to thread a drive into the chute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (No.) 2 is great,'' said Andrade. ``I still think the
big hitters will be able to get home, but it actually makes the
fairway wider for the average hitter. Before you were trying to hit
a hook around there, and it was tight. Now it's open more. It gives
you a little breathing room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long hitter, the (No. 2) fairway was maybe 90 yards
wide,'' said Tom Lehman. ``For me, the fairway was maybe 25 yards
wide. And I'm not short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit some 3 and 4-irons into that green, and I won't be
able to do that anymore,'' Justin Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on which day you speak with Greg Norman, the response
may differ. While telling one reporter recently that he considers
the changes ``very well balanced and needed from the standpoint of
15, 17 and 2, especially,'' he told another that he feels any
alterations are messing with the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to step on the tee and say, `Gene Sarazen did this,'
or, `Byron Nelson did this,' and feel the same piece of nostalgia
and history,'' Norman said. ``When you change it, you change all of
that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
