<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-HISTORY04     04-03 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-HISTORY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Course as masterpiece
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By the end of this week, one of the hundreds of
journalists covering the Masters might write that Augusta National
architect Alister MacKenzie is spinning in his grave over the newly
grown rough and four lengthened holes.
</P>
<P>
   But if the auld Scottish doctor ever got annoyed in the
hereafter, it was probably because he never was paid properly for
his Depression-era design, according to a new book about the
course. MacKenzie and tournament co-founders Bobby Jones and
Clifford Roberts always viewed the course as a work in progress,
and over the years the suggestions of everyone from members to
spectators to sportswriters, even, have resulted in about 75
alterations to the fabled course.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the tweaking, Augusta National annually stages one
of sport's most dramatic finishes because the spirit of MacKenzie's
philosophy is still intact, confirming his place as one of the
greatest architects in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He never lived to see that kind of recognition for his work at
Augusta and died with paltry financial reward for his efforts. When
writer David Owen began researching his newly released book, ``The
Making of the Masters,'' he knew Augusta National had a rocky
start. The extent of the bad times startled him, as he discovered
documentation that included tempestuous, sometimes grimly humorous,
correspondence from MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things he said were exaggerations for humorous
effect,'' Owen said. ``But it wasn't like Augusta National was a
rich club ignoring MacKenzie. All the people were trying to make
ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Depression, Augusta National had an immensely
difficult time securing members, despite Jones' fame as the winner
of golf's Grand Slam and one of the most popular athletes of the
times. The club's archives are full of rejection letters from
businessmen who were invited to join. Facing a shortfall in funds,
grandiose plans for a grand country club were cut back to 18 golf
holes.
</P>
<P>
   Even those plans were tentative in 1931 when MacKenzie started
laying out the course over the grounds of an old nursery. The
members did not commit to build the course until early 1932.
MacKenzie reduced his fee from $10,000 to $5,000 to speed the
project, which he viewed as his finest achievement.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1932, the course had been open for several months and
MacKenzie had been paid only $2,000, not even enough to cover his
estimated expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am at the end of my tether,'' he wrote Roberts from his
California home. ``No one has paid me a cent since last June, we
have mortgaged everything we have and have not yet been able to pay
the nursing expenses of my wife's operation. . . . Can you possibly
let me have, at any rate, $500 to keep us out of the poor house?''
</P>
<P>
   With greens fees barely covering the payroll, the club didn't
have any money. A few months later, MacKenzie wrote again, saying
that his electricity and phone were about to be cut off and he
feared foreclosure on his house. Perhaps the worst indignity: ``I
have been reduced to playing golf with four clubs and a Woolworth
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   To save pennies, he and his wife started trimming each other's
hair and gathering fallen wood to heat their home. In 1934, the
63-year-old MacKenzie suffered a brief illness and died suddenly,
having never played Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his spirit shaped the history of the invitational tournament
started that same year. MacKenzie and Jones held the same
philosophy of design, that a course should be rewarding, not
punitive; beautiful, not artificial; surprising, but not unfair.
MacKenzie achieved those design goals by working with the land, not
merely moving it, and created two masterpieces of great natural
beauty: the heavily flowered Amen Corner at Augusta National and
the spectacular Pacific Coast views of Cypress Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``All his courses that I have played have been interesting; in
every instance he has placed interest and enjoyment ahead of
difficulty,'' Jones later wrote.
</P>
<P>
   That sensibility dictated Augusta National's appearance and
play. MacKenzie hated for a player to look for a lost ball, so he
designed wide fairways with many routes to the green. An errant
drive could be nullified by an excellent second shot, and it is
those approaches that require a panoply of shotmaking.
</P>
<P>
   The large, heavily contoured greens are so demanding that they
offer only a few spots where a player can expect a birdie, and they
influence the placement of the approach shot and the drive. Like
the bunkers, the greens are more deceptive than they look, a legacy
from MacKenzie's days in the British military as a camouflage
expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one who very much equated the game of golf to life, and
he believed that the design of the golf course should parallel
that,'' said Denis Griffiths of Braselton, the designer of Chateau
Elan and former president of the American Society of Golf Course
Architects. Griffiths had just finished reading MacKenzie's book
``The Spirit of St. Andrews.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Variety, excitement, disappointment were elements of the game,
and his design radiated that,'' Griffiths said. ``Fairness was not
necessarily part of the game, and if you look at Augusta National
and see what happens on the greens, that's evident. . . . Just when
you think everything is going great, there's going to be a
catastrophe on a MacKenzie course. The golfer is continually
challenged and expects the unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, MacKenzie's legacy will entice the best
players in the world into one of sport's most dramatic finishes.
Augusta National's array of back-nine birdie chances means that the
leader at the turn must attack the course, a very different
scenario from the finish at the next stop on golf's Grand Slam, the
U.S. Open. The host courses are so penal that par almost always is
a good score, and the winner is usually a plodding survivor.
</P>
<P>
   At Augusta National, Owen said, ``The back nine on Sunday is the
epitome of what MacKenzie and Jones were trying to do. They wanted
to present situations where the superior player can demonstrate his
superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the par 3s and par 5s. Based on length alone, the
145-yard 12th hole should be a pushover. But Rae's Creek, the
swirling winds and the slope of the green creates a narrow margin
of error.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the pond-fronted 16th. Second-generation
golf-course architect Rees Jones was 7 years old when his father,
Robert Trent Jones, helped redesign it. ``The thing about it,
there's no place to miss it,'' he said. ``If you're above the hole,
it's treacherous, and you can't miss it left. You can get in real
trouble in the water there and on 15, which make a kind of
make-or-break finale. It may be one of the top dozen par-3s in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Both 13 and 15, the par 5s, can be reached in two, which Jones
insisted upon, and MacKenzie concurred. They dangled that reward to
the long hitters, while entertaining the members with a hole that
wasn't terribly long.
</P>
<P>
   During the years, MacKenzie's original design has weathered
technological improvement, including lawn mowers that shave the
greens to a whisker's length, making them faster than he ever
envisioned. The pros who first played Augusta National considered
it insufferably long, because its state-of-the-art watering system
cut down on how far the ball rolled. Today, the long hitters, such
as runaway 1997 Masters champion Tiger Woods, threaten to make some
of the holes pitifully short, which is why four holes were
lengthened this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Augusta National remains a place where spectators are as
apt to talk about the course as they are about the players, and
that too is a credit to the man who never got much of it when he
was alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A course like this really doesn't just happen,'' Griffiths
said. ``You wish it could happen in every design. It all fits
together. If we all experience this at least once in a round of
golf, we've done well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
