<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-HOLLINS04     04-03 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-HOLLINS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hollins had role at start
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No women belong to Augusta National Golf Club. But at
one point, the course's development was in the hands of Marion
Hollins, a woman far ahead of her time.
</P>
<P>
   Newly discovered correspondence that fills out the history of
Augusta National, home of the Masters, says that the course's
architect, Alister MacKenzie, sent Hollins to oversee construction
because he held her opinion in such high esteem. Her name already
might be familiar to those steeped in Masters lore, because she
played an important role in bringing together MacKenzie and Masters
co-founder Bobby Jones.
</P>
<P>
   David Owen, the author of a new book called ``The Making of the
Masters,'' discovered Hollins' added influence in an old letter
between MacKenzie and Augusta National's other co-founder, Clifford
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians describe Hollins as the dominant female athlete
of the 1920s, the counterpart to Masters co-founder Bobby Jones in
the ranks of women's golf. She was a long-hitting winner of the
1921 U.S. Amateur, a race-car driver and a polo player who competed
against men.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a totally unintimidated figure who stood out at that
time, a larger-than-life figure in any era, but especially in the
20s,'' Owen said. ``She was an amazing athlete and a real
visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a wealthy New Yorker, Hollins moved to
California to help promote the fledgling golf courses on the
Monterey Peninsula. It was mostly her idea to build Cypress Point,
considered one of the game's greatest gems, and she suggested
MacKenzie as the architect.
</P>
<P>
   The course's signature hole is the long par-3 16th, with its
carry over a jagged inlet of the Pacific Ocean. MacKenzie credited
Hollins with that hole's design, because she erased doubts that the
challenge was too severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Hollins said she did not think it was an impossible
carry,'' MacKenzie wrote later. ``She then teed up a ball and drove
to the middle of the site for the suggested green.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollins went on to build her own golf course _ Pasatiempo,
Spanish for ``passing of time'' _ near San Francisco, and it also
was designed by MacKenzie. Its opening in 1929 featured an
exhibition by Hollins and Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones played because he had unexpected free time. He had just
lost his first match in the U.S. Amateur at what is now Pebble
Beach. On the same trip, he played Cypress Point, and he was
smitten with MacKenzie's designs. He got a chance to walk and chat
with MacKenzie as he golfed with Hollins at Pasatiempo.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, MacKenzie started work on Augusta National.
When Roberts complained that he wasn't spending enough time on
site, MacKenzie sent Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are her own ideas valuable, but she is thoroughly
conversant in regard to the character of work I like,'' MacKenzie
wrote Roberts. ``I want her views and also her personal impressions
in regard to the way the work is being carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   Another idea that Jones and Roberts borrowed from Hollins was to
hire the firm of Frederick Law Olmsted _ the designer of Central
Park in New York and Piedmont Park in Atlanta _ as their landscape
architect. ``In a lot of ways it seemed likely that they were
inspired either directly or indirectly by what she had done at
Pasatiempo,'' Owen said. ``There are so many parallels between what
she did and what Jones and Roberts later did.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollins was at her zenith during her brief stint at Augusta. The
year before, in the middle of the Depression, she had made $2.5
million on an oil deal. She sunk much of it into Pasatiempo,
turning it into a playground for some of Hollywood's biggest stars.
</P>
<P>
   But the course ultimately drained her. In 1937, Hollins wrecked
her car and went into a physical and financial tailspin. She lost
her course and, despite a brief return to competitive golf, died of
cancer in 1944 at age 51. Today, Pasatiempo survives as one of the
best public courses in America _ and the forerunner of Augusta
National. For the flamboyant Hollins, that would have been
something to brag about
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
