<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TIGER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods happy at No. 2
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Tiger Woods left Augusta National in 1997 with
the 42-long green jacket, people assumed that he would collect a
wardrobe full of them by his 30s. Combined with all those Sunday
red shirts, surely his closet would look like Christmas in April.
</P>
<P>
   A source no less credible than Jack Nicklaus said Woods would
secure more Masters titles than he and Arnold Palmer combined (10),
prompting the question: Who's going to beat Tiger on those other
years?
</P>
<P>
   And now comes the answer: Well, maybe David Duval, for one. It
is doubtful to count on the same effort each year from defending
champion Mark O'Meara, but it certainly appears that Duval could
challenge for another 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome a challenge,'' Woods said. ``That's why we play out
here. I know that's why I play _ to challenge myself and hopefully
come out on top against the best players. And to know I've beaten
the best, that makes it even sweeter.''
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? Woods hasn't beaten the best since the '97
Masters. He came closest at last year's British Open, when he lost
by one stroke and beat everybody but O'Meara. Clearly, the pressure
is on for Tiger to contend this year at Augusta. If he has another
bad outing, fans are going to wonder if winning by 12 and beating
the all-time scoring record in '97 was his future or his fantasy
week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Duval replaced Woods at the top of the world rankings
last Sunday _ rankings that few seem to respect _ the new No. 1
doubts that his most serious rival will just vanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all regard Tiger in a very high manner,'' said
Duval, who seems genuinely excited about whatever rivalry develops
in the coming years. ``His abilities to play this game are
unbelievable. Any time my name has been put in the hat as far as (a
rivalry with Woods), I find that flattering. You're talking about a
great, great golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who chose not to defend his BellSouth title and stayed at
his home course in Orlando to play with O'Meara, is hoping that
formula works for him again. If he shoots a 59 again this week _
like he did in a practice round with O'Meara in '97, Augusta could
be his playground after a quiet tie for eighth in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I can get my game to where it will be ready to go,
clicking on all cylinders,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods displayed significantly better distance control and played
more consistently in 1998 _ 13 top 10s in 20 appearances _ but he
won only once. And there have been changes:
</P>
<P>
   _ He fired agent Hughes Norton of International Management.
</P>
<P>
   _ He fired his caddie, Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan,'' replacing him
with New Zealander Steve Williams.
</P>
<P>
   _ He has a girlfriend, Jauna Jagoda from California, who wasn't
with him last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods is not convinced that it's he and Duval vs. the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to say that right now,'' Woods said. ``If I
was playing as well as I had in 1996, 1997, when I won a few
tournaments . . . it would be kind of neat to go head-to-head that
way. But as far as dominant, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Duval's ascension might help Woods in the long run. He
doesn't react well to being pulled in all directions _ example, at
the 1997 U.S. Open, when he would not talk with reporters after a
bad opening round. As long as he remains golf's greatest marketing
draw, not necessarily its best player, Woods seems reasonably
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish (the spotlight) was more on David,'' Woods said. ``I
mean, he's one of my friends out here, and it's nice that he has
actually played some great golf. But it has also been a big lift
off me, because it has taken some of the media requests that I've
had to do historically and put them on him. And now he's gotten a
little taste of it. It's very difficult to do, balance all of that.
When you're out here working, you're trying to get ready for a
tournament. It's difficult to be tugged and pulled and try and find
enough energy to play in a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't be a problem this week. Enough patience to handle
Duval could be another story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
