<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little tenure in coaching
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For several minutes, Phoenix general manager Bobby
Smith had been doing his best to smother thoughts that his hockey
coach lacked job security. Smith attributed a recent slump to
injuries. He blamed some losses on a since-demoted backup
goaltender. He said rumors of a coach's imminent firing ``are a
great way to undermine a hockey team. It gives players an excuse to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the general manager said something that seemed to indicate
that Coyotes coach Jim Schoenfeld had better look over his shoulder
after all. Asked if Schoenfeld's future was tied to the postseason,
Smith said, ``I think we all know the importance of the playoffs _
for every team, but particularly us, since we've never made it past
the first round of the playoffs. The entire makeup of our team
could be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months ago, Schoenfeld was on track to be
honored as coach of the year. Phoenix started the season 17-3-3 and
looked like a serious threat for the Stanley Cup. But the Coyotes
have played less than .500 hockey since _ including a 2-11 stretch
_ and Schoenfeld now finds himself at the core of the NHL's annual
spring fever: coaches on the firing line.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching positions might be less stable in hockey than in any of
the other three major pro sports. At least nine teams _ Phoenix,
Carolina, Chicago, Edmonton, Los Angeles, Montreal, New York
Islanders, Philadelphia and Tampa Bay _ are contemplating coaching
changes, as well as Detroit, where Scotty Bowman may retire. Three
coaches -- Vancouver's Mike Keenan, Chicago's Dirk Graham and the
Islanders' Mike Milbury, who as coach-GM fired himself from the
bench _ already have been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Six teams changed coaches before this season, four others midway
through last season. Excluding first-year Nashville, 19 of 26
coaches are in their first or second season with the team.
Schoenfeld is in the second year of a three-year deal and there
have been no extension talks. The Coyotes haven't made it to round
two of the playoffs since they were the Winnipeg Jets in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld might think that two years is a short tenure, but
it's twice as long as that of his predecessor, Don Hay.
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches on the hit list:
</P>
<P>
   _ Larry Robinson, Los Angeles. Robinson turned down a contract
extension before the season, and the chances of him seeing that
offer again are slim. The Kings fizzled this season and have made
the playoffs only once in Robinson's four years. The team is moving
into a new building and has a season-ticket base this year of only
8,500. Few question Robinson's coaching ability, but some people
think that he lacks the temperament and patience to be a head
coach, having even expressed self-doubt after some losses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jacques Demers, Tampa Bay. The league's only remaining
coach-general manager most certainly will lose at least one of his
titles and possibly both. The team is under the new ownership of
Bill Davidson, and Demers is part of the old regime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roger Neilson, Philadelphia. The Flyers have had six coaches
in the last seven seasons, so there's a point at which changing
loses credibility with fans. The problem is that another playoff
failure could lead to general manager Bob Clarke's exit. Owner Ed
Snider is losing patience. If Clarke's gone, Neilson probably would
follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alain Vigneault, Montreal. The Canadiens have personnel
problems, which probably makes general manager Rejean Houle less
secure than Vigneault. But in the demanding province of Quebec,
nonplayoff seasons rarely have survivors. Montreal has had nine
coaches since Scotty Bowman left in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Maurice, Carolina. The Hurricanes probably will win the
Southeast Division, but they could lose in the first round to a
lower seed like the Flyers. Maurice failed to make the playoffs his
first two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Stewart, N.Y. Islanders. Milbury replaced himself with
Bill Stewart, who might have talked his way out of the job by
bringing up the team's shallow talent pool and financial problems
after a recent loss.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lorne Molleken, Chicago. Promoted from assistant when Graham
was axed, Molleken has support from some of the players. It might
not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ron Low, Edmonton. General manager Glen Sathers keeps saying
that the Oilers' problems aren't Low's fault and that the coach is
safe. The first part of that sentence is true.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
