<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panthers acquire damaged goods
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turns out the Florida Panthers might have been
victimized by more than bad luck when Pavel Bure required
season-ending knee surgery. How about stupidity? Team orthopedist
David Attarian told the Palm Beach Post that Bure's first
reconstructive surgery in 1995 ``set him up for a series of
injuries.'' It turns out that when Bure joined the Panthers in New
York in January after the trade with Vancouver, Florida general
manager Brian Murray had the forward examined by a New Jersey team
physician. Attarian didn't examine Bure until the team returned to
Florida a few days later. Attarian said that when he performed
arthroscopic surgery on Bure's knee last month he could see that
the original reconstructive surgery had failed. Attarian said ``a
lot of information was never made public.'' In fact, the discovery
was known by only three people _ Attarian, Murray and team
president Bill Torrey. Murray didn't even tell his brother, Terry
Murray, who happens to coach the team. Attarian backed off his
comments the next day, saying, ``I thought the risk of injury was
the same as any other player in the NHL.'' But after the admitted
earlier deception, who was going to believe him or anybody in the
organization? At the very least, Brian Murray can't look good in
the eyes of owner Wayne Huizenga _ especially with the Panthers
having just given a five-year, $46.5 million contract to a player
who has had two knee reconstructions in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Stewing
</P>
<P>
   Islanders interim coach Bill Stewart angered management this
past week when, after a loss to the Rangers, he said his team
didn't ``have the resources'' to compete. ``Certainly, if we had
the resources to acquire NHL talent, would it be a different story?
You answer the question. . . . Have you looked at our lineup?
Enough said.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors persist that coach Alain Vigneault won't be the only
casualty in Montreal after the season and that team president
Ronald Corey will clean house and elevate adviser Jacques Lemaire
to general manager. Lemaire has said he didn't want the job,
currently occupied by his close friend, Rejean Houle. . . . After a
loss to Nashville, Tampa coach Jacques Demers made his players stay
in their uniforms and skates while watching lowlights of the game
on videotape. . . . Florida's Dino Ciccarelli, 39, has been told by
a spine specialist to rest his ailing back for two months, and it's
unlikely the team will bring him back next season . . .
Pittsburgh's Matthew Barnaby, unpopular in the Buffalo locker room
before being traded, had his eye blacked and two teeth loosened
after being punched by ex-teammate Rob Ray in a game. . . . Ottawa
forward Andreas Johansen hit a $75,000 incentive bonus when he
scored his 20th goal and celebrated by taking his teammates out to
dinner. ``That's what happens,'' he said, ``when you get a bonus
and guys read about it in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
