<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two minutes with Patrick Roy
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Position, team: Goalie, Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   On his decision to bypass free agency and sign a contract
extension: ``I knew everybody in my family was happy to stay in
Colorado. I was happy with the numbers, and Colorado was my first
choice for many reasons. I'm happy with the direction of the team,
getting people like (Theo) Fleury and (Dale) Hunter. They proved
that they are thinking about winning the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing this team to the Avalanche Stanley Cup teamof 1996:
``The year we won the Cup, we knew we had to beat Detroit to have a
chance. This year you have at least eight or nine very solid teams
that believe they have a chance to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   On last year's playoff collapse: ``The Olympics really hurt our
team. Emotionally, it was tough on our coach (Marc Crawford) and
some of our players. But this year everybody is confident and
fresh. I'm not saying we're going to win the Stanley Cup, but I
believe we should have a good playoff run.''
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEYTOWN
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up another one for ``Yankee flatball.'' For the second
straight year, the Atlanta Fire midget hockey team has advanced to
the national championships, which begin Wednesday in Sylvania,
Ohio. Last year was the first year a team from the Southeast
advanced to the nationals. The team comprises high school age
players and plays out of The Cooler in Alpharetta. The Fire went
35-8-12 during the season and recently won the Southeastern
District title.
</P>
<P>
   NO SURE THING
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is on the verge of clinching its second straight
Presidents Trophy, awarded annually to the NHL's regular-season
champion since 1985-86. But the points leader has gone on to win
the Stanley Cup in only three of 13 seasons thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Season _ Season _ Stanley Cup
</P>
<P>
   1985-86 _ Edmonton _ Montreal
</P>
<P>
   1986-87 _ Edmonton _ Edmonton
</P>
<P>
   1987-88 _ Calgary _ Edmonton
</P>
<P>
   1988-89 _ Calgary _ Calgary
</P>
<P>
   1989-90 _ Boston _ Edmonton
</P>
<P>
   1990-91 _ Chicago _ Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   1991-92 _ N.Y. Rangers _ Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   1992-93 _ Pittsburgh _ Montreal
</P>
<P>
   1993-94 _ N.Y. Rangers _ N.Y. Rangers
</P>
<P>
   1994-95 _ Detroit _ New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   1995-96 _ Detroit _ Colorado
</P>
<P>
   1996-97 _ Colorado _ Detroit
</P>
<P>
   1997-98 _ Dallas _ Detroit
</P>
<P>
   1998-99 _ Dallas _ ----
</P>
<P>
   THRASHER UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   General manager Don Waddell left Friday for a 10-day scouting
trip in Europe. . . . The lottery to determine the order of the top
12 selections in the June 26 amateur draft probably will be held in
mid-May but a date hasn't been finalized. Waddell likely will be
scouting at the World Championships in Norway at the time, but the
team will send a representative to New York. The Thrashers will
pick no lower than third and as high as first. They will be
weighted in the lottery to pick second, behind only the team that
finishes with the worst record (probably Tampa Bay). They will pick
second in all other rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
