<HEADER>
A4856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLWEST04-COX     04-03 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No Flame-out from Sutter
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA Calgary's Brian Sutter won't get any consideration for
coach of the year, but no coach is doing more with less right now.
When the Flames traded Theo Fleury to Colorado, most people
projected the team's playoff death. But Calgary still had a hold on
the eighth playoff spot in the Western Conference after going 7-5-2
in its first 14 games after the Fleury trade; Calgary was 21-30-10
before the deal. One reason is the goaltending of Ken Wregget, who
has lost only four of 12 starts since returning from a back injury.
Three of the losses were by 2-1 scores. But the biggest reason is
Sutter, who has managed to hold together one of the lowest-paid,
talent-starved teams in the league, despite an eight-game losing
streak in December. In addition to losing Fleury, their best player
and spiritual leader, the Flames have been decimated by injuries.
But the Flames even earned a tie recently vs. Colorado _ and
Fleury. Sutter, once thought to be on the firing line after the
season, has the players' support, and it would difficult for
managment to justify a change. Sutter also is the lowest-paid NHL
coach, at $278,885. ``I've definitely learned more about how to win
with Brian than anyone else,'' center Andrew Cassels said.
</P>
<P>
   Hot wing
</P>
<P>
   Amid the euphoria caused by Detroit's winning ways after trades
for Chris Chelios and others, it should be noted that the biggest
reason for the upswing is Sergei Fedorov. The talented but
sometimes enigmatic Russian has played so well of late _ five goals
in six games, 23 points and a plus-seven in the last 20 _ that he
has earned praise even from coach Scotty Bowman. That's no easy
feat. ``He's playing a solid two-way game. And he's putting some
pressure on the other team's defensemen when he carries the puck.
He's been forcing the other team into making mistakes.'' . . .
Wings owner Mike Ilitch on the deals for the old and high-salaried
Chelios, Wendel Clark, Ulf Samuelsson and Bill Ranford: ``I'm
always concerned with payroll, but when it comes down to the 1-yard
line, you weigh the payroll and weigh all the other things that go
with it and the possibility of having a shot at winning the Stanley
Cup. You tell yourself it's going to be an expensive venture, it's
a dangerous venture, it's a risk, but we're risk-takers.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   From Nashville tough guy Patrick Cote after scoring his first
NHL goal: ``Now I've cracked the ice, and I can go for a second
one. By the way, I'm still going to fight.'' . . . Phoenix's Robert
Reichel had six goals and three assists in his first six games
after being traded by the Islanders. But Reichel, who will be a
restricted free agent this summer and will command well over $2
million annually, is considering returning to his native Czech
Republic. . . . Pretty startling admission by Colorado's Claude
Lemieux after the acquisition of tough guy Dale Hunter: ``Everybody
knows we're a pretty passive club when it comes to emotion.'' . . .
Flashback: When Quebec, later Colorado, traded Hunter to Washington
in 1987, the Nordiques received two players and a No. 1 draft pick,
who turned out to be Joe Sakic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
