<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-CHANGE _ Augusta National Golf Club made some very
important changes to the course since the 1998 tournament. Here is
a look at those changes, why they were made and what impact they
will have on this year's tournament. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH ILLUSTRATION. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-HISTORY _ When Bobby Jones and Clifford Roberts
decided to build a course in Augusta in the early 1930s, both men
immediately contacted golf course architect Alister McKenzie in
California. Jones had played McKenzie's crown jewels _ Cypress
Point at Pebble Beach and Pasatiempo in Santa Cruz and several
European courses _ and was impressed with his work. For McKenzie,
disaster followed. For three years or so, he put his life into
Augusta and went broke in the process. Because of Augusta's dire
financial situation in the early years, McKenzie was forced to
literally beg for money that never came. He died shortly before the
first Masters tournament in 1939. (Hiskey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-HOLLINS _ Don't think it's well known that the owner
of Pasatiempo, a woman, was McKenzie's apprentice during the vision
for laying out Augusta National. In fact, McKenzie sent her on two
occasions to Augusta to look at the lay of the land before
construction began. When Bobby Jones balked at McKenize sending
``an apprentice'' to help out, McKenzie wrote to Jones that Ms.
Marion Hollins was, in his opinion, as good a golf designer as
anyone in the world. She also was a good golfer _ the 1921 U.S.
Amateur champion. (Hiskey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-TIGER _ When he left Augusta two years ago, Tiger
Woods was the prohibitive favorite to win a handful of green
jackets. But he's a co-favorite this year, at best. (Sheeley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-OFFICEPOOL _ When it comes to the office pool, here
are 10 you want; 10 you might want; 10 sleepers and 5 to avoid.
(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MASTERS-SHOPPING _ AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Augusta, Ga., is known for
it's famous country club and golf tournament, the Masters. However,
there's also plenty to do there besides watch a little dimpled
white ball soard through the air _ like, shop. The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution has produced a full page layout for use during
the week of the Masters (April 5-11) that includes text, photos,
and tips boxes on getting there and where to eat and stay.
(MJohnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
