<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4858 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DECISION-880(2     04-03 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DECISION-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CLINTON APPROVED THE STRIKES ON BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW, KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(lb) 
 By TIM WEINER and JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A few hours before U.S. cruise missiles struck
downtown Belgrade on Friday night, President Clinton met with his
top advisers in the Cabinet Room of the White House, and weighed
what one White House official who was at the meeting described
Saturday as the fundamental question: ``Can our air power make
Milosevic sue for peace?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no answer yet,'' the official said. Nevertheless,
Clinton has approved continuing attacks in and around Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, hoping that high-tech weapons can break the will of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be able to answer for a week or two,'' said the
official, who attended the meeting and discussed it on condition of
anonymity. ``We haven't turned the heat up enough. That is the
heart of the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton authorized the sixth concerted cruise-missile attack on
a foreign city of his presidency _ and the first on a European
capital _ in what is now being judged as perhaps the most difficult
foreign-policy problem he has confronted.
</P>
<P>
   He faces a test of what amounts to the Clinton Doctrine: using
air power to try to coerce political change abroad at little or no
risk to U.S. soldiers. His cruise-missile diplomacy now faces a
grim calculus. If it does not soon pound Milosevic into political
submission, there will be few ethnic Albanians, maybe none, left in
Kosovo to protect.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the air campaign against the Serbs may have weakened
the security forces' infrastructure, but it has not achieved its
declared political goal of stopping the relentless campaign to push
the majority ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo. Few military
commanders are openly confident that air power alone will quickly
achieve that aim.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign could take weeks or months, senior
administration officials warned. But Serbian security forces may
achieve their goal of driving ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo in as
little as 10 to 20 days, the NATO spokesman, Jamie Shea, said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The full horror of what has happened in Kosovo is still unknown,
a senior U.S. official said. There may be ``50 Srebrenicas,'' he
said, referring to the Bosnian town from which 7,000 Muslim men
fled in July 1995, only to be captured and then shot and buried by
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The enormity of the campaign over Kosovo is felt across the
administration. One senior official involved in Kosovo policy said
Clinton made the ``most fateful decision of his presidency'' when
he decided in late March to go ahead with the air strikes without
considering using ground troops to stop the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, an official said there was ``anxiety across the
board'' about achieving Milosevic's capitulation, with military
officers asking basic questions, like ``Is this guy going to
yield?'' and ``Do we have the right strategy?''
</P>
<P>
   Another official said he had often wondered about when ``the big
one'' _ the foreign crisis that would threaten to spin out of
control _ might strike the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the big one,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the cruise-missile assault on Belgrade, Clinton met late
Friday with Vice President Al Gore and the tight circle known as
``the small group'' _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen; Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright; George Tenet, the director of central
intelligence; Sandy Berger, the national security adviser; and Gen.
Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. The small
group reconvened Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday they discussed the military and political dimensions
of taking the war against Milosevic to the streets of his capital,
White House officials said. And they assessed the public pressure
for quick results from the continuing attack on Belgrade in days to
come, given the heart-rending images of terrified refugees fleeing
Kosovo, according to an official at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the mood at the Friday evening meeting with
Clinton was determined, if sometimes grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say Milosevic drives everyone out of Kosovo,'' he said.
``That doesn't stop the bombing. If in a week, 10 days, he's still
defiant, we'll take stock.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kosovo is purged of its 1.8 million ethnic Albanians, the air
campaign will continue to strike Serbian forces, hoping to push
them out of the province and eventually make way for some kind of
internationally recognized enclave guarded by NATO troops,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the room was saying, we're OK, we're on course,''
the official said. ``The weather has hampered us; the NATO
bureaucracy has hampered us. Now we're going to start to do real
damage. Let's not start looking at other options.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stay focused and turn up the pressure,'' he said.
``We're going to keep hitting Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   The political sensitivity of striking downtown Belgrade was so
strong that NATO commanders specifically sought Clinton's approval
for destroying the first targets, the Yugoslav federal Interior
Ministry and its counterpart for the republic of Serbia, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After sounding out his advisers with his customary concerns
about civilian casualties, Clinton gave a go-ahead to hit the first
targets and conduct expanded attacks in days to come, the officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He strongly believes we have to intensify the air campaign,
including the broadening of the target list to include the things
Milosevic values most,'' said a spokesman for the National Security
Council, David Leavy. ``The president has made it clear: We will go
after both troops in the field and the command and control centers
that go to the heart of Milosevic's power and his repression in
days to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent military history _ in Iraq and elsewhere _ provides
little basis for believing that smart bombs and cruise missiles
alone can convince a determined dictator to change course.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, three separate attacks on Baghdad _ first on its
intelligence headquarters and then on military targets _ did little
or nothing to undermine President Saddam Hussein. A twin assault on
Afghanistan and Sudan last year, aimed at what the administration
said were sites linked to the exiled Saudi terrorist Osama bin
Laden, created mostly disbelief among allies and defiance in the
Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Sudan, Clinton, concerned about killing
civilians, shied away from one likely military target to select a
factory that produced drugs for people and animals. The
administration has been unable to convince many allies that the
factory was tied to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Even if attacks on the fuel depots and command centers of
Milosevic's military force slow or stall his concerted attacks in
Kosovo, it is unclear that the notorious Serbian paramilitary
forces will be stopped by high-tech attacks from afar, Pentagon
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When the bombing campaign began, the ``ethnic cleansing'' of
Kosovo had just begun, and Clinton said the NATO attack aimed in
part ``to deter an even bloodier offensive against innocent
civilians.'' But in his weekly radio address Saturday, the
president stopped short of predicting that air power alone would
stop the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal,'' Clinton said, ``is to exact a very high price for
Milosevic's policy of repression and to seriously diminish his
military capacity to maintain that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Clinton telephoned Prime Ministers Tony Blair of
Britain and Jacques Chirac of France to discuss the military and
humanitarian facts on the ground. Blair said Saturday that NATO's
attacks must ``continue until the whole policy of ethnic cleansing
in Kosovo is defeated'' and vowed that Milosevic would be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   In the White House situation room on Saturday morning, Cohen,
Albright, Shelton, Tenet and Berger reconvened to review the damage
done by the attack on downtown Belgrade and to discuss where and
when to strike again, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plans are unchanged: to bomb Milosevic to
the bargaining table.``What we're doing is thinking about the
political arrangements after he capitulates and accepts a
negotiated outcome,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   One outcome might be an ``international protectorate'' for
Kosovo under which the ethnic Albanians could return home under the
guard of NATO troops, he said. He did not say whether ethnic
Albanian leaders had been approached about such a solution. Nor is
it clear that thousands of NATO troops and millions of dollars in
Western aid would be sufficient to induce them to go back.
</P>
</TEXT>
