<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-UPSTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO-CASE FURY BARELY RESONATES AT GIULIANI EVENTS UPSTATE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had not yet addressed the
700 business and political leaders squeezed into a college
gymnasium to eat filet mignon and hear his tips for transforming
troubled cities into centers of prosperity. But as the dinner rolls
were passed, Peter Goold was exuding enthusiasm about New York
City's graffiti-free subways and litter-free streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city seems to be not as harsh or dirty a place anymore,''
said Goold, who owns an apple orchard outside this industrial city
about 150 miles north of Manhattan. ``And Rudy Giuliani has
provided the leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goold had little to say when the conversation turned to
Amadou Diallo, the unarmed West African immigrant whose fatal
shooting by four white police officers has roiled that same city
for eight weeks and sparked intense criticism of Giuliani. ``People
up here aren't as close to it, so they're not as moved by it,'' he
explained. ``It just seems distant to us.''
</P>
<P>
   While elected officials, movie stars and hundreds of regular
citizens in New York City have assailed Giuliani's handling of the
Diallo case, the fury seems not to have spread to upstate New York,
where the Republican mayor recently began testing the waters for a
possible Senate race. Giuliani received standing ovations, fervent
praise and even a ``Citizen of the Year'' award during visits to
Ithaca, Syracuse and Troy last month, even as his approval ratings
back home fell precipitously and throngs of protesters accused him
of insensitivity to minority residents' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews over the last few weeks, about three dozen
residents of four upstate cities _ including Republicans and
Democrats, avid followers of Giuliani and people who could barely
pronounce his name _ expressed sorrow about the shooting. But the
majority of people interviewed in those predominantly white
communities said they did not understand why the mayor has been
under attack since Diallo died in a hail of bullets on Feb. 4. Most
also defended Giuliani, applauding his crime-fighting tactics and
predicting that the Diallo incident would not hurt his chances in a
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened there is an unfortunate incident, but you can't
blame Rudy,'' said Michael Verdile, a restaurant owner who came to
hear Giuliani speak last Tuesday at the Troy dinner, organized by
the Rensselaer County Regional Chamber of Commerce. ``With 40,000
police officers on his force, things are going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Sherman, a Troy bakery owner who did not attend the dinner
but said he had followed Giuliani's career, offered a similar view.
``He shouldn't be blamed for something the police did,'' Sherman
said. ``If you've got the police doing all this undercover stuff to
clean up the streets, some innocent people might get hurt by it.
But over all, it's going to do some good.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani has not officially declared himself a
candidate for the Senate seat that Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a
Democrat, will relinquish when he retires next year, the Mayor has
behaved like one for months, aggressively raising money and giving
speeches around the nation. The prospect of Giuliani as a Senate
candidate has stirred considerable excitement upstate, where voters
are mostly Republican and eager for a strong candidate to make a
possible run against Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has also expressed
interest in the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall's Senate race between Alfonse M. D'Amato, the
Republican incumbent, and Charles E. Schumer was a strong reminder
of upstate residents' strong Republican leanings: although Schumer,
a Democrat, won the election, he carried only 6 of the 52 counties
north and west of the New York City metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   But while Giuliani has an advantage over a Democratic candidate
in upstate New York, most upstate residents interviewed said they
still knew little about him _ except that he had reduced crime. In
Schenectady, a city of 65,000 about 15 miles from Troy, Joan Grant
said all she knew about Giuliani was that ``the taxi drivers are
more friendly and the city is better-looking since he took over.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Diallo incident, Mrs. Grant said she knew from the
local television news that the actress Susan Sarandon had been
arrested while protesting the shooting. But Mrs. Grant, a volunteer
in a thrift shop, said she knew little else about the controversy
because, ``I don't want to hear news if it's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In his upstate appearances, Giuliani has talked mostly about his
strategies for reducing the city's crime rate and its welfare rolls
and for improving its economy _ strategies that he said could work
just as well in other parts of the state. But toward the end of his
speeches in Syracuse and Troy, he also offered a spirited defense
of the Police Department, saying that the police had used less
force in recent years and stressing that they deserved respect. At
both dinners, his comments on the police were met with hearty
applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in our little towns around here have a real respect for
what law enforcement goes through,'' said Neil J. Kelleher, the
Republican chairman of the Rensselaer County Legislature, who
attended the dinner in Troy. ``We tend to take things a little
slower than some of the downstate folks, and we are a little more
patient, and we are more willing to step back and allow an
investigation to take its natural course.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher was not the only person interviewed who suggested that
upstate residents had markedly different views of the Diallo
controversy than some city residents. John Stevens, a lawyer in
Ithaca who heard Giuliani speak at the Tompkins County Lincoln Day
Dinner on March 19, said it was not the shooting itself, but the
intense media coverage that followed, that had created the
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the view from here is that a lot of what goes on in
New York is a matter of screaming `Fire!''' he said. ``Every time
you turn around there is a new controversy, and it always has to
revolve around racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Several upstate residents said news of the protests that the
Rev. Al Sharpton led against Giuliani and the police had
intensified their support for the mayor, because they so strongly
disliked Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those protests will probably add five points to Rudy's
support,'' said William Troy, a lawyer who attended the Ithaca
dinner. ``Al Sharpton and his professional agitating represent
something just incomprehensible up here.''
</P>
<P>
   But while interviews suggested strong upstate support for
Giuliani and his response to the Diallo incident, they also
suggested that minority residents of upstate New York are wary of
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Bradford, a black resident of Schenectady, said the case
confirmed his longstanding suspicion that Giuliani was racially
insensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are taking a second look at Giuliani after Diallo,''
said Bradford, a gas station attendant and part-time student. ``But
not up here. Upstate is out of touch with New York City, and it's
too bad, because this kind of problem is like cancer. If you don't
cut it down down there, it's going to spread up here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
