<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-IRABU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBRENNER'S KISS: IRABU GOES FROM FROG TO PRINCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hideki Irabu was expected to rejoin the Yankees
Saturday, in the team's latest installment of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher, who was called a fat toad by the Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner after failing to cover first base in an
exhibition game on Thursday, was initially told to remain at the
team's Florida training complex, and that he would rejoin the team
Tuesday in Oakland, Calif., for the Yankees' regular-season opening
series. Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, said Ramiro
Mendoza would pitch Wednesday in a day game against the Athletics,
calling it his decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Steinbrenner _ who has taken on a fatherly mien as this
series of events has unfolded _ told The Associated Press in Tampa,
Fla., Saturday that ``it would be my hope'' that Irabu would start
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner also said Irabu's role ``will be determined'' by
the manager, but his stated desire that Irabu will start places
Zimmer in an uncomfortable position. Some of Irabu's teammates are
fed up with what they perceive as preferential treatment for the
hard-throwing pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   If Zimmer starts Mendoza, as he said Friday he intends to do,
then he will be contravening the wishes of the owner. On the other
hand, if he starts Irabu, Zimmer will appear powerless in the eyes
of those disgusted players.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, in recent years, has been as active as always in
the formulation of the team.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the owner made the decision last November to sign
Bernie Williams, once it appeared Albert Belle would sign with
Baltimore and Williams could be headed to the rival Boston Red Sox.
It was Steinbrenner's decision to keep Orlando Hernandez in the
pitching rotation last June and move Mendoza to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, however, has allowed Manager Joe Torre great
flexibility in determining how he would use players, and except in
rare instances, the owner's involvement in day-to-day decisions has
been kept out of public view. But as Torre recovers from
prostate-cancer surgery and Zimmer tries to establish himself,
Steinbrenner is in the forefront of the team's handling of Irabu _
perhaps because he feels the right-hander is hampered by a lack of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``His teammates are anxious to have him back,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``He will do fine. It's a good day for the Yankees. We wanted
Hideki to know we are all behind him. I'm glad he spent the two
days here.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu worked out for 18 minutes in a bullpen early Saturday with
Billy Connors, the director of player personnel, while Steinbrenner
met with Irabu's agent, Don Nomura. Irabu did not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens will pitch the regular-season opener for the
Yankees on Monday night, with Hernandez going on Tuesday night. For
now, Mendoza is scheduled to pitch Wednesday afternoon, but this
appears to be a fluid situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
