<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WOMEN'S-HOTEL-2TAK     04-03 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN'S-HOTEL-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOTEL'S BAND OF ELDERLY WOMEN DEFY NEW YORK DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo., France)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Past rows of vacant rooms, at the end of a corridor
deep in the dust of demolition and renovation, a handwritten sign
taped to the door of No. 701 is like a muffled cry: ``Occupied.
Please do not touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Here lives Suzanne Remy, one of the last residents of the
Allerton Hotel for Women. In her time, Mademoiselle Remy created
hats for Greta Garbo and Marlene Dietrich. She sold $17,000 gowns
at Bergdorf Goodman on commission. When the Germans occupied her
native Paris 59 years ago, she worked the switchboard at the
American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though her tenancy is protected by law, just staying put,
she said, seems like an act of defiance. In her 8-by-10-foot room,
with a broken faucet and a hot plate, Ms. Remy is part of a
dwindling band of 48 residents who have withstood a campaign to
drive them from the Allerton, a faded grande dame of single room
occupancy at East 57th Street and Lexington Avenue that its owners
hope to convert into a luxury hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Like the better-known Barbizon, the 448-room Allerton opened in
the 1920s as a genteel residential hotel for young ladies of good
breeding and professional aspiration. As recently as the 1960s, it
still had a marble staircase, grand pianos in the lobby, and
white-gloved elevator maids who enforced the cardinal rule: no men
above the third floor. But decades of neglect took their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Today the hotel is hard-fought terrain in New York City's real
estate wars. Tourist demand and a booming economy are driving the
biggest surge of SRO conversions since the early 1980s. For tenant
advocates and landlords alike, the Allerton is a new testing ground
for 15-year-old local laws that try to restrict the redevelopment
of single room occupancies in an effort to stem homelessness and
protect longtime residents from harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1997, the Allerton's management waged an
illegal campaign of lockouts and verbal abuse to oust tenants, most
of them elderly or frail, from rent-regulated rooms, an
administrative hearing officer for the city's Department of Housing
Preservation and Development concluded late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotel employees shouting at tenants, cursing at tenants,
referring to them as losers or crazy, screaming at tenants about
rent in the street, following a tenant into a diner daily for
several weeks and asking her about moving out, and threatening
placement in a nursing home if tenants did not go away are examples
of harassment,'' the hearing officer, Frances Lippa, wrote in a
decision rendered December 31, after hearing testimony over a
13-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where could I go?'' asked Ms. Remy, a tiny woman with a black
organdy bow in upswept hair, perched on a floral bedspread piled
with doctor bills and medicine for asthma, emphysema and glaucoma.
Still chic after all these years (exactly how many, she would not
say), she gave a small shrug at the water-damaged ceiling and
mottled walls of the room where she has lived since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   She pays $153 a week, much more than the $3.27-a-day charged for
the room where the longest permanent resident, a former model, has
lived for five decades, but low compared to the alternatives.
Studios in the neighborhood start at $1,195 a month, and at the
Allerton, recently renamed the Habitat Hotel, modestly renovated
rooms without private bath or toilet cost tourists $75 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Property Markets Group, a real estate investment
company that took control of the hotel in 1997, say that whatever
harassment the tenants endured under the previous management has
nothing to do with them. Ongoing renovations, including a new
lobby, new pipes and electrical rewiring, represent major
improvements in exchange for minor inconveniences, they say, not a
form of harassment, as some tenants have charged.
</P>
<P>
   The company pressed city housing officials to overrule the
hearing officer and grant the hotel a ``certificate of
no-harassment,'' which is legally required before vacant rooms in
an SRO can be reconfigured into the upscale suites of a more
lucrative tourist-class hotel. But last month, after most tenants
refused to go along, the city denied the application. The hotel
management must now wait three years before it can reapply and then
must show that tenants were not harassed during that period. For
now, only renovations that do not change the number of units are
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that justice was served,'' said Franklin R.
Kaiman, the lawyer who opposed the city's harassment case against
the hotel, on behalf of the hotel's longtime owner, Allan Goldman,
and for Property Markets Group, which has agreed to lease the hotel
from Goldman for 49 years at $2.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the incidents cited by the hearing officer occurred when
Goldman controlled the hotel and employed a manager to run it.
Goldman said in an interview that he was unaware of any harassment,
but the hearing officer concluded that it was conducted on his
behalf, and that pressure to force tenants out continued to some
degree after Property Markets Group took over. Technically Goldman
still owns the hotel, but all business decisions, and profits or
losses, fall to Property Markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company, owned by Kevin P. Maloney, a former banker, and
Ziel Feldman, a real estate lawyer, controls about 75
rent-regulated buildings in Manhattan, including two other SRO's
where luxury hotel conversions are planned and one SRO where
conversion is underway even as tenants have filed harassment
complaints and a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Around a conference table on the fifth floor of the former
Allerton, the thump and whine of construction in the background,
Kaiman and his frustrated clients said it was not rational for
tenants to reject offers of settlement that had included better
rooms, private bathrooms, and in a few cases, up to $15,000, all
contingent on enough tenant support for the conversion to win city
approval. Since that never happened, they said, tenants who wanted
a deal lost out.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiman contended that tenants who rejected the offers were
manipulated by MFY Legal Services, a city-financed nonprofit agency
that provides representation for SRO tenants.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for MFY counter that tenants made up their own
minds, and with good reasons. Amy J. Mayer, who has handled the
case since the hearing, said the company's tactics and track record
alienated most of the tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really strong group of women,'' she said. ``They
stood up for themselves in a very brave way.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Last year, developers filed 99 applications for certificates of
no-harassment affecting 2,331 SRO units in Manhattan, more than a
fourfold increase since 1993, according to an analysis of city
figures by the West Side SRO project. The Allerton application was
one of only three denied since January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The women of the Allerton seem unlikely combatants. Some, like
the red-haired secretary who retired from NASA soon after Neil
Armstrong walked on the Moon, say they are too fearful of
management retaliation to let a newspaper print their names.
Others, like the woman who worked for a New Deal think tank in the
1930s, are too proud to draw attention to their reduced
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But Mehru Ramnagar, a 74-year-old retired nurse who has been a
mainstay of the revolt, said softly, ``Just because they are old,
it doesn't mean that they are nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel declined rapidly in the 1980s, when many of its rooms
were ``warehoused,'' or deliberately kept vacant, according to city
findings. Tenants testified that verbal abuse began in 1993, when
Goldman hired Gary Greene as the hotel's manager. Greene, the
tenants said, told people he had been hired to clear out the place.
Greene denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the harassment hearing began late in 1997, there
were fewer than 60 residents and Property Markets Group had taken
charge.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, men, some of them Marymount Manhattan College
students, were lodged on floors where only women had lived before.
The students soon left and sued, contending their rooms were
uninhabitable. Then workers ripped out communal bathrooms and
toilets floor by floor, and tore up the hallways, making them
treacherous to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Some floors were left like that for months, and heat, hot water,
electricity, telephone and elevator service were repeatedly
disrupted, tenants and their lawyers said. The hotel management
said the disruptions were minimal considering the scale of needed
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   City records show that the hotel was fined at least five times
by city agencies last year for creating a fire hazard, working
without permits and not supplying heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not targeting elderly women to recapture rooms _ that's
totally ridiculous,'' responded Ron Simoncini, whose public
relations company represents Property Markets Group. ``The
suggestion that we've done anything but what we're supposed to do
here insults us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, before the harassment hearing concluded, Kaiman, the
lawyer for the hotel's owners, sent a letter offering each of the
seven tenants who had testified $15,000 and a renovated room with
private bath if all would recant their testimony, and an extra
$10,000 each if they moved out. The five remaining tenants refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dirty money,'' said one tenant witness, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, saying she did not want old friends to know
how she lives now. She testified that desk clerks ridiculed her use
of a walker and called her a loser.
</P>
<P>
   When the hearing officer's decision went against the hotel, a
new flurry of settlement offers appeared under tenant doors: They
would be moved away from construction and provided private
bathrooms with no rent increase for life if they agreed to the
conversion and the city approved it despite the harassment finding.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 11 of the 48 tenants showed interest in the deal,
according to documents supplied by both sides. One wrote the city
that as a past victim of rape, she was tormented by having to share
a bathroom with strange men and wanted the private bathroom offered
in the deal. ``Yes, construction is noisy and messy, but it is also
temporary,'' she said, in a letter supplied by Kaiman, ``and when
it is completed, our standard of living will have soared.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the tenants felt bullied and insulted, Ms. Mayer
said, and dreaded more construction. Some already considered
modernization a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took the light over my bed,'' one lamented. ``They said I
could have a fax.''
</P>
<P>
   The divide between the real estate men and their tenants runs
deep. Maloney, a 40-year-old native of Casper, Wyo., cited Internet
capability and durable pipes as improvements worth the disruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year from now, 90 percent of the people will say it's so
much better here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Remy does not expect to live that long. ``I'm being very
strong about it,'' she said, with a wave of her hand that released
a faint whiff of Chanel No. 5. ``But believe me, at night I have my
weak moments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
