<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WR     04-03 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-950&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANS TO SEND TROOPS TO ALBANIA FOR REFUGEE RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATS to delete graphics note)  
 (Eds: Subs to reorganize and rewrite; updates throughout)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-LEGAL,
KOSOVO-KLA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-McCAIN,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX-REVIEW, KOSOVO-POWELL-REVIEW,
KOSOVO-HITECH-REVIEW, KOSOVO-BALKANS-OUTLOOK-REVIEW.) 
(rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO said Saturday that it was planning to
send a force of 6,000 to 8,000 troops to Albania to provide
security and emergency relief for the masses of Kosovo Albanians
who have been driven from neighboring Yugoslavia by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is mobilizing all its available resources for this urgent
humanitarian requirement,'' the alliance's spokesman, Jamie P.
Shea, said. He announced that allied ambassadors had asked the top
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of the United States, for a plan to
deploy an operational headquarters, helicopters, troops and
supplies to Albania as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Shea also said that Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain,
commanding a force of more than 10,000 British, French and German
troops in Macedonia that was originally intended for a peacekeeping
mission in Kosovo, was ordered to put all of them to work helping
Macedonia deal with the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Macedonia, saying it was overwhelmed by the flow of
people into the country, announced that it would close its border.
Defense Ministry officials in London said 200,000 Kosovo Albanians
are currently making their way toward Macedonia on the road from
Pristina, the Kosovo capital.
</P>
<P>
   More than 165,000 refugees have already arrived in Albania from
Kosovo since the allies began bombing to try to stop the Serbian
campaign, according to allied officials. Shea said that 55,000
people crossed into Albania Friday alone, and that 290,000 Kosovo
Albanians had fled into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro in the
last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this rate,'' Shea said Saturday, ``if you do a mathematical
calculation, Serb forces will have emptied Kosovo of its entire
population in 10 to 20 days.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that despite the missile attacks that blew
up the Yugoslav and Serbian Interior Ministries headquarters in
Belgrade shortly after midnight, bad weather overnight kept large
numbers of allied planes from going after the Serb forces driving
people from Kosovo. Those operations would continue once the
weather cleared, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea and others here deny that the air campaign targeted the
Yugoslav president, Slodoban Milosevic, who has shown no signs of
relenting in his campaign against the 1.8 million ethnic Albanians
who once lived in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the business that we're into,'' said the British
air commodore, David Wilby, the allied military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Saturday, Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain issued
some of the strongest statements yet by an allied leader against
the Yugoslav leader, ``Your policy of ethnic cleansing is an act of
barbarity,'' he said in a message broadcast on Sky Television. ``We
will defeat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark charged Saturday that the flood of refugees was part of a
deliberate strategy by Milosevic to destabilize the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a calculated, deliberate, arranged, pre-planned
humanitarian catastrophe,'' he told a small group reporters at the
alliance's military headquarters in Mons, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It serves two purposes,'' Clark added. ``Not only does it
change the demographics in Kosovo, but it helps to destabilize
Macedonia. So it is part of his ongoing strategy to cause
difficulty for that democratic government.''
</P>
<P>
   To help the refugees, NATO erected 3,500 tents Saturday and
plans to ship another 5,000 tents over the next 24 hours, Western
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials here said they believed that the Serbian
campaign was aimed at emptying a large triangle of territory in
Kosovo, roughly a triangle between Pristina and the cities of Pec
and Prizren, of its ethnic Albanian inhabitants and replacing them
with Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen some reports of Serbian refugees from the Krajina
entering Kosovo,'' said Edgar Buckley, a British official,
referring to a region of Croatia that was largely emptied of Serbs
in fighting in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With clouds and rain keeping most of the 450-odd allied planes
from hitting the Serbian military and police forces enough to keep
them from driving more refugees out, the allies are now being
forced to deal with the humanitarian disaster spreading into
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who met with the
Albanian president and prime minister Saturday in Tirana, canceled
a stopover in Rome to fly to Skopje, Macedonia. The Macedonians
said they decided to close the border out of concern that the
massive influx of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo could upset the
ethnic balance of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their concerns are absolutely legitimate and understandable,''
Talbott said, after meeting with Kosovo refugees in a tent city of
2,000 in Tirana. ``We are seeing with our own eyes today a policy
on the part of Yugoslavia to undercut the viability of neighboring
states.''
</P>
<P>
   But Talbott's delegation also sped to Macedonia with the aim of
pressuring its leaders to open up the borders again and let the
refugees in, another American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has absorbed 55,000 ethnic Albanian refugees in the
last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The allies say they have observed about 25,000 people backed up
inside Kosovo behind the border crossing point waiting for the Serb
authorities to let them pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not let you down,'' Blair told the refugees in his
British television interview Saturday. ``We will make sure that you
are able to return to your homes, and live in your homes in
peace,'' he said. ``That is our promise to you and we will carry it
out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that Jackson had already asked for 1 million food
rations, 50,000 gallons of drinking water, and 187,000 blankets and
was setting up a feeding station near the border with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Three American soldiers on a border patrol fell into Serbian
hands earlier in the week and were taken prisoner. A Western
official said Saturday that there was evidence the three American
soldiers now being detained in Yugoslavia were kidnapped by
Yugoslav special forces who crossed into Macedonia and took the
Americans out.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have also expressed concern about the situation in
Montenegro, which is federated with Serbia within Yugoslavia.
Milosevic replaced eight Yugoslav military commanders in Montenegro
this week, allied officials said, and could be preparing a coup
there.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempt to destabilize the government of Montenegro ``could
have more serious consequences,'' Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine
of France said in Paris Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which fears an uncontrolled influx of refugees across the
Adriatic, asked its allies on Friday to create a force to ensure
the safety of the refugees in Albania. Italy has offered to lead
the force and provide most of the soldiers for it, according to an
Italian official here.
</P>
<P>
   American, British and French warplanes continued to launch
attacks from bases in Italy Saturday, officials said, in an effort
to stop the Serb persecution and stem the refugee flow.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the allies met here to discuss other emergency steps to
deal with the victims of the violence in Kosovo, British and NATO
officers said that the American and British cruise missiles
launched from ships at targets in central Belgrade in the predawn
hours Saturday morning had caused no significant damage to civilian
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise missile attacks destroyed the Serbian and Yugoslav
Interior Ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Air Marshal John Day, chief of the British defense staff in
London, described these headquarters as ``the nerve center of
operations planned to drive out ethnic Albanians in a campaign of
violence, intimidation and thuggery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's attacks will continue and can be intensified even
further if necessary,'' he said. ``The weather is forecast to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We only need a couple of days of good weather to be able to
have a maximized effect,'' Shea said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said allied planes had managed Friday to hit staging areas
used by the Yugoslav 547th Mechanized Brigade for attacks against
civilians, but he did not say how much damage the planes did.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks were in three areas along the road between Prizren
and Djakovica in southwestern Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
