<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TENEMENTS-REAL-3TA     04-03 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TENEMENTS-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: MAKING TENEMENTS MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN S. OSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What's a tenement?'' asked Daniel Khodadadian, a
28-year-old physician doing his residency at Lenox Hill Hospital,
as he stood, keys in hand, ready to enter his own renovated
tenement building at 167 East 77th St. a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since Khodadadian and his parents arrived in the United States
from Iran via Israel only 14 years ago, settling on Long Island,
his unfamiliarity with the term is understandable. But what would
the reformers of yesteryear say if they heard that at a rent of
almost $1,300 a month he is living in an apartment that is only 10
feet wide and 20 feet long?
</P>
<P>
   It has a living room, with a stove, refrigerator and sink on one
side, and a bedroom. The bathroom is about 7 feet square. Lenox
Hill Hospital, which is around the corner, is the tenant of record
and pays part of the rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very small and there's not much light, but convenience is
the main reason I live there,'' Khodadadian said. ``Actually when I
moved in two years ago I was on the first floor in under 150 square
feet. I've moved up in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers are living in an era of tenement renaissance, and
the rents that a tenement building like 167 East 77th St. can
capture because of its Upper East Side location are only one side
of the story. Another side is that it is happening with both public
and private investment, sometimes in the same project, and in
Manhattan it encompasses neighborhoods that vary greatly in average
household income.
</P>
<P>
   As a housing type, tenements are nothing more than residential
buildings constructed for use by three families or more before
changes in building standards were made by the Multiple Dwelling
Law of 1929. The critical change was that all windows that provide
light and ventilation had to be at least 30 feet from any wall or
other obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   After that, new apartments had more light and air, although
because of the Depression, it took years before many were built. In
tenements of earlier vintage many apartments are dark and airless
because interior windows face narrow light shafts, if there are
interior windows at all.
</P>
<P>
   Tenements were built by the thousands in the middle and late
19th century and the early 1900s under regulations that
progressively introduced higher standards for light and air and
fire safety. They are classified as Old Law tenements when they
were built under the rules of the Tenement House Act of 1879, and
New Law tenements when built under reform legislation adopted in
1901.
</P>
<P>
   There are also pre-Old Law tenements, built both before and
after the initial Tenement House Act of 1867.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Law (1879) gave rise to narrow interior light shafts in
tenement buildings, at first mere slots, and then wider openings
athwart a building shaped like an upside-down T when viewed
head-on, and finally two air shafts, usually 18 feet wide, in a
dumbbell-shaped building. Many Old Law tenements are 80 feet long,
built on lots 20 to 25 feet wide and 100 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   The New Law (1901) mandated lot coverage of no more than 70
percent, replacing the unenforceable 65 percent maximum in the Old
Law, according to Richard Plunz in his 1990 book ``A History of
Housing in New York City,'' published by Columbia University Press.
But air-shaft dimensions were increased to courtyard size, obliging
builders to utilize larger sites.
</P>
<P>
   These and other rules gave rise to pre-World War II buildings
that provide superior housing to this day. The better New Law
buildings were called apartment houses. ``Middle-class people
didn't want to say they lived in a tenement,'' Plunz said.
</P>
<P>
   The early tenements, with small and poorly ventilated rooms and
possibly toilets in rear-yard outhouses or hallways, became
synonymous with the overcrowded, unsanitary and unsafe housing
conditions of the immigrant poor on the Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these conditions still exist. ``What I see,'' said
Victor Papa, the court-appointed administrator of a building near
Chinatown, ``is what Jacob Riis saw _ squalid situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Riis was the 19th-century writer who turned tenement reform into
a crusade with newspaper articles and then a book, ``How the Other
Half Lives,'' in 1889.
</P>
<P>
   Papa runs the 1904 midblock tenement at 211 Madison St., between
Clinton and Rutgers streets. It is in a section of the city that is
densely populated by Chinese immigrants, many of whom are crowded
into small apartments with outmoded appliances and poorly
functioning plumbing. ``I see cramped apartments, rodents, broken
windows,'' Papa said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen of the 20 apartments in 211 Madison have tubs in the
kitchen and tiny toilet rooms, as they did nearly 100 years ago,
Papa said. Rents average only $312 a month, although the existing
tenants, faithful rent-payers, could probably pay twice that
amount, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Papa said he hopes to get a low-interest city loan of about
$20,000 an apartment to improve the building. He said he considers
long-term owner negligence to be the principal cause of the
building's conditions.
</P>
<P>
   What has brought so many tenements back _ with modernized
apartments _ has been a combination of forces: governmental subsidy
programs and the inability of the private market to supply enough
new apartments for a mass market, and the rising level of market
rents in Manhattan locations that are filled with tenement
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Since contemporary society resists the relocations that are
necessary for demolition and the construction of modern buildings
in the areas of greatest housing demand, rehabilitation becomes a
housing safety valve.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results are the anomalies suggested by Khodadadian's
situation: For the privilege of living in a strong market location
he is paying a higher rent for less space in an old building than a
low-income tenant is paying in East Harlem or West Harlem for a new
family-sized apartment built or renovated with city subsidies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Newly built apartments in gut-renovated _ and usually subsidized
_ buildings are perhaps the cream of late 20th-century tenement
housing stock. Next in line come the moderate rehabilitations done
to occupied tenement buildings. In the private market, improvements
are made to individual apartments only after long-term tenants
vacate. But in subsidized projects building-wide improvements are
combined with the reconstruction of bathrooms and kitchens even in
occupied apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, one goes to residential buildings that years ago
fell into city hands through foreclosure to find the finest
examples of tenement revival in Manhattan. And one goes to areas of
market strength, where the private market is able to upgrade
apartments without public assistance, to find the oldest tenement
buildings upgraded with modernized, if often quite small,
apartments for incoming tenants.
</P>
<P>
   On East 13th Street between Avenue A and Avenue B in the East
Village, Dana Discordia, a 33-year-old actor and filmmaker who grew
up in Saugerties, rented a 250-square-foot apartment two months ago
up one flight of stairs at the rear of the building, paying $815 a
month. ``I found a pullout couch that was 5 feet 1 inch long _ it
wasn't easy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also found privacy, his goal after living with a roommate on
Bleecker Street and paying half the $612 rent each month. ``There
the bathroom was in the hallway, but here it's inside, and that's a
plus,'' Discordia said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Eldon Bullock, who is also an actor, lives in a
modern fourth-floor one-bedroom apartment at 827 10th Ave., near
55th Street. It was renovated with tenants in occupancy four years
ago at a cost of $40,000 an apartment under the city's Tenant
Interim Lease program. The building was one of five contiguous
occupied 1880s tenements on an urban-renewal site.
</P>
<P>
   With Bullock taking the lead, the tenants organized and
ultimately bought the building from the city for $1, later
converting it to a limited-equity co-op by making an equity payment
to the co-op of $250 a unit. Bullock now pays maintenance of $403 a
month for 600 square feet of well-lighted modern space on the
fourth floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Settlement Housing Fund, the nonprofit company that served
as the tenants' development consultant, has itself been involved in
upgrading 86 tenement buildings with 3,000 apartments over the last
27 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renovating these buildings isn't an easy thing to do,'' said
Carol Lamberg, executive director of the Settlement Housing Fund
``Each one is unique. It's not a cookie cutter. You can't do things
on the cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost constraints are a constant issue between developers and the
city government in tenement renovations. Current controversies in
gut renovation often revolve around the question of whether
elevators should be installed in six-story tenements that are being
totally rebuilt, or whether trash chutes should be installed so
that tenants don't have to carry garbage to the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   A high-cost renovation to a six-story building that is left a
walk-up may prove a poor investment in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   But basically these buildings, rebuilt for low- or
moderate-income tenants, get far more dollars invested in them than
do the privately owned tenements, which usually need less systems
replacement. Many government-assisted buildings were vacant or
severely deteriorated when work began, and that alone means higher
costs per apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Vacancy has important advantages in housing restoration. It
leads to better buildings, and imaginative treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Mandel, the principal in the architectural firm bearing
his name, has been the architect in 20 city-assisted gut
rehabilitations of Manhattan tenements since 1980, usually working
on behalf nonprofit developers.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Hope Community Inc., as the nonprofit developer,
completed the amalgamation of a strip of five Old Law tenements
east of Fifth Avenue on 110th Street into a single modern elevator
building, 8-18 East 110th St. A center hall runs east and west
through all five buildings on all five floors. There are 59
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   A new five-story element with the lobby and the elevator was
built on what had been vacant land at the west side of the
tenements. ``That structure made it possible for us to construct
essentially a single new elevator building,'' Mandel said.
</P>
<P>
   But from the outside it looks like a strip of Old Law walk-ups.
Tenants pay $400 to $600 a month for apartments that range in size
from studios to three-bedrooms. Financing came from the federal
government's low-income tax-credit program and a long-term 1
percent mortgage from the city.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, on East 115th Street between First and Pleasant
avenues, a series of empty Old Law and early New Law tenements were
rebuilt with a small park in the middle where a building once
stood. ``In the early days I kissed off Old Law tenements,'' Mandel
said. ``But if we aren't forced to reuse the old interior light
shafts for bedroom light, they have real potential.''
</P>
<P>
   As rehabilitations rather than new buildings, bedrooms with
windows facing shafts are legal. And the higher the bedroom count
in an apartment, the larger the subsidy a low-income apartment is
entitled to. Therefore there is an incentive to create high bedroom
counts, which can mean chopped-up apartments with poorly lighted
interior rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way to get family-sized units into Old Law
tenements,'' said Beth Cooper Lawrence, a Manhattan architect.
</P>
<P>
   Often tenants themselves want more bedrooms, however tiny they
are. That has been the experience of Robert Perl, president of
Tower Brokerage on East 10th Street, the owner-developer in 25
tenement renovations since 1985, mainly in the East Village and
Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   In three 1880s tenements at 213 to 217 East 10th St., for
example, he has upgraded half the 70 apartments over the last six
years as tenants have moved, totally gutting, reconfiguring and
re-equipping those that had had very long-term occupancy by the
prior tenant. Twenty long-occupied units still have old-fashioned
tubs in the kitchen for bathing, and tiny but ventilated rooms for
a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many arrivals are singles in their 20s and they want separate
bedrooms,'' Perl said. Typically, two singles with incomes of
$30,000 to $50,000 a year rent 450 square feet of modern space with
a full ``three-piece'' bathroom _ sink, toilet, and either a tub
with a shower or a shower stall _ paying from $1,100 to $1,400 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Many apartments are in dumbbell-style buildings, with two
apartments in front, two in the rear, with a center stairway, small
corridors and a narrow air shaft between buildings. Rehabilitation
upon vacancy may not produce an apartment reconfiguration, as it
usually does in vacant tenements when public financing is
available.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What would Jacob Riis say about these conditions, Perl was
asked. ``Jacob Riis would be thrilled,'' he said. He noted that
there are full bathrooms with sink, toilet and tubs or showers,
plus adequate light and air, and few young children to generate
overcrowding. ``We have modern apartments for students and young
professionals starting careers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the East Village renovator will look for much
higher rents. Perl spoke of a vacant rundown tenement at 510 East
11th St., which he renovated three years ago for $300,000, putting
in a pub on the ground floor and three floor-through apartments
upstairs. The apartments were rented at about $2,500 a month.
``They're worth about $3,000 now,'' Perl said.
</P>
<P>
   Builders often say that the cost of gut-renovating and
rebuilding an individual Old Law tenement is not justified by the
quality of the building and apartments that result.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases it would make more sense to build new efficient
multiple dwellings instead of renovating the old tenements,'' said
Jeffrey Levine, the principal in Levine Builders of Douglaston,
Queens. He spoke from the experience of having renovated many an
old tenement.
</P>
<P>
   At 350 West 14th St., on Ninth Avenue, Levine consolidated four
vacant tenements and added three floors above with duplex
apartments with terraces, creating 49 condominium apartments for
the developer Alan Friedberg in 1987. The apartments sold out in
six months at an average price of $175,000.
</P>
<P>
   Levine was also the builder in the gut renovation of three Old
Law tenements on West 116th Street just east of Frederick Douglass
Boulevard. They stand in the midst of similar but unrenovated
tenements of the same vintage, enhancing the value of the entire
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   This work was done with financing from the city's
participation-loan program, which has been one of the key financial
engines for tenement improvement work. Blended with private
market-rate financing, the public-private loan holds rents down.
</P>
<P>
   The city has financed or helped finance rehabilitations in 703
tenement buildings since 1994, the start of the Giuliani
administration, and the Department of Housing Preservation and
Development expects to fund 423 more over the next two years. In
prior administrations many more were financed, but the figures were
not available.
</P>
<P>
   Tenement renovations are under way without public assistance as
well, most recently gaining steam in East Harlem. The most active
company is R.E. Management, at Third Avenue and 99th Street, the
owner of 50 buildings with 1,200 apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Its ``crown jewel'' is the six-story walk-up at 244 East 117th
St., said Leonard Pikaard Jr., executive vice president. Only last
year a total renovation was completed, creating 41 apartments. Now
these small but well-equipped and well-lighted apartments provide
young one- and two-person households with modern apartments renting
for $800 to $1,100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The developer spent an average of $50,000 an apartment to put in
all new building systems, new windows, a new roof and doors, and
new apartment interiors. In addition, there is marble in the foyer,
ceramic-tile floors, a new marble stairway in the center and a new
intercom system.
</P>
<P>
   In consideration of the fact that the market principally
consists of young adults without children, the developer maintained
the high apartment count of the unrenovated tenement. Many
apartments have no more than 450 square feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to gear renovations to the Section 8 and welfare
market, which basically meant a mother with several children, so we
had a lot of bedrooms,'' Pikaard said. ``Now we're gearing
buildings to younger families, so we have fewer bedrooms and larger
rooms, but the same number of apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   On East 114th Street, between Pleasant and First avenues
opposite Jefferson Park, a typical tenement renovation approach is
under way. As two-bedroom railroad flats are vacated, they are
converted into large studios, renting for about $800 a month. Five
years ago, each railroad flat _ a floor-through with small rooms in
a straight row _ would have become one subsidized three-bedroom
apartment, Pikaard said.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the company's apartments have not been
renovated in over 50 years, Pikaard said. ``Some of them look as
though they've been trashed, but others have been well taken care
of, even though the equipment is antique,'' he said. Most of these
are rent-controlled units renting for $70 to $300 a month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One long-term low-rent tenant in a postage-stamp size apartment
is Frank Reginio, 79, who retired as a postal worker in 1974 and
has lived at 235 East 111th St., second floor rear, since 1944. His
mother-in-law had the twin apartment next door when he moved in,
and when she died in the 1960s he and his wife took it over. They
now pay $75 for each apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I raised two children here,'' Reginio said. ``We
used to have to make two coal fires every day in the stove for
heat, until they put steam in.'' He still has a tub in the kitchen
for bathing. His mother-in-law's apartment is for sleeping. ``I
wouldn't want to move,'' he said. ``I'm used to it here. I'm used
to the neighborhood. I feel safe in it. Where would I move to?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
