<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HEAT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNDERMANNED NETS STILL OVERCOME THE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With Jayson Williams, their leading
warrior, in the hospital with his broken right leg immobilized, the
Nets played with the desire and intensity that Williams so often
exhibited to defeat the Miami Heat, 88-77, Saturday at the
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, a huge upset that gave the Nets two straight
victories for the first time in this bizarre season, came one game
after Williams suffered his season-ending injury in a 90-85 victory
over the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (19-11) had demolished the Nets (7-24) in two previous
meetings this season, winning by a combined total of 49 points.
Alonzo Mourning, the brutish center who is playing as well as
anyone in the league, treated New Jersey as his own little punching
bag, totaling 49 points, 28 rebounds and 9 blocks in the two games.
</P>
<P>
   With Williams _ not to mention his backups Jim McIlvaine and
Rony Seikaly _ out with injuries, the sentiment going in was that
Mourning would have a heyday against the small, depleted Nets and
their inexperienced starter, Will Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning indeed had his way, recording 23 points, 17 rebounds
and seemingly blocking one out of every three Nets' shots in
swatting away nine. But the Nets overcame his dominance with
hustle, balance and ferocity, and attacked the basket to foul him
out with 3 minutes 53 seconds remaining and the Nets ahead by
77-69.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn led the Nets with 27 points, but shot only 6 for
24 from the floor. Though his touch was missing, Van Horn, who was
4 for 20 entering the fourth, scored six straight points to spark
an 11-2 run midway through the fourth that put the Nets up by 13
points with 6:27 left to play. Chris Carr's 3-pointer made it
74-61.
</P>
<P>
   Miami pulled within 80-74 on a 3-pointer by Terry Porter with
1:11 left to play, but Stephon Marbury scored on the Nets' next two
possessions on a driving layup and two free throws that sealed it.
Marbury, whose backup Elliot Perry played exceptionally well,
finished with 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   Though he scored only 15 points, Kendall Gill was the Nets' star
because of his defensive brilliance. Recording his first
triple-double as a Net, Gill grabbed 10 rebounds and made an
incredible 11 steals, which broke assistant coach Eddie Jordan's
franchise record of 10. His final rebound came on the last shot of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth straight loss for Pat Riley's Heat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A spirited second quarter by the Nets shocked nearly everyone at
Continental Arena, especially the Heat. Playing outstanding
defense, New Jersey outscored Miami by 28-14 in the quarter to turn
a 24-16 first-quarter deficit into a 44-38 halftime lead. The most
remarkable thing about the run was that much of it occurred with
Marbury, Van Horn and Kerry Kittles on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   A Nets' lineup of Gill, Elliot Perry, Mark Hendrickson, Jamie
Feick and Chris Carr outscored Miami by 11-4 over a 3 minute 41
second stretch to give the Nets a 30-28 lead midway through the
quarter. Gill, whose tremendous defense helped the Nets defeat the
Atlanta Hawks on Thursday, was key again, making five of the club's
six steals in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's hustle, combined with the team's excellent rotations,
enabled the Nets to limit Miami to just six field goal attempts
over the first seven and a half minutes of the quarter. With no
true center on the floor, Casey and his main assistants, Jim Lynam
and Eddie Jordan, had the Nets rotating and trapping in ways that
disrupted the Heat's attack. The Nets also used a half-court trap
that sped up the game and helped nullify Miami's size advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, streaking in the open court, carried much of the load
offensively as well, scoring six points. Carr, who hoisted nine
shots in the quarter, scored eight points, and Feick helped the
Nets outrebound Miami in the first half with four second-quarter
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury and Van Horn returned with 6 minutes 2 seconds left in
the half and, seemingly energized by the play of the reserves,
sparked the Nets to a 12-2 run that pushed the lead to 12 points,
42-30, on a 3-pointer by Marbury three minutes before the half. One
minute later, Casey reinserted Kittles, who had sat out the entire
quarter, for Gill.
</P>
<P>
   The move backfired, as the defensive intensity dropped
immediately, and Miami cut the lead to six by intermission. The
Heat, probably responding to a vigorous tongue-lashing by their
head coach, Pat Riley, opened the third quarter fiercely, pulling
within two points twice in the first four and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets had the answer in Marbury. Hitting a 16-footer, two
driving layups and a free throw, the fearless point guard helped
rebuild the Nets' lead to 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Gill continued to shine on both ends of the floor, especially
defensively, as New Jersey limited Miami to six made shots (two of
which came on goaltending calls against Van Horn ) in the quarter.
Confident and at their best, the Nets led by 61-52 heading into the
final period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
