<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOATING-FITNESS-NYT &LR;      04-03 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-FITNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROP ANCHOR, NO PROBLEM. BUT NOW TRY PULLING IT UP.  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: THE UNITED ARAB EMIRATES, Calif., R.I.)   By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Competitive sailors, buoyed by tactical skills
and time on the water, generally assume a take-it-or-leave-it
approach when it comes to physical fitness. As chewing gum is to a
baseball player, fitness training has been a personal thing for
sailors. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the U.S. Sailing Team has hired a roving
strength and conditioning coach. On a commercial level, one of the
top female sailors in the country recently produced an extensive
exercise videotape geared for boaters at sea or on the dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sailing is not more physical than it used to be,'' Jonathan
Harley, Olympic director for U.S. Sailing, the sport's governing
body, said last week. ``But everybody else is treating it as
such.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, sailing and powerboating are sports that can require
as little energy as tweaking a mainsail sheet or throwing a dock
line. But at the highest rung of the sport, fitness is taking off.
</P>
<P>
   Boaters often need abdominal and back muscles for such tasks as
pulling up an anchor, sheeting in a mainsail, or hiking out; arm
muscles for grinding on a winch or hauling an engine; and leg
muscles for lifting a spinnaker pole, or moving wet sails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sailing is like a big chess match,'' Harley said. ``It's a
fairly cerebral game. But at the Olympic level, sailors in foreign
countries with better funding than the United States are pouring
their money into people. We need to spend our own money
judiciously, but our people have got to get in better shape too.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality set in for the American team when it became apparent
that one-design classes such as the Finn, a boat once revered for
the brawny sailors it attracted, is now slimming down. A Finn
sailor a decade ago who weighed 210 pounds might well weigh 190
pounds today. Yet the 1990s sailor is likely to be stronger and
more agile.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting to the workout focus is Betsy Alison, a four-time
yachtswoman of the year from Newport, R.I. She is currently
competing with an all-female crew in the International Rolex Cup
Regatta in St. Thomas, V.I. But off the water, Alison has a new
business.
</P>
<P>
   She and a partner, Sandy Hayes, began marketing a two-part
videotape two months ago entitled ``Fitness Afloat.'' Hayes, a
nationally certified personal trainer from Scituate, Mass., also
sails competitively. The 60-minute exercise program works best on
board a boat or at the dock, but is adaptable for home, too.
</P>
<P>
   Workout tools include a towel, a coiled line and a 26-inch boat
fender. Instead of weights, they also suggest using winch handles,
or bottled water. Their exercise mat is a boat deck _ a 40-foot
Tartan sailboat was used for the video. But nearly any boat will do
as long as it is big enough to stretch out on. ``Sandy used the
workout program on a boat-delivery home from Bermuda, and I've done
it on a trawler in Seattle,'' Alison said.
</P>
<P>
   The series focuses on the needs of boaters, both competitive and
recreational. Over all, balance is key.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmation of that theory came last March at the International
Sailing Federation World Championships in Dubai, United Arab
Emirates. Alison's team won a gold medal in the women's
match-racing event, and a silver in fleet racing. She and two
teammates each were 38 years old; a fourth teammate was 28. The
all-female crew had worked out ahead of time in the fitness series
they helped develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in tired at the end of the day, but we never hurt even
though we sailed 38 races in 11 days,'' Alison said. ``A lot of the
other sailors were Olympic competitors, and we heard them complain
way more than I thought possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison's team did not do as well at the Congressional Cup
regatta last month in Long Beach, Calif. But it was not because of
poor fitness. The team was in 10th _ and last _ among a group of
mostly America's Cup-level men's teams. ``The guys had experience
over us,'' Alison said. ``But we were steadily improving all week,
and won a couple of starts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alison-Hayes videotape series ($39.99) is meant for men and
women, but its degree of difficulty depends on the person.
Information can be obtained by calling (877) FIT-AFLOAT. An
unrelated book on the subject, ``Sailing Fitness'' ($30.95 from
Fitness Books) by Dr. Michael Blackburn, can be ordered from the
Armchair Sailor Bookstore in Newport, R.I., (800-29-CHART). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
