<SLUG> BC-BBO-MLB-OPENER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New season begins in Mexico
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the San Diego Padres intend to make it back to the
World Series next fall, they'll have a long way to go. Like from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 baseball season commences tonight in Monterrey, Mexico,
where the Padres face Colorado at 8 o'clock. Last week Cuba, this
week the Mexican coast. Is this the big leagues, or a Caribbean
tour excursion?
</P>
<P>
   Monterrey is giddy in hosting the first season opener ever held
in its country. When a final batch of tickets went on sale
Thursday, a crowd of 1,000 had gathered by 2 a.m. The game site
becomes doubly significant to Rockies third baseman Vinny Castilla,
born in Oaxaca, Mexico, and one of the most prominent Mexican stars
in history.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't wait. I just can't wait,'' Castilla said. ''The people
in my country will give me so much support and appreciation. Now
they'll get to see me for the first time. Baseball has never had an
opening day in Mexico. We're talking about a very historic game.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also talking about the best Canadian-born player.
Rockies right fielder Larry Walker could open the season on the
disabled list after sustaining a strained rib cage muscle Tuesday
while taking batting practice. The Rockies were scrambling Saturday
for contingencies for replacing one of the game's most productive
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't have somebody, we've got a good enough team where
we can pick each other up,'' Rockies manager Jim Leyland said.
''Nobody wants to lose a player, especially a player of his
magnitude. But what the hell? That's part of the game. You can't
roll over.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly on opening day. The rest of the majors pick up the
schedule Monday with a full slate of games. The Braves open the
year with a three-game series with Philadelphia beginning Monday at
4:10 p.m. Tom Glavine, 20-6 last year when he won his second Cy
Young award, will face Phillies ace Curt Schilling (15-14), opening
a seven-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
