<SLUG> BC-LOTTO-ROLLOVER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery jackpot rolls over to $190 million
 &HT;    By Will Anderson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Big Game? Fat chance!
</P>
<P>
   Nobody won Friday's record $160 million Big Game jackpot,
meaning the money will be rolled over into the next drawing, to be
held at 11 p.m. Tuesday. The new jackpot will be worth an estimated
$190 million, said Georgia Lottery spokeswoman Parquita Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers drawn were 8-25-26-28-35 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   Although the odds are slim _ about 1 in 76 million _ of winning
the six-state lottery, people were snatching up tickets at a
frenzied pace just before the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Sellers, a clerk at a Chevron service station in Marietta,
had six customers waiting in line for tickets when sales ended at
10:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody don't win it Tuesday, they'll probably have to
hire all new cashiers for the store,'' said Sellers, 54. ``I have
worked every Tuesday and Friday night for the past month, and I am
dead tired when I get off work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although $190 million is a lot of money, the largest-ever
lottery jackpot was won by 13 factory workers in Columbus, Ohio,
last July. The winning Powerball ticket was worth $295.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
