NYT-04-03-99 1821EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0404-COX     04-03 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO FIGHTS TWO ENEMIES: SERBS AND HUMAN MISERY
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Clinton administration declaring that ``no
target is off-limits'' in Yugoslavia, NATO destroyed another bridge
across the Danube River Saturday. At the same time, the alliance
raced to stop a ``demographic earthquake'' in the Balkans as
hundreds of thousands of refugees flee into the countries bordering
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus on the alliance ... is very, very much on the
demographic earthquake that we are experiencing in and around
Kosovo,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said in Brussels. He spoke as
NATO prepared to use ground troops to help provide humanitarian
relief to the ethnic Albanians who have fled Kosovo since the
bombing of Yugoslavia began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   But as NATO turned its attention to the refugee problem, it also
continued its bombing campaign, now aimed at Yugoslavia's largest
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Serb television reported NATO destroyed a second Danube River
bridge, this one in Novi Sad, Yugoslavia's second largest city and
a major industrial center. The bridge was struck just hours after
allied missiles turned key government buildings in Belgrade, the
country's capital, into rubble.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the misery of refugees, Shea said NATO is
mobilizing ``all its available resources for this urgent
humanitarian requirement.'' He said allied ambassadors had asked
Gen. Wesley Clark of the United States, NATO's commander, for a
plan to deploy up to 8,000 troops to Albania as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 24 Marines from the 24th Marine Expeditionary Unit,
aboard ships now in the Adriatic, were dispatched Saturday to
Macedonia and Albania to help NATO assess the humanitarian needs
there.
</P>
<P>
   The ``demographic earthquake'' consists of an estimated 290,000
refugees who have left Kosovo in the last 10 days. More than
100,000 have arrived in Albania, where 6,000 NATO troops were
dispatched to help them. Another 65,000 refugees are trapped in
cold, muddy fields in Macedonia. There, where NATO peacekeeping
forces vacated their own barracks to provide shelter to some of the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this rate, if you do a mathematical calculation, Serb
forces will have emptied Kosovo of its entire population in 10 to
20 days,'' Shea said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With Kosovo's neighbors facing a humanitarian disaster, NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana suggested that an alliance-led
protection force could go into Kosovo to return ethnic Albanian
refugees ahead of any signing by Yugoslavia of a peace agreement.
But NATO officials emphasized that NATO ground forces are not
prepared to invade Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a C-17 left Dover Air Force Base, Del., with a first
shipment of food relief to the Balkans. Its cargo is 30,000
high-calorie packaged meals destined for Albania, via an air base
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will use private airlines to ferry additional
rations throughout the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is also airlifting 200 tents, 1,500 cots, 3,000
blankets, 8,000 sleeping bags and cargo-handling equipment such as
forklifts to help speed the dispersal of the relief.
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. European Command in Germany will begin shipping 80
U.S. military trucks and another 30 trucks purchased by the State
Department to Albania. The trucks will be used to move relief
supplies from ports and airports.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in his weekly radio address, urged Americans
to contact charities, churches and international relief
organizations to assist in the relief effort. ``We will remind the
victims of this conflict that for all they have lost they have not
been abandoned or forgotten,'' he said on the eve of the Christian
celebration of Easter.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has directed $91 million in humanitarian aid
to the region since last year. And last week, Clinton authorized
another $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the president was calling on Americans to ``open our
hearts and our arms'' to the refugees and to pray for the three
American soldiers being held prisoner in Yugoslavia, the spokesman
for his National Security Council was sending a chilling warning to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. That warning came one day
after cruise missiles destroyed a complex of government offices in
downtown Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is that no target is off-limits that is involved
in the repression of Kosovo, including downtown Belgrade,'' said
National Security Council spokesman David Leavy. ``As we move
forward in the days to come, we will continue to intensify the
strikes to make clear to Mr. Milosevic our determination to
significantly degrade his military capability,'' Leavy added.
</P>
<P>
   The message translated into new orders Saturday for the U.S.S.
Theodore Roosevelt, a nuclear aircraft carrier with 75 aircraft,
including 46 strike planes. The carrier, known as the ``Big
Stick,'' was ordered to the Adriatic Sea instead of the Persian
Gulf. The Roosevelt battle group includes four cruisers, destroyers
and frigates, a combat support ship and a submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also dispatched another 13 F-117A stealth
fighter-bombers from Holloman Air Force Base, N.M., to join NATO's
air campaign against Yugoslavia. Due to arrive Sunday, the
additional planes will bring to 24 the number of F-117s available
for missions. One crashed in Yugoslavia on March 27.
</P>
<P>
   In his address Saturday, Clinton once again reminded Americans
that the military mission in Kosovo is ``a difficult and dangerous
one,'' but contended that it is ``necessary and right.''
</P>
<P>
   But British Prime Minister Tony Blair delivered the sternest
message yet to Milosevic. In a television interview, Blair said,
``Your policy of ethnic cleansing is an act of barbarity. We will
defeat you.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
