</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4887 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-COX     04-03 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR REFUGEES, FROM ONE HELL INTO ANOTHER
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHKODER, Albania A white, windowless van stops outside a white
stucco Catholic church here causing a cloud of gray dust to billow
under its wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer church workers fling open the back door to show the
cargo. More than 20 refugees from Kosovo squint at the burst of
sunlight and begin to carefully unfold their arms and legs to step
down from the van.
</P>
<P>
   For seven hours, they have been jammed in the back of this
airless van, bouncing down a rough, winding mountain road from the
Kosovar border. They have been in the van since sunrise with
nothing to eat or drink. Most are women and children, with a few
gray-haired men. One tiny woman is in her 80s and must be helped
down and into a wheelchair. They appear dazed and exhausted as they
emerge, glancing indifferently at their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   This is their destination _ at least for a while _ after the
long exodus from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some have traveled five days from their homes inside Kosovo.
They tell the now familiar stories of being driven from their
houses by armed and masked Serbian paramilitaries. They reported
seeing bodies along the way and say that Serb forces beat refugees.
Many walked for more than 20 miles to reach the border, where they
were herded into the van and brought here.
</P>
<P>
   But they may have to move on soon. There is no room in Shkoder,
a desperately poor city already burdened by refugees who began
flooding in eight months ago as conditions in Kosovo worsened.
Despite the strain, they are welcome for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are our brothers and we will welcome them,'' said Bisera
Bisdan, a Shkoder woman who was selling secondhand clothes at a
sidewalk flea market. ``But we are very poor. We live hand to
mouth. What can we give them?''
</P>
<P>
   The city can handle about 2,000 refugees by placing them in
temporary dormitories and private homes, municipal officials say.
But as of Saturday, more than 3,000 refugees had registered in the
city and more than 2,000 more were en route to a place already
unable to cope with them.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions in Shkoder, one of the half dozen destinations
for the Kosovar refugees in Albania, couldn't be more desperate. It
is remote from the capital of Tirana, located about 50 miles to the
south, and has barely enough food stores to feed the refugees
without pushing the whole town into even deeper despair. There are
no jobs for the residents, much less the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Shkoder illustrates the refugee crisis across Albania. Without
immediate help, the refugees will deplete the already limited
resources of the city, eventually making the plight of residents
and refugees hard to distinguish.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimated that between 120,000 and 200,000 refugees
have come to Albania, Europe's poorest country. At the same time,
the pressure on Albania increased Saturday when neighboring
Macedonia said it would close its borders to refugees. Macedonia
called on its neighbors and the European Union to help shelter the
massive wave of ethnic Albanians. Many of the 50,000 waiting to
enter Macedonia are expected to head for Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Before the start of NATO bombing more than a week ago, there
were 26,000 refugees in Kosovo _ already considered the maximum
this very poor country could host.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is already a crisis,'' said Naim Zoto, the minister for
social affairs. ``The existing state structure will not be able to
cope with 200,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the country's bakeries have had their supplies
exhausted, and food merchants are raising prices to match growing
demands fueled by the crisis. Drinking water, urgently needed in
the explosion of makeshift refugee camps, is also in critically
short supply. Officials reported that six refugee children have
died from dehydration, while another seven adults have died from
various other causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can for a short time provide the basics _ a shelter to
sleep in and bread to eat,'' Zoto said. ``We're talking about the
very basic things a human being needs to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, officials express anxiety over what they consider a
very slow response by international aid agencies. Government
leaders worry that if aid efforts aren't accelerated immediately,
the death rate among the refugees will rise.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the road system in Albania is so poor that it will
be difficult to distribute supplies as they arrive, Zoto said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, traffic through Tirana has doubled with a sharp
increase in vans and heavy trucks carrying food and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   While Albanians have welcomed the refugees in their homes,
Albanian officials caution that they cannot long rely on individual
acts of generosity. In addition to the fact that most Albanian
families can barely support themselves, officials say that Kosovar
families _ they frequently number 30 or more _ often refuse to be
separated, thus making them difficult to place.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Albanians in the southern, more Mediterranean region of
the country have far less sympathy and will be less hospitable to
the refugees than those who live in the northern more mountainous
regions adjoining Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, the country's transition from a closed
communist society to an open free market has been arduous and
property ownership issues are often confusing. This makes it very
difficult for humanitarian agencies to acquire land for tent camps
or buildings to be converted into dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   This has forced the government to place refugees in public
places. Outside Tirana, more than 2,000 refugees live in a camp of
200 U.S. Army tents pitched around the drained swimming pools at
the city's aquatic center.
</P>
<P>
   In Shkoder, more than 600 refugees have been placed in the
city's Sports Palace, which is about the size of an average U.S.
high school gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   The decrepit old arena on Saturday was littered with food and
garbage. On the worn floor, teenage boys shot baskets with plastic
water bottles. Near nightfall, more than 2,000 more refugees were
expected to be crammed in the arena more than three times its
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   This prospect makes worries Titiana Littamel, an Italian who
teaches language at a university in Shkoder. Even before the
arrival of refugees, poverty-related crime has been so high in the
city that it has been dangerous for residents to venture out after
sunset. Gunfire fills the air each night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot even think what it will be like,'' Littamel said.
``In the morning, then what? The problem is Shkoder it is simply
too poor. It cannot bear this.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are somewhat better at the dormitories built by the
Caratis relief agency at the Church of the Holy Rosary. The
dormitories, created from an old warehouse adjoining the church,
house 700 people, about 20 to a room. It looks like a prison, with
dark corridors and damp concrete floors. There is one toilet,
shower and sink for every ten families. All the laundry is done in
the sink. About 350 have lived there for eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, this is war,'' said Miska Hushi, a mother of four.
``Things could be worse, but this is not our home. People want to
live in their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   When the van pulled up unexpectedly Saturday to dump 20 refugees
into the mission's care, the Franciscan monks who work there
scrambled to provide them food and water. The refugees were hustled
into the canteen and given beans, goat cheese and bottled water.
They ate and drank lustily. On one wall of the cinderblock dining
hall is written the phrase in Albanian: ``Kosovo is martyred.''
There also are pictures drawn by the children at the shelter; one
depicted the houses in her village with smoke rising from their
roofs.
</P>
<P>
   For Helena Palushaj, 17, of the Kosovo town of Kramovik, Sunday
was to be the most special day, her wedding day. Instead, she
arrived in the van here Saturday, her fiance missing.
</P>
<P>
   Helena and her father, Frrok (CQ), had been traveling for days,
often on foot after leaving their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My girl was to be married,'' said her father. ``Instead we are
here,'' he said, eating a piece of bread. ``It was to be the best
moment of our life. Now it is the worst. How can this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton is the London-based European correspondent for
Cox Newspapers. His e-mail is: Bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
