<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/03/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 3, 1999 -- NY-WOMEN'S-HOTEL-2, 04-03
-- The former Allerton Hotel for Women in Manhattan has been
undergoing renovation for years. Some tenants say the construction
is meant to drive them out. The Allerton is a faded grande dame of
single room occupancy at East 57th Street and Lexington Avenue that
its owners hope to convert into a luxury hotel. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 3, 1999 -- NY-WOMEN'S-HOTEL-1, 04-03 --
Suzanne Remy, who once created hats for Greta Garbo and Marlene
Dietrich, is one of the last residents of the Allerton Hotel for
Women in Manhattan. Ms. Remy, whose tenancy is protected by law,
has stayed put despite a campaign of harassment to get her and the
other tenants to leave. The Allerton is a faded grande dame of
single room occupancy at East 57th Street and Lexington Avenue that
its owners hope to convert into a luxury hotel. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- April 3, 1999 -- BBO-SEASON-ONETIMERS-3, 04-03
-- Joe Cleary in his brief stint as a pitcher for the Washington
Senators in 1945. More than 50 years after the ball was hit, Joe
Cleary, now 80, can still recall his brief career as a pro pitcher
for the Washington Senators in 1945. In that game, the Boston Red
Sox scored 12 runs, leaving him with an earned run average of
189.00 -- still the highest calculable ERA in the history of
baseball. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 3, 1999 -- BBO-SEASON-ONETIMERS-2,
04-03 -- More than 50 years after the ball was hit, Joe Cleary, 80,
can still recall his brief career as a pro pitcher for the
Washington Senators in 1945. In that game, the Boston Red Sox
scored 12 runs, leaving him with an earned run average of 189.00 --
still the highest calculable ERA in the history of baseball. When
he returned to the dugout, he and his manager nearly came to blows.
``It was like he'd just found me in bed with his wife,'' says
Cleary. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- April 3, 1999 -- BBO-SEASON-ONETIMERS-1,
04-03 -- Fred Van Dusen, one of a countless number of ballplayers
who have come up to the major leagues for a single game, often at
the end of blowouts or in the waning days of a losing season. Van
Dusen got hit by a pitch in his one appearance for the Philadelphia
Phillies in 1955. He never batted again. ``Well, they didn't get me
out,'' says Van Dusen, an insurance broker in the Bronx. (Joseph
Kugielsky/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) TAMPA, Fla. -- April 3, 1999 -- BBA-SEASON-JETER, 04-03
-- Derek Jeter, the foundation of two New York Yankees
championships in his first three years in the majors, is set to
begin his fourth year as the Yankees' everyday shortstop. A scout
who saw Jeter play baseball in the summer of 1991 in Kalamazoo,
Mich., Jeter's hometown, predicted that he would become the
foundation of a winning club. (Jon Adams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HAVANA -- April 3, 1999 -- CUBA-CRIME, 04-03 -- A police
officer watches from a roof and Cubans from their balconies as a
Good Friday procession moves through Old Havana. Cuba, once immune
to high crime rates, is now grappling with a crime wave. The rise
is taking place as Cubans struggle with hardships caused by the
collapse of their Soviet patron 10 years ago, Communist Party
policies and more than three decades of economic embargo by the
United States. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- April 3, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MCCAIN, 04-03 --
Sen. John McCain, 62, R-Ariz., checking some notes before a recent
television interview on the crisis in Kosovo. McCain, spent more
than five years as a prisoner of war in Vietnam and learned, he
says, the dangers of limited measures. He is now a forceful
advocate of all-out intervention in the Balkans. ``In Pyongyang and
Baghdad and Tripoli, they are paying close attention to this
situation,'' he says. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PHILADELPHIA -- April 3, 1999 -- LUXURY-LINER, 04-03 --
Robert Hudson Westover is leading an effort to preserve the liner
United States, which is 17 stories high, weighs 59,000 tons and is
990 feet long. The ship, which made its first voyage in 1952, made
its last in 1969. To raise money for the ship, Westover and an avid
band of preservationists has formed the SS United States Foundation
and a Web site. ``This ship is just too beautiful and too important
to let slip through our fingers,'' says Westover. (Timothy M.
Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LARAMIE, Wyo. -- April 3, 1999 -- WYO-MURDER-AFTERMATH,
04-03 -- The Rev. Stephen M. Johnson, a Unitarian minister, plans
to hold an Easter service near the cross of stones marking the spot
where Matthew Shepard, a gay 21-year-old college student, was found
near death last October in Laramie, Wyo. ``I have seen people come
out here with a pocketknife and take a piece of the fence, like a
relic, like an icon. To have a piece of the experience here is
powerful to people,'' says Johnson. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
