<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PROTEST-MARCH-NYT &LR;      04-03 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROTEST-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP PLANS $1-MILLION MARCH TO PROTEST POLICE MISCONDUCT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A group of politicians, business executives,
religious leaders and community groups who banded together in
response to the shooting death of Amadou Diallo have turned their
energy to organizing a large demonstration aimed at illustrating
the breadth of emotion about police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they have already raised about half the $1
million needed for the April 15 march from the federal court in
downtown Brooklyn to federal offices in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The wide coalition immersed in the planning includes labor
groups, Jewish organizations, gay civil rights advocates, state
legislators and veterans of the Rev. Al Sharpton's many protest
marches.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the event has taken the form of a high-voltage
political campaign. About a dozen strategists, including staff
members lent by elected officials and the city's largest labor
unions, have been working round the clock in an office on the
seventh floor of the headquarters of Local 1199, the National
Health and Human Service Employees Union on West 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a prominent role is Sharpton, who has served as the
adviser to the family of Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant
who was struck down in a barrage of police gunfire in February in
the doorway of his Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rivera, the president of 1199, has also played a major
role. And a group of business executives, led by Ed Lewis, the
publisher of Essence magazine, has raised money from other business
leaders to assist in advertising and promoting the march. Rivera
said the coalition has raised $470,000 so far.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of the march are the same elected officials,
clergy and representatives of various community organizations who
met last week and listed 10 points to create ``a safer and more
just New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Those demands would involve, in some measure, changes in police
policies and the enactment of new state laws. They include hiring
of more black and Hispanic police officers, creating a permanent
special prosecutor for police brutality and corruption in New York,
strengthening the Civilian Complaint Review Board and ending the
use of hollow-point bullets. The organizers also want the Justice
Department to release annual reports documenting police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the legislators who have participated in the
coalition meetings acknowledged the difficulty in getting many of
their suggestions converted into law.
</P>
<P>
   In the State Assembly, for example, many members have already
introduced a proposed residency requirement for New York City
police officers and a bill that would bar what is known as the
48-hour rule from future contracts with the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The rule gives police officers two business days to consult with
union lawyers before they speak to investigators. It was not
invoked in the Diallo case because it applies only when the
department pursues administrative charges.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the bills have been introduced by Democrats, who
have failed to find sponsors in the Republican-controlled Senate.
``We know that some of it will not be easy to get passed,'' said
Assemblyman Keith L.T. Wright, a Harlem Democrat who is chairman of
the Black, Puerto Rican and Hispanic Caucus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
