<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-IMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS WILL SEE DUELING IMAGES OF JOHN A. GOTTI DURING TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A soft-spoken, selfless, self-made businessman who
lavishly supports charities for abused and abandoned children.
</P>
<P>
   An arrogant, brawling, greedy mobster who relishes the illicit
wealth that flows to him as the leader of one of the nation's most
powerful Mafia groups.
</P>
<P>
   These are the Januslike descriptions of John A. Gotti that will
begin unfolding on Tuesday when jury selection begins at his trial
in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti is accused of being the acting boss of the Gambino crime
family and of leading a criminal enterprise that reaped more than
$20 million from Mafia rackets in the New York City region from the
mid-1980s to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The battle looms as one of the most significant mob trials of
the decade. Mafia experts say Gotti's conviction would almost
certainly destroy the Gotti faction's domination of the family and
would probably eliminate the Gambino family as one of the major
powers in America's Mafia. Gotti's father, John J. Gotti, 58, is
serving a life sentence for murder and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   For federal prosecutors, the case appears to have weakened since
the younger Gotti was indicted with 22 other defendants in January
1998. An acquittal of Gotti, the main target of a complex
three-year federal-state investigation, would stall the
government's campaign to dismantle the Gambino family.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, who insists he has no links to organized crime, has
rejected government deals for a prison sentence of about six years
in exchange for a guilty plea to reduced charges. By risking a
trial, Gotti, 35, may face 20 years in prison if convicted of
violating the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act, known as RICO.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials say that Gotti has strived to remake
his public image in recent years, realizing that he was under
investigation and that he would eventually face racketeering
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation, the officials add, began before his
indictment and included frequent appearances at parent-teacher
meetings and visits in which he delivered cookies for parties at
his children's schools. Gotti also spent more evenings at his
14-room, $700,000 home in Mill Neck, Nassau County, with his wife,
Kim, and four children instead of maintaining his previous schedule
of late nights in bars and dance clubs, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti has also become a generous contributor to hospitals that
help abused children and to Hale House, which cares for infants
exposed to illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti has altered his appearance as well. A stocky man, 5 feet 9
inches tall, who keeps in shape by weight lifting, he now dresses
conservatively in suit jackets with a tie or stylish turtleneck
shirts instead of in his customary attire of a track suit or jeans,
a windbreaker and a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, in a request that stunned defense lawyers and
prosecutors, Gotti, who has been under house arrest since October,
asked a judge to revoke his $10 million bail and agreed to be
jailed for the duration of his trial, which is expected to last
about two months. His lawyers had indicated that he was
impoverished and unable to pay $24,000 a month for the guards who
monitor his movements. But some federal and state investigators
said the request might be a ploy to gain sympathy and to refute
government contentions that he grew rich from crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like his father, he is very publicity conscious,'' said Bruce
Mouw, a former agent with the FBI who led the bureau's Gambino
squad until his retirement last year. ``He and his father have
their own spin machines, but he really has not changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
