<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCEALED-FIREARMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSITION B LANGUAGE RESULTED FROM POLITICAL, LEGAL COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ When Missourians go to the polls Tuesday,
they will have to look closely to find the hottest issue on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B, which would allow residents to carry concealed
firearms, is buried within an arcane legal description that talks
about sheriffs and the St. Louis County police chief and the
satisfaction of ``various statutory requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   How a straightforward attempt to legalize concealed firearms
became a brainteaser on the ballot is a lesson in political
compromise and legal wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Rebecca Cook adopted the ballot language last
January after a lawsuit required the state to throw out language
stipulated by the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The result was something of a patchwork proposal suggested by
the sponsors of the referendum _ Rep. Wayne Crump of Potosi and
Sen. Harold Caskey of Butler _ and House Speaker Steve Gaw, Senate
leader Ed Quick of Liberty and Alex Bartlett, an attorney for gun
opponents who sued to block the lawmakers' version.
</P>
<P>
   The original language, crafted by the bill's supporters,
contained more than 50 words, which is prohibited by law. But it
also contained loaded phrases to make the referendum more palatable
to voters who might feel uneasy about their neighbors toting
concealed firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature's language talked about ``law-abiding citizens''
carrying firearms ``for personal protection,'' when the proposal
would allow people guilty of serious misdemeanors to get permits to
carry firearms for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Mills, a former state Highway Patrol superintendent who
opposes concealed firearms, sued to block the language from
appearing on the Tuesday ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Cole County Circuit Court ruled that state law requires the
secretary of state, not the legislature, to draft an impartial
ballot description.
</P>
<P>
   So Cook began taking suggestions on ballot phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the parameters of the law, the secretary wanted to
reach a consensus,'' said June Doughty, Cook's general counsel.
``The goal was to find language that would avoid litigation or at
least withstand a legal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 14, Crump sent Cook a memo suggesting a 48-word
description that talked about law-abiding citizens getting gun
permits after passing a criminal background check and completing a
firearms training course.
</P>
<P>
   Other legislative leaders submitted oral recommendations,
Doughty said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Doughty asked for feedback on three versions. One
was Crump's version. The second asked whether Missouri should no
longer consider it a felony to carry a concealed firearm unless the
carrier lacks a permit.
</P>
<P>
   The third asked whether sheriffs should issue permits to carry
concealed firearms up to 16 inches long and let permit-holders
carry the firearms anywhere but church, school or government
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Crump sent a memo back objecting to the second and third
proposals. At a meeting Jan. 21, Cook suggested the following
wording: ``Shall sheriffs be required to issue permits to carry
concealed firearms to citizens who satisfy various statutory
requirements?''
</P>
<P>
   A later memo suggests controversy about ``sheriffs'' as opposed
to ``law enforcement'' and about ``citizens'' as opposed to
``persons.'' Questions were raised about ``be required.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, the attorney for Mills, later questioned how the bill
would apply to St. Louis County, where the bill would give the
police chief, not the sheriff, the authority to issue permits.
</P>
<P>
   Cook finally settled on this: ``Shall sheriffs, or in the case
of St. Louis County, the chief of police, be required to issue
permits to carry concealed firearms to citizens who apply if
various statutory requirements are satisfied?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point,'' Doughty said, ``was to get an accurate
summary in the form of a question that people would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that was accomplished is debatable. But the wording did
satisfy the courts, which tossed out a legal challenge from gun
supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
