<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRARY TO ECONOMIC REPORT, THINGS ARE BETTER NOW THAN IN THE
'70S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The wet-blanket brigade's stock in trade is
socioeconomic observations that are not only implausible but also
pointless.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a class-warfare outfit calling itself United for a
Fair Economy issued a report trying to make the case that Americans
are worse off today than in the early '70s. If anybody thinks that,
they either weren't around back then or suffer from amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   One assertion in this regard is that U.S. workers earn less in
inflation-adjusted terms than they did a generation ago. Another
claim is that only the rich are benefiting from the stock market
boom because wealth is becoming more concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how one wants to slice and dice economic data,
there are probably statistics to support these views. Those with an
ax to grind always find a way to massage numbers of choice to make
any point they wish. However, those who insist on using data
selectively to substantiate improbable claims are like the drunk
who finds a lamppost more useful for support than for illumination.
</P>
<P>
   As Benjamin Disraeli once noted, there are ``lies, damned lies
and statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, any human with powers of reasoning and observation
can't help but conclude that most Americans are materially better
off now than they were a quarter of a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   A recently published book entitled Myths of the Rich and Poor is
said to do a good job of making that point. Its thesis is that the
true economic state of the human condition is better assessed by
observing consumption patterns than wealth and income statistics.
</P>
<P>
   This makes sense, because personal consumption fuels two-thirds
of economic growth. The U.S. economy has been expanding almost
nonstop since the early '80s. It's not just the richies spending
the money driving this boom. Consumer behavior reflects broad-based
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, what's the point of the exercise? Is the implied goal
to achieve passage of laws ensuring a ``fair share'' of economic
output for everyone?
</P>
<P>
   The most impoverished societies in human history have resulted
from proletariat uprisings seeking equal distribution of economic
resources. Russia comes immediately to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Such exercises become even more pointless when viewed in the
context of alternatives. Even Sweden, a model of enlightened
socialism, has been forced to acknowledge the limits of trying to
create economic equality.
</P>
<P>
   If working-class Americans think they should be doing better,
where do they go to improve their lot? Despite its imperfections,
America is the last best hope for individuals seeking to fulfill
their economic, political and spiritual potential. The reason is
simple. It's called personal liberty.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a market economy operating in the context of a
reasonably liberal political system makes unequal distribution of
resources inevitable. The freedom of movement ensures that those
with more money, superior smarts or better connections will fare
better than those without.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't imply, however, that the relatively disadvantaged
in this regard can't make a good life for themselves. They can,
because the freedom that works for the better off works for them,
too.
</P>
<P>
   So let's quit bellyaching and get back to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-99 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
