<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-RELIEF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RELIEF ORGANIZATION HELPING BALKAN REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ The flier begins with this direct plea:
``Urgent S.O.S. _ Kosovo in need.''
</P>
<P>
   In January _ well before NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia and
the forced exodus of ethnic Albanians from their native Kosovo _ a
nonprofit Kansas City, Kan., organization mailed that flier to its
1,000 members in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   North American Croatian Relief Inc. was looking for food,
clothing, bottled water, toiletries _ anything that might help the
refugees who had left or soon would be fleeing their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Now packed inside the former St. Mary's Catholic
Church are thousands of boxes. Most of them bear hastily scrawled
labels, in Croatian and English, indicating the contents: clothes
for men, women and children; bedding; nonperishable food.
</P>
<P>
   These days one usually can find volunteers packing and labeling
the boxes inside the church's dimly lighted and pewless sanctuary.
Every day the pile grows, now measuring some 60 by 30 feet. The
boxes spill onto the altar and, in places, reach as high as 9 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In two to three weeks, if all goes well, as many as four semis
will pick up the boxes for the first leg of the long journey to
Albania, one of Europe's poorest countries. More than 100,000
Kosovar refugees have entered the country, creating what the United
Nations calls a ``major humanitarian emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the boxes must wait until Croatian Relief
raises $20,000 to $30,000 to cover shipping costs. So far, the
organization has collected about $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started this drive, we had no idea it would come to
this point,'' said Bob Soptic, president of North American Croatian
Relief.
</P>
<P>
   Soptic, high school counselor of Croatian descent, was referring
not only to the unfathomable generosity spread before him but also
to the equally unfathomable number of ethnic Albanians forced to
flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Soptic, of Roeland Park, Kan., said Croatian Relief held five
fund-raisers each year and two drives to collect goods to assist
refugees in the Balkan region. The push to help Kosovar refugees is
taking place during what would normally be this year's first drive.
</P>
<P>
   From February into early March, the donations came in at a
steady pace. Then, as speculation increased that a NATO attack
could lead to more refugees, the pace of donations picked up. Now,
St. Mary's sanctuary is nearly full.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other area organization, Heart to Heart
International of Olathe, has been soliciting help for Kosovar
refugees. But Croatian Relief is unique because its sole mission is
to provide ongoing assistance to people displaced by the conflicts
in the Balkans, regardless of their national or ethnic identity.
</P>
<P>
   The organization was founded in the early 1990s by members and
associates of St. John the Baptist Catholic Church. It is about a
block from St. Mary's; both sit atop Strawberry Hill, a Croatian
neighborhood in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Many Croatian Relief members are first- and second-generation
Croatians whose ancestors built the church at the turn of the
century. When they began hearing reports of displaced Croats in
letters from distraught Croatian relatives, they were moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something had to be done,'' said Soptic, who grew up in St.
John the Baptist parish but now is a member of another Catholic
church. ``We had to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the organization focused only on Balkan children.
Then in 1993, the parish sent its new pastor, the Rev. Frank
Horvat, to Croatia to see how the church could help. What Horvat
saw astonished him: Entire towns and cities destroyed. Cemeteries
plowed over. Babies and elderly people in orphanages and refugee
camps.
</P>
<P>
   After Horvat's visit, the organization's members decided to
provide relief to refugees of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Croatian Relief has members from 17 states, including
Missouri. Soptic estimates that over the years the organization has
sent more than 900,000 pounds of commodities to the Balkans, trying
to ship goods to where the need is most urgent.
</P>
<P>
   To help assess that need, the organization relies on Boris
Stancic, who emigrated from Yugoslavia to the United States in
1969. Stancic, a board vice president, keeps in touch with the
Croatian Red Cross, Croatian Catholic Charities and Croatian
bishops, priests and nuns. He has made four trips to Croatia since
1992 and has witnessed the same scenes of desperation that Horvat
saw.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Horvat, Stancic, of Kansas City, Mo., is able to draw
from personal experience to make sense of what he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, at the age of 17, Stancic experienced life without home
and country himself. Dissatisfied with his life under Yugoslavia's
then-Communist regime, he fled to Italy, where he and several
hundred other Hungarians and Yugoslavs lived in a former Nazi work
camp. Three months after Stancic arrived, the Italian government,
giving no reason, sent Stancic and several others back to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Stancic was jailed after Yugoslav forces caught
him and two companions trying to cross the Italian border. A decade
later, Yugoslavia relaxed its borders, and Stancic and his family
came to Kansas City, Kan., where his brother had been living for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal,'' Stancic said of his struggle to find a
permanent home. ``If you move to another country, you have to look
for a roof above your head, and love.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, inside St. Mary's sanctuary, Stancic motioned to the
thousands of boxes before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That right here,'' he said in his thick Croatian accent, ``is
love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
