<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PURGE-COX     04-03 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PURGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE DEATH OF PEC: HOW THE SERBS BESIEGED AND EMPTIED A KOSOVAR
CITY
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROZAJE, Montenegro, Yugoslavia First came the uneasy delight at
the news that NATO warplanes were striking their enemy, the Serbs.
Hours later came the terror of growling tanks through their streets
and gunfire echoing from house to house.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was the sorrowful mass exodus as thousands of
ethnic Albanians from the Kosovo city of Pec an hour drive from
this border hamlet were ordered out of their homes and out of their
country by hundreds of well-armed Serb security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Families were separated. Young men disappeared and were presumed
to be executed. Lifelong memories and treasured possessions were
left behind as the people of Pec were made refugees.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Sunday, a caravan of cars, buses and trucks, scores
of them with police behind the wheels, carried the refugees north
toward the border with Montenegro. Behind them, parts of their city
were smoldering and in ruins at the hands of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the five days that followed the start on March 24 of U.S.-led
air strikes against Yugoslavia, Serb security forces had expelled
or executed most of Albanian population of Pec (pronounced Pesch),
refugees said. By the middle of last week, NATO satellite and spy
plane imagery confirmed that the city and surrounding villages of
180,000 were virtually deserted and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo have streamed through
the border town of Rozaje, in the neighboring republic of
Montenegro. In interviews, two dozen refugees offered accounts _
all impossible to independently verify _ of the dismantling of Pec.
</P>
<P>
   Some blamed the Yugoslav army and Serb police. Others spoke of
paramilitary troops and thugs in ski masks and black gloves.
</P>
<P>
   All agree that only hours after the NATO attacks began March 24,
Serb forces backed by army tanks and armored vehicles began a
systematic sweep of the city to expel the ethnic Albanians and
destroy their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some men were arrested and are now presumed dead. Many families
were robbed of their money and valuables.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians were forced from their homes and eventually
across the border to Montenegro, Albania or Macedonia, part of an
estimated 300,000 Kosovars that have fled bloodshed and anarchy
inside their own borders since NATO air strikes began.
</P>
<P>
   For Enver Kelmenoj, 26, an apprentice electrician, the fear
began even before U.S. and NATO warplanes left their bases. He was
awake at 11:30 on the Tuesday night before the air campaign began,
listening to a Voice of America radio report that NATO strikes on
Serb targets were imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Like most ethnic Albanians in the besieged Kosovo province, we
was elated that NATO was soon to be in action. ``But we knew what
that meant. We knew we would have to go,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The following night, March 24, Lumtunje Arifaj, needed no radio
to tell her the air strikes had begun. The 23-year-old lived in a
house in Pec near the Yugoslav Army barracks. She heard the tanks
and armored cars rumble to a start and pull out of the gate late
that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bah-boom, all night this was the music,'' she recalled. ``We
are near the military barracks and we heard the tanks going out and
some voices in Serbian saying, 'Faster, faster, speed up,' telling
each other to hurry. They were firing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the city, Kelmenoj listened at the window
from his darkened bedroom. ``We could hear the soldiers firing
their guns and singing their army songs, like they were
celebrating,'' he recalled. ``I heard a burst of automatic fire and
then them singing, 'Kosovo is Ours.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Serb offensive intensified and most ethnic
Albanians were huddled in their homes, listening to increasingly
frequent explosions and gunfire resounding outside. Those with
cellars hid there. Electricity was cut and the phones went dead.
</P>
<P>
   Columns of thick, black smoke rose over the city as houses
blazed. People saw soldiers firing into structures and buildings
crumbling as tank rounds slammed into them.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Serb forces had been running raids in the villages
surrounding Pec, trying to root out the Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA) and halt their hit-and-run guerrilla war. Many residents of
Pec had believed they were off limits, that the war would not reach
the commercial center of western Kosovo, which had a small Serb
minority.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, those illusions had disappeared for Isa Ramea, 49, a
metal worker. His cellar was occupied with his wife and three
daughters and five other families, ``35 people in all,'' cowering
in the bowels of his house near an historic monastery in the
western outskirts of Pec. Earlier he had seen some blocks of houses
flattened by tanks or artillery. Three tanks and about
</P>
<P>
   50 troops moved down his street. ``This part of the city was
surrounded by paramilitary and police. We couldn't move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They lived on bread and cucumbers and shared two candles between
them for light. They could hear footsteps above as police searched
the house and took belongings. Eventually, their candles and their
luck ran out. The security forces discovered them and forced them
to began the march to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Deme Kosova, 65, considers himself a Yugoslavian first, a
Kosovar Albanian second. When U.S.-brokered peace talks failed to
reach a settlement on Kosovo, his wife told him they should leave.
When NATO air attacks began, she told him again. He told her time
and again that Pec was their home and they would be safe. But after
watching his city smolder for several days, he
</P>
<P>
   finally began to take notice when Serbian neighbors in his
apartment block, worried about his safety, suggested that it was
time for him to go. The following day, Sunday, they would leave in
what would be an organized expulsion of thousands from Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbs and Albanians, we all got along together when I was a
child ... The tragic loss is that I lost my trust. I lost my
illusions that in the end there would be unity as Yugoslavians,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, March 28, was departure day for thousands from Pec. The
security forces assembled scores of buses, trucks and cars along
the broad promenade in the city center and herded much of the
population there.
</P>
<P>
   From his apartment building, Kosova did not wait for the police
to come to him. At 11 a.m., he could see from his apartment the
exodus: ``I told my wife that we cannot wait for the police to come
because if we wait for them to come they may kill us here. So we
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, 14-year-old Drilon Zeka and his little brother,
Qendrim, 9, ran into the woods near their house after their uncle
told them Serb troops were heading down the street. They found a
shed in which to hide. Hearing rumors of previous Serb atrocities,
Drilon feared the troops would kill his little brother. With the
help of a couple of young men also in the shed, they
</P>
<P>
   wedged the little boy between two piles of wood. They didn't
remain concealed for long. Serbian police found them and arrested
the two men. Drilon and his brother were herded along with others
to the center of town and the forced evacuation to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day Sunday, most of the city was on the move,
some on foot but most driven to the border of Montenegro, where
they made their way to the grimy truck-stop town of Rozaje, on a
mountain pass near Pec.
</P>
<P>
   Undiscovered, Zoje Kastrati, 31, her husband Mehmat, a farm
hand, and their two young sons, remained in their home in Pec,
apparently in one of the last neighborhoods to be reached in the
terrifying sweep. Since the NATO air strikes began, they took in
five other families, covered the windows with heavy blankets and
attempted to remain as quiet as possible for the next five
</P>
<P>
   days in hopes that their house would not be entered. Ironically,
their four-story home was near the city center where most of the
population was being herded the day before.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, armed men, some uniformed and others in civilian
clothing, entered the house and demanded that the family leave.
They claimed to be part of a militia and they dragged Mehmat down
the stairs, claiming he was with the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that I would never see him again because they would
kill him or take him away forever,'' his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   After a check of his documents, they released him, but demanded
money and jewelry. The family said they gave the forces about
$1,700 and jewelry in return for a promise that they and their
family and friends could remain in the house for another three
days.
</P>
<P>
   The promise lasted only until Wednesday, when they were forced
out by security forces. They walked over the border on foot.
</P>
<P>
   She had given up the family's fortune in vain, hoping to buy
three more days in Pec. Perhaps the siege would end. Perhaps NATO's
air war would prevail. Perhaps peace talks would resume. Kastrati
said: ``We hoped something would happen that would allow us to stay
forever there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Holmes is the Moscow correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
