<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-FIREARMS-2TA     04-03 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-FIREARMS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI BANNED CONCEALED WEAPONS IN 1800S TO APPEAR MORE
CIVILIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For years Jesse James and his gang terrorized
Missouri, firing their guns without remorse as they robbed banks,
trains and homes.
</P>
<P>
   They were fired upon, too, as Union soldiers, vigilantes, lawmen
and ordinary citizens in pursuit turned to their guns for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Pinkerton agents bombed James' farmhouse in Clay
County in 1875, killing the outlaw's half brother and maiming his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri lawmakers, convinced that this escalation of violence
was hurting the state's image, outlawed concealed weapons several
months later.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Missouri voters will decide whether to make
concealed firearms legal again. If Proposition B passes, Missouri
will join 43 states that allow some form of concealed firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Few states, however, match the heritage of conflict and violence
in Missouri, home of James and site of the Union Station Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's 1875 concealed-weapons measure was born, in part, out
of the embarrassment of Democratic state officials. The state's
inability to stop James and his colleagues from preying on rail
traffic was providing campaign fodder for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The concealed-weapons provision, part of a new constitution
pounded out over 74 days in 1875, was an effort to persuade those
outside Missouri of the state's regard for law, said Dick Steward,
social sciences professor at Lincoln University in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that would attract new settlers and new investments
was seen as a positive step,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the law also was designed to keep weapons out of the hands
of people that some legislators deemed untrustworthy, such as freed
slaves, said Tom Carroll, associate professor of sociology and
criminology at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Missouri having been a slaveholding state, with a large
number of freed ex-slaves, there were considerable fears that the
weapons might be used for what the legislators considered nefarious
purposes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the earliest days of the Missouri territory, the problem was
not too many guns but too few.
</P>
<P>
   A 1792 federal law mandated that, in all states and territories,
male residents ages 18 to 45 maintain a personal military
preparedness. That included reporting to occasional militia musters
for drilling.
</P>
<P>
   It also included owning a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Missouri's men felt that an intrusion. Some even mocked
the law, showing up for musters with rakes, poles and cornstalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Average, ordinary working men just didn't like to be bothered
with state or federal regulations,'' said Mary Ellen Rowe,
associate professor of history at Central Missouri State University
in Warrensburg.
</P>
<P>
   One reason was the expense. ``If you are talking about a day
laborer in St. Louis, you are talking about six months' wages just
to provide yourself with a halfway decent musket, plus powder and
lead,'' Rowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes prevailed even in wartime. In the War of 1812 the
Missouri territorial governor complained that only about a quarter
of Missouri militia members were battle-ready. That was despite a
decision in 1807 by the federal government to dole out old Army
surplus weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years before statehood in 1821, though,
territorial authorities near St. Louis began confiscating weapons
that possibly had been stolen from federal arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1836 the city of St. Louis passed an ordinance against
concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom was that getting concealed weapons out
of the hands of ordinary citizens was a step toward demonstrating
Missouri's more civilized nature,'' Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   This was necessary, in part, because of Missouri's taste for
dueling in the decades before the Civil War. Among states west of
the Mississippi River, only Louisiana has served as the site of
more duels, said Steward.
</P>
<P>
   A sandbar in the Mississippi River came to be called Bloody
Island, after about 40 duels were staged there in full view of St.
Louis spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would line up on the shore and watch,'' Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   Dueling was especially popular in St. Louis, where many doctors,
lawyers and professionals had brought with them their fascination
with the dueling code upon migrating from the South, Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City gun owners, meanwhile, were not nearly so civilized.
The brutal guerrilla warfare that raged before and during the Civil
War was so pitiless that ``even hardened prostitutes stayed away''
from this area, writes Kansas City historian Lawrence Larsen in an
upcoming encyclopedia on violence in America.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of the Civil War ushered in the outlaw era.
</P>
<P>
   Just one month after the war ended, ``Wild'' Bill Hickok gunned
down an outlaw next to the courthouse steps in Springfield. The
next year, in 1866, a bold gang of bandits thought to have included
Jesse James stunned residents of Liberty by robbing a bank in
daylight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1875 lawmakers hoping to curb violence in the state made
concealed weapons illegal. But those hoping for a more civilized
20th century in Missouri would be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City streets under the management of the Thomas
Pendergast machine, which flourished in the late 1920s and
throughout the 1930s, often proved just as dangerous as during the
city's frontier days.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Mayerberg, a Kansas City religious leader who spoke out
against the machine, survived an assassination attempt in the early
1930s. Four persons died of gunshot wounds at polls in the 1934
municipal elections. MORE
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ 1934 municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
   But of all such outrages, the most far-reaching would be the
June 1933 Union Station Massacre in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Many know how four law officers, along with fugitive Frank Nash,
died in an exchange of gunfire just outside the station. Less
well-known, according to author Bob Unger, was how the massacre was
sparked by a panicking federal agent discharging a shotgun he was
unschooled in operating. With two shots he killed Nash and two
fellow lawmen.
</P>
<P>
   The agent was not even supposed to be armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``By law, agents were not supposed to carry guns except under
the most extreme conditions,'' said Unger, author of The Union
Station Massacre. ``But the reality was that whenever they felt
threatened, they carried all the weapons they could get their hands
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Within about a year of the massacre, President Franklin D.
Roosevelt had signed nine anti-crime bills into law, creating a new
federal code. One change allowed federal agents to use and carry
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But J. Edgar Hoover (who became FBI director) didn't wait for
that,'' Unger said. ``He shipped machine guns to agents in Kansas
City in about three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite violent incidents such as the massacre, random violence
was not common, said Bill Gilmer, a Kansas City police officer from
1939 to 1969. Gilmer said few people thought to carry guns for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They respected law enforcement for having weapons and being
there to take care of them,'' said Gilmer, who wrote Glory Be to
St. John, a history of the Police Department. ``There was a deep
respect of guns and what they could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, the most visible violence shifted from
political thuggery to random crime, said Gilmer, the last officer
Pendergast appointed. Gradually, people became more open to guns,
he said. Still, it has only been in the last two decades that the
gun culture has become more prevalent. Ironically, Gilmer said,
law-enforcement technology has advanced, giving police greater
weapons against criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think people feel as safe as they did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in an era of falling crime rates, it's still the
perception of widespread lawlessness that is fueling support for
Proposition B.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
