u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-PREVIEW04-CO     04-03 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-PREVIEW04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds `armed and dangerous'
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ No matter what venue the Cincinnati Reds visited
for exhibition games this season, or no matter what team came to Ed
Smith Stadium in gorgeous Sarasota, the reaction was the same.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts, general managers and baseball officials scanned the
roster, looked up at the team wearing their spring-training black
hats, and said, ``Amazing. This was put together with a payroll
just over $34million. You can say what you want, but general
manager Jim Bowden did a wondrous job over the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1995, there was reason to go to Florida
for something other than sunshine and palm trees. For the first
time since 1995, the Cincinnati Reds appear ready to compete for a
National League Central championship.
</P>
<P>
   General managers said it. Field managers said it. Baseball
officials said it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is dangerous and easily could win the division,''
they said.
</P>
<P>
   And they are right.
</P>
<P>
   A team with a suspect starting rotation added left-hander Denny
Neagle, left-hander Steve Avery and right-hander Jason Bere to go
along with proven winners Pete Harnisch and Brett Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   If any of those five slip, right-hander Steve Parris and
left-hander Dennys Reyes proved last year they are more than
trinkets. They easily can be plugged into the rotation without it
being catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   A team with no visible power outlet added Greg Vaughn _ one of
only four players to hit 50 or more home runs last year. Vaughn
also had 119 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   A team with no accomplished center fielder added Mike Cameron,
who kept Mark McGwire from hitting 71 home runs last year by
leaping above the Comiskey Park right-center wall to snag McGwire's
bid for yet another home run.
</P>
<P>
   A team with no bench last year added seasoned and proven
veterans like Hal Morris, Mark Sweeney, Mark Lewis, Michael Tucker
and Brian Johnson. Add to that the veteran leadership of shortstop
Barry Larkin, and the Reds could be on their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a very fun year for the Cincinnati Reds and a
not-so-fun year for other teams in the National League Central ...
in fact, the entire National League,'' said one NL scout. ``This
team is armed and dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after last season had concluded, Bowden listed three
areas that needed to be addressed before the 1999 campaign began
and he put postage on each one _ the starting pitching, the bench,
defense in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need to do this year is catch the ball,'' Harnisch
said. ``Play good, solid defense. We can't play so-so defense, we
have to be good. We have good pitching and we will score runs. If
we play defense, this team can be real, real good.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation began boldly.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden traded popular and productive second baseman Bret Boone,
along with left-handed pitcher Mike Remlinger, to the Atlanta
Braves for Neagle, Tucker and future rotation member Rob Bell, one
of Atlanta's top pitching prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, one of baseball's best defensive second basemen, had his
best offensive year, leading the team in home runs (24) and RBIs
(95). ``I love Bret Boone, as a player and as a person,'' Bowden
said. ``I hated to trade him, but when you have a chance to get the
players we got, especially a proven winning pitcher like Neagle,
you pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't shooting blanks.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden next aimed his semi-automatic at the center fielder and
his ardor for Cameron became a mission. The Chicago White Sox
wanted Paul Konerko, a player with potential unfulfilled and not a
part of the plans in Cinergy Field. Konerko went for Cameron and
another hole was plugged.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the team was better ... but still not a
contender. Power was missing. Bowden had been trying to trade
injury-prone Reggie Sanders for nearly two years, but could find no
takers.
</P>
<P>
   Then his telephone rang in January. It was from San Diego
general manager Kevin Towers and if Bowden had known beforehand
what Towers wanted, he would have accepted a collect call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you take Greg Vaughn for Reggie Sanders?'' Towers asked.
``And, oh yeah, we'll throw in Mark Sweeney if you'll include
Damian Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden sputtered ``yes,'' and pinched himself to awake from his
dream. It was no dream. For two players Bowden didn't want, he
received two he really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said yes and called a press conference within the hour
before Towers changed his mind,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, most of the pieces were there.
</P>
<P>
   And not only will the team barely be recognizable because of new
faces, some of those faces will be adorned by facial hair for the
first time since 1967 and the team will be wearing new uniforms
with black trim added to the traditional red.
</P>
<P>
   For once, too, the Reds have a chance at returning to a long-ago
tradition ... winning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
