u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-WAR-BOS &LR;      04-03 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACEDONIA CLOSES BORDER TO KOSOVO REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND ANNE KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ This Balkan nation shut its borders on the
11th day of NATO airstrikes in Yugoslavia Saturday, stranding some
55,000 refugees in a massive, muddy field where nearly a dozen
elderly ethnic Albanians and newborn infants have already died.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which marked the first border closing by a
neighboring Kosovo, alarmed Western officials still grappling to
get a handle on the refugee crisis, and heightened concerns that
governmental instability could spread.
</P>
<P>
   But as Kosovars continued to flee the province by the thousands,
NATO warplanes bombed downtown Belgrade for a second day, and
officials repeated their threat to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic that ``no target is off-limits.'' President Clinton also
expressed his resolve, saying the United States must ``stand with
all our NATO allies to see it through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation cannot do everything. We can't stop all the
violence. But there are times when looking away simply is not an
option,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not address a report that US officials were
considering taking in some of the ethnic Albanian refugees. German
officials announced Saturday they would open their doors to the
displaced, and encouraged other countries to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana also addressed the refugee
tragedy, suggesting alliance forces might be able to return ethnic
Albanians to their homes in Kosovo even if Yugoslavia did not agree
to a peace treaty. Although the plan would mean placing ground
troops in hostile Serb territory, Solana described the potential
mission as one designed to allow Kosovars to return home, not as an
effort to wage war on the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the BBC began airing footage of what it said
were sites of mass murder, showing the bodies of what were believed
to be ethnic Albanian men. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said in a BBC interview that ``they were killed for one reason
only: they were of the wrong ethnic identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the edges of Kosovo, aid workers rushing to lend
assistance faced some of their greatest geographic and logistical
hurdles Saturday, as NATO officials estimated some 290,000 ethnic
Albanians had fled since airstrikes began March 24, and another
300,000 were on their way.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, the number of Kosovar refugees Saturday reached an
estimated 170,000, creating an enormous crisis for the poorest
nation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the ethnic Albanians flooding the northern
border, Albanian officials have been deploying buses and trucks to
move people south toward the capital, Tirana. But the pace of the
influx, combined with the country's delapidated and winding
mountain roads, has made it difficult for officials to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nightmare situation,'' President Rexhep Meidani said.
</P>
<P>
   Meidani, along with leaders of several aid organizations, held
out hope that neighboring Macedonia would reopen its borders to the
refugees, most of whom say they were stripped of their
identification and driven from their homes in Kosovo by Serb
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, a poor nation of 2 million residents, has already
taken in approximately 115,000 ethnic Albanians since NATO
airstrikes began and Milosevic began stepping up his campaign of
ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   US and Western allies were rushing to send some 200 tents, 8,000
sleeping bags and 1,500 beds to Macedonia, Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth H. Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said their forces would also step in to help.
General Mike Jackson, the British commander of 11,000 NATO troops
in Macedonia, was Saturday given authority to direct soldiers to
provide assistance in the refugee crisis. NATO officials also plan
to send 6,000 troops to Albania. There were no immediate plans to
send US or NATO military assistance to Montenegro, which is still a
part of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and where some 32,000
ethnic Albanians have fled in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   In Blace, Macedonia, the human misery had only worsened
overnight. Overnight rain reduced to a swamp the huge valley field
where up to 50,000 refugees were waiting to be allowed in. Several
were reported to have died waiting to leave the field. The crying
of children pierced the air. Scuffles broke out as hungry,
exhausted refugees clashed with police who held them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an unbelievable scene,'' said US Major Henry Cate, a
NATO spokesman in Blace. ``We are going to try to help these people
as best we can. But it is a monumental undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the population of Kosovo continued to empty out, NATO
and Pentagon officials indicated increasing success in the air
campaign against Milosevic, saying that on Friday they had struck a
complex of military headquarters in downtown Belgrade and set them
on fire. Serb television also reported Saturday that a second
bridge had been hit in the major city of Novi Sad, two days after
NATO missiles destroyed a bridge over the Danube River, blocking
the major commercial route.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, NATO forces continued to rely on sea-launched Tomahawk
missiles, which can function despite the bad weather conditions
that have clung to the region for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Defense specialists had begun to worry that the supply of
Tomahawks was running low. But Pentagon officials confirmed
Saturday that the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt has been
authorized to take part in the airstrikes, instead of being sent to
the Persian Gulf for its scheduled duty near Iraq. The USS Theodore
Roosevelt, equipped with some 75 warplanes and a number of cruise
missiles, is scheduled to arrive in the Adriatic Sea Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, just inside the Kosovo-Macedonia border, tens of
thousands of others waited in squalor for the chance to enter a
country that has said it will only accept refugees bound for
someplace else. Some NATO officials said they were shocked not only
at the lack of official response but also at the disorganization of
humanitarian agencies dispatched to fix the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees, said it ``is a tragic situation and we
are trying our best to handle it.'' But the Macedonian government,
she said, ``is understandably frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the few signs of encouragement was a sudden halt to the
trains from Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, which Serb authorities
had been using to transport ethnic Albanians out of town. Refugees
claimed Pristina had been emptied out, saying hundreds of thousands
of other refugees were waiting to cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly further east, the commander of the three American
soldiers who were captured on Wednesday by Yugoslav forces said he
had temporarily suspended patrols in the area where his men were
seized.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe, Lieutenant Colonel James Shufelt
said the situation in the border area northeast of Kumanovo,
populated by ethnic Serbs who oppose the bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia and who have repeatedly threatened US scouts patrolling
the area, had become ``untenable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullen reported from Macedonia, Kornblut from Washington. Globe
correspondent Susan Milligan contributed to this report from
Albania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
