<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPTIVES-PATROL-BOS &LR;      04-03 2078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTIVES-PATROL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY BELIEVES THREE SOLDIERS TAKEN WITHIN MACEDONIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETROVAC, Macedonia _ Staff Sergeant Chris Stone's voice was so
flat, so unemotional, that when he radioed for help Wednesday, his
superior officer, Sergeant First Class Jim LaShelle, didn't think
he was serious.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, LaShelle's skepticism inadvertently cut Stone
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grid 675. . .'' Stone said, before LaShelle broke in on the
radio line to make sure Stone wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   But that was only half of a six-digit number needed to locate
Stone and two other soldiers whose Humvee had been surrounded by
Serbs on Wednesday. His colleagues had a general location, but not
an exact one. When Stone repeated that they were taking direct
fire, LaShelle knew it was true and bolted up straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plow through 'em!'' LaShelle yelled. ``Plow through 'em!''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Stone heard him, or whether they could have been saved
even if Stone had not been cut off, is still unclear. The radio
went dead, and most of Stone's comrades in the 1st Squadron of the
4th US Cavalry assumed Stone, Staff Sergeant Andrew A. Ramirez, and
Specialist Steven M. Gonzales were dead, too.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 hours later, pictures of the soldiers, bruised and
sullen, turned up on Serbian television, abruptly ending what had
been a desperate search for them in rugged, hostile terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with those who were out patrolling with the three US
soldiers suggest they were on a routine but inherently dangerous
mission, skirting the border with a paranoid country that may have
been convinced that US troops were preparing to invade.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers' colleagues insist that their comrades were too
experienced and knew the frontier too well to have strayed
inadvertently into enemy territory. They said they believe the
three were victims of edgy Serb forces and an unmarked, disputed
border.
</P>
<P>
   According to the interviews, conducted Saturday at the home base
here of the 350 soldiers from the squadron to which the three
prisoners belong, the patrol made them vulnerable to anyone
determined to snatch them. And the capture has made them a
bargaining chip in President Slobodan Milosevic's showdown with
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers of the US Cavalry pride themselves on being
flexible and adaptable. They are the successors of the Cavalry that
scouted the American frontier and that were depicted riding to the
rescue in Saturday matinees of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, they were part of a United Nations mission that kept
watch along Macedonia's border with Yugoslavia. While there were
twice as many troops from Nordic countries taking part, it was the
presence of the 350 Americans that made Milosevic hesitant to
encroach on the border with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But the UN mission ended abruptly in February when China,
angered over Macedonia's recognition of Taiwan, and exercising its
veto as one of the UN's five Security Council members, refused to
renew the mission's mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Cavalry could be sent back to its headquarters in
Germany, however, the situation in Kosovo deteriorated sharply. On
March 24, the day NATO began bombing Yugoslavia, the Cavalry
formally began scouting the border to protect 11,000 NATO troops
waiting in Macedonia to implement a peace plan in Kosovo. They
peeled off their blue UN patches and berets, and changed the paint
on their armored vehicles from UN white to standard Army green.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Colonel James Shufelt, the captured soldiers'
commanding officer, said the mission went from simple observation
to combat reconnaisance _ that is, surreptitiously looking for Serb
troop movements and locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a UN mission, you want to be seen,'' Shufelt said. ``Now
the tactical mission was not to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the bombing and heightened hostilities, the Americans were
theoretically in more danger than before. But the reconnaisance
missions in fact took them farther from, not closer to, the border,
so they should have been even less likely to encounter Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   But the border is unmarked, and there has been a long-running
dispute between Yugoslavia and Macedonia about its exact location.
Fed a steady diet of stories suggesting that US reluctance to
commit ground troops in Kosovo was an American trick, Yugoslav
forces moved closer to the border. The captured soldiers' comrades
are convinced that the Yugoslavs crossed the border to surround and
snatch them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Serb forces crossed the border and dug trenches in
Macedonian territory, in the area where the soldiers were taken,
according to Alexander Ivanofsky, a former Macedonian soldier.
Ivanofsky and other Macedonian soldiers dug their own trenches
about 70 yards away, but the standoff ended peacefully four days
later when the Serbs left as abruptly as they had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   While some in Congress have criticized the Army, saying the
captured soldiers should not have been allowed to patrol alone and
were too lightly armed, Shufelt said the criticism is fine in
hindsight, but does not take into account the operational demands
put on his troops.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the 1st Infantry, the Cavalry is among the best-armed
fighting units in the Army. But their heavy equipment was left
behind at their German headquarters, deemed inappropriate for a UN
mission. Even if it had been decided it was needed for border
scouting to protect NATO troops, it is unlikely that it would have
made it here in time to avert the capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally would rather be in a tank or a Bradley,'' Shufelt
admitted, ``but the reality is you can scout from a motorcycle.
Would I prefer to have my heavy stuff? Yes. Could we do the job
with what we had? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The captured soldiers, Shufelt said, were part of a patrol that
included three Humvees. As a standard precaution, border scouts
establish what they call a ``rally point,'' to which they race if
there is a hint of danger. Once there, the patrol commander can
make sure everyone is accounted for, and take action if someone is
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The rally point changes as the observation posts do. On Tuesday,
Lieutenant Wayne Mahoney found a new rally point, an isolated spot
between a group of villages northeast of Kumanovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said he noticed an immediate rise in hostility once the
NATO bombing began and Cavalry vehicles reverted to their standard
Army green.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were UN, people waved at us,'' he said. ``When we went
to green, they started stoning us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the local residents were ethnic Serbs, Mahoney said
he had no reason to think they were capable of springing a trap or
tipping off Serb forces about the frequent US patrols. He believed
the rally point he picked out was isolated enough not to draw
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That place was totally unthreatening,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone was patrolling with Mahoney on Tuesday when the rally
point was selected, but Ramirez and Gonzales were not. While
Mahoney and those in the other two Humvees continued their patrol
Wednesday afternoon, Stone directed Ramirez to drive toward the
rally point so that Ramirez and Gonzales would know where it was.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, 24, from Los Angeles, had risen quickly in the Army and
was a career man. Stone, a Michigan native praised by his
colleagues as a meticulous student of reconnaisance, sat next to
Ramirez, using a hand-held global positioning system, which allowed
him to determine they were about 3 miles from the border. Gonzales,
21, a Texan, manned a .50-caliber Browning machine gun mounted on
top of the Humvee, his torso exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Shufelt and other officers said they believe the three soldiers
drove into either an ambush or a Serb unit that had set up a
heavily armed border patrol of its own.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a local postman, Slave Markovic, showed a Globe
reporter the unmarked dirt road he and other ethnic Serbs say the
US soldiers were driving on when they were captured. Macedonian TV
quoted residents of the Yugoslav village of Slavuevac as saying the
Americans had driven about a mile into Serbian territory before
they were captured. Markovic, 36, who said he had heard but had not
seen the shooting, added that he is convinced the Americans
unwittingly crossed the border.
</P>
<P>
   But the three soldiers' comrades vehemently dispute that, saying
they knew the border too well and had a positioning device with
them. Corporal Michael Fernicola, who did basic training with
Gonzales and is friendly with all three, said they were
conscientious soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergeant Stone would stay late to read maps, to make sure he
doesn't make mistakes. He knows that terrain. He wouldn't go off
course,'' Fernicola said.
</P>
<P>
   LaShelle, who was in charge of the three-vehicle patrol, was
even more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm positive they were not in Yugoslavia,'' he said. ``We had
been out there the day before. The landmarks are clearly
identifiable. They are very reliable people. I have complete faith
in their navigational ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the soldiers could have inadvertently crossed into
enemy territory, Shufelt, their commander, said, ``Is it possible?
Yes. Is it probable? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone is praised by fellow soldiers for being calm under
pressure. It was that coolness that momentarily fooled LaShelle
when the distress call came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergeant Stone's voice didn't seem right. That's why I asked
him if he was bullshitting,'' LaShelle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Four, this is Blue Five,'' Stone said. ``We're in
contact. We're taking direct fire.''
</P>
<P>
   About a mile away, LaShelle grabbed his radio, admonishing
Stone, saying, ``You better not be bullshitting me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not,'' Stone replied. ``We're taking direct fire. We're
trapped. They're all around us. We can't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, one of the nearby scouts set out on foot
to look for his comrades. It was an extremely dangerous operation,
snaking and sneaking through the farmland and rolling hills, armed
only with an M-16 rifle.
</P>
<P>
   LaShelle radioed that he was going to take his Humvee toward the
rally point to find them, but Captain Keith Igyarto, the troop
commander manning the radio back at base, ordered him not to,
fearing another ambush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good thing,'' LaShelle said in hindsight. ``I might have
driven right into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The captured soldiers' comrades presume they were heavily
outgunned, and the narrow dirt road made it impossible to turn and
escape.
</P>
<P>
   When Mahoney heard Stone's plea for help, ``I thought they got
shot. I thought they were hurt. I had a medic with us and I told
him to get the medical supplies ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney picked up an interpreter and began asking local
villagers if they had seen anything or heard shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they didn't know anything, or if they knew, they
weren't saying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First Lieutenant Jim Tighe, a Norwell native and 1997 Boston
College graduate, took a Blackhawk helicopter up to look for his
comrades. But by the time Tighe was overhead, the Humvee had
disappeared without a trace, presumably driven across enemy lines
by Yugoslav forces or sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   French, British and Italian pilots also looked for the missing
soldiers. After a frustrating, futile, all-night operation, the
search was called off suddenly when Brigadier General John Craddock
called Shufelt in the field and said, ``They've just been shown on
CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Shufelt, who had not slept in more than 24 hours, raced back to
base so he could see the pictures on TV. His soldiers looked like
they had been beaten up by their captors, but Shufelt was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the possibilities, I was just relieved to see they were
alive,'' he said. ``The challenge now is how to get them back.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is what is frustrating Cavalry soldiers most. Stone,
Ramirez and Gonzales are now chips in a game of diplomacy. Swedish
diplomats have been thwarted in their attempts to see the soldiers.
The Serbs say they will put the soldiers on trial. President
Clinton says they are entitled to prisoner of war status under the
Geneva Convention and warns that Milosevic will pay a heavy price
if they are harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, for the first time since the bombing began, the scouts
of the US Cavalry did not go back to the area where their comrades
were captured. Shufelt called off the patrols there Friday night,
at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Wild West out there,'' Jim Shufelt said, shaking his
head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
