<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      04-03 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSOVIC PLANS TO DRIVE ALL ETHNIC ALBANIANS FROM KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never has it been clearer: Within three weeks, unless Slobodan
Milosevic has a sudden change of heart or unless NATO ground forces
abruptly move to intervene, Kosovo will be depopulated of almost
all its 1.8 million ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO air power alone may yet deter the Yugoslav president. Or
the alliance could dispatch troops into Kosovo, under the guise of
an international peacekeeping force to care for those Albanians he
can't rout.
</P>
<P>
   But splitting up Kosovo is still being publicly rejected by all
sides _ Serb, Albanian, even American. And if trends continue, a
NATO official indicated Saturday, a ``massive ethnic cleansing''
will be complete in the province by late this month.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Kosovo is on a path toward becoming a Serb-only
province _ the fulfillment of Serb nationalists' six-century dream
to retake their religious and ethnic heartland, a place so sacred
in Serbian history, religion, and myth that they romanticize it in
epic poetry.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House and European governments continued
Saturday to decry the persecution of ethnic Albanians, and launched
more waves of warplanes and cruise missiles to punish the Serbs,
NATO countries again indicated that they have no intention of
fighting their way into the province to stop the Albanian expulsion
or to protect displaced Albanians inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   British and US units are readied to go to the region to help
protect Kosovo refugees, a NATO spokesman, Jamie Shea, announced
Saturday, but Milosevic would have to pull back his forces and give
his approval for them to enter Kosovo to set up havens. Whether
Milosevic will do that before he has cleared out most of the
Albanian population depends on whether he wants to endure more NATO
bombing so that he can pull off a historic transformation of Kosovo
_ and go down in Serb legend as the man who reversed the Kosovo
defeat of 1389 _ or whether he sees merit in cooperating (having
gotten most of what he wants) and bringing in international aid
both to help the remaining refugees and to rebuild the province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO would have to move extremely quickly into the landlocked
province to stop the Serbs' aims. At the present rate of ``ethnic
cleansing,'' Shea said, Serbs ``will have emptied Kosovo in 10-20
days from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States and other countries are stepping up
efforts to alleviate the suffering of refugees crossing into
Macedonia and Albania, President Clinton remains opposed to a
ground attack to protect ethnic Albanians or to roll back Serb
gains. In his weekly radio address Saturday, Clinton said that he
and allied leaders intended to ``exact a very high price'' from the
Serbs for driving Albanians out, but that the Operation Allied
Force bombing missions were the only method NATO would use.
</P>
<P>
   While some Balkan analysts see the merit of an ethnically
segregated Kosovo, military analysts say there is little the West
can do to establish even a foothold for ethnic Albanians without
waging a costly ground war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can do anything fast enough to make a real
difference,'' said retired Major General William Nash, who
commanded Army forces in Bosnia in 1995 and '96, and who is now at
the National Democratic Institute for International Affairs in
Washington. ``In a reasonably permissive environment, you might
have a chance to set something up, but if you go in under hostile
conditions, you end up with conditions you couldn't live with.''
</P>
<P>
   No one likes the idea of partition _ not the United States, nor
Kosovars, nor the Serbs _ and at this point Milosevic is calling
the shots in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the ground and we've got the refugees,'' said retired
Lieutenant General Terry Scott, a fellow at Harvard's Kennedy
School of Government. ``Unless we are willing to take it away with
ground troops, there will never be an independent state.'' Even if
NATO could force one, said Scott, it would be a tense situation,
one he likens to the Korean Demilitarized Zone, where two rivals
peer suspiciously across an internationally supervised border,
waiting for the next war.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it is not an option, Serb nationalists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that President Milosevic wants to carve up
Kosovo, because the Serbian public is solidly behind the position
of defending Kosovo to the bitter end,'' said Radmila Milentijezic,
a former Serbian information minister.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian leaders in the United States met with Clinton
and his national security advisers last week at the White House and
urged that Kosovo not be carved up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appealed to the president not to reward Milosevic for
genocide and ethnic cleansing by giving him a piece of Kosovo,''
said Harry Bajraktari, a New York-based political advocate for
Kosovar Albanians. ``He said partition is absolutely not a
possibility. He said we are going to win this, the bombing is going
to intensify and we will hit targets that will hurt Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, when Yugoslavia was fraying, Serb intellectuals
talked openly about cantonment of the province. A former Serb
president, Dobrica Cosic, did not believe Serbs and Albanians would
be able to live together peacefully. The Belgrade Academy of Arts
and Sciences later adopted the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Milosevic unleashed Serb nationalism by
declaring to Kosovo Serbs that ``no one will ever defeat you
again,'' revoking Albanian autonomy in the province, and
sanctioning campaigns of ethnic cleansing in Croatia, Bosnia, and
Kosovo. Now the facts on the ground are changing.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees must ``go back with peace and dignity,'' Emma Bonino,
humanitarian affairs commissioner of the European Union, said
Saturday. But once people are forcibly uprooted, it is extremely
difficult to return things to normal, said retired Brigadier
General John Reppert of the Kennedy school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track record on returning war refugees is extremely bad,''
said Reppert, who has studied the problems in Bosnia, Moldova, and
Ossetia. ``Unless there is a short-term solution that freezes
positions in place, the refugee issue will become a Red Cross issue
and not a UN issue.''
</P>
<P>
   If refugees are simply herded into camps in the hills of
southwestern Kosovo, they will end up ``like Indians on a
reservation . . . they will become wards of the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will be targets for Serb artillery, said retired
Lieutenant General Bernard E. Trainor, a fellow at the Kennedy
School. ``It doesn't make any sense. They have havens right now in
Albania, Macedonia, and Montenegro without having to fight for
them. Western nations should be spending their money there and
doing whatever they can to find homes for them in Cambridge, Miami,
and Australia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, he and other analysts say: Unless there is a
startling turn of events, Kosovo's Albanians are not going home.
</P>
<P>
   Globe correspondent Colum Lynch, at the United Nations,
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
