<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESURRECTION-FAITH-BO     04-03 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESURRECTION-FAITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL EVENT OF CHRISTIANITY MAKES DEMANDS OF CHRISTIANS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Resurrection is not for sissies.
</P>
<P>
   It is either an unprovable murder mystery story or the most
profound miracle of the Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   Christians have differed over its meaning since Paul admonished
the Corinthians almost 2000 years ago for not believing in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between saying `We don't have to believe
it' and `We have difficulty believing it,' '' notes Allen Callahan,
a New Testament scholar at Harvard Divinity School.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Resurrection has been all but lost in a warm and
fuzzy profusion of Easter eggs, rabbits and daffodils. What it
demands of Christians who take it seriously is awesome: a belief in
the bodily resurrection by God of his son, Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it absolutely terrifying when I have to preach on
Easter,'' says Richard Spalding, co-pastor of the Church of the
Covenant in the Back Bay, a hybrid of the United Church of Christ
and the Presbyterian Church. ``To believe in the Resurrection
stretches credulity, everything. To me, it is the Mount Everest. It
doesn't get any higher than that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a stretch that countless Christians simply cannot make.
They treat the event as metaphor, not historical fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in the bodily resurrection, but I believe in
the symbol and power of the story,'' says Betsy McAlister-Groves, a
member of Spalding's congregation. ``You can get sidetracked in
trying to figure out if it really happened. Does that then mean I'm
not a Christian? The answer for me is no.''
</P>
<P>
   For Syd Smith, another member of the congregation, who has
attended the church for 16 years, the Resurrection is even more
problematic. ``It's very scary and confusing,'' he says. ``I've
hardly known what to do with it for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk is foreign to David Seales, pastor of the Central
Assembly of God, a Pentecostal church in East Boston. Seales holds
that belief in the bodily resurrection is ``absolutely crucial''to
Christianity. Must someone believe it to be a Christian?
``Certainly,'' he responds. ``Paul doesn't mince words on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the Rev. Matthew Lamb, a theology professor at
Jesuit-run Boston College. ``The `progressives' in the church are
really retrogressive,'' he says. ``Not to believe in the bodliy
resurrection is to denigrate God's creation in the whole material
universe. It is not just a moral truth. Every human being is
destined to an eternal life in the glory of heaven or the pains of
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   So where does all of this leave a spiritual person who wants to
be a Christian but does not honestly accept the bodily resurrection
of Jesus? In a bad spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible conundrum,'' says Rose Ann Olmstead, co-pastor
with Spalding at Church of the Covenant. ``It's a place of torture
and depression, of constant feelings of failure and incompleteness.
They say, `I can't make myself fit there. I want to be a person of
faith but I don't want to give up my integrity.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is no easy answer for this group. ``They should deepen
their personal friendship with Jesus Christ,'' advises Lamb.
Olmstead takes a softer tack. ``I say to them, `Let it go. This may
not be the event or the service that's going to change your life.
God is not interested in taking captives. Find your own story.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nicholas Krommydas, chancellor of the Greek Orthodox
Diocese of Boston, acknowledges how difficult this process is, but
maintains, ``Ultimately you fall short of the intent of the New
Testament if you don't believe in the bodily resurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is hamstrung by this theological knot. The Rev.
Paul Kilroy, pastor of St. Ann University Parish in the Fenway,
says the subject does not arise much among his congregation. ``It's
not a faith issue for most of our people,'' he says. ``The question
complicates the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The theologian Michael Novak believes the towering
miracle of the Resurrection is particularly hard for people to
accept today because we have lost track of the smaller miracles
that occur around us throughout the year. ``The miracles of daily
life were small steps that prepared them for the larger miracles in
the New Testament,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not so today. ``As a result,'' Novak continues, ``The
Resurrection seems far more highly unusual than for people of the
past who were much more accustomed to the terrors of life and death
and the wondrousness of everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``bodily'' means is open to endless debate. Where
theologians like Lamb take it literally, others like Sam Lloyd,
rector of Trinity Church in Boston, do not. ``There was a
groundbreaking event. We don't know what it was because the
accounts are too elusive to know for sure,'' says Lloyd. ``But
Christian faith does not require Jesus's physical body to be
reassembled.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, says author James Carroll, a former Catholic
chaplain at Boston University, Paul's reference to the bodily
resurrection in his letters to the Corinthians comes secondhand.
``This is a man who never met Jesus (in the flesh),'' notes
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Kilroy chooses discretion over valor on the issue. ``I'm not
going to have a quiz on Sunday asking, `Do you believe in the
bodily resurrection?' '' he says. ``They'll respond, `What do you
mean?' and then we'll all have a fistfight.'' Besides, he adds,
``People are more interested in the results of the Resurrection and
the gift of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Carroll, ``There is theological movement within the
Catholic Church on the meaning of this story. The New Testament
reflects diversity of opinion on all of the major questions.'' The
dogged pursuit of objective data, he adds, is relatively recent.
``The proof, the physical detail _ this is an Enlightenment
obsession,'' notes Carroll. ``Before the Enlightenment, people were
much more comfortable with the mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Miracles are often more accessible to those who suffer. The
Resurrection is a case in point. ``Those on the lower strata of
society have an easier time wrestling with this,'' says Ray
Hammond, pastor of the Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church in
Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The miracle of the Resurrection has to be seen through the
lens of your own experience. As an African-American, the odds that
I'd be sitting here given where we were 100 years ago were very
long,'' he explains. ``It's all about faith and hope for the
impossible. In the African-American tradition, we understand what
this means in the life and death of possibility. It's very real to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, belief in the Resurrection provides the possibility
of living a different life. ``You have the capacity to risk
again,'' says Lloyd. ``The Resurrection has a huge relevance in the
orientation toward life and possibility, rather than a life of
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmstead agrees. ``What's important about it is that it makes a
mind shift possible. It allows us to see an event in a way that is
dramatically different from the view you once had of it. You see
racism for the first time. You see a Mongoloid child and realize
this is a really precious human being instead of just seeing the
limitations of that life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' she concludes, ``that God wants us to be open to
these kinds of shifts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
