<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, April 4. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHINA-ARIZ _ Elizabeth Mann, Arizona's most important business
connection to Beijing, has risen to prominence through mastery of
what the Chinese call ``guanxi,'' the cultivation of contacts with
powerful people. Educated in the United States and China and fluent
in the languages and cultures of both countries, Mann personifies
the energetic and growing Chinese business presence in the U.S.
However, two of Mann's contacts have been linked to major scandals
and she has been the subject of two criminal investigations. By
JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GROWTH-PHX (undated) _ From Queen Creek to Surprise, Laveen to
Higley, bulldozers threaten the Mayberrys of central Arizona. Small
towns where people raise ostriches and hang out at watermelon
festivals are under siege, targeted not just for 100 or 200 new
homes, but for thousands of them. The small-town, rural atmosphere
is on a collision course with the growth machine of America's
sixth-largest city. Places that used to be in the boondocks have
become housing hot spots. By CHRIS FISCUS. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PROM (Phoenix) _ Racks and racks of donated fancy dresses lined the
quiet Phoenix store Saturday morning as a line of girls snaked
across the sidewalk outside. There is little to tell about these
dresses' pasts: a tiny hole where a pin likely held a corsage in an
elegant long purple dress; a tugging at the hem of a light pink
shift where a bridesmaid might have caught the heel of her dyed
pump; a little rip where a shimmery bracelet tore the tulle of a
white gown. But the high school girls cared less about where these
dresses _ part of a unique giveaway program _ came from and more
about where they were going. By LAURA TRUJILLO. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ I've become acquainted lately with
breathlessness, with exhaustion, with weakness. It has made me
think of young Nicky Contreraz, tortured to death at the Arizona
Boys Ranch just over a year ago. When I said I was sick, I was
believed. When Nicky said he was sick, he was forced to do push-ups
over a bucket of his excrement soiled clothing. He was required to
eat his supper while sitting on a toilet. He was ridiculed and
insulted, told he was a slacker who deserved an Academy Award. He
was killed. By E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
