<HEADER>
A4916 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     04-03 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN STIRS UP HORNETS NEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA - which threatens to be fan-tas-tic all over the place
refuses to look away from its interests in Dixie, where
constituents still believe ``trail mix'' refers to the
fraternization of Coca-Cola and Jack Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the IQ of two GQ coaches, there is on-court prosperity
in Florida. Even though Mookie Blaylock's shooting percentage is
falling, a new arena is rising in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But a comprehensive revival just might hit the spot in good, ol'
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Hornets now have Eddie Jones at shooting guard, but
they're a little thin at shooting owner.
</P>
<P>
   So league commissioner David Stern and Hornets owner George
Shinn dropped a dime on Michael ``CEO'' Jordan. They want Michael
to purchase half of the team. They surveyed the box scores, and
realized Jordan has owned the Hornets for years, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, wooing Jordan sounds like a dandy plan, even though
recruiting the greatest basketball player in history for ownership
seems a bit like purchasing a stealth bomber to dust crops.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan's involvement would generate interest, and help push
Charlotte's creaking, 11-year-old, 23,000-seat arena (including its
woefully inadequate 12 skyboxes) into the abyss of obsolescence.
</P>
<P>
   What it already has done is inspire Chicken Little ``scoops''
concerning Jordan's return to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Chew on this:
</P>
<P>
   Jordan would slum around with the other Hornets and lure NBC
while his ownership loot is placed in escrow. See, the NBA does not
allow players to own teams. When Jerry Buss of the Lakers was told
owners couldn't be players
</P>
<P>
   , he reflected upon his dating scorecard and thought he would be
ordered to sell the team.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, with rumors of Jordan back in uniform, the obvious
incredibility leap required rumormongers to install Phil Jackson as
Charlotte's new bench boss. Free of the Zen &AMP; Jerrys management
strife he endured in Chicago, Jackson could even make personnel
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's believed Phil thinks Charlotte is too square
to truly appreciate the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Jordan's camp has announced that the tale of his
on-court return is pure fiction.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ownership news is real. But if Jordan owns 50
percent and Shinn owns 50 percent, who makes the big decisions? If
Jordan is not allowed to purchase a majority interest, his bailout
investment seems like nothing more to the franchise than found
money.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely (sorry, Nike), if Jordan holds the hammer, on-court
proceedings probably would be altered in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Hornets player, having Jordan as the boss might feel
a bit like finding out your landlady is Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   At least you'd feel pressure to clean up your act.
</P>
<P>
   (SUBHED) Talking Euro trash
</P>
<P>
   The last time Stern presided over the NBA Draft's first round,
four European players (not including the University of Pacific's
Michael Olowokandi) were selected.
</P>
<P>
   After pestering several NBA scouts, we can reveal it is quite
possible that only one Euro will crack the first-round lineup in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Weiss is a 22-year-old 7-footer who's playing
professionally in France. But Weiss' most-prominent adviser also is
the big cheese of his current team. So don't be shocked if Weiss is
not in the NBA next season.
</P>
<P>
   (SUBHED) Kid stuff
</P>
<P>
   The leading candidates to hop from high school to the NBA this
year are 6-11 Jonathan Bender of Picayune, Miss., and 6-91/2
DerMarr Johnson, a Maryland kid who completed his prep career at
Maine Central Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Both players participated in a tournament at Cal State Dominguez
Hills last summer, where their alleged uninspired performances
failed to attract the blessings of greatness freely given by the
self-annointed judges of prep hoop talent.
</P>
<P>
   But Bender and Johnson are the rage now. Bender scored 31 points
in the McDonald's-sponsored all-star game to tie a record held by
Jordan. Johnson looked slick while tossing in 19.
</P>
<P>
   Some NBA watchdogs consider Bender a lottery pick, while Johnson
might be selected late in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   If they decided to bypass college.
</P>
<P>
   (SUBHED) Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls will have miles of salary-cap room after this
season, but may choose to hire a few economical players to go with
their lottery pick and a Euro or two. After helping the Magic
clobber the Bulls on Friday, Orlando's Penny Hardaway who can opt
out of his contract this summer almost begged for the Bulls to sign
him. ... It was a tough week for Portland's Isaiah ``Take It Easy''
Rider. In addition to wading into the expensive seats to hold a
debate with a Warriors fan, he was sued for causing ``emotional
distress'' during an incident in Detroit in 1997. The plaintiff, it
should be pointed out, is not former Blazers coach P.J. Carlesimo.
... If you look beyond the hype, you'll see that Vancouver's Mike
Bibby is having a better rookie season than Sacramento's Jason
Williams. Both are averaging 13 points per game, but Bibby is
shooting 42 percent from the field and handing out almost seven
assists per game. Williams' corresponding numbers are 38 percent
and 5.5 dimes. Bibby also stinks a bit less on defense. Williams'
offense has been a bit ripe the last eight games; the kid has made
just 28 percent of his field-goal attempts, which suggests a more
appropriate nickname might be ``Off-White Chocolate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
