<DOCNO> NYT19990403.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4917 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--BLINEBURYOLAJUWO     04-03 1662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BLINEBURY </SLUG>
 OLAJUWON-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By Fran Blinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After all the years, the seasons and the games, the
shots and the rebounds, the makes and the misses, the highs and the
lows tumble together like a kaleidoscope, and all you do is keep
playing.
</P>
<P>
   Records fall, barriers are broken, and the greatest ones never
seem to notice them, like mileposts on a wide-open freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how it came to pass that Hakeem Olajuwon gathered in
the feed from Scottie Pippen in the third quarter Thursday night in
Salt Lake City, turned and fired in the sweetest 13-foot baseline
jumper to become only the 12th player in NBA history to score
25,000 points in his career, then had to be reminded of the fact
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,'' he said. ``I don't keep up with these things. I let
the statisticians keep up with the numbers. That is their job. Mine
is to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years he's done that like only a handful of others before
him, recently passing the likes of Elgin Baylor, Adrian Dantley and
Robert Parish on the scoring list and now closing in on greats such
as Jerry West, John Havlicek and Oscar Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Where did the time go? And how did Olajuwon make the leap from
the young colt with the frisky legs, relentless drive and perpetual
smile at the University of Houston to a thoughtful 36-year-old and
worldwide basketball icon in the blink of our eyes?
</P>
<P>
   There's a line from Lily Tomlin's one-woman play on Broadway:
``If I'd have known it was going to be all this, I'd have settled
for half.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years with the Rockets. It's like looking through the
wrong end of a telescope. The beginning seems so far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time thinking in those terms myself,'' Olajuwon
said. ``The first time anybody told me about the 25,000 points was
when we were in LA. I said, `25,000? Who are you talking about?
That can't be me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at it that way, trying to take in all 15 years
and the numbers that have been built up, and see that I am still
comfortable on the court, still full of energy, you realize that I
have been blessed to have it all happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as we have been privileged to have a courtside seat to
watch it take place. The stranger from the faraway place of Lagos,
Nigeria, who was dropped on the doorstep of Guy V. Lewis has
literally grown up in our midst, while at the same time Houston
finally has grown into a championship city because of him.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought on those first nights he stepped onto the
floor at Hofheinz Pavilion as such a raw, young talent and made
like King Kong trying to swat down every shot as if it were an
attacking airplane that he could take himself and us so far?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drafted him No. 1 back in 1984, we thought we were
getting a Bill Russell-type player,'' said Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich, a scout in those days. ``Based on what we had seen of
him in college, we were expecting a defensive center who would be
able to challenge people coming into the lane, somebody who would
be able to go to the boards and get us some rebounds. Frankly,
anything else would have been a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   But it turned into so much more, like picking up a trinket at a
flea market and having it turn out to be the Hope Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon chuckles at the memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what they all thought of me back then,'' he said.
``Defense. That was what they got from scouting the college games.
What everybody was missing was the real learning, the real
development in my game, and all of that was taking place at Fonde
(Recreation Center).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I played against Moses (Malone) and all of the
other players from the NBA and gained my confidence. That's where I
was able to try out so many of the things that eventually became a
regular part of my game. I have always known that my game could be
much more than what other people were expecting. The seeds were
planted earlier. But Fonde is where they were cultivated.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular misconception is that Olajuwon's game in his early
NBA days was nothing more than an endless stream of offensive
rebounds and follow-up dunks. But if you watch the replays on ESPN
Classic Sports, you can see even then the deadly turnaround jump
shot that eventually would develop into the Dream Shake. You can
see in the highlights from the 1986 NBA Finals against the Boston
Celtics that the monster was moving faster than other big men,
spinning this way and whirling that way, and turning into something
the NBA never had seen before.
</P>
<P>
   During the NBA's golden anniversary celebration in 1997, when
Hakeem was named one of the top 50 players in history, Russell and
Wilt Chamberlain sought out Olajuwon to tell him he was the modern
player they thought carried their torch today _ relentless,
dominating.
</P>
<P>
   He has spun along the baseline and whirled in the lane like a
top for so long that we tend to forget he was the first big man to
do those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those early days in the NBA were fun, playing with Ralph
Sampson, being part of the Twin Towers,'' Olajuwon said. ``Because
we both had another big man to support us, we could both try
different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Twin Towers was an exciting time. I never thought back
then about all of the things I might be able to accomplish
individually. I have never looked at individual goals. You have to
play the game each day and always set your sights on winning a
championship right now. You can never say that your team is too
young or is several years away. You play to win now. Because the
next year or the year after are never guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw it happen up close, injuries eventually bringing
Sampson's career to a painful, grinding halt. In Olajuwon's 15
years, he has battled through phlebitis in his leg, a fractured
orbital socket and an irregular heartbeat, all the while expanding
his game and pushing at the envelope of what was possible for a big
man until it all came together in a harmonic convergence in 1994
and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two years the Rockets beat us in Phoenix and went on to
win the championship, he was simply phenomenal,'' Charles Barkley
said. ``There was nothing we could do to stop him, nothing anybody
could do. He was a thing of beauty. Now, it's an honor to play with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   A Most Valuable Player season in 1993-94 seemed to test his
limits, but it was only a prelude to the magical 1995 playoff run
and, in particular, the series against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like nothing I have ever seen,'' Tomjanovich said. ``To
see him take apart David Robinson the way he did. To think of all
the different moves he made. There are times today when I'll see
highlights and just feel privileged to have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the equivalent of planting a flag on Mount Everest, the
last step up to the highest peak. But from that cold, lonely place,
the only view of the world is down. That's the battle Olajuwon has
been fighting for the past three seasons as knee injuries _ and
eventually surgery on one _ took away his strength, quickness and
mobility, and the whispers grew to a roar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard all of the talk, that Hakeem is not hungry anymore,
that he has his two championships and is satisfied,'' Olajuwon
said. ``They overlook the obvious, that for the past several years
I have not been physically able to play the game, to play my game,
which relies on speed and agility.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so quick to forget, so quick to make judgments
without having all of the information, all of the facts. They see
me trying to play my game without getting the same results, and
suddenly it is because I am too old or not hungry anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is frustrating when you are used to being a dominating
player and you find that you can't dominate. It has nothing to do
with being satisfied. If anything, I was less satisfied over the
past several years, because I was not myself. I knew it was a
physical problem, but that did not make it easier for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He demonstrated his commitment by embarking on an offseason
training program under the guidance of triple jumper Frank
Rutherford, a fellow UH alum, regaining the strength in his legs to
make all of the explosive moves and rediscovering the fluidity to
spin on the baseline for his jump shot or dance into the lane for
his baby hook.
</P>
<P>
   It was a learning process as Olajuwon searched for his timing
while hunting for his proper place in a crowded offense that
includes Barkley and Pippen. The early weeks of the shortened
season were a struggle, but the past month has seen Olajuwon
steadily regain his form. He scored 32 points against the Jazz and
dominated the third quarter with 14 points, three rebounds, two
blocked shots and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 wonderful minutes, it was all back. And those games are
stringing together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have anything to prove,'' Olajuwon said. ``Anything
that I do now is not a reaction to criticism or talk. It is about
being healthy. For the first time in several years, I can play
without the pain or the limitations that my body was putting on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is exciting for me that I can make the moves and feel like
they are natural again. The game is fun again. I am enthusiastic
each night, and there is no reason to think I can't go on.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says two more years, taking him to the end of his current
contract, will be enough. It is times like these, stopping to note
mileposts like 25,000 points, that tell him it's been a longer road
than he ever imagined when getting off that plane from Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never set goals like that, but the number speaks for
itself,'' he said. ``I've had some problems, some injuries.
Overall, I have had a wonderful career.''
</P>
<P>
   The smile is warm, the satisfaction genuine. But now those
chocolate-brown eyes are dancing again, and you can tell Hakeem is
dreaming of the next time he gets the basketball, the next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
