<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4918 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     04-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER COMPLAINTS ARE GORILLA WARFARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something that bothers more than a few NBA players when they
travel to Phoenix, but rarely gets discussed, has once again caused
a stir.
</P>
<P>
   The agent for Sacramento Kings center Oliver Miller is claiming
the Suns are guilty of racism because of a recent skit performed by
the infamous Gorilla mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Blakeley filed a complaint through the NBA Players
Association with the league office, because Miller was upset
regarding a skit that ridiculed the 390-pound center's weight
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Gorilla lampooned the 6-foot-9 former Phoenix player by
wearing a Kings jersey with Miller's name and number on it.
</P>
<P>
   The jersey was stuffed with pillows. The Gorilla waddled, then
fell to the floor. Miller's family also happened to be in
attendance that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an obese, black, ugly gorilla to portray a professional
African-American basketball player is very offensive,'' Blakeley
told the Toronto Globe and Mail. ``In my mind and in the minds of
many of the players who are in a predominantly black league, a
gorilla is imprudent. It's racist, we think, and we can't believe
the Suns continue to have a mascot like this.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that NBA players remember how stubborn Arizona
was in recognizing Martin Luther King Day.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who has never controlled his weight, isn't exactly the
most credible player to protest the Gorilla's antics. But some
might feel differently if you knew the racism charge was first
leveled by Kareem Abdul-Jabbar when he played with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar once got into a shoving match with the Gorilla in
front of the Lakers bench.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Suns forward Clifford Robinson, who is an African-American, said
he doesn't consider the Gorilla to be a racist symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' Robinson said. ``I found what he does quite
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is Suns owner Jerry Colangelo, who often acts
like he can do anything, except win an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo admitted the skit may have crossed the line of decency
but refused to consider complaints about the gorilla's racial
overtones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say absolutely, unequivocally that has never been
true,'' Colangelo said. ``There may be different views about skits,
about whether they are in good taste or bad taste. But the fact is,
it has always been in the form of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about time Colangelo, one of the NBA's old-guard owners,
gives the Gorilla an early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Hold off the celebration: Before everyone gets too carried away
with the Trail Blazers' incredible start, two things to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _The club has a much tougher second-half schedule, including
four games with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   _Portland is showing signs of displaying its better-known
personality traits.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared throughout Wednesday's game against Sacramento,
forcing coach Mike Dunleavy into the role as the leader of what is
sometimes the NBA's most successful three-ring circus.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Rider did not play against the Kings because of a league
suspension, Stacey Augmon was ejected after a running feud with
Sacramento guard Vernon Maxwell, and Rasheed Wallace was so angry
that at one point he cursed at Dunleavy and warned the coach to get
away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No coaching job in the NBA is easy,'' diplomat Dunleavy said.
</P>
<P>
   Not worth a dime: As further proof that Orlando's Penny Hardaway
is one of the most despised players in the league, even
professional malcontent Derrick Coleman (of all people) ragged him
hard last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically walked up to me and said I was washed up,''
Hardaway said of a little chat with DC during the game that
resulted in both getting technical fouls. ``Apparently a lot of
people around the league feel the same way. I'm not having any more
games like this for the rest of the season. You're going to see a
different Penny Hardaway. I can't have people disrespecting me.''
</P>
<P>
   So three games later, Penny goes 4 of 10 with 11 points, four
assists and three rebounds in a loss at Washington. Even worse, he
sits out the entire fourth quarter even though the Magic was down
by just four points with four minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what (Chuck) Daly was thinking,'' Hardaway said.
``How do you leave your top guy on the bench with the game on the
line? It doesn't surprise me what he does. You have to go with the
flow to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   No homer: Former Celtics great Bob Cousy, who does color
commentary for the team, doesn't mind telling it like it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they start playing well, I'll be the biggest cheerleader
they've ever had. But when they suck, I'm going to tell people how
I feel,'' Cousy said. ``I'm not going to blame the refs (something
partner Tom Heinsohn does constantly), or say that the guy has a
bad ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie. I feel sorry for Rick Pitino right now
and I worry about him. Sometimes I think he's going to have a
nervous breakdown if he keeps going at that pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick observation: The Clippers might not have a better record
if they had drafted Toronto swingman Vince Carter (18.4 points, 6.0
rebounds, 2.6 assists, 1.35 blocked shots in 35.3 minutes per
game), but they sure would be a lot more entertaining to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the shadow: Guard Damon Frierson spent most of this past
season playing behind All-American teammate Wally Szczerbiak at
Miami University in Ohio. But Wednesday night at the Portsmouth
Invitational Tournament in Virginia, Frierson wowed NBA scouts by
scoring 17 of his game-high 25 points in the second half of the
tournament's opening game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The NBA column appears Sundays in the Daily News. Staff Writer
Scott Wolf can be reached via e-mail at Scwolf1aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
