<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TRY TO HEAL IN MIND AND BODY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ With a victory over the Indiana Pacers just
four days ago, Coach Jeff Van Gundy did not need to remind the
Knicks of strategies or tendencies as they worked out Saturday at
SUNY-Purchase. But what the team did need before flying off to face
the Pacers in Indianapolis for a nationally televised game on
Sunday afternoon was the gentle stretching and massaging of the
training staff and the not-so-gentle massaging of their minds by
the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   What they face on Sunday is not only Indiana (21-11), the
Central Division leader, but an assortment of physical ailments in
their own locker room. Larry Johnson, Patrick Ewing, Chris Dudley
and Marcus Camby all sat out Saturday's practice, leaving Kurt
Thomas, Herb Williams and Ben Davis as the only frontcourt players
available.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who sprained his right knee in the Knicks' victory over
Indiana on Tuesday, said Saturday that he would not play on Sunday.
Ewing most likely will play through the pain of a sore left
Achilles' tendon, and Dudley (sore left knee) and Camby (left groin
strain) were listed as day to day. Davis, who is on the injured
list, could be activated before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just probably jumped the gun a little bit I guess,'' said
Johnson, who sat out Thursday's game against Cleveland but said
before that game that he would return on Sunday. ``I ran that day
before the game and I rode the bike and I felt pretty good. But
when I was sitting on the bench, I didn't feel good at all. It's
not where I want it to be. I want to look at it tomorrow, try to
get there early, run up and down on the court and see how I feel.
Maybe I'll play Tuesday or Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ewing should be available, Van Gundy tried to keep the
team from using the injuries as an excuse. The two days off, Friday
and Saturday, were the first such breather for the Knicks in a
month. It was clearly not enough of a break to get the team
healthy. Even with two consecutive victories, the Knicks are 18-14,
clinging to the seventh seeding in the Eastern Conference playoff
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not discouraged,'' Van Gundy said. ``It's just how it is.
You have to deal with it the best way you can, which is to move
forward and get ready for the game. Whoever you have, you go out
there expecting to win. I don't know who we're going to have
tomorrow, but I know one thing, if we're not expecting to win, then
we shouldn't even get on the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   While the physical woes may or may not be healed enough by game
time, Van Gundy said it would be simple to tell if the mental
approach was intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be able to see it by how we play,'' Van Gundy said.
``If we're playing aggressively and hard, then we're playing to
win. It's what we've got to do, because sometimes you can feel
sorry for yourself in situations like this and moan about what you
don't have instead of concentrating on what we do have. I want our
guys to concentrate on what we do have, which is enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will start Latrell Sprewell in Johnson's place on
Sunday for the second straight game. After impatiently waiting for
his opportunity to start, Sprewell struggled through an 11-point
performance with more turnovers (four) than field goals (three) on
Thursday. If Dudley and Ewing are healthy enough, they will start
in the frontcourt, with Thomas filling in.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are back to full strength after playing the Knicks
without Antonio Davis on Tuesday and losing Jalen Rose to an
ejection in the second period of that game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Van Gundy does not want players to rush back into the
lineup, particularly Johnson, who underwent a magnetic resonance
imaging examination following Tuesday's game. That revealed a
grade-one sprain of the medial collateral ligament. Johnson has not
seen the team doctors since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to be back,'' Van Gundy said of Johnson. ``The
problem is you can't wait until you're totally healthy or else the
season will be over because of the schedule. And if you come back
too soon and reinjure yourself, you can miss, like, 12 games. It's
really a fine line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this season was going to be like this because of the
compacted schedule. We just have to deal with it. We'll have enough
guys. You go out there with the right mentality, we're going to
have an opportunity to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
