<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      04-03 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DESTROYS 2ND BRIDGE ON DANUBE AND A RAIL LINK  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after reducing security ministries in
downtown Belgrade to collapsed rubble, allied forces destroyed a
second bridge over the Danube River in Yugoslavia Saturday while
NATO troops in neighboring Bosnia blew up a railway that officials
said the Yugoslav army was planning to use as a resupply line for
troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring a deepening military involvement, Secretary of
Defense William Cohen has approved a request by NATO's supreme
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, to send Apache attack helicopters to
Albania along with two types of rocket batteries used to back them
up, a Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of the Apaches, the Army's low-flying gunship
used to destroy tanks, still needs to receive approval from NATO's
political authorities, who remain wary of the introduction of the
helicopter and the rockets. The Apaches carry the political risk of
being viewed as the introduction of ground troops, because to put a
battalion of the Apaches and a battalion of each of the rockets
into Albania would require putting a force of 2,000 Army soldiers
on the ground in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also ordered the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt _
with 46 strike jets _ to cancel a planned trip to the Persian Gulf
and join in the strikes against Yugoslavia. The carrier, which is
expected to enter the Adriatic Sea by Monday, is accompanied by
three other ships and two submarines able to fire Tomahawk cruise
missiles, bringing the total number of those vessels in the region
to 11.
</P>
<P>
   The order followed the addition of 13 more American F-117
stealth fighters and five B-1 bombers, as well as new contributions
from the British and French earlier this past week. Before the
attacks began on March 24, American and NATO officials had insisted
that they had more than enough air power in the region to carry out
a sustained campaign against the forces of President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes Saturday against the bridge in the northern Serbian
town of Novi Sad began what officials said would be an intense
night of air raids and missile strikes against targets throughout
Yugoslavia. Dozens of aircraft, including F-117 fighters, departed
from bases in Italy as darkness fell, while B-52s equipped with
cruise missiles left a base in England.
</P>
<P>
   Although attacks were hampered again by rain and dense clouds
reaching to 30,000 feet, there were signs of clearing Saturday
night, and officials at NATO and in Washington vowed to use any
breaks in the weather to redouble the attack against those Yugoslav
forces routing ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On the 11th day of its raids on Yugoslavia, NATO found itself
grappling with two deepening missions at once: a military one and a
humanitarian one.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it pressed attacks, the alliance announced Saturday that
it was considering sending a force of 6,000 to 8,000 troops to
Albania to help impose control along the border with Kosovo, where
thousands of refugees are massing with little food or shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced the delivery of the first 30,000 of
500,000 rations of food for refugees in Albania and said it planned
to send 200 tents, 8,000 sleeping bags and 1,500 cots to Macedonia,
to which thousands of refugees have fled.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge destroyed Saturday was the second blown up in Novi
Sad, a major city northwest of Belgrade. The first, a steel
suspension span, collapsed in a twisted wreck after being struck by
missiles fired from an American F-15 on Thursday. The second
bridge, a newer concrete span, was struck not long after dark in
Yugoslavia Saturday night. Serbian television showed the bridge
split in two in the Danube, Europe's longest waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav authorities and witnesses interviewed by Serbian
television said there were cars crossing the bridge at the time of
the strike, but there was no immediate report on casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks in Novi Sad cut one of the main transportation links
between Belgrade and the northern part of the country. NATO
commanders defended the destruction of the bridges, even though
both are far from the fighting in Kosovo to the south. At NATO's
headquarters in Brussels, a military spokesman, Air Commodore David
Wilby of Britain, said Saturday that ``vital supplies'' for
Yugoslav military and police units crossed the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual expansion of its tactics, NATO also used its
peacekeeping troops in neighboring Bosnia to destroy a rail link
between Yugoslavia's dominant republic, Serbia, and the second
remaining republic, Montenegro. Some six miles of the railway
skirted Bosnian territory, a legacy of the formerly unified
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO official said troops from NATO's Stabilization
Force blew up the railway early Saturday morning, ostensibly to
enforce the terms of the peace agreement governing Bosnia, which
prohibits hostile forces from operating anywhere in the country.
But the officials said NATO believed that Milosevic's forces were
preparing to use the link to send troops and equipment into
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   While such forces could have continued on to Kosovo to reinforce
the campaign under way there, Milosevic may also have been moving
to crack down against Montenegro's president, Milo Djukanovic, who
has not displayed blind loyalty to Belgrade since the attacks
began.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the NATO allies have seen Djukanovic as a
potential challenger to Milosevic's iron grip on what remains of
Yugoslavia. And cutting the railway could well help head off
attempts by Belgrade to crack down there, attempts that Britain's
Ministry of Defense warned on Friday appeared to be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the raids, Milosevic's forces continued their attacks in
Kosovo. Wilby said two Serbian paramilitary groups ``with a proven
record of brutality'' _ the Tigers and the White Eagles _ were
looting villages.
</P>
<P>
   With the foul weather grounding most aircraft, NATO has been
able to do little to attack the forces fighting in the field in
Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
