<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH GOES ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hollandsworth, the former Rookie of the Year
who had nailed down the Dodgers' fourth outfielder spot, was placed
on the 15-day disabled list Saturday with a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth suffered the injury to his right leg after running
out a ground ball during Friday night's 8-1 victory over the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Hollandsworth was walking without a limp. But
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said Hollandsworth ``could barely
walk'' Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, who demanded a trade in the offseason, was the
Dodgers' top hitter this spring, batting .418 with three homers and
eight RBI in a team-high 79 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a workhorse (this spring),'' Johnson said. ``I was
shocked to see him go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Placing Hollandsworth on the DL probably means outfielders
Trenidad Hubbard and Jacob Brumfield will make the roster. But
Johnson said he's leaning toward carrying three catchers: Todd
Hundley, Rick Wilkins and rookie Paul LoDuca.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hundley)'s legs were a little heavy last night,'' Johnson
said. ``I don't want to bury him after the first week to 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca, 26, played in 126 games at Triple-A Albuquerque last
year and six with the Dodgers. He entered Saturday with a .316
spring batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've contributed to the team,'' LoDuca said.
``I've handled the pitching staff OK. Yes, I would be disappointed
if I didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Auditioning: Three rookie pitchers bidding to make the roster
pitched Friday in Anaheim, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handers Jeff Williams and Onan Masaoka and right-hander
Jamie Arnold all pitched scoreless innings, but Williams and
Masaoka both walked two and Arnold walked one.
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka, the most impressive rookie in Vero Beach, struck out
Garret Anderson to get out of a bases-loaded situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to see Masaoka get out of a little jam,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, who just turned 25, is an intriguing prospect. He was a
first-round pick by the Braves in 1992 but only pitched in nine
games above Double-A in seven seasons. He is a converted starter
with a career minor-league record of 32-44.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran relievers Greg Cadaret and Pedro Borbon were scheduled
to make appearances Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my left-handers in the bullpen to get a taste of their
left-handed hitters,'' Johnson said. ``They may not like the taste
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilly preview: It was fitting the first visit by the Yankees to
Dodger Stadium since the 1981 World Series was accompanied by a
temperature that dipped into the 50s during batting practice. It
was weather that, well, reminded one of October.
</P>
<P>
   Will these two teams meet again in the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best team in baseball,'' said Kevin Malone, the
Dodgers general manager, of the world-champion Yankees. ``They have
proved they are the best. They are where we want to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
