<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL CHALLENGE ROMPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- General Challenge, taught a few lessons during a trip
to Louisiana last month, took a talented Santa Anita Derby field to
school Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ridden confidently by Gary Stevens, the 3-year-old gelding went
into high gear at the three-eighths pole and cruised to a 3
1/2-length victory over 2-1 favorite Prime Timber in the $750,000
Grade I steppingstone to the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   It was another 3 1/2 lengths back to 5-2 second choice Desert
Hero before an on-track crowd of 35,023.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge's reputation took a hit in the Louisiana Derby
when he lunged at the start, made a big move and then flattened out
in the stretch. Now, he could be favored when the field goes
postward for the Kentucky Derby on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That race was kind of a disaster,'' Stevens said of General
Challenge's first action outside of California. ``But I think it
worked out as a positive for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a lot happen to him in just the last month, with
shipping to New Orleans for his first time racing out of town and
then flying back here. He's been asked to clear some pretty good
hurdles.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of General Meeting cleared his latest hurdle with plenty
to spare. He looked more like the horse who won the Grade II Santa
Catalina Stakes so impressively in January at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like once they have that initial experience of
traveling and being in a battle, they're either going to respond
negatively or positively,'' Stevens said. ``That's what separates
the very good horses from the mediocre horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had every right today to regress again, but he took a huge
step forward. I think that says a lot for his character and what
kind of race horse he is.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge sat just off pacesetter High Wire Act's early
fractions of 23.46, 47.30 and 1:11.46 before Stevens moved on him
as the field approached the far turn. He led by a half-length at
the top of the stretch and toyed with the others the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was the addition of blinkers that helped a Bob
Baffert-trained horse. Baffert added blinkers to Prime Timber in
last month's Grade II San Felipe Stakse and he responded with a
two-length victory.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was General Challenge's turn, and he loved the
equipment change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't make him run faster, but they did make him
focus,'' Stevens said. ``It's basically like the little kid that
you tell 'em to sit in the corner and keep their mouth shut and
their eyes and ears open. That's what the blinkers do for him.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge's final time of 1:48 4/5 for the 1 1/8 miles
was well off the stakes record of 1:47, but it was good enough to
give Baffert his third Santa Anita Derby victory in the past four
years. It was Stevens' seventh victory in the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Sent off as the 5-2 third choice in the wagering, General
Challenge returned $7.60 for his fourth victory in five races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for him to do this,'' Baffert said. ``He's
just learning how to run. He just plays around. The blinkers made
the difference. He was a big, goofy son-of-a-gun. He needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest disappointment in the race was trainer Bobby
Frankel's filly, Honest Lady. The daughter of Seattle Slew laid
close much of the race along the rail, but had nothing in the
stretch and faded to seventh in the eight-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel was not available for comment, but jockey Kent
Desormeaux was puzzled by the showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think something is amiss with her,'' he said.
``She just wasn't herself today. We didn't want the lead today. I
loved my spot. I was sitting right in the pocket, waiting to
explode. Unfortunately, when the opportunity presented itself to
push forward, my gun wasn't loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber almost did not run. Baffert said the son of Sultry
Song had a large bruise on his left hind leg Friday and came close
to being scratched before it improved by early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   David Flores had Prime Timber sitting fifth through much of the
early going before he unleashed a nice kick that resulted in a
second-place finish and a probable berth in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty happy with the way he finished,'' Flores said. ``I
know that Silver Charm was second in this race two years ago and
Real Quiet was second last year. I think we're in a pretty good
spot right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm and Real Quiet parlayed second-place finishes here
into Kentucky Derby victories.
</P>
<P>
   Said Corey Nakatani, rider for Desert Hero: ``The other horse
was just in an easy gallop. But still, I thought we were going to
get him at any point. But the winner just kept on running, finding
another gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero, running his first race for new trainer Richard
Mandella, is also likely to travel to Churchill Downs for the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens will be there, and though he would not say if he's
committed to ride General Challenge, the veteran jockey left little
doubt where his heart lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty obvious what my feelings are about this horse,''
he said. ``My biggest hope right now is that he just stays healthy
through the next month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
