<HEADLINE>
INJURED STARS TUMBLE TO BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _The buzz coming into yesterday's game between the
Stars and the St. Louis Blues was about who was going to be playing
for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The difference turned out to be who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, flamboyant winger Brett Hull played his first game in St.
Louis since jumping from the Blues to the Stars through free agency
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Centers Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk and Guy Carbonneau didn't
play, though, and therein lies the reason for the Blues' 5-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to use it as an excuse, but your No. 1, No.
2 and No. 3 centers ... '' said Hull, the implication obvious.
``You don't use it as an excuse, but as a challenge, and we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent injuries prevented Modano (groin), Nieuwendyk (knee) and
Carbonneau (ankle) from playing in Hull's welcome-back game, an
outing steeped in anticipation and short on delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Modano and Co. prevented the Stars from playing their
game.
</P>
<P>
   They struggled to generate any type of consistent offensive
threat. The most glaring evidence of the trio's absence was seen on
faceoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't start with the puck,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said, ``and you're not going to win many games if you don't start
with the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   The times when a team is most likely to have the puck _ power
plays _ the Stars played as if they didn't want it.
</P>
<P>
   Hull described the power play as ``awful,'' with the 0-for-5
result as proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``No shots, no aggressiveness,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor
explained. ``We had chances, and our power play has to come
through.'
</P>
<P>
   The problems, injury-based and otherwise, finally caught up to
the Stars in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner than Stars center Tony Hrkac had tied the score at 2-2
did the Blues add three goals in 10 minutes, including two by left
winger Pavol Demitra, who finished with two goals and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played the way we needed to play to win,'' Hitchcock said,
``for two periods.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig: ``That's what happens when
you get down by a couple of goals, you start pinching, trying to
make something happen and there is a lot of room to look really
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis seemed always to be playing with a lead. Each time,
the Stars scored to tie it, the Blues untied it.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues were up 1-0 when Hull scored his first goal at the
Kiel Center as a member of the visiting team.
</P>
<P>
   His goal had a certain style that defined his time in St. Louis.
He spun around to the side of the goal, faked as if he was going to
pass and instead slipped it past Blues goalie Grant Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   His goal, like his presence, elicited a few boos and a
smattering of applause from the 20,113 fans in attendance. Mostly
though, fans greeted Hull with casual indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Hull had a much stronger reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first period, I could barely move,'' he said afterward.
``I was really nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   He had played in St. Louis for 11 seasons and looked forward to
playing against his former team in his former city on Nov. 21, but
was sidelined with a bruised kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he had to wait better than four months for his return.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe too much time had passed. Maybe it's too close to the
playoffs. Maybe the Stars' uniform has come to look natural on him.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Hull's homecoming turned out to be about
who wasn't here instead of that he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play for the Blues anymore,'' Hull said.
</P>
</TEXT>
