<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' LONG SEASON ENDS WITH SPICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know what you've always said, and I've never disagreed _ the
baseball season is simply too long.
</P>
<P>
   But we were both wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I got your looooong season right here:
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars are about to catch the Rangers, both going and
coming.
</P>
<P>
   The last time we saw the Rangers in Arlington, they were playing
for the right to win a world championship. Sorta.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were attempting to survive against the Yankees in
the opening round of the baseball playoffs. God apparently was not
pleased about such frivolous competition. He made it rain real
hard. A game that started on Oct. 2 ended in the wee hours of Oct.
3. In two days, the Rangers scored no runs and went home for the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the Stars started skating for the right to win a
world championship. The Stanley Cup, everyone predicted, was theirs
to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, nothing has changed, except the Rangers open
another American League season tomorrow, and the Stars are still
killing time, waiting on the Stanley Cup playoffs. But there are
two weeks remaining in the NHL's regular season. Will it ever end?
</P>
<P>
   Being the best hasn't been a problem for the Stars thus far.
Definite proof, however, won't be available until the playoffs
begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is our comfort level,'' said winger Pat (''Little
Ball of Hate'') Verbeek. ``With our record, we put ourselves in a
position of being comfortable at this point. That is both good and
bad. Lately, it's been bad. We haven't played with desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the Cowboys, none of the local Big Four has ever had
a better shot at winning a world championship. And it may be a long
while before the Cowboys are again considered title titans. The
Stars are our only hope.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the taskmaster, Ken Hitchcock has had this team
playoff-ready since February, but gliding through these next two
weeks is not exactly on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blessing,'' Hitchcock said, ``that our remaining
schedule is as tough as it is. Detroit \Rtoday\S, Phoenix twice,
Colorado, Anaheim _ these are the kind of games when pride and
competitiveness take over. We need that.''
</P>
<P>
   Speak of a blessing, maybe it also wore a different disguise
last week when Mike Modano had to sit down. Something about a
pulled groin muscle. Modano will be out seven to 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest fear this time of year centers on a key injury,''
said Hitchcock. ``But the time Mo will miss could mean renewed
energy when we need him the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk joined Modano on the injured-scratched list
yesterday when the Stars lost in St. Louis. Health is a current
team concern, but all the ailing will return for the start of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And in early April, the Stars will accept any kind of playoff
edge. Modano may have also figured, accidentally and painfully, in
another of those.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, he was leveled by Jeremy Roenick of Phoenix.
Roenick was slapped with a game misconduct for what the Stars
termed a ``cheap shot,'' but he was not suspended by the league.
</P>
<P>
   From some of us came a howl that the Stars didn't ignite a riot
after Modano took that hit in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what it did for that game was wake us up, and suddenly
Derian Hatcher took over, and we went on to win,'' said Hitchcock.
``It's also something that has not been forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the Stars will go back-to-back with Phoenix, playing
at Reunion on the 14th and there on the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Stars have an answer directed right at Roenick?
Locker-room talk suggests as much, but there might be more involved
here.
</P>
<P>
   A Coyotes-Stars playoff series is certainly a possibility. One
player didn't want to be quoted last week, his theory being why
talk about it publicly until it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are some teams you have a healthy hate for,'' he
added. ``You don't like them, but you respect them. Detroit and
Edmonton fall in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Roenick took that cheap shot, we didn't have much of a
rivalry with Phoenix. Now there's a hate. And it's not a healthy
hate. We don't like that team, and we don't respect that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice here, the sound of playoff gears starting to grind to
life.
</P>
<P>
   While baseball locally has gone and come, the hockey team awaits
the end of the longest season. And then the serious stuff can
start.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
