<HEADLINE>
HOLDING THEIR BREATH FOR JUSTICE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've become acquainted lately with breathlessness, with
exhaustion, with weakness. It has made me think of young Nicky
Contreraz, who died a tor turous death at the Arizona Boys Ranch
just over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pneumonia has left me feeling loose and tangled as a puppet cut
away from his strings. And yet my trouble is nothing compared with
the infection that caused Contreraz to lose his breath, vomit con
stantly and suffer through uncontrolled diarrhea. And which
eventually left 2{ quarts of pus in the linings of his lungs for
the medical examiner to find.
</P>
<P>
   That's only one of the differences be tween us. Another is this:
</P>
<P>
   When I said I was sick, I was believed.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicky said he was sick, he was forced to do push-ups over a
bucket of his excrement-soiled clothing. He was re quired to eat
his supper while sitting on a toilet. He was ridiculed and
insulted, told he was a slacker who deserved an Acad emy Award.
</P>
<P>
   Then he died.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Pinal County prosecutors filed first-degree murder
charges against five Boys Ranch employees in connection with
Contreraz's death.
</P>
<P>
   The story disappeared under all the news of war in Kosovo, the
murder of a local police officer and the freak winter storm that
descended on the state. &QL; 
LOST COMMENTS
</P>
<P>
   With that story were lost the comments of lawyers working for
ranch employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecutor doesn't know what's going on,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wonder if this is simply a response to aggressive
lawyers,'' added another. ``This is absolutely beyond real ity. No
one has ever thought that this was a first-degree murder case.''
</P>
<P>
   He's never spoken, I guess, to the fam ily of 15-year-old
Nicholaus Contreraz.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can they live with themselves saying stuff like that,
defending people who did what they did to Nicky?'' asked Connie
Woodward, Contreraz's grand mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they have children? Would they feel that way if someone did
this to their child?''
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of questions prose cutors will ask a jury _
and should ask a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Contreraz was in Boys Ranch because he'd gotten into trouble,
most recently for joy-riding in a stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   The boot camp outside of Oracle was supposed to be a place where
discipline and hard work were used to straighten out wayward kids.
</P>
<P>
   Contreraz wasn't straightened, however. He was broken. &UR; He had
been sick for days before he died. The nurse who saw him during
this time, and is one of those charged in his death, declared him
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But how could the others not have known he was ill?
</P>
<P>
   They've been around kids. Is it com mon for a youngster who's
``faking it'' to vomit constantly and defecate in his pants? Or
were they so bent on punish ment, on setting young Nicky straight,
that they ignored the obvious?
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing into the charges has been scheduled for
April 13. &QL; 
`GOT TO BE SOME JUSTICE'
</P>
<P>
   Among those who will be there are Contreraz's mother and
grandmother. They'll be making the trip from outside of Sacramento,
from which they sent Nicky to Arizona. And to which he was returned
in a box.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has got to be some justice somewhere in all this,''
Connie Wood ward said. ``Arizona must have laws against murder,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   It does. And they say if someone dies during the commission of a
felony _ like abusing a child _ the charge can be mur der in the
first degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Nicky in my sleep almost every night,'' Woodward said.
``I'll never forget the Friday before he died, talking to him, and
having the people at the ranch tell me, `Don't worry, you've got a
strong healthy young man here.' It haunts me.''
</P>
<P>
   A guilty verdict won't change that.
</P>
<P>
   It can't reverse the pain and the humili ation. It can't revive
a suffocated boy. But it might, at least in a small way, help his
tortured family breathe a little easier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
