<HEADLINE>
MABEES GET A SECOND CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- Thanks to General Challenge's powerful victory in
Saturday's Grade I Santa Anita Derby, owners John and Betty Mabee
figure to get another shot at the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Best Pal ran second at Churchill Downs for the Mabees in 1991
after finishing second to Dinard in the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert said that after General Challenge finished a
disappointing fifth in the Louisiana Derby last month, the gelding
became known as ``Rodman'' around the barn. They figured the real
General Challenge did not show up in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rodman shows up (in Kentucky), he'll be tough,'' John Mabee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the General Challenge camp also has another nickname for
their horse -- the `Paint Horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he stepped in a bucket of paint,'' Baffert said.
``He's got all that white.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Mabees have a lot more green stuff after Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gary Stevens does not think the Kentucky Derby distance of 1
1/4 miles will be a problem for General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a long, fluid stride, Stevens said of the strapping
son of General Meeting. `He feels like he will run all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Big Jag made it three consecutive victories when he won the
Grade II $200,000 Potrero Grande Breeders' Cup Handicap by a neck
over 21-1 longshot Early Pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Big Jag, a 6-year-old gelding, ran the 6 1/2 furlongs on the
main track in 1:15 1/5 and returned $3.60 as the 4-5 favorite. Gold
Land was the official second-place finisher after Early Pioneer was
disqualified and placed fourth for interference at the top of the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse feels like a machine to me,'' said winning rider
Jose Valdivia. ``I've never been on one that can run the way he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The guaranteed $1 million Pick Six pool was $1,564,444. Five
of the six winners were favorites, and a winning ticket returned
$374.40.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Neil Drysdale-trained Sweet Life, ridden by Alex Solis,
rallied in the stretch to overtake pacesetter Lady At Peace and win
the $75,000 Providencia Stakes for 3-year-old fillies at 1 1/8
miles on the turf.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive victory for the daughter of Kris
S. and first stakes triumph. Sweet Life was the 2-1 favorite and
won by a head. Smittenby finished third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
