A5155 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-03 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT HAS DECISIONS TO MAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ By saddling the first- and second-place finishers in
the Santa Anita Derby, Bob Baffert put a month of headaches behind
him _ and condemned himself to another.
</P>
<P>
   March was not the trainer's best month. An injury forced the
abrupt retirement of once top-ranked 3-year-old Exploit. Two other
Kentucky Derby hopefuls, General Challenge and Straight Man,
suffered their first losses. Silver Charm, the 1997 Derby winner,
ran up the track in Dubai, and Real Quiet, the '98 Derby winner,
was withdrawn from a major race in Arkansas. A shouting match with
a jockey agent over riding assignments led to Baffert shoving the
man _ and left the impression he was cracking under all that bad
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person I know of who had a worse week than I had was
Coach K,'' Baffert said more than once in recent days, referring to
Mike Krzyzewski, coach of NCAA final loser Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at about noon Friday, Baffert discovered that new
top-ranked 3-year-old Prime Timber had a tender hind foot and might
have to be scratched from the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that after the big performances by General Challenge
and Prime Timber in the West's major Kentucky Derby prep race
Saturday, Baffert pleaded for a few hours to savor the victory
before being forced to think about what's next.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Baffert's chances of winning a record third straight
Run for the Roses on May 1 look outstanding again.
</P>
<P>
   A day before the Santa Anita Derby, his 3-year-old filly
Excellent Meeting trounced a weak field in the Fantasy Stakes at
Oaklawn Park in Arkansas. An hour before the Santa Anita Derby, his
(begin ital)other(end ital) 3-year-old filly Silverbulletday ran
away with the Ashland Stakes at Keeneland in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Santa Anita race right before the Derby, Baffert's
colt Finder's Gold dominated an allowance race to put himself back
on the road to Churchill Downs _ or at least the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Now the challenge for Baffert is to pick his team for the
Kentucky Derby, a team that will include at least two horses or as
many as ...?
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty!'' Baffert said with aplomb when he was asked how many
horses he could conceive of entering in a Kentucky Derby. Twenty is
the Derby limit.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Baffert can choose from among six 3-year-olds,
assuming they all stay healthy and train well. General Challenge:
He's confirmed on an April 13 flight to Louisville after Saturday's
3 {-length victory, the California-bred gelding's first race since
he was fitted with blinkers to improve his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today he focused all of his energy in the right direction when
he got to the starting gate,'' jockey Gary Stevens said of the
high-spirited horse.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, composure comes easier with 33,551 fans behind the
rail. Let's see how he handles the Churchill Downs crowd of
140,000-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber: He'll be on that flight too, and his fans
shouldn't be discouraged by Saturday's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   With a slow early pace working against them, Prime Timber and
David Flores were able to rally from fifth to second in the last
three-eighths of a mile. The effort looked even stronger half an
hour later, when Baffert revealed he feared he'd have to scratch
the colt because of the sore foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have stepped on something. He was noticeably off in
the back (left) leg,'' Baffert said. But the trainer's staff
removed the shoe and treated the foot overnight. Whatever they did
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really going to set him up (for the Kentucky Derby).
He ran the same race Real Quiet did last year,'' Baffert said. As
Real Quiet did, Prime Timber and General Challenge covered the
final eighth of a mile in about 12 3/5 seconds, which says good
things about their chances at 1 \ miles.
</P>
<P>
   Straight Man: Already in Kentucky, Bob and Beverly Lewis'
talented but underseasoned colt might run April 18 in Keeneland's
Lexington Stakes, a back door to the Derby. Baffert wishes he had
another month to prepare him.
</P>
<P>
   Straight Man seems unlikely to be pushed into the Derby if
Baffert has other horses. Which he will.
</P>
<P>
   Finder's Gold: Saturday's win probably was too little, too late,
to get him to Louisville. His breeders and owners, John and Betty
Mabee of San Diego, also have General Challenge and Excellent
Meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday: Now the hard part: The champion 2-year-old
filly of 1998 has done enough to merit a Derby try in an average
year. But owner Mike Pegram has already won a Derby with Real Quiet
and would settle for the Kentucky Oaks _ the fillies' Derby _ the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting: Now the harder part: Would the Mabees rather
have two shots at the Derby _ with General Challenge !ital!and!off
Excellent Meeting _ or one shot at the Derby and one at the Oaks?
</P>
<P>
   Mabee indicated that unless something goes wrong with General
Challenge, the filly is bound for the Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   This is the remarkable statistic on Baffert's Santa Anita Derby
success: In the past four years, he has won the race three times,
and finished first or second with six different horses, who
competed in the colors of six different owners.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if Baffert can keep all of his 3-year-olds healthy and pick
the right race for each, he'll keep all of his owners happy.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he won't finalize any decisions until the week of
the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' he said, ``the few dark hairs I have on the back of
my neck are going to be white after the next few weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
