<HEADLINE>
BEHRENS CAPTURES OAKLAWN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Ark. _ In the absence of Real Quiet, Behrens made a
lot of noise.
</P>
<P>
   With his impressive victory in yesterday's $750,000 Oaklawn
Handicap, the 5-year-old at once exorcised two past demons:
inconsistency and misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   Ridden by Jorge Chavez, Behrens overpowered pacesetting
runner-up Littlebitlively in the last furlong of the sloppy Oaklawn
Park race to win by 2 1/2 lengths in a fast 1:47.77 for a mile and
an eighth. It was the second such performance in a row for the
5-year-old, who also won the Gulfstream Park Handicap last month.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens had been expected to face Real Quiet, last year's
Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner. But Real Quiet's trainer, Bob
Baffert, abruptly changed course earlier this week and stayed in
California because of displeasure over the handicap weights, which
had Real Quiet spotting Behrens 6 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It would have taken a big effort for any horse to beat Behrens
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him do what he wanted to do,'' said Chavez, and Behrens
clearly wanted to run.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens stayed within two lengths of Littlebitlively through
swift early fractions of 46.29 seconds for a half-mile and 1:09.90
for six furlongs. He drew abreast of Littlebitlively entering the
lane and pulled away convincingly with only minimal encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, owned by Bill Clifton Jr. of Waco _ a longtime Oaklawn
regular _ and Don and Anne Rudder of Avon, Conn., paid $5 as the
slight favorite. Littlebitlively finished 1 3/4 lengths ahead of
third-place stablemate Precocity, the defending race champion who
rallied from last place on a track drenched by mid-afternoon
thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr Fong, the second favorite, was a well-beaten fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Luck, originally part of a three-horse entry owned by
John Franks and trained by Bobby Barnett, was a late scratch.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Behrens would follow a good race with a terrible
one, and often behaved erratically as well. But since a hairline
fracture in his hock was discovered and surgically corrected, he
has been a model racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   Last year ``was a disaster,'' trainer Jimmy Bond said. ``But
now, he has come back and we have something to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, beaten by a nose on a sloppy track in the 1997 Travers
Stakes, has won six races from only 15 lifetime starts, and has
earned $1,839,000. As a young horse, he had bone chips removed from
a leg, and he carries a screw inserted into his injured hock last
summer that obviously is causing him no discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   The next start for Behrens, Bond said, could be the May 29
Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs, which like the Oaklawn
Handicap, is part of the 12-race NTRA Champions on Fox series for
older horses. Behrens picked up 10 points in the series standings
for winning yesterday, and holds a 22-20 edge over Free House and
Puerto Madero.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
