A5157 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-TEXAS-RELAYS-TEX     04-03 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TEXAS-RELAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COUNTRY DAY STAR RACES TO 100 WIN IN 10.11
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The television was working late into the night at Amar
Johnson's place. And the show was spellbinding.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the former Fort Worth Country Day star and current
freshman sensation for the Texas Longhorns, spent a long evening
watching videotapes of his No. 1 opponent in yesterday's Texas
Relays invitational 100 meter dash, two-time Olympic gold medalist
Mike Marsh. He studied Marsh's start, his technique, anything that
might give him an edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the World Championships in 1995 and '97, the
Olympics in '92 and '96, the Goodwill Games ... everything I could
get my hands on,'' Johnson said. ``I learned I would have to get
out fast. If you don't get out to a fast start against him, he'll
get you.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get Johnson yesterday at Mike A. Myers Stadium, as the
19-year-old Longhorn got off to what he called ``the best start of
my life'' and blew away the 31-year-old Marsh with a time of 10.11
seconds, the best college time in America this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear freshmen say they want to run fast later,'' said
Johnson, who beat Marsh by .03 seconds. ``I said, `No, I want to do
it now.' Nobody believed in me except my teammates. Nobody even
knows who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20,000-plus fans who packed Texas' new track facility
yesterday found out when Johnson, running on the far outside in
Lane 9, shot out in front early and never gave an inch. His time
was by far a personal best, surpassing the 10.28 he ran two weeks
ago, and automatically qualified him for the NCAA outdoor
championships June 2-5 in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   It also broke the Johnson family record, previously held by
Amar's father, Robert, who ran 10.18 at Northeast Louisiana in the
1980s. Amar said his father was among the many who had counseled
him in preparation for yesterday's race, along with Texas coach
Bubba Thornton and world record holder Donovan Bailey, who trains
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Donovan I was going try his approach,'' Johnson said.
``He doesn't start well, but he comes on at the end. He said,
`Don't do that.' Get out fast. Get out low and keep driving.''
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson caused the biggest stir, TCU's sprinters were also
dazzling, running a 38.64 to win the University men's 4x100-meter
relay. Despite a sloppy baton exchange between leadoff man Bryan
Howard and Jarmiene Holloway, the Horned Frogs still cruised to an
easy victory in the nation's best time of the young outdoor season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, TCU's Lindel Frater, Ricardo ``Flash'' Williams and
Holloway swept the first three places in the University men's 100,
running 10.20, 10.21 and 10.23, respectively. Howard ran 10.21 to
finish third in the invitational 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all equal,'' said Frater, a sophomore from Jamaica.
``And because of that, we have a great relationship. It's like
we're all in one head, because we think a lot alike. And mostly
what we think is that we've got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   UT-Arlington's Marsha French did her job yesterday, winning the
women's shot put with a national-best throw of 53-9 3/4, good
enough to automatically qualify her for the NCAA meet. The junior
transfer from Northeast Louisiana has now set personal bests in her
past two meets since changing her form to gain extra momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out here expecting to throw a personal best, not to
win,'' she said. ``I've worked so hard for this. I've had the
potential all along. I just needed to show people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austin All-Stars felt they had something to prove in the
invitational 4x100 and 4x200 relays, mostly because they were
matched up against an HSI team that featured reigning world
champions Maurice Greene and Ato Boldon and former world champ Jon
Drummond.
</P>
<P>
   But former UT-El Paso star Obadele Thompson gave the All-Stars
an early lead over Drummond and HSI in both races, and anchor
Rohsaan Griffith took it from there, holding off Curtis Perry in
the 4x100 and Greene in the 4x200 to give his team a pair of
stunning victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who it is, I'm not going to let the race get away
when I'm on top,'' Griffith said. ``I know they wanted these bad,
especially the 4x200 after we'd already beaten them in the 4x100.
But our sprinters are just as good as theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas sprinters proved they were the best in the women's
division, winning all three relays yesterday _ all in meet record
time. The Longhorns' 42.90 in the 4x100 and 3:28.48 in the 4x400
were national bests.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
