<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SEND MATEO, ZIMMERMAN TO TRIPLE A
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Outfielder Ruben Mateo and pitcher Jeff
Zimmerman were the most impressive rookies in the Rangers' spring
camp, but it wasn't enough to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Both, as expected, were sent to Triple-A Oklahoma when the
Rangers finalized their 25-man roster yesterday before a 6-4
exhibition loss to the New York Mets at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates looked for ways during the final days of
spring training to get Mateo on the roster but came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an organizational decision on Ruben Mateo,'' Oates
said. ``A lot of discussion went into it. The decision was based
not only on what's best for Ruben but what's best for the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The big winners yesterday were outfielder Scarborough Green and
infielder Jon Shave, who won the final two roster spots. Green beat
out Milt Cuyler as the fifth outfielder and pinch-runner, and Shave
beat out Scott Sheldon and Rafael Bournigal as the second utility
infielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively I thought they were all alike and Shave had the
best spring offensively,'' Oates said. ``Im my mind, Shave won the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo hit .283 with four homers and 11 runs batted in in 53
at-bats, but the Rangers are set with Tom Goodwin in center. Mateo
could platoon with Lee Stevens at designated hitter when Rafael
Palmeiro is ready to play first but the Rangers want him playing
every day at Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo and Zimmerman were being kept around in case Palmeiro and
pitcher John Wetteland would not be ready for Opening Day. But
Palmeiro and Wetteland continue to show that they are close to
overcoming spring training health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, slowed by an ankle problem this spring, retired the
side in order yesterday in his one inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concerns were done two outings ago,'' Wetteland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very encouraged,'' pitching coach Dick Bosman said.
``Physically he feels good. He trains well. What he did this winter
in getting his arm ready sustained him to get through the other
thing. Now that's under control, his arm is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who underwent two knee surgeries in the past two
months, had two singles in four at-bats yesterday. He was 4-for-11
with a home run in three exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' Palmeiro said. ``I'll take it. I've done
better, but you don't get to that locked zone for a long time.
Hopefully I can get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's long shot bid to make the team seemed to fade when
he allowed five runs in his last four appearances. He gave up three
runs in his first 10 innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   But Oates said a bigger factor was taking two left-handers _
Eric Gunderson and Mike Munoz _ a long reliever _ either Esteban
Loaiza or Mike Morgan _ who could pitch a high number of innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimmerman threw the ball well for me all spring,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers treated me great,'' Zimmerman said. ``I thought I
proved I could get big-league hitters out. Now I just need to go
down there and work on a few things and be ready if something opens
up this summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
