<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BETTER OR WORSE, RANGERS PITCHING STAFF SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Curt Schilling isn't going to ride to the
rescue. The Rangers set their 11-man pitching staff for Opening Day
yesterday and expect to stay with it for a while.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff had a 5.51 earned-run average, with opponents
hitting .301.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan won the fifth spot in the rotation with a 1.53 ERA.
Esteban Loaiza lost it with an 8.09 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' front three starters of Rick Helling, Aaron Sele
and Mark Clark were 7-4 with a 5.54 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett finished the spring 1-3 with a 6.26 ERA after
allowing five runs (only two earned) in four innings yesterday.
Opponents hit .299.
</P>
<P>
   The setup relievers of left-handers Mike Munoz and Eric
Gunderson and right-handers Danny Patterson and Tim Crabtree
combined for a 5.19 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all done the work; they've done their preparation and
largely they've executed,'' pitching coach Dick Bosman said.
</P>
<P>
   NO MORE SUITS
</P>
<P>
   A Ballpark in Arlington landmark is gone. The Rangers replaced
the 501-foot, ``Hit it Here, Win Free Suit'' sign on top of the
right-field roof.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' two lefthanded power-hitters weren't too distressed
considering nobody has yet to hit a ball on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't stand on second base and hit it that far,'' Rafael
Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if they had Mark McGwire around,'' Lee Stevens said.
``They have a new Sonic sign in the bullpen. It seems a lot of my
home runs go into the bullpen. Maybe if I hit the Sonic sign I'll
win a week's supply of Coney Dogs and limeade.''
MORGAN SETS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan is going into the record books, 21 years after
making his major-league debut with the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers officially added Morgan to their roster yesterday,
the 11th team he has played with in his career. That's one more
than reliever Bob Miller, outfielder Tommy Davis and pitcher Ken
Brett.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, 39, was 18 when he pitched in his first major-league
game with Oakland in 1978. Since then he has played with the
Yankees, Blue Jays, Mariners, Orioles, Dodgers, Cubs, Cardinals,
Reds, Twins and Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   EVANS DESIGNATED
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Tom Evans was designated for assignment yesterday,
one day after being claimed on waivers from the Toronto Blue Jays.
The Rangers are hoping to get him through waivers and send him to
Triple A Oklahoma.
INJURY REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore was out of the lineup yesterday
with a slightly strained left hamstring muscle. His absence was a
precautionary measure and he said he would be ready for Opening
Day.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on outfielder Ruben Mateo's right wrist showed no
fractures or other serious problems. The diagnosis is a bone bruise
and he is available to play when he joins Oklahoma.
METS 6, RANGERS 4
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored five runs off Rangers starter John Burkett in
four innings. The Rangers finished the spring with a 14-14 record.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate: Ivan Rodriguez, Juan Gonzalez and Rusty Greer were
a combined 5 for 10 yesterday and together hit .413 for the spring,
with 10 homers and 38 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound: Mike Morgan had two more scoreless innings
yesterday and finished the spring with a 1.53 ERA, the lowest on
the club.
</P>
<P>
   In the field: Gonzalez dropped Brian McRae's fly ball in the
fourth inning, a three-base error that led to a four-run inning for
the Mets. Three of the four runs off pitcher John Burkett were
unearned.
</P>
<P>
   On the basepaths: Scarborough Green, who made the team primarily
as a pinch-runner, got picked off in the sixth inning by reliever
Scott Stewart and thrown out in the eighth trying to steal. He
would have been safe but he elected not to slide and was tagged out
when his foot dragged off the base.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
