u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      04-03 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PREPARES 8,000 TROOPS FOR ALBANIAN RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO said Saturday it would send as many as 8,000
troops to Albania to contend with what an alliance spokesman called
a ``demographic earthquake'' caused by the flood of refugees being
driven out of Kosovo by Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb blasts rocked the outskirts of Belgrade again early today.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and U.S. officials said, however, there was still no
consideration of introducing ground forces to fight their way into
the Serbian province, where the troops of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic have been attacking ethnic Albanians and herding
them out toward the borders.
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate of exodus, ``Serb security forces would have
more or less emptied Kosovo'' in 10 to 20 days, said NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, in Europe to
review the worsening humanitarian disaster for President Clinton,
was prepared to implore Macedonia to reopen its northern border
with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders in Macedonia, which has absorbed an estimated
55,000 refugees in recent weeks, are concerned that the influx
could upset the delicate ethnic balance of the small nation.
Approximately 25,000 more ethnic Albanians were waiting to stream
across, aid workers said.
</P>
<P>
   New NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia were hampered by a thick cloud
cover over the Balkans Saturday, but a cruise missile slammed into
a second bridge over the Danube River near Novi Sad.
</P>
<P>
   Early today, Agence France-Presse news service quoted an
official Yugoslav source as saying a police academy and an oil
refinery near Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, had been hit. Reuters
said a fuel dump at Kraljevo, in southern Serbia, had also been a
target. NATO did not immediately confirm the strikes. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In Belgrade, Serbians reacted with defiance as they viewed the
ruins of two government buildings struck early Saturday and
destroyed by NATO cruise missiles. Vlajko Stojijkovic, the Serbian
interior minister, said the attacks were ``acts of a monster
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO air commander David Wilby said: ``Our attack went well.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they had no news of the three U.S. Army
soldiers who were picked up by Serb forces Wednesday on the
Kosovo-Macedonia border and may face Yugoslav court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have any new information,'' said Navy Capt. Steve
Pietropaoli, a Pentagon spokesman. ``We have heard some assurances
from the Yugoslav government'' that the three soldiers are being
well cared for, he said. ``We didn't see much reassurance out of
the pictures that were shown on TV of those soldiers. We expect
them to be released immediately.``
</P>
<P>
   The three detainees are Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville;
Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and Staff Sgt.
Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remembered the soldiers in his Easter eve radio address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us keep in our prayers the three brave American servicemen
now being held without justification in Belgrade, that they may
return to us soon,'' Clinton said. ``Let us do what we can and what
we must for peace to prevail and let us stay the course until it
does.''
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, spokesman Jamie Shea
said that allied ambassadors had asked U.S. Army General Wesley
Clark, the alliance's military chief, to quickly ship an
operational headquarters, helicopters, supplies and troops to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is mobilizing all its available resources for this urgent
humanitarian requirement,'' Shea said. ``The focus of the alliance
is still very, very much on the demographic earthquake that we are
experiencing in and around Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea also said that more of some 10,000 British, French and
German troops _ originally sent to Macedonia for a prospective
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo _ have been ordered to work with the
refugee crisis there.
</P>
<P>
   The expanding refugee crisis appeared to force NATO to
reconsider its terms of peace with Milosevic. Although allied and
U.S. spokesmen said the cease-fire proposal put forward in France
last month remained on the table, there were signs NATO was
prepared to insist that Milosevic take additional steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly President Milosevic has shown that he is not the best
person to govern Kosovo after the actions of the recent days,''
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Milosevic could not be
allowed to present ``some plan to salvage what he can from this and
present himself as a peacemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Without addressing any possible new peace formulation, Clinton,
in his radio address, called for steadfastness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation cannot do everything,'' Clinton said. ``We can't
end all suffering. We can't stop all violence, but there are times
when looking away simply is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our military mission in Kosovo is a difficult and dangerous
one, but it's necessary and right and we must stand with all our
NATO allies to see it through.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican response, Virginia Gov. James Gilmore, a
former NATO counter-intelligence officer, questioned whether
Clinton himself had the resolve to stick with the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interests abroad cannot be defended without a clear
understanding of what our aims are and without a careful plan for
bringing our military might to bear upon an achievable objective,''
Gilmore said. ``This is one of the most simple tests of leadership.
This is a test that I hope President Clinton will pass, but I fear
he won't.''
</P>
<P>
   A new Newsweek poll found that 83 percent of Americans would
support sending U.S. forces to rescue the U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Support for using ground forces in the Balkan fighting now
commands a majority of support, the survey showed, measured at 54
percent, compared with 47 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, based on interviews with 750 adults on Thursday and
Friday, had a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of Britons being published in today's Sunday Times showed
even stronger support for using ground troops in Kosovo: 66 percent
in favor and 27 percent opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said ground troops were ``not a panacea either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They would take time to find, to raise, to deploy, and we
don't have that time, quite frankly, in order to do what we can to
arrest the current humanitarian situation in Kosovo,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Blair, conferring by telephone Saturday, said the
missile attacks on the Serb and Yugoslav interior ministries had
sent ``a powerful message'' of NATO's resolve. The nearby buildings
are the headquarters of the police units believed to be planning
attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some allied officials conceded that the ministry staffs almost
certainly had been moved out, but Air Commodore Wilby, of the
British Royal Air Force, said that even if the buildings were
empty, the attack showed ``we have moved our thinking process and
our striking process up to the heart of the matter. And we have
shown that we can prosecute our attacks right in the heart, in the
nerve center, where all this began.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said, however, that the cloud cover _ going up to 30,000
feet _ continued to limit aerial bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the weather improvement in the Balkans area has
yet to materialize, and we were hampered in our efforts to mount
operations by manned aircraft,'' Wilby said. ``It seems that the
weather has proved to be a temporary ally of President Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   In other humanitarian developments, an Air Force C-17 cargo
plane flew from Dover Air Force Base in Delaware Saturday with
30,000 packaged meals destined for Kosovar refugees, Defense
Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said each packet contains enough food to feed one refugee
for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about 2,200 calories and it is non-meat, so it can be
eaten by people of all faiths,'' Bacon said. Most of the Kosovar
Albanians are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Additional U.S. military planes were dispatched with unloading
equipment and airport operations gear to help control the
increasing traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright conferred by telephone
Saturday with the foreign ministers of France, Germany, Italy and
Britain about potential threats by Milosevic against Montenegro,
which along with Serbia makes up what is currently known as
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said the officials
``warned that any effort of the Belgrade regime to undermine the
democratic government of the Republic of Montenegro could have the
most serious consequences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
