<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-03 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5167 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-USC-LADN     04-03 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DEFEATS NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first inning and the game-tying runner that
was caught stealing. Take those away and the Cal State Northridge
baseball team might have earned a win against its nationally ranked
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Matadors fell three game below .500 with an 11-6
loss to USC on Saturday at Matador Field, completing the Trojans'
three-game sweep of the nonconference series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the exact same thing,'' CSUN starter Jim DeBiase said,
referring to Friday's doubleheader in which the Matadors gave up a
significant lead early in the game before staging a comeback. ``But
like I said, (USC) is a great hitting team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our adrenaline kind of kicks us back. We have some battlers on
this team, though. They don't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors (20-23) drew within one with a six-run seventh. The
tying run was on second with no outs, but Dan Phillips was thrown
out attempting to steal third while Eric Horvat struck out. The
next batter, Jeremy Sickles, also struck out to end the inning with
a 7-6 USC lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Patrick led off the CSUN seventh with a double and ended
Trojans starter Justin Lehr's shutout by scoring two batters later
on a single up the middle by Mike Bumstead. Lehr (4-1) was removed
after forcing in a run with a walk to Tim Arroyo. The second error
of the inning by USC second baseman Dominic Correa brought in two
runs and put runners at the corners with no outs. Six consecutive
Matadors reached base before Horvat struck out.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN reliever Andy Davidson didn't allow a run in 51/3 innings
of one-hit work, but the Trojans (20-16), ranked 25th by Collegiate
Baseball, had already done their damage with a seven-run first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put up a lot of runs,'' Lehr said. ``I think that really
helped us. We jumped on what they gave us. We had some mistakes
that hurt us, so the early runs helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Davidson led off the game with a triple and capped the
scoring with a single in his second at-bat of the inning to drive
in Lehr. Errors by shortstop Jason Watkins and center fielder
Phillips didn't help DeBiase (7-3), who allowed eight of the 10
batters he faced to reach base. The senior right-hander gave up
five earned runs on five hits in two-thirds of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some tough breaks,'' DeBiase said. ``I got some
balls up; they're a great-hitting ball club. They're national
champs. I just wasn't on today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehr was on at the plate and on the mound before tiring in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   He went primarily with his fastball to retire the side in order
twice, strike out six and give up four hits in six-plus innings.
Lehr also went 3 for 3, including two doubles, with a walk and two
RBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
