<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO SAID TO DEPICT MASS KILLINGS BY SERBS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Kosovar refugee who said he recently escaped a massacre in his
village gave the BBC what he said was a videotape of the aftermath
of the incident that shows the bodies of nearly 100 men who he said
were killed by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The footage, which the man gave to a BBC correspondent in
Albania on Saturday, may be the first images documenting the
atrocities that many of those fleeing Kosovo have described to
reporters and foreign aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to establish independently the authenticity of
the amateur videotape, which was recorded by a man from the town of
Krusa e-Madhe, a small village in the southwest of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Melaim Bellamica, told a story that has become a
familiar one among the hundreds of thousands of refugees that have
been pouring out of Kosovo since NATO began bombing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He said that on March 25, the day after NATO's first bombs were
dropped, Serbian forces began shelling the area. Later that day,
soldiers entered the town and began separating the men from women
and children, who were told to leave the village. He said that some
of the men, fearing the worst, tried to escape and were killed on
the spot. The others, he said, were shot one by one. None of them
were armed, he said, nor were they fighters with the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The footage which was broadcast on BBC and ABC News on Saturday,
showed the bodies of men, dressed in civilian clothing, sprawled in
fields surrounding the town. The video indicated that some of the
men had been shot in the back of the head or under the jaw.
</P>
<P>
   On CNN Saturday night, an elderly man from the same village was
interviewed as he crossed the Albanian border on the back of a
tractor. His description of the attack by Serbian forces was
similar to that of Bellamica. ``They put the men up against a wall
and shot them,'' said the man, who was allowed to leave because of
his age, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellamica said he survived the massacre by hiding for a week. He
filmed the bodies on April 1, after Serbian forces had left the
area, and arrived in Albania on Saturday. He gave the tape to
George Alagiah, a correspondent for the BBC, along with a list of
the names of those who were killed. ``I've done this so that my son
and my grandson will never forget what the Serbs did to the
Albanian people,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
